[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this Introduction, I will share with you three topics:   Exciting chess − Why the Leningrad System is an ideal opening if you want to play for a win like Nakamura or Dubov.   Chess improvement − I gained 150 rating points by picking up the Leningrad @@StartBracket@@and I have a terrible memory for opening lines!@@EndBracket@@, so I want to use this course to show how it will make you a better chess player with both White and Black, not just a better Leningrad player.  Big names in the history of the Leningrad − The context of the opening, its history, and the great players over time: from Tartakower to Euwe to Korchnoi to more recently Caruana, MVL, Nepomniachtchi, Giri, and Carlsen.   1. Exciting Chess: The Leningrad is a strategic opening with not a lot of forcing lines. This means that White players who like to memorize long variations are at a disadvantage. The opening’s main character is that White tends to play on the queenside and Black in the center and kingside. There is a lot of dynamic play and usually, the side with the more active pieces has the advantage.  The chances that you are facing a knock-out novelty like in the Sicilian, King's Indian, or Grünfeld are close to zero. On the other hand, if you are looking for a quiet game, then forget it. There is no standard way of playing, you need to apply your understanding and that is why White players who play the London or the Colle System often suffer quick losses against the Leningrad.  2. Chess improvement: One of the most difficult things for a chess player is to accept your limitations. I will never have a photographic memory and I cannot calculate as deep as Carlsen or Anand. I am amazed if I watch Peter Svidler or Peter Leko online at how quickly they seem to understand the position and come up with strong moves, it takes me 5-10 minutes. But I did manage to improve my rating with more than 150 points when I picked up the Leningrad, I went from around 2225 to 2393.  I had picked up a book by a German GM, Stefan Kindermann, around 2002, and till today I still prefer this as my main weapon against 1.d4, 1.c4, and 1.Nf3. I have played other openings: King's Indian, Grünfeld, Slav, Nimzo-Indian, Queen's Indian, Dutch Stonewall, Benoni, but every time I come back to the Leningrad. The main reason is that I know where my pawns and pieces need to go and on which targets in White’s camp I need to focus.  By studying the Leningrad I improved my chess understanding of piece play and pawn structures and this has also tremendously benefitted my play with White. I have always been interested in chess improvement, I have my chess trainer license, I have coached many players and for my own chess, I worked in the past with great trainers like Mark Dvoretsky, Mihail Marin, Adrian Michalchishin, Tibor Karolyi, Laszlo Hazai and Ian Rogers. I am also a senior leader in the corporate world and I truly enjoy coaching executives in the areas of strategy and leadership skills.   I tried to use all these experiences in my 7-year project  The Anand Files  when I studied deeply how a world champion trains, prepares, and develops different strategies to win the title three times in a row. So when Chessable approached me after  The Anand Files , I made it clear that I wanted to do something around chess improvement. I want to use my lessons learned from the chess world, the corporate world, and working with Anand and his team to help others in the chess world.  The course on the Leningrad is not another opening course, it is a vehicle for chess improvement and hopefully the start of a dialogue between you and me on the Chessable platform. The script for the opening lines will show you my analysis  (I found so many mistakes in top-level games)  , and the video series is where I will go deep in the chess improvement area: how you recognize the strategic important aspects, what to do if you cannot remember the exact move order and how you can ‘feel’ whether something will work, without having to calculate like a grandmaster.  I will also discuss my own games, the good, the bad, and even the ugly ones @@StartBracket@@see thebloopers chapter@@EndBracket@@. Before we dive into an overview of the repertoire, let’s quickly look at the historical context of the Leningrad System.  3. Big names in the history of the Leningrad: The Leningrad is one of the most important systems in the Dutch Defense. The Dutch was first mentioned by Elias Stein in his book from 1789  Nouvel Essai Sur Le Jeu Des Échecs , avec des réflexions militaires relatives à ce jeu @@StartBracket@@New essay on the game of chess with military reflections on the game@@EndBracket@@. Stein was living in the Netherlands at the time his book was published and there he recommended the Dutch as the best response against 1.d4.  It is not clear to me when the first game was played with the Leningrad System, but in a book from 1976 by T. D. Harding on the Leningrad, he mentions the games Potter versus Coburn and Dr. Ballard from 1874, and in 1920 the top-level game between Nimzowitsch and Tartakower.  Other strong players played the Leningrad, such as Réti and Bogoljubow, so the Dutch setup with ...g6 and ...Bg7 is quite old, but the name ‘Leningrad’ is much younger and was probably established at the end of the 1940s/early 1950s. There was a player called Vinogradov from Leningrad who played it in 1936 at least twice. Maybe he was the inspiration for what happened about 10 years later: Kuzminykh played it in the semifinal of the 16th USSR championship in Leningrad and later years he continued playing it in Leningrad.  In 1949 the player Kopylov also played it in Leningrad and in 1951 he became famous by using the Leningrad System to beat Botvinnik. In 1952 Vinogradov published an article on the system in the leading Russian chess magazine and even Korchnoi  (who was also from Leningrad)  played it for a short while.  Although it is not entirely clear who started using the name Leningrad System first, it is clear that it must have started in these years. Many strong players have played it since Larsen, Spassky, Topalov, Bareev, Vachier Lagrave, Nepomniachtchi, Kamsky, Nakamura, Caruana, and Mamedyarov. All have in common that they are fighting players, trying to get away from long theoretical lines, and creating unbalanced positions. }
1. d4
{ In this overview for simplicity reasons I focus on this move, but the repertoire also deals with  1.c4  ,  1.Nf3  ,  1.g3  ,  1.f4  , and  1.b3  . }
1... f5
{ The Dutch Defense! We immediately like to determine the type of play. There are players who prefer  1...d6  or  1...g6  and then later move to a Leningrad line, but I prefer to keep things as easy as possible. }
2. Nf3
{ A lot of White players consider the move 1...f5 as a provocation and they will try to punish Black immediately. So instead of  2.Nf3  , there are separate chapters on  2.Bg5  −Hopton Attack,  2.h3  −Korchnoi Attack,  2.e4  −Staunton Gambit,  2.Qd3  −Manhattan Variation and  2.g4  −Kreijcik Variation.  Although from a theoretical point of view all these lines result in equal positions, in my experience most White players overpress and quickly end up in a lost position. The exception is maybethe lines with  2.Nc3  ,  which are more positional in nature, but there Black's long-term prospects tend to be excellent based on the pair of bishops. It is also good to realize White doesn't need to develop the knight to f3, it can also go to f4 via h3 and this is dealt with in a separatechapter. }
2... Nf6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2
{ Instead of this move, White has an important option with the move  4.b4  . This can be played at move four, five, or even six and there are several move transpositions. My mainrecommendation is based  on the move ...d7-d5 followed by active play on the queenside, but as an alternative, I go quite deep in the lines where Black aims for the ...e7-e5 push. }
4... Bg7 5. O-O
{ Instead of castling, White can play  5.h4  either with the knight still on g1 or on f3, and this move is becoming increasingly popular because White players are realizing that against the main lines in the Leningrad System, Black has no problems. If White is going for the direct attack with h2-h4-h5 there are two or three ideas that Black needs to watch out for @@StartBracket@@for example taking on h5 is rarely OK@@EndBracket@@ but then we end up with a promising position. }
5... O-O 6. c4
{ There are also systems where the white c-pawn moves to c3. The idea is to put the queen on b3 and sometimes this is done in combination with a bishop to c4 @@StartBracket@@instead of developing it to g2@@EndBracket@@ and/or the king's-knight on f4. The character of play is very different from the one with the pawn on c4, but the amount of theoretical lines is not too big. }
6... d6 7. Nc3
{ My mainrecommendation for Black is the system with 7...c6 in which I believe Black has comfortable play in all lines. Instead of the system with 7...c6 I also showthe system with  7...Qe8  including some of White's most challenging options. I have played 7...Qe8 many times myself,  but I believe that nowadays the system with ...c6 is more reliable, especially for an over-the-board game. }
7... c6
{ This ismy preferred choice for Black. Here I discuss a lot of options for White:  8.Qb3  ,  8.b4  ,  8.Qc2  ,  8.d5  ,  8.Re1  ,  8.Bg5  ,  8.Bf4  ,  8.e3  ,  8.b3  ,  8.Rb1  . }
