1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6 8. Bf4
{ A rare move in the Leningrad System, but here White has a specific idea that is worth mentioning. }
8... Nh5
{ Black loves to chase away the bishop and play ...f5-f4. Note that ...h7-h6 is in this case a bit slow, even if Black plays ...g6-g5 on the next move. We are still not yet ready for ...f5-f4 with the knight on f6. }
9. Rc1
{ This is White's specific idea: giving up the pair of bishops to increase control over the squares in the center.   If  9.Bd2  then Black happily occupies the center with  9...e5  and we might already start hoping for an advantage with the nice pawns  on f5 and e5. And if White drops the bishop back to e3 with  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp2p1bp/2pp2p1/5p1n/2PP1B2/2N2NP1/PP2PPBP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Be3  ,  Black plays ...f5-f4 with tempo.  9...f4  and Black is already better. }
9... Nxf4 10. gxf4 Nd7 { Preparing ...e7-e5. } 11. e3 h6
{ We want to avoid Ng5.   The immediate  11...e5  gives White the option to make a quick draw. I prefer to rule out the freedom of choice.  12.Ng5  Qe7  13.d5  c5  and White can continue to attack the black rook, so instead of perpetual check, perpetual attack on the rook, but the result is the same.  14.Ne6  Rf7  15.Ng5  with a draw.   11...a5  with the idea to avoid b2-b4 when the black knight lands on c5 doesn't work, White quickly becomes active.  12.c5  , a great move.  12...dxc5  13.Ng5  . It suddenly turns out Black  is weak on the b3-g8 diagonal.  13...Nf6  is the best way of defending against Ne6.  14.Qb3+  e6  .  Yes, this loses a pawn, but ...Kh8 is met by Nf7+.  15.Nxe6  a4  16.Qc4   If White takes the pawn with  16.Nxa4  , Black plays  16...c4  , and after the queen takes the pawn,  17.Qxc4  Rxa4  and soon we will be in an equal endgame.  16...Bxe6  17.Qxe6+  Kh8  18.dxc5  with  a clear advantage for White with an extra pawn and the possibility to occupy the d-file after Rfd1. }
12. b4 e5
{ There is no more Ng5 and Qb3+ so Black is ready for our favorite push. } 13.
dxe5 dxe5
{ Black has the better long-term prospects with the pair of bishops and a healthier pawn structure. }
