1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2
{ I will discuss first the lines with b2-b4 where the white c-pawn is not yet on c4. }
4... Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. b4
{ There are quite a few moments when White can play for a setup with b2-b4, already from move four onwards. The main things to remember:  If White has put the c-pawn on c4, Black's plan with ...d7-d6 followed by ...e7-e5 is not always effective, so a setup with ...d7-d5 @@StartBracket@@usually played after ...c7-c6@@EndBracket@@ is the way to go.  If the pawn is still on c2, Black can often gain a tempo on the b4-pawn with ...Nc6 because b4-b5 is answered by ...Na5 and ...d7-d5, with a nice square on c4 for the knight. If White defends the b4-pawn with a2-a3, Black has sufficient time for ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5. }
6... Nc6 { 6...d5  is atransposition to the lines with 5.b4 and 6.O-O. } 7. a3
d6
{ Black plays for the standard plan of pushing ...e7-e5, making use of possible pins on either the rook on a1 or the bishop on b2, if White takes on e5. }
8. Bb2 e5 9. dxe5 Ng4 10. Qd5+
{ This check is part of several lines in the b4-systems, but Black doesn't need to worry. }
10... Kh8 11. Nbd2 Ngxe5
{ We want to take with the g4-knight because otherwise it may get kicked by h2-h3 at some point. }
12. Qb3 Qe7
{ Black is ready to put the bishop on e6 and has the option to become active on the kingside with ...f5-f4. If White plays b4-b5, Black can take on f3 with a check and then put the knight from c6 on e5 @@StartBracket@@just make sure you don't lose the b7-pawn@@EndBracket@@. }
