7... c6 8. d5 h6
{ Preventing the knight jump to g5 and preparing the next move. } 9. Nf4 g5 10.
dxc6 bxc6 11. Nfd5
{ If White plays  11.Nd3  Black is already better after  11...e5  . } 11...
Nfd7
{ If Black plays  11...Nxd5  instead, White takes back with the pawn,  12.cxd5  forcing Black to play  12...c5  . I don't fully trust it for Black since the queenside pieces are still in their initial position. And @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/p3p1b1/2pp1n1p/3N1pp1/2P5/2N3P1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...cxd5  fails to  12.Bxd5+  Nxd5  13.Qxd5+  and the rook drops. }
12. e4 e6 { First chasing the knight on d5 away. } 13. Nb4 Ne5
{ Not only attacking the pawn on c4 but also defending the c6-pawn which would be attacked by both the knight on b4 and the bishop on g2 after White takes on f5. }
14. exf5 exf5 15. Nd3
{ If White defends the pawn on c4, the kingside will get into trouble:  15.b3  f4  16.Bb2  f3  and Black plays with an extra piece now that the bishop on h1 is out of play. }
15... Nxc4
{ This is an extra pawn for Black and although the situation is still a bit unclear, I don't think White has sufficient compensation. Black can play ...Ne5 or ...Kh8 because White is hoping for tricks with Qb3. Before considering ...Qc7 to protect the pawns on c6 and d6  (on c7 the queen no longer defends the pawn on d5)  , Black has to resolve the threat of Qb3. }
