[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3
{ In this overview we will discuss systems that are linked to the London and Colle setups. In many of these lines, Black prepares the pawn push to e5 and then continues with ...g6-g5-g4, creating a dangerous kingside attack. One of the advantages of playing the Leningrad System is that there is no easy life for White in these setups compared to the Slav and all the Indian Defenses. }
2... Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. Bf4 d6 4. e3 g6 5. h3
{ White creates a safe haven for the f4-bishop. These types of systems are common among amateur players who prefer similar setups with White regardless of how Black responds. }
5... Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O e6
{ Black starts preparing for ...e6-e5, but this is easier to accomplish with a queen on e7, so that's why we first push ...e6. }
8. Bh2 Nc6 9. Nbd2 Qe7
{ Black is ready for ...e6-e5 but can also continue with ...b7-b6 and develop the c8-bishop followed by bringing the rook from a8 to the center. Later, the knight can be placed on e4 followed by ...g6-g5. Meanwhile, White's initiative on the queenside hasn't even started yet. }
