1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. h3
{ Preparing g2-g4. Some lines transpose to the2.g4 lines with a later h2-h3. }
2... Nf6 3. g4 d5 4. Qd3
{ Although this position has arisen quite a few times in practice, the engine disapproves and gives Black already some advantage. }
4... c5
{ This direct attack on the white center is stronger than  4...Nc6  , but even that move promises Black an edge. }
5. gxf5 Nc6
{ The move  5...c4  is also a valid option,  but you only have to know one line that results in a clear advantage. Also later in this line, the engine points out there are several ways to an advantage for Black, but I have tried to identify a clear logical line. }
6. Nf3 Ne4
{ This is an important move to win back the pawn on f5 and create threats against the white queen. }
7. dxc5 Bxf5 8. Qb5
{ It looks nice to have a queen on b5, but Black can easily take over. } 8...
a6 9. Qxb7 Rc8
{ Black has now a serious threat in ...Nxc5 and the queen has no squares. } 10.
Qb6 Qd7 11. Nc3 e5
{ Black has a large advantage, the pawn on c5 hangs, and if White plays  12.Be3  , Black simply answers with  12...d4  . }
