1. g3 f5
{ Many other moves are possible, but we want to stick to typical Leningrad System play, if possible. }
2. Bg2 Nf6 3. d3
{ White is preparing e2-e4 and Black normally responds by taking on e4 @@StartBracket@@to lock in the bishop on g2@@EndBracket@@ and play ...e7-e5 to grab some space in the center. }
3... d6 4. c4
{ White decided on a typical setup from the English opening and this position can also arise from the 1.c4 move order. }
4... g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. e3
{ This is a modest move with the intention to increase the central pressure with d3-d4 at a later stage. }
6... O-O 7. Nge2 c6
{ There are different ways of playing this position with Black, but I try to stay close to the plans we know from the main lines of the Leningrad System. }
8. O-O a5
{ Considering White 'forgot' to play b2-b4 before castling, we may as well block this option for now. }
9. b3 e5 { Grabbing space in the center is always a good idea. } 10. Ba3 Na6
{ This knight can go to b4 in certain lines, reducing the pressure on d6. } 11.
Qd2 Nb4 12. Rad1 Qe7
{ It is important to put the queen on e7: White often wants to play d3-d4-d5 followed by Nf4 and then Ne6. With the queen on e7, white must sacrifice a pawn to place the knight on e6. }
13. d4 e4
{ This is the standard reaction when White plays d3-d4. The alternative of maintaining the tension in the center is usually not advisable because White will take on e5 followed by Qd6, infiltrating in Black's position.  Black has a number of ideas in this position: ...g6-g5 to stop White's Nf4, a rook can be placed on e8 and the queen on f7, followed by ...d6-d5.  Meanwhile, White has also some ideas we need to be prepared for: f2-f3, to undermine our center  (that is why we put our rook on e8 so that after we take on f3, the pawn on e3 is weak)  , d4-d5  (we usually answer by playing ...c6-c5)  and Bxb4. But we simply take back and do not need to defend the pawn on b4 immediately because White's pawn on a2 is weak. }
