[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Réti Setups − 1.g3 without c4"]
[Result "*"]

1. g3 f5
{ Many other moves are possible, but we want to stick to typical Leningrad System play, if possible. }
2. Bg2 Nf6 3. d3
{ White is preparing e2-e4 and Black normally responds by taking on e4 @@StartBracket@@to lock in the bishop on g2@@EndBracket@@ and play ...e7-e5 to grab some space in the center. }
3... d6 4. e4
{ A rare move − the characteristics of the position will resemble a 1.e4 e5 opening soon with a strange bishop on g2 and Black being happy to have exchanged the f-pawn so later we can start action on the f-file. }
4... fxe4 5. dxe4 e5 { Blocking the bishop on g2 behind the e4-pawn. } 6. Ne2
Be7
{ Black continues to develop and castle kingside. Castling queenside is normally not a good idea in these lines because White can easily push the queenside pawns forward and generate a dangerous attack. }
7. O-O O-O 8. Nbc3 c6
{ Preventing White's knight jumps to d5, which would yield a nice space advantage. }
9. h3 Be6 { Black continues with normal development. } 10. f4 Nbd7
{ Black has completed development. Some White players may now be tempted to push forward with f4-f5 followed by g3-g4. Black responds by putting the bishop on c4 or f7, but here is what you need to remember: with white pawns on f5 and g4, White is threatening g4-g5. Black's response is ...h7-h6 followed by ...Nh7. Next, we will play ...Bg5 and exchange the dark-squared bishops. The dark squares on white's kingside have become weak with all the pawns on light squares  (h3, g4, f5, e4)  and White has no attacking chances anymore.  If White doesn't play f4-f5 but goes for normal moves like Be3 and Qd2, Black will continue with ...Qc7, ...Rad8, and maybe one day ...d6-d5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Réti Setups - 1.Nf3 without c4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 f5 2. d3
{ This line became popular because Magnus Carlsen won convincingly against a much stronger opponent in only 19 moves. Many years since then have passed and nowadays it is not a big problem for Black anymore. }
2... d6
{ I like this move a lot better than  2...Nc6  after which White can play the tricky  3.d4  .  After 2...d6 it doesn't make sense for White to play d3-d4, because that would transpose to a main line of the Leningrad while being a full tempo down. }
3. e4 e5
{ The standard reaction, when White plays e2-e4, Black usually plays ...e7-e5. Because the white bishop is still on f1, Black doesn't take on e4 first. We would only do that if the bishop is on g2, so the bishop would be locked behind the e4-pawn. }
4. Nc3 Nc6
{ 4...Be7  is not great because Black doesn't take control over the square d4.  5.d4  fxe4  6.Nxe4  d5  ,  at least Black should have played ...Nf6 here, but even then White has a clear advantage.  7.Neg5  Black is in big trouble with the exposed king.  7...exd4  8.Bd3  Qd6  9.Nxd4  and White was winning in Svidler-Bu, Tbilisi 2017. Black's king is not safe and the pieces don't coordinate well. }
5. exf5 Nge7
{ A key move.  5...Bxf5  was played in the famous game between a young Magnus Carlsen and Dolmatov, which resulted in a crushing win for White.  6.d4  Nxd4  7.Nxd4  exd4  8.Qxd4  Nf6  9.Bc4  c6  10.Bg5  b5  11.Bb3  Be7  12.O-O-O  Qd7  13.Rhe1  Kd8  14.Rxe7  Qxe7  15.Qf4  Bd7  16.Ne4  d5  17.Nxf6  h6  18.Bh4  g5  19.Qd4  1-0 Carlsen-Dolmatov, Moscow 2004. }
6. g4 { A strange move but it defends the pawn on f5, so we need to check it. }
6... h5 { We don't want to keep the pawn on f5 alive for too long. } 7. f6 gxf6
8. Ne4
{ Looks scary for Black, so it is important that we know the following move and are comfortable with it. }
8... Ng8 { At first, it may feel awkward, but Black is fine here. } 9. gxh5 Bg4
{ A nasty pin and White has only one move. } 10. Be2 Bxh5 11. Ng3 Bg6
{ White is ahead in development, but without the initiative that doesn't mean much. }
12. c3 Qd7 { Preparing to castle queenside. } 13. d4 O-O-O
{ Black has a clear advantage with a safer king and a better pawn structure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Réti Setups - 1.Nf3 without c4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 f5 2. d3
{ This line became popular because Magnus Carlsen won convincingly against a much stronger opponent in only 19 moves. Many years since then have passed and nowadays it is not a big problem for Black anymore. }
2... d6
{ I like this move a lot better than  2...Nc6  after which White can play the tricky  3.d4  .  After 2...d6 it doesn't make sense for White to play d3-d4, because that would transpose to a main line of the Leningrad while being a full tempo down. }
3. e4 e5
{ The standard reaction, when White plays e2-e4, Black usually plays ...e7-e5. Because the white bishop is still on f1, Black doesn't take on e4 first. We would only do that if the bishop is on g2, so the bishop would be locked behind the e4-pawn. }
4. Nc3 Nc6
{ 4...Be7  is not great because Black doesn't take control over the square d4.  5.d4  fxe4  6.Nxe4  d5  ,  at least Black should have played ...Nf6 here, but even then White has a clear advantage.  7.Neg5  Black is in big trouble with the exposed king.  7...exd4  8.Bd3  Qd6  9.Nxd4  and White was winning in Svidler-Bu, Tbilisi 2017. Black's king is not safe and the pieces don't coordinate well. }
5. exf5 Nge7
{ A key move.  5...Bxf5  was played in the famous game between a young Magnus Carlsen and Dolmatov, which resulted in a crushing win for White.  6.d4  Nxd4  7.Nxd4  exd4  8.Qxd4  Nf6  9.Bc4  c6  10.Bg5  b5  11.Bb3  Be7  12.O-O-O  Qd7  13.Rhe1  Kd8  14.Rxe7  Qxe7  15.Qf4  Bd7  16.Ne4  d5  17.Nxf6  h6  18.Bh4  g5  19.Qd4  1-0 Carlsen-Dolmatov, Moscow 2004. }
6. f6 gxf6 7. d4 d5
{ My improvement over a game played by Kindermann.  7...Bg4  was played by Kindermann against Ganguly in Germany 2017, and although the game ended in a draw, I believe White won the opening battle. }
8. dxe5 fxe5 9. Ng5
{ White is getting ready for a combination of Qh5+ and Bd3. } 9... Bf5 10. Bd3
Qd7
{ Making sure that if White takes on f5, Black can capture with the queen and a check on h5 is harmless. If White does nothing special here, say O-O, Black will take on d3, play ...Ng6, and now that the f7-square is protected by the queen, castle queenside. Black is probably already a bit better in such a line, so White needs to take action. }
*

