[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Réti Setups - 1.Nf3 without c4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 f5 2. d3
{ This line became popular because Magnus Carlsen won convincingly against a much stronger opponent in only 19 moves. Many years since then have passed and nowadays it is not a big problem for Black anymore. }
2... d6
{ I like this move a lot better than  2...Nc6  after which White can play the tricky  3.d4  .  After 2...d6 it doesn't make sense for White to play d3-d4, because that would transpose to a main line of the Leningrad while being a full tempo down. }
3. e4 e5
{ The standard reaction, when White plays e2-e4, Black usually plays ...e7-e5. Because the white bishop is still on f1, Black doesn't take on e4 first. We would only do that if the bishop is on g2, so the bishop would be locked behind the e4-pawn. }
4. Nc3 Nc6
{ 4...Be7  is not great because Black doesn't take control over the square d4.  5.d4  fxe4  6.Nxe4  d5  ,  at least Black should have played ...Nf6 here, but even then White has a clear advantage.  7.Neg5  Black is in big trouble with the exposed king.  7...exd4  8.Bd3  Qd6  9.Nxd4  and White was winning in Svidler-Bu, Tbilisi 2017. Black's king is not safe and the pieces don't coordinate well. }
5. exf5 Nge7
{ A key move.  5...Bxf5  was played in the famous game between a young Magnus Carlsen and Dolmatov, which resulted in a crushing win for White.  6.d4  Nxd4  7.Nxd4  exd4  8.Qxd4  Nf6  9.Bc4  c6  10.Bg5  b5  11.Bb3  Be7  12.O-O-O  Qd7  13.Rhe1  Kd8  14.Rxe7  Qxe7  15.Qf4  Bd7  16.Ne4  d5  17.Nxf6  h6  18.Bh4  g5  19.Qd4  1-0 Carlsen-Dolmatov, Moscow 2004. }
6. Nh4
{ This may look strange but White is trying to get the queen to h5 as quickly as possible. }
6... Nxf5 7. Qh5+ g6
{ Black has to sacrifice this pawn and then chase White's queen away. } 8. Nxg6
Ng7 9. Qh4 { White is offering a queen swap. } 9... Qxh4 10. Nxh4 Nd4
{ Ensuring White loses the right to castle because there is no other way to defend c2. }
11. Kd1 Be7
{ Black has the better chances here: the pieces are more active, White probably needs to play Nf3 and after taking on f3, White's extra pawn  (three against two on the kingside)  is worthless. If given a chance, Black will continue with castling queenside and putting a rook on f8. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Réti Setups - 1.Nf3 without c4 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 f5 2. d3
{ This line became popular because Magnus Carlsen won convincingly against a much stronger opponent in only 19 moves. Many years since then have passed and nowadays it is not a big problem for Black anymore. }
2... d6
{ I like this move a lot better than  2...Nc6  after which White can play the tricky  3.d4  .  After 2...d6 it doesn't make sense for White to play d3-d4, because that would transpose to a main line of the Leningrad while being a full tempo down. }
3. e4 e5
{ The standard reaction, when White plays e2-e4, Black usually plays ...e7-e5. Because the white bishop is still on f1, Black doesn't take on e4 first. We would only do that if the bishop is on g2, so the bishop would be locked behind the e4-pawn. }
4. Nc3 Nc6
{ 4...Be7  is not great because Black doesn't take control over the square d4.  5.d4  fxe4  6.Nxe4  d5  ,  at least Black should have played ...Nf6 here, but even then White has a clear advantage.  7.Neg5  Black is in big trouble with the exposed king.  7...exd4  8.Bd3  Qd6  9.Nxd4  and White was winning in Svidler-Bu, Tbilisi 2017. Black's king is not safe and the pieces don't coordinate well. }
5. exf5 Nge7
{ A key move.  5...Bxf5  was played in the famous game between a young Magnus Carlsen and Dolmatov, which resulted in a crushing win for White.  6.d4  Nxd4  7.Nxd4  exd4  8.Qxd4  Nf6  9.Bc4  c6  10.Bg5  b5  11.Bb3  Be7  12.O-O-O  Qd7  13.Rhe1  Kd8  14.Rxe7  Qxe7  15.Qf4  Bd7  16.Ne4  d5  17.Nxf6  h6  18.Bh4  g5  19.Qd4  1-0 Carlsen-Dolmatov, Moscow 2004. }
6. d4 exd4 { I don't trust  6...Bxf5  . } 7. Nxd4 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Nxf5
{ Black is trying not to fall behind in development, which could be dangerous with the disappearance of the f- and e-pawns. }
9. Qg4 c6
{ The difference with the Carlsen-Dolmatov game is clear: the black knight is better positioned on f5 than on f6 and with ...c7-c6 and ...d6-d5 next, Black can take control over the light squares. }
10. Bd3 Qe7+
{ Maybe  10...g6  is also possible,  but I don't like to create weaknesses on the side where White is already attacking. White could try to attack g6 with h2-h4-h5 and it is not clear how to defend. }
11. Ne2 Qf7
{ This was the idea of ...Qe7+. Black is defending the knight without moving any pawns, has developed the queen and moved it away from a dark square where it could be attacked by Bg5. }
12. Bg5 h6
{ Now that the queen on f7 covers the g6-square, Black can allow this weakening pawn move to get rid of the bishop. }
13. Qe4+ Be7 14. Bxe7 d5
{ A nice intermediate move, Black is taking control of some central squares. }
15. Qb4
{ 15.Qe5  is also possible and after the queens are exchanged on e7, we have reached an equal endgame where Black can hope for some advantage by pushing the pawn majority on the queenside, while for White it will be harder to do this on the kingside because it could expose the king after short castling. }
15... Qxe7 16. Qc3 O-O
{ The position is equal and Black has no problems. Next, we can play ...Bd7 and ...Rae8, maybe move the queen to g5 although it is unlikely we will be able to create a real attack. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "English Setups − 1.Nf3 with 5.c4"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c4
{ We have transposed to an English opening that could also have started with 1.c4. Also, at any point, White can decide to play d2-d4 and transpose to a main line of the Leningrad System. }
5... O-O 6. Nc3 d6 7. d3
{ This was White's final chance to make it a 1.d4 opening. } 7... Nc6
{ In all these English lines I like the knight on c6. Placing the knight on a6 is less logical in these types of positions because after the knight moves to c5 there is a pawn on d3 preventing a future knight jump to e4. }
8. Rb1 a5
{ Black can also play without the inclusion of ...a7-a5 and a2-a3, but I feel that opening the a-file benefits Black. }
9. a3 Nh5
{ The pawn push b2-b4 is not working because the knight on c3 would be hanging, thus Black is preparing ...f5-f4. }
10. Bd2 f4 11. b4 axb4 12. axb4 Nd4
{ Making maximum use of the fact that, contrary to most English lines in these types of positions, the black e-pawn is still on e7. Black has an active position, the a8-rook has the open file, the c8-bishop can come to g4 followed by ...Qd7 or ...Qc8  (be careful not to drop the pawn on b7!)  and because Black's b- and c-pawns are still on their initial squares, it is much harder for White to create the typical English queenside play. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Leningrad Variation 7...c6 − Main Lines"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 7...c6 − 8.Qb3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6
{ The main line of the Leningrad System where my preference is to play with  7...c6  . I have also made a brief overview of why I think the main alternatives  7...Qe8  and  7...Nc6  are inferior.   The idea of playing ...c7-c6 is to take away the d5-square from White while, at the same time, it is also a useful waiting move. In many lines of the Leningrad System, Black needs to play ...c7-c6 eventually, but by playing it this early we can still adapt our plans based on the setup White chooses. }
8. Qb3 { This move became popular based on a great game by Korchnoi. } 8... Kh8
{ Stepping away from an annoying check with c4-c5. } 9. Re1
{ Preparing e2-e4. } 9... Na6
{ 9...Ne4  10.Qc2  Nxc3  11.bxc3  Nd7   11...e5  This direct central counter doesn't solve Black's problems.  12.e4  White tries to prove that Black has occupied the center too early with only the bishop on g7 that has left the 8th rank.  12...c5  13.dxe5  dxe5  14.exf5  Bxf5  15.Qe2  Nc6  16.Ng5  White has the more pleasant position, is ready to put a knight on e4 and with that, the bishop on g7 will go to sleep. Also, the pawn on c5 can become weak and a white rook could land on d6. Eventually, White won in Raessler-Rickert, ICCF email 2016.  12.e4  And White had a clear advantage in Galanov-Spitz, ICCF email 2012. Black doesn't have any active plans other than pushing ...e7-e5 which transposes to the line with 11...e5. }
10. e4
{ Usually, in the Leningrad System White will achieve an advantage if e2-e4 will get in before Black has the chance to play ...e7-e5 and ...f5-f4. }
10... fxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Rxe4 Bf5
{ 12...e5  13.Be3  Bf5  I analyzed the alternative   13...exd4  14.Bxd4  Nc5  but this is not great either.  15.Bxg7+  Kxg7  16.Qc3+  Qf6  17.Re7+  And White will exchange queens and have a much better endgame with the rook already on the 7th rank.  14.Rh4  The rook is quite annoying here, the black king doesn't feel safe on h8, but g8 is also not really an option with the queen on b3.  14...exd4  15.Nxd4  Nc5  16.Qd1  Qe7  17.Nxf5  Rxf5  18.b4  Ne6  19.Rc1  We have been following the game Konstantinov-Ringsborg, ICCF email 2016. White has a nice advantage with the pair of bishops and more space. }
13. Rh4 Qb6
{ Trying to exchange queens to reduce the pressure.   13...Bf6  I thought for a while that this would give Black an okay position.  14.Bh6  Qb6  15.Qc3  Qb4  16.Qc1  Bxh4  17.Nxh4  Kg8  I wondered why the engine gives a clear play for White...  18.Bxf8  Rxf8  19.b3  Nc7  20.Nxf5  Rxf5  21.Qe3  This is the reason, White's bishop is stronger than the knight and the pawn on e7 is weak. Although Black managed to make a draw in Ehrbar-Narusberg, ICCF email 2016, I would not recommend this position to anyone. }
14. Qe3 Kg8 15. Ng5 Bf6 16. Qe2 Nc7 17. Be3 d5
{ And White has a nice advantage again with the more active pieces and the weak pawn on e7 that is going nowhere. }
