[White "1. Leningrad Variation 7...c6 − Main Lines"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 7...c6 − 8.b4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6
{ The main line of the Leningrad System where my preference is to play with  7...c6  . I have also made a brief overview of why I think the main alternatives  7...Qe8  and  7...Nc6  are inferior.   The idea of playing ...c7-c6 is to take away the d5-square from White while, at the same time, it is also a useful waiting move. In many lines of the Leningrad System, Black needs to play ...c7-c6 eventually, but by playing it this early we can still adapt our plans based on the setup White chooses. }
8. b4 e5
{ This move is possible because the knight on c3 is not protected. In general Black wants to play this move as soon as possible to create further space for development.   8...Ne4  , some strong players like Vallejo Pons and Laznicka have played this move.  9.Bb2  d5   9...Be6  10.Nxe4  fxe4  11.Ng5  Bxc4  12.Qc2  Bd5  13.Bxe4  White can claim a clear advantage with his lead in development and control over the light squares.   9...a5  10.b5  a4  11.Rc1  Nxc3  12.Bxc3  cxb5  13.cxb5  Nd7  and now White could have increased his advantage by simply playing  14.Qd3  in Yuffa-Laznicka, Pardubice 2016.  10.Qb3  Be6  11.Nxe4  fxe4  12.Ng5  . I believe Black is struggling to equalize in this line. }
9. dxe5 dxe5 10. e4
{ White's idea is to take on f5 and put pressure on the e5- and f5-pawns. }
10... Qxd1
{ If Black immediately plays  10...f4  , White's  11.Qb3  will be annoying. }
11. Rxd1 f4
{ With or without queens, if we leave this pawn on f5, White will take on f5 and start putting pressure on the e5-pawn. If we ever play ...e5-e4, White will have great squares for the pieces on d4 and f4 and could potentially break down the center with f2-f3. }
12. a4
{ Now that the center is blocked White wants to advance on the queenside. }
12... a5
{ The right move, immediately stopping the white expansion on the queenside.   12...Bg4  is not precise.  13.Ba3  fxg3  14.hxg3  Nbd7   Losing is  14...Nxe4  15.Nxe4  Bxf3  16.Bxf3  Rxf3  17.b5  and the knight and rook will stay in the corner while White will put the  rook on d8.  15.a5  Rfd8  16.c5  and it seems to me that White can claim some advantage. When the time is right a5-a6 can be played, a rook can occupy d6, one of the knights can move to c4 and/or put the g2-bishop on c4 via f1. Black doesn't have a lot of counterplay and needs to react based on what White plays. }
13. b5 Bg4
{ Now Black threatens to play ...Nbd7-c5 and the pawn on a4 looks weak. White needs to take action. }
14. gxf4 exf4 15. Ba3 Re8 16. e5 Nfd7 17. Rac1 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Bxe5
{ White has sacrificed a pawn but is ahead in development, which yields just enough compensation. }
