{ There is no reason to wait any longer with this central push. } 11. dxe5 dxe5
12. e4 f4
{ We don't want to allow White to take on f5, because that can be followed by Re1 with serious pressure on the e5-pawn. And if that pawn moves forward to e4, there are some big holes on d4 and f4.   Taking  12...Nxe4  is not okay for Black.  13.Nxe4  fxe4  14.Ng5  Nc7  and now I think  15.Be3  is better than the game move  15.Bxe4  in Safarli-Kuzubov, Nakhchivan 2016.  White can always take back on e4 at a later stage, preferably with the knight.  It seems to me that White has a clear advantage, Black's isolated pawn on e5 blocks the bishop on g7, the queen is passive on e8 and it is not easy to generate counterplay. Meanwhile, White can double rooks on the d-file and/or put a knight on d6. }
13. gxf4
{ Taking the pawn on f4 always needs to be analyzed. Black's reaction is normally along the lines of a bishop to g4, a knight to h5 followed by ...Nf4, and sometimes a second knight on e6 for additional support. The idea is that this setup gives Black a dangerous initiative against the white king. }
13... Nc7 14. fxe5
{ Taking  14.Nxe5  is also an option, Black will play  14...Ne6  and ...Nh5 followed by taking the pawn on f4. }
14... Nh5 15. Rb1 Bg4 16. Ne1 Qxe5
{ With a gain of tempo because the knight on c3 hangs and Black is ready for ...Nf4. }
17. h3 Bxh3 18. Bxh3 Qxc3 19. Qxc3 Bxc3
{ Black has won back the invested material and the pieces are more active than White's. White will need to be very precise to maintain the balance. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Leningrad Variation 7...c6 − Main Lines"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 7...c6 − 8.Qc2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6
{ The main line of the Leningrad System where my preference is to play with  7...c6  . I have also made a brief overview of why I think the main alternatives  7...Qe8  and  7...Nc6  are inferior.   The idea of playing ...c7-c6 is to take away the d5-square from White while, at the same time, it is also a useful waiting move. In many lines of the Leningrad System, Black needs to play ...c7-c6 eventually, but by playing it this early we can still adapt our plans based on the setup White chooses. }
8. Qc2 Na6 9. a3
{ The move ...Nb4 is not really a threat, but White intends to generate play on the queenside with b2-b4. }
9... Qe8 10. b4 e5
{ There is no reason to wait any longer with this central push. } 11. dxe5 dxe5
12. e4 f4
{ We don't want to allow White to take on f5, because that can be followed by Re1 with serious pressure on the e5-pawn. And if that pawn moves forward to e4, there are some big holes on d4 and f4.   Taking  12...Nxe4  is not okay for Black.  13.Nxe4  fxe4  14.Ng5  Nc7  and now I think  15.Be3  is better than the game move  15.Bxe4  in Safarli-Kuzubov, Nakhchivan 2016.  White can always take back on e4 at a later stage, preferably with the knight.  It seems to me that White has a clear advantage, Black's isolated pawn on e5 blocks the bishop on g7, the queen is passive on e8 and it is not easy to generate counterplay. Meanwhile, White can double rooks on the d-file and/or put a knight on d6. }
13. Bb2 g5
{ The engine gives also this move as an option, but I don't see the point because on the next move it continues with ...Bg4 anyway, and then why would we want the pawn to be on g5? }
14. Rfe1
{ A powerful move, if Black now continues with ...g5-g4 and ...f4-f3, White will play Nh4 and Bf1 and Black has no attack while White has control over the light squares and can increase the pressure on the queenside.   Even taking the pawn is an option for White:  14.Nxg5  Qh5  15.h4  h6  16.Nf3  Bg4  17.Nh2  and maybe Black has sufficient compensation for the pawn, but it is not clear as White doesn't have any major weaknesses. }
14... Bg4 15. c5
{ In themain line that I recommend, the Black knight is on c7 and the pawn on g6, which I prefer over this position with a pawn on g5 that is hanging and a knight on a6 that is offside. }
15... Kh8 16. Rad1 Nc7 17. Nb1 Qh5
{ This should be the justification of playing ...g6-g5, the black queen can come to h5, and maybe this gives Black sufficient play to maintain the balance. }
