[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6
{ The main line of the Leningrad System where my preference is to play with  7...c6  . I have also made a brief overview of why I think the main alternatives  7...Qe8  and  7...Nc6  are inferior.   The idea of playing ...c7-c6 is to take away the d5-square from White while, at the same time, it is also a useful waiting move. In many lines of the Leningrad System, Black needs to play ...c7-c6 eventually, but by playing it this early we can still adapt our plans based on the setup White chooses. }
8. Qc2 Na6 9. b3 Nb4
{ This move has been played by two 2600 players but I failed to find equality for Black. }
10. Qd2 a5
{ I also analyzed a pawn sacrifice with  10...e5  11.dxe5  dxe5  12.Nxe5  Qa5  13.Nd3  Nxd3  14.exd3  and Black certainly has some play, but to me, it feels too much as a computer line and behind the board, I think it is easier to find good moves with White than with Black.  A sample line:  14...f4  15.d4  fxg3  16.hxg3  and now this would be ok if Black were not a pawn down, so he is taking some drastic measures in the search for compensation.  16...Ng4  17.f3  Nh6  18.Ne2  , White is trying to stabilize.  18...Qxd2  19.Bxd2  Nf5  , still playing actively.  20.Bc3  Ne3  21.Rf2  a5  and maybe Black has sufficient compensation, but it is still an extra pawn for White. }
11. Bb2 Ne4 12. Nxe4
{ 12.Qc1  was also a good option, both knights need to return to a6 and f6 at some point and the question is what Black has achieved then. We need to be careful that the a5-pawn doesn't become a weakness @@StartBracket@@for example with a bishop on c3 and a queen on d2@@EndBracket@@ and the break ...e7-e5 is not going to happen any time soon. }
12... fxe4 13. Ng5 d5
{ Whenever we consider this structure with Black with pawns on e4 and d5, Black needs to ask how quickly White can attack them with pawns on f3 and c4. Here the answer is found pretty quickly. }
14. a3 Na6 15. f3 h6 16. Nh3
{ And now Black is forced to give up the pawn on e4 because  16...Bf5  fails to  17.g4  . }
16... exf3 17. exf3 dxc4 18. bxc4
{ White's position looks a lot more natural than Black's with the pawn on e7 and the offside knight on a6. }
18... Nc5 19. Rad1 Nb3
{ Not sure the knight is effective here, but going back to d7 wasn't attractive either. }
20. Qe3 a4 21. Nf4
{ We have been following the game Cheparinov-Bartel, Dubai 2014 and although Black eventually won, this position is clearly better for White. Black has several weak pawns @@StartBracket@@g6, e7@@EndBracket@@ weak squares @@StartBracket@@e5 and e6@@EndBracket@@, and the knight is a bit unlucky on b3. }
