{ The main line of the Leningrad System where my preference is to play with  7...c6  . I have also made a brief overview of why I think the main alternatives  7...Qe8  and  7...Nc6  are inferior.   The idea of playing ...c7-c6 is to take away the d5-square from White while, at the same time, it is also a useful waiting move. In many lines of the Leningrad System, Black needs to play ...c7-c6 eventually, but by playing it this early we can still adapt our plans based on the setup White chooses. }
8. Qc2 Na6 9. b3 Kh8
{ Black is preparing a Stonewall setup with a bishop on g7, something that can work quite well, but here I don't trust it. }
10. Bb2 Nc7 11. Rae1 d5
{ The problem with this setup is that it can be passive for Black. Both sides have a nice square for their knights @@StartBracket@@e5 and e4@@EndBracket@@ but in addition, White has more space on the queenside and can easily expand further. Black cannot really too much on the kingside. }
12. Bc1 { Taking out Black's ideas with f5-f4. } 12... Be6 13. Na4
{ White begins the operations on the queenside. } 13... Ne4 14. Bf4 Ne8 15. Rd1
{ Protecting the pawn on d4 and preparing for a future knight retreat to e1, followed by f2-f3. }
15... Qa5 16. Be5 N8f6 17. Nb2
{ Black cannot take on  17...Qxa2  because of  18.Ra1  winning the queen. }
17... Rac8 18. c5
{ Firmly establishing a grip on the queenside, ready to push b3-b4-b5 when possible. }
18... b6 19. Nd3 bxc5 20. dxc5 Nd7
{ White's position seems more harmonious, natural moves can be played and there are no weaknesses either. }
21. b4 Qa3 22. Bxg7+ Kxg7
{ And now White could have claimed a large advantage in the game Romanov-Khairullin, St. Petersburg 2013 if he would have played the text move. }
23. Nd4 Bf7 24. f4 { White is clearly better. } *

