9... Nc7 10. b4 Be6 { Immediately hitting the weak c4-pawn. } 11. Nd2 Rc8 12.
Bb2 Qd7 13. Qd3 d5
{ Going for the light squares strategy that is so typical of the Stonewall setup. }
14. cxd5 cxd5 15. Rbc1 Ne4
{ The most natural square for the knight, putting pressure on White's queenside. }
16. Nf3 Qd6 { Hitting the weak b4-pawn. } 17. Nb5 Nxb5 18. Qxb5
{ We have been following the game Zhou-Nguyen, Ningbo 2011, and now I like the active text move. }
18... Rc4
{ I think Black can claim some advantage. These types of Stonewall positions are playable for Black if we have an active plan and here that is the case. White's b4-pawn is weak and that gives Black the chance to double rooks on the c-file. }
