{ This is the standard reaction we will see in many lines. Black gets a weak pawn on d6 but creates counterplay against White's pawn on c4.   8...Bd7  is too slow.  If Black doesn't want to play ...e7-e5, the attention can be switched to the queenside, for example with taking on d5 followed by ...b7-b5, but here this is taking a lot of time and White will create serious pressure with moves such as Re1 and e2-e4.  9.Re1  Na6  10.e4  .   White's plan to push e2-e4 is something we always need to be aware of as a Black player.  10...Nxe4  we don't want to allow e4-e5, so taking is the only option.  11.Nxe4  fxe4  12.Rxe4  Nc5  13.Re1  with a clear advantage for White.  The e7-pawn is weak and can be attacked by Bg5 while the knight can go to e6 via d4 and there is very little Black can do. }
9. dxe6
{ This is the main continuation. Both sides have a weak pawn, Black on d6, White on c4. If both sides can protect their pawns, Black will aim for ...d6-d5 in such a way that we can take back with pieces on d5 without ending up with an isolated pawn, which in this position would not be an asset. }
9... Bxe6 10. b3
{ This move looks so innocent, but before you know it, we might lose the d6-pawn. }
10... Na6
{ With the idea that after  11.Ba3  we will have  11...Nc5  .  White then needs to play Qd2 and bring a rook to d1 to hit d6 again. }
11. Bb2 { A modest move. } 11... Qe7
{ This is a sample line to illustrate how to play with Black if White makes suboptimal moves. }
12. Rc1 { Not clear why the rook would be good on c1. } 12... Rad8 13. Nd4 Bc8
{ If possible, Black wants to keep the bishop. } 14. a3 Ng4 15. Nf3
{ Again a strange move by White. } 15... f4
{ White has played suboptimally and Black becomes active. Most of the time we are happy if we can play ...f5-f4. }
16. Rc2 Bf5 17. Rd2 { And now White is already tactically getting tricked. }
17... fxg3 18. hxg3 Ne3 19. fxe3 Bxc3 20. Bxc3 Qxe3+ 21. Kh2 Qxc3
{ Here White can still fight, but the next move is a losing one. } 22. Rxd6 Bc2
23. Qd4 Qxd4 24. Rxd4 Bxb3
{ Black won quickly in Miedema-Nijboer, Dieren 2008. White's pawn structure has too many weaknesses with the pawns on a3, c4, and e2 and therefore Black is likely  (even with best play from White)  to end up with one or more dangerous passed pawns on the queenside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Leningrad Variation 7...c6 − Main Lines"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 7...c6 − 8.d5 e5 9.dxe6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6
{ The main line of the Leningrad System where my preference is to play with  7...c6  . I have also made a brief overview of why I think the main alternatives  7...Qe8  and  7...Nc6  are inferior.   The idea of playing ...c7-c6 is to take away the d5-square from White while, at the same time, it is also a useful waiting move. In many lines of the Leningrad System, Black needs to play ...c7-c6 eventually, but by playing it this early we can still adapt our plans based on the setup White chooses. }
8. d5
{ This is the old main line. White grabs some space, forcing Black to play ...e7-e5 soon because otherwise, the position would be too cramped. However, after ...e7-e5 White will take on e6 and try to prove that the pawn on d6 is weak. }
8... e5
{ This is the standard reaction we will see in many lines. Black gets a weak pawn on d6 but creates counterplay against White's pawn on c4.   8...Bd7  is too slow.  If Black doesn't want to play ...e7-e5, the attention can be switched to the queenside, for example with taking on d5 followed by ...b7-b5, but here this is taking a lot of time and White will create serious pressure with moves such as Re1 and e2-e4.  9.Re1  Na6  10.e4  .   White's plan to push e2-e4 is something we always need to be aware of as a Black player.  10...Nxe4  we don't want to allow e4-e5, so taking is the only option.  11.Nxe4  fxe4  12.Rxe4  Nc5  13.Re1  with a clear advantage for White.  The e7-pawn is weak and can be attacked by Bg5 while the knight can go to e6 via d4 and there is very little Black can do. }
9. dxe6
{ This is the main continuation. Both sides have a weak pawn, Black on d6, White on c4. If both sides can protect their pawns, Black will aim for ...d6-d5 in such a way that we can take back with pieces on d5 without ending up with an isolated pawn, which in this position would not be an asset. }
9... Bxe6 10. b3
{ This move looks so innocent, but before you know it, we might lose the d6-pawn. }
10... Na6
{ With the idea that after  11.Ba3  we will have  11...Nc5  .  White then needs to play Qd2 and bring a rook to d1 to hit d6 again. }
11. Bb2 { A modest move. } 11... Qe7 12. Ng5 Bd7 13. Qc2
{ And now an example of how not to play with Black. The moves are natural, but the problem is that Black doesn't become active. In the Leningrad System, we need to be careful not to get in a position of sitting and waiting because often in the long-term, the weaknesses of the d6-pawn and e6-square begin to count. }
13... Rad8 14. Rad1 Rfe8
{ 14...Nh5  with the idea of becoming active  with ...f5-f4 just falls short of one tempo.  White will play  15.Qd2  to protect the knight on g5 and attack the pawn on d6 and next Nh3 will follow and Black can forget about ...f5-f4. }
15. e3 Bc8 16. Rfe1 Nc5
{ I have played these types of positions myself with Black and you think you have done everything right, but is hard to decide how to continue. Often we put a knight on e4, exchange some pieces, and are left with a weak pawn on d6. The only thing Black can hope for is that a well-timed ...d6-d5 can solve that weakness. }
17. b4 Ne6
{ Black is lacking space and would like to exchange a pair of knights.   After  17...Nce4  18.Ncxe4  Nxe4  19.Nxe4  fxe4  20.Bxg7  Kxg7  we have one of those positions where White has all the chances: the pawns on e4 and d6 are weak, White can double on the d-file and/or expand on the queenside. I think in a practical game it is difficult to hold with Black. }
18. Nf3 a6 19. a3 Qf7 20. Na4 { Starting operations on the queenside. } 20...
Qc7 21. Qb3 Ng4 22. h3 Ne5 { Black wants to exchange pieces. } 23. Nxe5 dxe5
{ The weak d-pawn is solved but Black's problems are not over, there is a potential hole on d6. }
24. c5 { Fixing the queenside. } 24... Qf7 25. Nb6 Nf8
{ Again Black hopes to reduce the pressure by exchanging pieces. } 26. Qxf7+
Kxf7 27. Nc4 Rxd1 28. Rxd1
{ Maybe this position is not directly winning for White but it is highly unpleasant and eventually, Berczes won against Pavasovic in Hungary 2006. }
*

