{ This is the main continuation. Both sides have a weak pawn, Black on d6, White on c4. If both sides can protect their pawns, Black will aim for ...d6-d5 in such a way that we can take back with pieces on d5 without ending up with an isolated pawn, which in this position would not be an asset. }
9... Bxe6 10. b3
{ This move looks so innocent, but before you know it, we might lose the d6-pawn. }
10... Na6
{ With the idea that after  11.Ba3  we will have  11...Nc5  .  White then needs to play Qd2 and bring a rook to d1 to hit d6 again. }
11. Ng5 Bc8 12. Qd2 { Preparing to attack d6 with Rd1. } 12... h6
{ I first analyzed  12...Nc5  but this move is slightly dubious.  13.Bb2  h6  .  Black wants to drive that knight away so that we don't need to worry about the c6-square or some check followed by Nf7. The disadvantage is that the pawn on g6 becomes weak.    14.Nf3  Qe7  , we  have to make space for ...Rd8 to protect the d6-pawn.  15.Rad1  Rd8  16.Nh4  g5  and now the pawn on f5 becomes weak.  17.Nf3  a5  18.e3  Nfe4  19.Qc2  Bd7  . I think Black is in some danger.  Both pawns, d6 and f5, are weak.  White has a plan to drive the knight on c5 away with a2-a3 and b3-b4. The other plan is to start exchanging pieces. The less pieces are on the board, the more Black will feel the weaknesses. Moves like Nb1 or Ne2 can be considered too. }
13. Nf3 d5 { Using the fact that b2-b3 has weakened the diagonal a1-g7. } 14.
cxd5 { This capture is a mistake. } 14... Ne4 15. Nxe4 fxe4
{ Black is winning material because of the rook on a1. } 16. Nd4 Qxd5 17. e3
{ Also after  17.Bb2  Black wins with  17...c5  . } 17... c5 18. Nb5 Qxd2 19.
Bxd2 Bxa1 20. Rxa1 Bf5 { Black is a healthy exchange up. } *

