{ I first analyzed  12...Nc5  but this move is slightly dubious.  13.Bb2  h6  .  Black wants to drive that knight away so that we don't need to worry about the c6-square or some check followed by Nf7. The disadvantage is that the pawn on g6 becomes weak.    14.Nf3  Qe7  , we  have to make space for ...Rd8 to protect the d6-pawn.  15.Rad1  Rd8  16.Nh4  g5  and now the pawn on f5 becomes weak.  17.Nf3  a5  18.e3  Nfe4  19.Qc2  Bd7  . I think Black is in some danger.  Both pawns, d6 and f5, are weak.  White has a plan to drive the knight on c5 away with a2-a3 and b3-b4. The other plan is to start exchanging pieces. The less pieces are on the board, the more Black will feel the weaknesses. Moves like Nb1 or Ne2 can be considered too. }
13. Nf3 d5 { Using the fact that b2-b3 has weakened the diagonal a1-g7. } 14.
Ba3
{ If the bishop goes to b2, Black will take on c4 and we might already be a bit better. }
14... Ne4
{ If Black has to move the rook, White will take on d5, the difference being that the rook on a1 is now defended by the other rook.   14...Re8  15.cxd5  Nxd5  16.Nxd5  Bxa1  17.Rxa1  Qxd5  18.Qxh6  , the start of a devastating attack over the dark squares.  18...Qf7  19.Bb2  Qh7  20.Qf4  and White has a winning advantage.  A combination of Ng5 and Qd4/Qc4+ will quickly decide. }
15. Nxe4 fxe4
{ Both the knight on f3 and the rook on a1 are under attack, while on the black side only the rook on f8 is hanging. }
16. Bxf8 Bxa1 17. Bxh6
{ If White plays  17.Qxh6  , Black wins after  17...Qxf8  . } 17... exf3 18.
Bxf3 Bf6 { In some lines, Bg5 could be unpleasant. } 19. cxd5 cxd5 20. Bxd5+
Kh7
{ One of those positions where the engine says it is equal but I think in practice I would always choose Black. Surely it must be easier to play with an extra piece? White will try to advance the f- and e-pawns while Black wants to complete development as soon as possible by attacking White's pieces @@StartBracket@@...Nc7, ...Bh3@@EndBracket@@ and exchange pieces. }
