{ This move could be an alternative but Black ends up in a passive position. I am still giving this line because the position is very typical for this 7...c6 line and it will help understanding why we want to avoid this with Black. }
12. Bf4 Rad8 13. Rad1 { White attacks the d6-pawn first. } 13... Ng4
{ Black can try a plan with  13...Nh5  and after the bishop drops back to c1,  14.Bc1  , play  14...f4  . However,  these plans with ...f5-f4 normally only work if they are the start of a kingside attack. Here Black loses the pair of bishops and the knight on a6 is far away from White's king, so the plan with ...f5-f4 is not effective. }
14. Nxe6 Qxe6 15. b3 Nc5 16. Qc2 Rfe8
{ Black wants to ensure that White cannot go e2-e4 in these types of positions. It is even better if we can occupy the e4-square with a black knight because it limits the power of the g2-bishop and thus compensates for White's bishop pair. }
17. Bg5 Rd7 18. Bc1 Nf6 { Black wants to keep control over the e4-square. } 19.
Bb2 Nfe4 20. Nxe4 Nxe4 21. Bxg7 Kxg7 22. Rd4
{ Again an important typical position: If Black does nothing, for example, shuffling the rooks, White will increase the advantage by putting pressure on d6, creating weaknesses on the kingside with h4-h5, and keeping the queenside break c4-c5 in reserve.  Normally we want to avoid these positions. Here Black is just in time to play the liberating d6-d5 because after the next move White needs to defend the pawn on e2. }
22... Nf6 23. e3 d5 { A crucial move to get rid of the d6-weakness. } 24. cxd5
Nxd5 25. Bxd5 Rxd5 26. Rxd5 Qxd5 27. Rd1 Qe5
{ Even this position is still better for White. Black has back-rank problems, a white rook is always threatening to come to d7 or d8 and after a rook swap, Black may lose the pawn on a7. Meanwhile, White can also put a rook on d4 and create new weaknesses with h4-h5 or with b3-b4, a2-a4 and then b4-b5.  In the game Anastasian-Gonzalez Acosta, Linares 2001, Black managed to escape with a draw, but we really want to avoid having to defend for such a long time. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Leningrad Variation 7...c6 − Main Lines"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 7...c6 − 8.d5 e5 9.dxe6 #21"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6
{ The main line of the Leningrad System where my preference is to play with  7...c6  . I have also made a brief overview of why I think the main alternatives  7...Qe8  and  7...Nc6  are inferior.   The idea of playing ...c7-c6 is to take away the d5-square from White while, at the same time, it is also a useful waiting move. In many lines of the Leningrad System, Black needs to play ...c7-c6 eventually, but by playing it this early we can still adapt our plans based on the setup White chooses. }
8. d5
{ This is the old main line. White grabs some space, forcing Black to play ...e7-e5 soon because otherwise, the position would be too cramped. However, after ...e7-e5 White will take on e6 and try to prove that the pawn on d6 is weak. }
8... e5
{ This is the standard reaction we will see in many lines. Black gets a weak pawn on d6 but creates counterplay against White's pawn on c4.   8...Bd7  is too slow.  If Black doesn't want to play ...e7-e5, the attention can be switched to the queenside, for example with taking on d5 followed by ...b7-b5, but here this is taking a lot of time and White will create serious pressure with moves such as Re1 and e2-e4.  9.Re1  Na6  10.e4  .   White's plan to push e2-e4 is something we always need to be aware of as a Black player.  10...Nxe4  we don't want to allow e4-e5, so taking is the only option.  11.Nxe4  fxe4  12.Rxe4  Nc5  13.Re1  with a clear advantage for White.  The e7-pawn is weak and can be attacked by Bg5 while the knight can go to e6 via d4 and there is very little Black can do. }
9. dxe6
{ This is the main continuation. Both sides have a weak pawn, Black on d6, White on c4. If both sides can protect their pawns, Black will aim for ...d6-d5 in such a way that we can take back with pieces on d5 without ending up with an isolated pawn, which in this position would not be an asset. }
9... Bxe6 10. Qd3
{ One of the main ways of defending the pawn on c4, hoping to put a rook on d1 and a bishop on f4 to win the d6-pawn. }
10... Na6 11. Ng5
{ White is trying to disrupt Black's piece coordination, but it is only temporary. }
11... Bc8 12. Rd1
{ Of course, we have to look at what happens if White immediately goes after the pawn on d6. }
12... h6 13. Nf3 Re8
{ The idea of this move is to ensure the bishop can come to e6 to attack the pawn on c4. }
14. Qxd6 Qxd6 15. Rxd6 Be6
{ It turns out that White cannot really defend the c4-pawn. } 16. Bf4
{ Defending with  16.b3  fails to  16...Ne4  and Black wins material while defending with @@StartFEN@@r3r1k1/pp4b1/n1pRbnpp/5p2/2P5/2N2NP1/PP2PPBP/R1B3K1 w - - 1 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Nd2  is not an option because of  16...Bf8  and the rook has nowhere to go. }
16... Nc5
{ If Black takes immediately, we may end up in slight trouble.  16...Bxc4  17.Ne5  Bf7  18.Nxc6  exchanging two minor pieces for a rook and two pawns. Materially speaking this means White is a pawn up in the end. Let's see:  18...bxc6  19.Bxc6  Nc5  20.Bxa8  Rxa8  21.Rad1  and although positions with unequal material are always hard to assess, it does feel like White has the upper hand.   White controls the d-file, can gain space with b2-b4, and create a passed pawn on the queenside with the help of the pawn on a2 and Black needs to be careful not to lose the a7-pawn. On the other hand, it is not so easy to see how Black can attack White, so I clearly prefer White here. }
17. Rad1
{ If White tries to transpose to the line in the previous note with the text move, Black has a good response in return. }
17... Nfe4 18. Nxe4 Nxe4 19. R6d3 Bxc4
{ Black has the advantage: the pawns on e2 and b2 are weak and if that is not enough we can also gain space with g6-g5. }
*

