9... Bxe6 10. Qd3
{ One of the main ways of defending the pawn on c4, hoping to put a rook on d1 and a bishop on f4 to win the d6-pawn. }
10... Na6 11. Ng5
{ White is trying to disrupt Black's piece coordination, but it is only temporary. }
11... Bc8 12. Bf4 Nh5
{ Whenever White has a bishop on f4, ...Nh5 comes into consideration, especially now with the white knight on g5. White runs the chance of becoming over-extended. }
13. Qxd6
{ We cannot always just sacrifice the pawn on d6 in the Leningrad System, but in this specific position Black has sufficient compensation. If we are trying to work out behind the board whether Black has enough or not, here are some guiding principles.  Typically Black wants to put pressure on the c4-pawn and ensure that the bishops on g7 and e6 have open lines and that White has no direct threats. Here this is all the case and Black also obtains the bishop pair. }
13... Nxf4 14. Qxf4
{ Black should not be afraid to play these types of positions: no weaknesses, great pair of bishops and the chance to push White back is present too. }
14... h6 15. Nf3 g5 16. Qc1 Be6
{ Three moves with tempo, every time attacking something. } 17. Nd2 Qa5 18. Qc2
Rad8
{ This position was reached in the game Jorczik-Piorun, Germany 2015, that Black eventually won. In the current position, Black has sufficient compensation for the pawn deficit, but the main problem is that it is difficult to play with White. Often Black loses a pawn but we are still better because of the pair of bishops. }
