[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Leningrad Variation − Sidelines"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 6.Nbd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. Nbd2
{ This move is rarely seen at the top level. The exception is Gelfand who used it at least three times, twice in a rapid game and once in a blitz game. White's idea is to push for e2-e4. }
6... d6 { Black uses the standard plan of playing for ...e7-e5. } 7. Re1 Nc6 8.
e4 e5
{ Although in practice more players take on e4 here with Black, I like this central push. For now, we keep the tension. }
9. dxe5 { White wants to blow up the center and take a pawn on e5. } 9... dxe5
10. exf5 gxf5
{ I don't like to take with the bishop here. White will not take immediately on e5 but just wait, strengthening the position since the e5-pawn will eventually fall. }
11. Nxe5
{ White takes the pawn, but it involves an exchange sacrifice. If White doesn't take on e5, Black will play ...e5-e4 with a fine position. }
11... Nxe5 12. Rxe5 Ne4 { Now the white rook on e5 is lost. } 13. Bxe4 Bxe5 14.
Bd3 Bg7
{ White has a pawn for the exchange but no concrete threats and both the d- and e-files are open for Black's rooks. Black may play ...Qf6 so it can help in defending the king and then ...Be6 and ...Rad8. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Leningrad Variation − Sidelines"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 6.Nbd2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. Nbd2
{ This move is rarely seen at the top level. The exception is Gelfand who used it at least three times, twice in a rapid game and once in a blitz game. White's idea is to push for e2-e4. }
6... d6 { Black uses the standard plan of playing for ...e7-e5. } 7. Re1 Nc6 8.
e4 e5
{ Although in practice more players take on e4 here with Black, I like this central push. For now, we keep the tension. }
9. c3
{ Black was threatening to take on d4. White is not just defending but is also opening the road for the queen to check from b3. }
9... fxe4
{ This move is much stronger than f5-f4, which is a standard reaction in other positions where the white knight is on c3. From d2 it does a much better job in defending the knight on f3 and it is harder for Black to create an attack. Taking on e4 ensures Black gets the typical active Leningrad type of play. }
10. Qb3+ Kh8
{ The move ...d6-d5 is also an option but it creates unnecessary complications because White can choose to take on e4 or e5 and eventually the black king will need to move to h8 anyway. }
11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Rxe4 d5
{ Black is threatening to build a strong center by playing ...e5-e4 on the next move so White has to play actively here. }
13. Rh4 e4 14. Ng5
{ White is going for the attack, but Black can defend easily. } 14... h5 15.
Rf4 Bf5
{ The rook on f4 has hardly any squares left. Black could not take the knight on g5 with the queen because White had Rxf8+ and the queen is lost on g5. }
16. Qxb7 { The only move by White to make it difficult for Black. } 16... Qxg5
{ Black can also first play  16...Na5  and then take on g5, it doesn't make a big difference. }
17. Qxc6 Qd8
{ Black simply defends the pawns on d5 and c7 and has sufficient compensation for the pawn deficit due to the poor position of the white rook on f4. It is more than likely that White will need to take on f5 with the rook @@StartBracket@@Black's next moves could be ...g6-g5 or ...Kh7 followed by ...Bh6@@EndBracket@@, sacrificing an exchange. White probably has some compensation but Black doesn't need to worry. }
