{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. Nbd2
{ This move is rarely seen at the top level. The exception is Gelfand who used it at least three times, twice in a rapid game and once in a blitz game. White's idea is to push for e2-e4. }
6... d6 { Black uses the standard plan of playing for ...e7-e5. } 7. b3 c6
{ Black has alternatives but is trying to be consistent with the rest of the repertoire. }
8. Bb2 Ne4
{ I think this is Black's best option, It is not easy to get ...e7-e5 in, and because White has not played d4-d5 Black can also not play the system with ...e7-e5, dxe6, ...Bxe6. So what to do with Black? Well, White would like to push e2-e4 either on the next move or after some preparation, so it seems a good idea to stop it. }
9. c4
{ 9.Nxe4  is not dangerous for Black.  9...fxe4  10.Ng5  d5  .  Black is OK here and can continue with ...Bf5, ...Nd7 and hope to get ...e7-e5 in one day. }
9... d5
{ Black changes to a Leningrad-Stonewall setup. In those systems, White normally plays on the queenside but here it is hard to generate anything because the bishop on b2 and the pawn on b3 block everything. }
10. Ne5 a5
{ Always a good idea to control the b4-square and to have the option to generate play with ...a5-a4. }
11. Rc1 a4 12. cxd5 a3
{ It is not a  must to play this, but why not play ...a3 immediately considering White's bishop on a1 will be quite passive? }
13. Ba1 cxd5
{ Taking back with the queen looks ugly and will possibly result in losing a pawn on e4 after Qc2. }
14. Nd3 e6
{ This seems to be more precise than ...Be6, the bishop would be a bit passive there. }
15. Nf3 Bd7 { Black wants to move the bishop to b5, which is a good square. }
16. Nfe5 Bb5 17. Re1 Nd7
{ Black has equalized, has no weaknesses, and all the pieces are active. Next, we can either exchange on e5 or play ...Rc8 followed by ...Qe7. }
*

