[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6 8. Re1
{ A sharp move, with the idea to play e2-e4 as soon as possible. } 8... Ne4
{ I believe this is the only sound option for Black. } 9. Qc2 Nxc3
{ Of course, taking with the queen is a valid option. } 10. Qxc3 Nd7
{ Black wants to push ...e7-e5 as soon as possible. } 11. e4 fxe4
{ There is no direct refutation if Black doesn't take on e4 and immediately plays ...e7-e5, but the chances are high that the pawns on f5 and e5 become weak. }
12. Rxe4 e5 13. Bg5 Nf6
{ 13...Qc7  is not good.  14.Qa3  Nf6  15.Re2  h6  16.Bxf6  Bxf6  17.c5  White keeps increasing the pressure on the center.  17...exd4  18.cxd6  Qb6  19.Rae1  Bf5  and I thought Black is okay until I saw the engine indicated the following:  20.Re7  Bxe7  21.dxe7  Rfe8  22.Qd6  c5  23.Qe5  and Black can resign,  a check on d5 with the bishop will be deadly.    23...Rac8  24.Nh4  White wins. The bishop on  f5  cannot be defended, if it goes to e6,  24...Be6  25.Nxg6  follows and on @@StartFEN@@2r1r1k1/pp2P3/1q4pp/2p1Qb2/3p3N/6P1/PP3PBP/4R1K1 b - - 3 24@@EndFEN@@  24...Bd7  the bishop is lost after  25.Qd5+  . And if Black does nothing about the bishop, White will play @@StartFEN@@2r1r1k1/pp2P3/1q4pp/2p1Qb2/3p3N/6P1/PP3PBP/4R1K1 w - - 3 25@@EndFEN@@  25.Bd5+  and  then Nxf5 and after the rook from e1 joins on e6, mate will follow. }
14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. dxe5 dxe5
{ Black has a powerful pair of bishops and White has the wrong piece on e4 to block the e-pawn. If there would be a knight on e4, White would probably have a large advantage. }
16. g4
{ An aggressive move but otherwise Black plays ...Bf5. White decides to win the e5-pawn by advancing the g-pawn. }
16... c5 { Getting ready for ...Bd7-c6. } 17. g5 Qd8 18. Nxe5 Qxg5
{ A sharp position in which Black has excellent chances with the bishop pair and a safer king. }
