[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6 8. Re1
{ A sharp move, with the idea to play e2-e4 as soon as possible. } 8... Ne4
{ I believe this is the only sound option for Black. } 9. Qc2 Nxc3 10. bxc3
{ This is White's most critical attempt: strengthening the center, potentially placing a rook on b1, and getting ready to hit with e2-e4. }
10... e5 11. Bg5 Qc7 12. c5
{ White’s usual way of disrupting Black’s center but Black is in time to push the e-pawn. }
12... e4 13. cxd6 Qxd6 14. Nd2
{ White has now multiple ways to put pressure on Black’s position  (e.g. f2-f3, Nc4-e5)  so Black needs to play precisely. }
14... h6 15. Bf4 Qe7 16. Nc4
{ Threatening to come to d6 with the bishop or knight. } 16... Rd8 17. f3
{ 17.g4  White wants to create weaknesses in Black’s kingside.  17...c5  18.gxf5  gxf5  19.d5  . A sharp pawn sacrifice that Black can better not accept because of the lack of development. After  19...Rxd5  White has two promising moves,  20.Ne3  and  20.f3  .  Therefore, @@StartFEN@@rnbr2k1/pp2q1b1/7p/2pP1p2/2N1pB2/2P5/P1Q1PPBP/R3R1K1 b - - 0 19@@EndFEN@@  19...Nd7  should be played.  20.Bc7  Re8  21.Rad1  Nf6  and Black is simply putting the pieces on active squares.  22.Bd6  Qd8  23.Bg3  Rf8  . Black  has overcome the opening problems. The resulting position is quite complex but Black can aim for plans with ...Nh5 followed by ...f5-f4. }
17... Be6 18. Ne5 Bxe5
{ It may look strange to give up the g7-bishop, but Black gains a few tempi, and we are left with only good pieces. }
19. Bxe5 Nd7 20. Bf4 g5 { It is important to push White back. } 21. Bc1 exf3
22. exf3 Re8
{ Black has sufficient counterplay. We can aim to get a knight to c4 and the bishop to d5 after for example ...Qf7, with good control over the central squares. }
