[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6 8. Re1
{ A sharp move, with the idea to play e2-e4 as soon as possible. } 8... Ne4
{ I believe this is the only sound option for Black. } 9. Qc2 Nxc3 10. bxc3
{ This is White's most critical attempt: strengthening the center, potentially placing a rook on b1, and getting ready to hit with e2-e4. }
10... e5 11. e4 fxe4
{ 11...f4  would be the normal reaction in the Leningrad System after  White has played e2-e4. However, there is an important rule to remember: ...f5-f4 is often a good move after White has taken on e5 already. If that is not the case yet, Black needs to assess the implications of c4-c5 before deciding to play ...f5-f4. The idea of c4-c5 is that with the pawns on d4 and c5 White is trying to destroy Black's center and take over the central power.  Here we have a position where it is clear that ...f5-f4 results in a large advantage for White.  12.c5  Bg4  .  Taking on g3 doesn't reduce the pressure on the pawns on d6 and e5.  13.gxf4  Bxf3  14.Bxf3  dxc5  .   If Black takes back on f4,  14...exf4  White will play  15.cxd6  with a large advantage because of the  pawns on d4 and e4. Similarly, if Black takes on d4  @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pp4bp/2pp2p1/2P1p3/3PPP2/2P2B2/P1Q2P1P/R1B1R1K1 b - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...exd4  White doesn't take back on d4 but first takes  15.cxd6  and after  15...Qxd6  White has  16.Qb3+  followed by e4-e5 and cxd4, taking away all the central squares from Black.  15.dxe5  and White is much  better, Qb3+ is a threat, the pawn on c5 is weak, and because of the white pawn on e5 both the bishop on g7 and the knight on b8 struggle to become active. }
12. Bg5
{ This move is a sharp continuation but I believe that there are several ways for Black to equalize. }
12... Qc7
{ Putting the queen on c7 with the idea to already defend both e5 and d6 is also fine for Black. }
13. Qxe4 h6
{ We don't ever want to allow White to play for tricks of c4-c5 in combination with Be7 after Black plays ...Nd7, so first the bishop needs to be chased away from g5. }
14. Bc1 Bf5 15. Qe2 Nd7
{ Black is ready for ...Rae8, so White needs to be fast. } 16. c5 dxc5
{ I think  16...Rae8  might also be OK for Black, but it involves taking more risk without any upside. }
17. Nxe5 Rae8 { Simple chess, just pin the queen and the rook on e1. } 18. f4
cxd4 19. cxd4 c5 { Breaking down the defenses of the knight on e5. } 20. Ba3
Qa5
{ Attacking the bishop and keeping an eye on the e5-knight over the fifth rank. }
21. Qc4+ Kh7 22. Bxc5 Nxc5 { The start of a liquidation sequence. } 23. dxc5 b6
{ If White now takes  24.cxb6  , Black takes back with check  24...Qxb6+  followed by ...Re7, simply preparing ...Rfe8 and there is no advantage for White. }
24. c6 Bxe5 25. fxe5 Rxe5
{ Black has full control over the c8-square and is likely to exchange queens on c5. After that, Black can use the rooks, bishop, and the king to start attacking the c-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Leningrad Variation − Sidelines"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 7...c6 − 8.Re1 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6 8. Re1
{ A sharp move, with the idea to play e2-e4 as soon as possible. } 8... Ne4
{ I believe this is the only sound option for Black. } 9. Qc2 Nxc3 10. bxc3
{ This is White's most critical attempt: strengthening the center, potentially placing a rook on b1, and getting ready to hit with e2-e4. }
10... e5 11. e4 fxe4
{ 11...f4  would be the normal reaction in the Leningrad System after  White has played e2-e4. However, there is an important rule to remember: ...f5-f4 is often a good move after White has taken on e5 already. If that is not the case yet, Black needs to assess the implications of c4-c5 before deciding to play ...f5-f4. The idea of c4-c5 is that with the pawns on d4 and c5 White is trying to destroy Black's center and take over the central power.  Here we have a position where it is clear that ...f5-f4 results in a large advantage for White.  12.c5  Bg4  .  Taking on g3 doesn't reduce the pressure on the pawns on d6 and e5.  13.gxf4  Bxf3  14.Bxf3  dxc5  .   If Black takes back on f4,  14...exf4  White will play  15.cxd6  with a large advantage because of the  pawns on d4 and e4. Similarly, if Black takes on d4  @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pp4bp/2pp2p1/2P1p3/3PPP2/2P2B2/P1Q2P1P/R1B1R1K1 b - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...exd4  White doesn't take back on d4 but first takes  15.cxd6  and after  15...Qxd6  White has  16.Qb3+  followed by e4-e5 and cxd4, taking away all the central squares from Black.  15.dxe5  and White is much  better, Qb3+ is a threat, the pawn on c5 is weak, and because of the white pawn on e5 both the bishop on g7 and the knight on b8 struggle to become active. }
12. Qxe4 Bf5 13. Qe2
{ In this position I give a main recommendation and a second option. } 13...
Nd7 { The main line, defending the pawn on e5. } 14. h3
{ White is planning to chase away the bishop with g3-g4. } 14... e4
{ A pawn sacrifice as we will soon find out. } 15. Ng5 Nf6 16. g4 Bd7 17. Nxe4
{ Black has sacrificed a pawn but in exchange White's king is in danger. }
17... Nxe4 18. Bxe4
{ Forced because taking with the queen  18.Qxe4  loses to  18...Re8  . } 18...
Qh4
{ Suddenly the h3-pawn is weak and after almost any move, Black will continue with ...h7-h5. }
19. Qf1 h5 20. Qg2
{ White could also have taken on h5, but Black first takes on h3 and then takes back on h5 and the result is an equal position. }
20... hxg4 21. hxg4 Bxg4
{ Black has won back the pawn and the position is about equal. It is a bit dangerous for White to take  22.Bxg6  since Black will play  22...Rf6  followed by ...Raf8 and the kingside initiative is becoming serious. }
*

