1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6 8. Bg5 { White's idea is to exchange on f6 and push e2-e4. } 8... h6
{ A loss of tempo playing in White's hands, who is happy to exchange on f6. }
9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. e4 fxe4 11. Nxe4 Bg7 12. Nh4 Qe8 13. f4
{ It becomes clear that Black has a backward pawn on e7 which is not mobile and also the pawn on g6 is weak. }
13... Na6 14. Kh1 Nc7 15. Qd3 Qf7 16. Rae1
{ White has obtained a clear advantage. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Leningrad Variation − Sidelines"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 7...c6 − 8.Bg5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6 8. Bg5 { White's idea is to exchange on f6 and push e2-e4. } 8... Ne4
{ Immediately countering White's idea of taking on f6 and pushing e2-e4. } 9.
Nxe4 fxe4 10. Nd2 Bxd4
{ I also analyzed  10...d5  but it appears White will come out on top after the complications.  11.Qb3  ,  whenever Black plays a setup with a pawn on e4 and another one on d5, White will try to undermine these pawns and take control of the light squares by putting pressure on d5 and playing f2-f3.    11...h6  12.Be3  Kh7  .  Stepping away from the queen on b3 and protecting the pawn on h6 so, if given the chance, Black can take on d4 with the bishop.  13.cxd5  cxd5  14.f3  exf3  15.Nxf3  Nc6  . Black is one to two tempi short of equalizing while White is ahead in development and can start concrete actions.   16.Ne5  Rxf1+  17.Rxf1  Nxe5  18.dxe5  Be6  .  Taking on e5 with the bishop will result in a lost endgame for Black after Rf7+ followed by Qxd5.  19.Qxb7  and I don't see how Black can equalize. White is a pawn up and the pawns on e7, d5 and a7 are weak. }
11. Qc2 e3
{ Giving White a useless extra pawn on e3.   Trying to defend the pawn with  11...d5  would end up in a bad position for Black after  12.Rad1  followed by cxd5. There is a pin on the d-file to the queen on d8 and White threatens to play Nxe4, because after ...dxe4 there is always Qc4+, picking up the bishop on d4. }
12. fxe3 Bg7 13. Rxf8+ Qxf8
{ We want to take back with the queen and not with the bishop or king because Black would lose a tempo to return them to g7/g8. After ...Qxf8 it may seem as we also lose a tempo after Rf1, but the difference is that White is playing Rf1 while after taking with king or bishop on f8, White can make many other useful moves as Rf1 is not forced. }
14. Rf1 Qd8
{ Black is behind in development and needs to make some precise moves to maintain the balance. The queen would be quite passive on e8. }
15. Qe4 Bf5
{ A temporary pawn sacrifice to develop as quickly as possible. If Black tries to defend e7 with  15...Bf6  , White will take  16.Bxf6  and after  16...exf6  17.Qf4  followed by Ne4, either f6 or d6 drops with a bad position for Black. }
16. Qxe7 Qxe7 17. Bxe7 Nd7
{ And a second pawn sacrifice, but the pawn on b2 also hangs. Developing the knight to a6 is a valid alternative, but considering that all the play is in the center, I prefer the knight on d7 from where it can quickly go to e5. }
18. Bxd6 Bxb2 19. g4 Bxg4
{ The strange move  19...Bc2  ,  preventing Rb1, is also playable. } 20. Rb1
Be5
{ Black wants to ensure that the knight comes to e5 so when White takes on b7, the knight is no longer attacked on d7. The move ...Be5 is the only way as other bishop moves lose material because when the knight on d7 hangs, Black doesn't have time to take a pawn on e2. }
21. Bxe5 Nxe5 22. Rxb7 Bxe2
{ White's advantage is so small that the game is likely to end in a draw. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Leningrad Variation − Sidelines"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 7...c6 − 8.Bg5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6 8. Bg5 { White's idea is to exchange on f6 and push e2-e4. } 8... Na6
{ Waiting with ...Ne4 for one move also seems playable. } 9. Qd2 Ne4
{ White is ready to place a rook on e1 followed by e2-e4, so at some point ...Ne4 is necessary and this is a good moment.   A line to illustrate what happens if Black refrains from playing ...Ne4:  9...Qb6  10.Rad1  Re8  11.Bxf6  Not only taking away Black's control over e4, but also the move f5-f4 is harmless if Black cannot follow up with ...Nh5 to start a kingside initiative.  11...Bxf6  12.e4  e5  13.Rfe1  and Black cannot stabilize the center. }
10. Nxe4 fxe4 11. Nh4 d5
{ Only move − we have to defend the pawn on e4 and giving up the pair of bishops with ...Bf5 would result in a clear advantage for White, Black doesn't have any active counterplay. }
12. Rad1 Nc7 13. cxd5 Qxd5
{ This may look strange, but there are two specific reasons for capturing with the queen here:   Black has now threats with ...Ne6, not only hitting the pawn on d4, but more importantly, the bishop on g5 hangs and if it moves to say e3, White may lose a piece after ...g6-g5.   A second reason is that if Black takes back with ...cxd5, White can attack the center with f2-f3 and Black cannot keep it under control and will end up in a passive position. }
14. Qe3
{ Defending the a-pawn by playing  14.a3  fails to  14...Ne6  and after the bishop moves, the knight on h4 will be in trouble. Note that after Qe3 the pawn on e4 hangs. }
14... Qxa2 15. Bxe4 Bh3 16. Rfe1 Qe6
{ Black is in time to defend everything and the position is about equal because the white pieces don't coordinate well. Black will play ...Nd5 and will gain central control before White can get e2-e4 in. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Leningrad Variation − Sidelines"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 7...c6 − 8.Bf4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6 8. Bf4
{ A rare move in the Leningrad System, but here White has a specific idea that is worth mentioning. }
8... Nh5
{ Black loves to chase away the bishop and play ...f5-f4. Note that ...h7-h6 is in this case a bit slow, even if Black plays ...g6-g5 on the next move. We are still not yet ready for ...f5-f4 with the knight on f6. }
9. Rc1
{ This is White's specific idea: giving up the pair of bishops to increase control over the squares in the center.   If  9.Bd2  then Black happily occupies the center with  9...e5  and we might already start hoping for an advantage with the nice pawns  on f5 and e5. And if White drops the bishop back to e3 with  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp2p1bp/2pp2p1/5p1n/2PP1B2/2N2NP1/PP2PPBP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Be3  ,  Black plays ...f5-f4 with tempo.  9...f4  and Black is already better. }
9... h6
{ I had a look at 9...h6 because now  10.h4  is too weakening for White after Black takes  10...Nxf4  .  So I thought White needs to drop back the bishop and Black achieves ...f5-f4. It is surprising to learn that White's expansion on the queenside is actually faster. }
10. Be3 f4 11. Bd2 Bg4
{ Black is focusing on developing the queenside.   The standard central push also doesn't bring equality:  11...e5  12.dxe5  dxe5  13.c5  .  White is taking control over the d6-square.  13...Be6  14.Ne4  and White has a clear advantage. Black doesn't have much of a kingside attack yet, while White has blocked the g7-bishop and can put a rook on d1, a bishop on c3, and start putting pressure on Black's center. }
12. Qb3 Qd7
{ There is no other good way of protecting the b7-pawn since  12...Qb6  is simply met by  13.Qc2  . }
13. d5 c5
{ Taking on  13...cxd5  with the idea to play ...Na6-c5 is too slow, White can either play  14.Ne4  or move the  queen and play b2-b4. }
14. Ne4 Na6 15. Bc3
{ White has a clear advantage, the black structure with the pawn on e7 is weak and it cannot really move forward because White would play dxe6 and the d6-pawn would be a problem. Also, the knight on a6 is passive, even on c7 it doesn't contribute much and Black lacks an active plan, there is no kingside attack. }
*

