[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Leningrad Variation − Sidelines"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 7...c6 − 8.e3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6 8. e3
{ A waiting move. In many lines in the Leningrad System White would like to play e2-e4, and here that would mean a loss of tempo. Even so, it is still a threat Black needs to watch out for.  The advantage of a waiting move here is that Black can now easily go wrong. One way could be by pursuing ...e7-e5 too quickly when White will counter with b2-b3 and Ba3 and the pawn on d6 will become weak. }
8... Na6
{ This is a playable alternative, but the disadvantage is that it is a line with a lot of exchanges resulting in a dull endgame, so limited chances for Black to play for a win.   8...Nbd7  is not good because of  9.Ng5  Nb6  And this square is almost never ok for a black knight in the Leningrad System because White either plays Qb3 or b2-b3 and the b6-knight doesn't have any future and doesn't help with pushing the e7-pawn. }
9. Rb1
{ This is the most critical attempt, preparing b2-b4.   If White plays  9.b3  , Black can play  9...e5  , making use of the fact that the bishop  on g7 has the knight on c3 and the rook on a1 in sight. }
9... e5
{ The alternative  9...Ne4  is less strong because White can just play  10.Qc2  ,  intending to take back on c3 with the b-pawn. }
10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Nxe5
{ Black has sacrificed a pawn but has sufficient counterplay. } 11... Qxd1 12.
Rxd1 Be6
{ Increasing the pressure on the white position, in many lines the knight on e5 has to move, and then pawn c4 drops. }
13. f4 Rfd8
{ White's extra pawn is on e3 and as long as it doesn't move to e4, that pawn doesn't mean a lot. Meanwhile Black needs to make maximum use of the active pieces and that is also the case for the rooks by trying to take over the d-file. }
14. Bd2 Nd7
{ A typical way of increasing the power of both bishops on g7 and e6. } 15.
Nxd7 Rxd7 16. Bf1 { The pawn on c4 has to be defended. } 16... Rad8 17. Be1 Nb4
{ Activating Black's final piece. } 18. Rxd7
{ If White would have played  18.a3  , the knight would jump  18...Nd3  , with annoying pressure. }
18... Rxd7 19. Nd1 { All White's pieces are on the back rank. } 19... Nxa2
{ It seems the knight has no way out after White's next move. } 20. Ra1 Bf8
{ But Black has time to cover the b4-square for the knight because the knight on d1 is protected by the rook on a1. }
21. Be2 Nb4
{ Now that the knight on d1 is defended, White was threatening to take on a2. }
22. Bxb4 Bxb4 23. Rxa7 { White remains a pawn up. } 23... Bc5 24. Ra8+ Kf7
{ This endgame is about equal, Black's pair of bishops and active rook @@StartBracket@@it could easily go to d2@@EndBracket@@ fully compensate for the pawn deficit and the e3-pawn that doesn't go anywhere. }
