1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6 8. e3
{ A waiting move. In many lines in the Leningrad System White would like to play e2-e4, and here that would mean a loss of tempo. Even so, it is still a threat Black needs to watch out for.  The advantage of a waiting move here is that Black can now easily go wrong. One way could be by pursuing ...e7-e5 too quickly when White will counter with b2-b3 and Ba3 and the pawn on d6 will become weak. }
8... a5
{ Making use of White's slow approach with e2-e3 to make an advance on the queenside harder. }
9. b3
{ White taking a slow approach with first e2-e3 and then b2-b3, so no wonder Black is ready to push: }
9... e5 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Ba3
{ White cannot take the pawn with  11.Nxe5  because of material loss after  11...Ne4  . }
11... Qxd1 12. Rfxd1 Re8
{ Black is simply defending the pawn on e5 and is ready to play ...Nbd7 and ...e5-e4. }
13. Na4 e4 14. Nd4 Nbd7 15. Bf1
{ White is redeploying the bishop to the queenside and Black is now trying to take control over the c5-square. }
15... Bf8 16. Bb2 Ne5
{ Black doesn’t mind giving up the bishop on c8, it is the only piece that doesn’t have a great future at the moment. }
17. Nb6 Rb8 18. Nxc8 Rbxc8
{ Black is already slightly better. We can play ...Nfd7 followed by ...Nc5 and then a knight to d3. We can also start attacking the queenside with ...a5-a4 @@StartBracket@@with or without a rook on a8@@EndBracket@@. }
