[Round "?"]
[White "2. Leningrad Variation − Sidelines"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 7...c6 − 8.b3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6 8. b3
{ Here I give three alternatives for Black:  8...Na6  is my recommendation,  8...Qc7  is also playable but a little passive, and  8...e5  equalizes but results in a lot of exchanges that will make it more difficult for Black to play for a win. }
8... Qa5 { I don't think this move gives Black sufficient chances. } 9. Bb2 e5
10. Qd2 Na6
{ 10...Qc7  is analyzed by Giri in the New in Chess Magazine 2013/6 where he annotates his win over Gelfand in Beijing.  11.d5  e4   Not good is  11...c5  because of  12.Ng5  Qe7  13.Ne6  Bxe6  14.dxe6  e4  15.Nd5  Nxd5  16.cxd5  with a fantastic position for White.   11...h6  Prevents the Ng5 idea, but Black doesn't have time for this slow move.  12.dxc6  bxc6  13.Rad1  Ne8  14.c5  Ouch...  14...dxc5  15.e4  f4  16.gxf4  exf4  17.Rfe1  Be6  18.e5  .  Look at the poor knights on e8 and b8 and the rook on a8, Black is in serious trouble here.   11...Qe7  is another move for which Black doesn't have time.  12.dxc6  bxc6  13.Ba3  Ne8  14.e4  f4  .  The move f5-f4 rarely works if all Black's pieces are at the back rank, but keeping the pawn on f5 is not advisable either because White will take on f5 and put a rook on e1 and there is no way Black can stabilize the center.  15.gxf4  exf4  16.e5  .  This hurts, a sample line:  16...Bxe5  17.Nd5  ,  a knight that cannot be taken because of the rook on a8.  17...Qe6  18.Nxe5  dxe5  19.Ne7+  Kg7  20.Nxc8  Qxc8  21.Bxf8+  Game over.   11...Na6  doesn't help with defending the pawn on d6, so after  12.Rad1  Black has to go  12...c5  but now is hit again with  13.Ng5  Qe7  14.Ne6  Bxe6  15.dxe6  and these complications work in White's favor.  15...Rad8  16.Nd5  Qxe6  17.Nxf6+  Qxf6  .  White starts eating the pawns on the queenside.  18.Bxb7  Nc7  19.Qa5  Qe7  20.Qxa7  and White has a winning advantage: extra pawn, pair of bishops, and more active pieces.  12.Nd4  Qe7   12...Re8  is a move Giri mentioned, but I don't think it works.  13.dxc6  bxc6  14.Nc2  Na6  15.Rad1  Rd8  .  A second move with the black rook, this doesn't look okay.  16.f3  Qb6+  17.Kh1  exf3  18.exf3  Nc5  19.Rfe1  and I prefer White's position. It is not easy to make the bishop on c8 active, White has occupied the e-file, the pawn on d6 is weak, and Black doesn't have the e4-square for the knights.  13.dxc6  bxc6  14.Rad1  Rd8  was the game Gelfand-Giri, Beijing 2013 and now White could have improved with  15.f3  e3  16.Qd3  Bb7  17.Nc2  and the e3-pawn drops, resulting in a winning position for White. }
11. Rad1 Re8 12. d5 c5 13. e4 Qd8 14. Ng5
{ With a large advantage for Grischuk in his game against Nijboer, Bilbao 2014. }
