2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6 8. b3
{ Here I give three alternatives for Black:  8...Na6  is my recommendation,  8...Qc7  is also playable but a little passive, and  8...e5  equalizes but results in a lot of exchanges that will make it more difficult for Black to play for a win. }
8... Re8
{ The move ...Re8 was played by Nepomniachtchi twice in online blitz games against Grischuk. It results in somewhat passive positions for Black, but in both instances, Black managed to make a draw. Although we should probably not pay any attention to the outcome of blitz games for opening evaluation. }
9. Bb2 Qc7 10. d5 e5
{ Black can also play  10...Na6  first but it is likely to transpose to the main line. }
11. dxe6 Bxe6 12. Ng5 Na6 13. Nxe6 Rxe6
{ Black will continue to put one knight on c5 and then one of the knights on e4 and this compensates for the loss of bishop pair and the weak d6-pawn. The disadvantage is that Black doesn't have an active plan, so creating winning chances will not be easy. }
