[White "2. Leningrad Variation − Sidelines"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 7...c6 − 8.b3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6 8. b3
{ Here I give three alternatives for Black:  8...Na6  is my recommendation,  8...Qc7  is also playable but a little passive, and  8...e5  equalizes but results in a lot of exchanges that will make it more difficult for Black to play for a win. }
8... Na6 { My main recommendation for Black. } 9. Bb2 Qc7
{ Threatening ...e7-e5, so White has to prevent it. } 10. d5 e5 11. dxe6 Bxe6
12. Ng5
{ And now, contrary to some other lines, Black has time to maintain the bishop, which makes it much easier to equalize. }
12... Bd7 13. Qc2
{ If White plays  13.Qd2  followed by a rook to d1, Black will defend with  13...Rad8  and ...Bc8. }
13... Rad8 14. Rad1 Nc5 15. e3 a5
{ Black is completely fine here. We are following a blitz game between Giri and Ponomariov, Beijing 2013. There are several interesting points in the following moves and I would like to show part of the game to illustrate Black's strong play.  First of all, the white knight on g5 is slightly annoying for Black, but if we play ...h7-h6, the g6-pawn is weakened, especially if after ...h7-h6 White plays Nh3-f4. Note how Ponomariov moves his queen to e7 to drive away the knight without weakening his pawn structure.  Chessable note: For more details on how to approach this position, kindly see the next Informational! }
*

