[White "2. Leningrad Variation − Sidelines"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 7...c6 − 8.b3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6 8. b3
{ Here I give three alternatives for Black:  8...Na6  is my recommendation,  8...Qc7  is also playable but a little passive, and  8...e5  equalizes but results in a lot of exchanges that will make it more difficult for Black to play for a win. }
8... Na6 { My main recommendation for Black. } 9. Bb2 Qc7
{ Threatening ...e7-e5, so White has to prevent it. } 10. d5 e5 11. dxe6 Bxe6
12. Ng5
{ And now, contrary to some other lines, Black has time to maintain the bishop, which makes it much easier to equalize. }
12... Bd7 13. Qc2
{ If White plays  13.Qd2  followed by a rook to d1, Black will defend with  13...Rad8  and ...Bc8. }
13... Rad8 14. Rad1 Nc5 15. e3 a5
{ Black is completely fine here. We are following a blitz game between Giri and Ponomariov, Beijing 2013. There are several interesting points in the following moves and I would like to show part of the game to illustrate Black's strong play.  First of all, the white knight on g5 is slightly annoying for Black, but if we play ...h7-h6, the g6-pawn is weakened, especially if after ...h7-h6 White plays Nh3-f4. Note how Ponomariov moves his queen to e7 to drive away the knight without weakening his pawn structure. }
16. Rfe1
{ Another line for illustration is the following:  16.Ne2  This move was played by Daniel Fridman against Viktor Laznicka in Reykjavik 2015.  16...Bc8  17.Bd4  h6  Black is creating play on the kingside, it is important not to play passively. If White is given a free hand, h2-h4, Nf4, a2-a3 followed by b2-b4 might be played, in some order, and Black would be in trouble because of lack of space. We want to move forward with the g-pawn and sometimes also ...h7-h6-h5-h4, but while doing so, Black needs to be careful that the pawn on f5 doesn't become weak.   17...Ng4  This is another way of creating play. The idea is to put the knight on a more active position either on g4 or e5 and then move forward with ...h7-h6 and ...g6-g5.  18.Nf4  Rde8  19.h4  Bf6  Preparing ...g6-g5 after ...h7-h6.  20.a3  h6  21.Nf3  g5  22.hxg5  hxg5  23.Ne2  Qh7  Black has already a clear advantage thanks to the initiative on the kingside.  18.Nf3  g5  19.Bb2  Rde8  20.Nfd4  Ng4  Defending the pawn on f5. 20...Rf7 was played by Fridman, but I think it is not the most natural move.  21.h3  Ne5  22.f4  A big commitment from White, the pawn on e3 is now weak, but there is no other way for White to make progress.  22...Ng6  23.Bc1  Qe7   Note that  23...Ne4  fails to  24.fxg5  hxg5  25.Nxf5  winning an important pawn.  24.Qd2   24.Nc3  White continues with a waiting strategy while Black will take action on the kingside.  24...h5  25.Qe2  h4  26.Qh5  Qf7  27.Nce2  g4  A sharp continuation, but 27...gxf4 is also a valid option. In all cases, there are lots of complications.  28.hxg4  fxg4  We have reached a complex position with mutual chances. The white queen can easily end up in trouble and Black can continue with moves such as ...Bf6, ...Kg7, and ...Rh8.  24...a4  and Black's position is fine. We have sufficient counterplay against the weak pawn on e3 and the pressure on the kingside and the main weakness, the d6-pawn, can easily be defended. }
16... Bc8 17. Qb1 Rfe8 18. Qc2 Qe7
{ Black is ready to attack the knight by playing ...Ng4. } 19. Nf3 Ng4 20. h3
Ne5 21. Nd4 Nf7
{ Black has optimized the pieces and now White becomes a bit impatient. } 22.
f4
{ Weakening the e3-pawn and the long diagonal a7-g1. Black can now move the queen to b6 and double rooks on the e-file. }
22... Qc7 23. Kh2 Re7 24. Re2 Rde8 25. Rde1 Qb6
{ Great play by Ponomariov, who eventually scored a full point by starting to attack the queenside. }
