[White "2. Leningrad Variation − Sidelines"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 7...c6 − 8.b3 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6 8. b3
{ Here I give three alternatives for Black:  8...Na6  is my recommendation,  8...Qc7  is also playable but a little passive, and  8...e5  equalizes but results in a lot of exchanges that will make it more difficult for Black to play for a win. }
8... a5
{ According to my analysis this line is a playable alternative for  8...Na6  . }
9. Bb2 Qc7 { I don't think this move is satisfactory for Black. } 10. d5
{ Creating a weakness on e6.   Also interesting is  10.Rc1  e5  11.dxe5  dxe5  12.e4  .  The crucial move, without this White would be worse, now some advantage can be claimed because it is not easy to complete development with Black.  12...f4  is the standard reaction, we don't want to take on e4 if White has Ng5 and can take back later with a knight on e4, locking in the bishop on g7, behind the e5-pawn.    13.gxf4  Nh5  14.fxe5  Bg4  Black needs to generate an attack in compensation for the two pawns.  15.Ba3  Nd7  16.Bd6  White has much better than taking an exchange on f8.  16...Qb6  17.c5  Qa7  was clearly better for White in the blitz game Mikhalevski-Nepomniachtchi, Berlin 2015. }
10... Na6 11. Nd4 Bd7 12. e4
{ There is always this central break that can put Black under pressure.   12.Rc1  Nc5  Black has to aim for ...e7-e5.  13.e3  e5  14.dxe6  Nxe6  15.Nxe6  Bxe6  .  These types of positions happen a lot in practice and every time the question is whether Black can hold. White has taken out any kingside active by preventing ...f5-f4 with e2-e3 and can now slowly strengthen the position further.    16.Qc2  Rad8  17.Ne2  The knight threatens to come to f4 with tempo hitting the bishop on e6 and making it more difficult for Black to play the liberating ...d6-d5. I think Black is a bit worse here. }
12... fxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Qb6
{ The problem for Black is that the standard reaction in this position of playing ...Nc5 followed by ...e7-e5 loses material:  14...Nc5  15.Bg2  e5  16.dxc6  bxc6  17.Nb5  And now either pawn d6 drops or an exchange on a8 because after  17...cxb5  18.Bxa8  Black cannot take back on a8 because of a queen check on d5. }
15. Rb1 Rf7
{ We have been following the internet game between Lesieg-Vovk, chess.com INT 2017, and now I suggest an improvement. }
16. Bg2
{ I think White has the advantage. Black has this structural weak e-pawn and the e6-square and trading pieces can make the problems grow. }
