[White "2. Leningrad Variation − Sidelines"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 7...c6 − 8.b3 #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6 8. b3
{ Here I give three alternatives for Black:  8...Na6  is my recommendation,  8...Qc7  is also playable but a little passive, and  8...e5  equalizes but results in a lot of exchanges that will make it more difficult for Black to play for a win. }
8... Qc7
{ A reasonable option, but it can result in a slightly passive position for Black. }
9. Ba3 a5
{ Doesn't work and neither do Black's alternatives here.   9...h6  is just too slow here.  10.Rc1  Kh7  11.d5  c5  12.Bb2  Nbd7  13.Qc2  and White was clearly better in the blitz game Vachier Lagrave-Nepomniachtchi, Dubai 2014.   After  9...Ne4  I think the critical continuation is  10.Nxe4  fxe4  11.Ne1  d5  .  If Black can stabilize the center we will be fine, but the problem is that after f2-f3 there will be a lot of pressure on e4 and d5.  12.f3  Bf5  13.fxe4  dxe4  14.Nc2  Rf7  15.Qd2  Nd7  Black has to complete development as soon as possible and try to find some activity.  16.Ne3  Bh6  17.Qc3  And White has some advantage thanks to the better pawn structure. }
10. Rc1 Na6 11. Qd2 Bd7
{ Black's problem is that the d6-square is weak. If we want to play ...e7-e5 we need to move the rook from f8 and even then, after taking on e5, White can play the annoying Bd6.   11...Nb4  was tried by Wang but after  12.d5  e5  13.dxe6  Bxe6  14.Nd4  Bf7  15.Nc2  Nxc2  16.Rxc2  Rfd8  17.Rd1  Bf8  White had a large advantage in Tomashevsky-Wang, St. Petersburg 2012. }
12. Rfe1 Nb4
{ Another way of preparing e7-e5, the a3-bishop is no longer hitting the rook on f8. }
13. Bb2 e5
{ The desired push, but Black has lost too many tempi and falls in a tactical trap. }
14. a3 Na6 15. dxe5 dxe5 16. Nb5
{ Black was busted in Karpov-Jussupow, Linares 1989. The e5-pawn is attacked twice and if Black takes the knight  16...cxb5  , White can always recapture  17.cxb5  and win the piece back on a6. }
