[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6 8. b3
{ Here I give three alternatives for Black:  8...Na6  is my recommendation,  8...Qc7  is also playable but a little passive, and  8...e5  equalizes but results in a lot of exchanges that will make it more difficult for Black to play for a win. }
8... Qc7
{ A reasonable option, but it can result in a slightly passive position for Black. }
9. Ba3 Re8
{ This move doesn't really prepare ...e7-e5 yet, because after exchanging on e5, White wins a pawn with Bd6. }
10. Re1 { Preparing e2-e4. } 10... Qa5 { And Black is preparing ...e7-e5. } 11.
Bb2 e5 12. e4 Nxe4
{ Black's first option in these types of Leningrad System positions is to look at  12...f4  , but here it is not great because after the simple  13.gxf4  Black doesn't have a great response: if we take back  13...exf4  , White is ready for  14.e5  .  And if Black doesn't take back on f4, both White's f-pawn and d-pawn are threatening to take on e5 and destroy Black's center. }
13. Nxe4 fxe4 14. Rxe4 Bf5 15. Re3
{ White would love to take on e5 and after ...dxe5, play Ng5 in order to block the pawn on e4. Black needs to be fast. }
15... e4 { Only move. } 16. Nh4 { On  16.Nd2  Black defends with  16...d5  . }
16... Nd7
{ Now  16...d5  would fail to  17.Nxf5  followed by Bh3 and the pawn on f5 is weak. }
17. Bc3 Qd8
{ The queen needs to be able to quickly go to g5 to protect the pawn on f5 after White has taken the bishop. }
18. Nxf5 gxf5 19. g4
{ Undermining Black's center. The opening of the white kingside is not a problem for White with a rook on e3 that can go to g3. }
19... d5 { Black has to maintain the grip in the center. } 20. gxf5 Qg5 21.
cxd5 cxd5 22. Bd2 Qxf5 23. Rg3 Kh8
{ White is a little better but it is not a big deal. My main problem with this line is that Black's position is a bit passive though. We don't have a lot of targets to focus on in this position. }
