[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Leningrad Variation − Sidelines"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 7...c6 − 8.Rb1 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6 8. Rb1
{ A logical move − White has focused on healthy development and now wants to expand on the queenside with b2-b4-b5, attacking the c6-pawn. For this plan, it is useful that the rook is no longer in the vision of the g7-bishop. }
8... Ne4 { This used to be the main move, but I don't recommend it. } 9. Qc2
Nxc3 10. bxc3
{ Kramnik played this move in Wijk aan Zee in 2010 against Nakamura, and since then ...Ne4 has the reputation of being dubious. }
10... e5
{ 10...Qa5  was played in Giri-Reinderman, Hilversum 2009.  Giri was quite young when he played the idea of bxc3 and he played it before Kramnik! }
11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Ba3
{ White's strategy is to disrupt the coordination between Black's pieces. }
12... Rf7 13. Rfd1 Nd7 { Black needs to develop the queenside pieces. } 14. e4
Bf8 15. Bxf8 Qxf8 16. exf5
{ Giri played this line with Black many years later. He faced here  16.Qd2  , when White had a small advantage and eventually won in Jakovenko- Giri, Tbilisi 2015. }
16... gxf5 17. Ng5 Re7 18. Rd6 Nc5 19. Qe2
{ 19.Qd1  was played in a correspondence game: Teeriaho-Gebur, ICCF email 2012, but I feel  the queen is better placed on e2. }
19... Bd7 20. Rbd1 e4 21. Qe3
{ This position is a bit better for White despite the ugly doubled c-pawns. White controls the d-file, has the more active pieces and the knight can go via h3 to f4 or even h5 where it will be quite annoying. }
