4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6 8. Rb1
{ A logical move − White has focused on healthy development and now wants to expand on the queenside with b2-b4-b5, attacking the c6-pawn. For this plan, it is useful that the rook is no longer in the vision of the g7-bishop. }
8... a5
{ Making it more difficult for White to expand on the queenside, who will now need the move a2-a3 and after a later b2-b4, Black can take and open the a-file for the a8-rook. }
9. Qb3
{ White is paying attention to Black's queenside, trying to prove there are some weaknesses. }
9... Na6
{ Black could also have played  9...Kh8  , but I prefer to develop a piece considering Black is behind in development. }
10. Rd1
{ A move that has been played in a few correspondence games and we have to take it seriously. }
10... h6 11. Be3 Rb8
{ Defending the pawn on b7 so that the bishop can be developed and sometimes Black can even push ...b7-b5. }
12. Rbc1 Nc7
{ The knight can go to e6 but also from c7 it supports the ...b7-b5 move. } 13.
Ne1
{ If White plays  13.d5  , Black responds with  13...c5  . The disadvantage is that after those moves it will be hard for either side to create a pawn break and a long strategic game ending in a draw has become more likely. }
13... Bd7 14. Nd3
{ Until here it was the game Iotov-Pirs, ICCF email 2014, but I want to improve Black's play by advancing on the kingside. }
14... g5
{ 14...Ng4  was played in the game, which results in complications that are maybe slightly favorable for White, but even more important, are not easy to play in an over-the-board game. }
15. Bd2 Be6 16. Qa4 Qd7
{ Black has reached a healthy position. All the pieces are developed, the pawn on a5 can be protected by ...Ra8 but as long as the c4-pawn hangs, there is no need. Meanwhile, the bishop can drop back to f7 and one day Black can play ...e7-e5. }
