{ White is paying attention to Black's queenside, trying to prove there are some weaknesses. }
9... Na6
{ Black could also have played  9...Kh8  , but I prefer to develop a piece considering Black is behind in development. }
10. Bg5 { Usually the idea of this move is to take on f6 and play e2-e4. }
10... h6
{ Black has valid alternatives, but I don't think we have to be afraid of White's plan. }
11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Rbd1
{ If White plays  12.e4  immediately, Black can respond by playing  12...e5  . }
12... Bg7 { Preparing ...f5-f4. } 13. e4 f4 14. e5 Bg4
{ It has become a sharp position but the pawn on e5 is not too threatening for Black @@StartBracket@@yet@@EndBracket@@, it is not going anywhere. }
15. c5+ Kh7 16. Nh4
{ White keeps the game going. If Qxb7, there is a high chance of a draw after ...Nb4 at some point followed by ...Rb8 and if the queen moves to a7  @@StartBracket@@only square@@EndBracket@@, ...Ra8 and the queen cannot escape and needs to return to b7 again and we get a repetition of moves. }
16... f3 { At least White is now playing without the bishop. } 17. Bh1 g5
{ It is a miracle to see that the knight on h4 survives. } 18. Qc2+ Kg8 19. Ng6
{ The knight still has no other squares to go to and might get lost in the long run. }
19... Rf7 20. cxd6 exd6 21. exd6
{ And now suddenly the e5-square has become available for the knight. } 21...
Qxd6 22. Ne5 Bxe5 { Black picks up the pawn but loses the nice bishop. } 23.
dxe5 Qxe5 24. Rfe1 Qg7
{ My engine says it is about equal, but in a practical game, I would prefer Black simply because the bishop on h1 is not participating. }
