{ The move  11...d5  is not great here because White can play  12.Bf4  with full control over the e5-square. }
12. Ng5 d5
{ Now ...d6-d5 is justified because White has lost control over the e5-square. }
13. Nf3 { Threatening to take control over e5 again with Bf4. } 13... g5
{ Not a pawn sacrifice because if White takes on g5, the pawn on d4 will also hang. }
14. Nb6 Rb8 15. Nxc8 Qxc8 16. Nxg5 Bxd4
{ There is no reason to take on g5, the knight on e4 is beautiful. } 17. Qa4
{ Attacking both the bishop on d4 and the pawn on a5. } 17... Bxc5 18. Qxa5 Qc7
{ Material is equal and Black has no problems. The knight on e4 and the bishop on c5 are active and after the queen moves from c7 @@StartBracket@@for example to d6@@EndBracket@@ the other knight will join via c7 and e6. }
