[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Leningrad Variation − Sidelines"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 7...c6 − 8.Rb1 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 c6 8. Rb1
{ A logical move − White has focused on healthy development and now wants to expand on the queenside with b2-b4-b5, attacking the c6-pawn. For this plan, it is useful that the rook is no longer in the vision of the g7-bishop. }
8... a5
{ Making it more difficult for White to expand on the queenside, who will now need the move a2-a3 and after a later b2-b4, Black can take and open the a-file for the a8-rook. }
9. Qb3
{ White is paying attention to Black's queenside, trying to prove there are some weaknesses. }
9... Na6
{ Black could also have played  9...Kh8  , but I prefer to develop a piece considering Black is behind in development. }
10. Na4 Ne4 11. c5+
{ The idea of c4-c5 is almost always to exchange a pawn on d6 or have Black take on c5  @@StartBracket@@if there is no check@@EndBracket@@ so that Black no longer has the ...e7-e5 push. }
11... Kh8
{ The move  11...d5  is not great here because White can play  12.Bf4  with full control over the e5-square. }
12. Rd1 Nc7
{ From here the knight not only covers the d5-square but also the e6-square, enabling a future ...Be6, which would not have been possible if Black would have gone ...Nb4. }
13. Ng5
{ If White plays  13.Nb6  , Black can first play  13...Be6  and then move the rook to,  for example, a6. }
13... Nxg5 { White was threatening to win material with Nf7+. } 14. Bxg5 Ne6
{ Attacking the bishop and the pawn on d4. } 15. Nb6 Rb8 16. Nxc8
{ If White defends the pawn on d4 with  16.Be3  , it will be hit by  16...f4  . }
16... Nxg5
{ Note that Black cannot recapture on c8 with the queen nor the rook because either the e7 or b7-pawn would be hanging. }
17. Nb6 d5
{ Securing control over the e4-square and stopping any White's ideas involving d4-d5. }
18. f4 { White has to prevent ...e7-e5. } 18... Ne4
{ A few sample lines: if White would have gone pawn grabbing with  19.Qa4  , Black would play  19...g5  , and White's king is in danger. If White takes @@StartFEN@@1r1q1r1k/1p2p1bp/1Np3p1/p1Pp1p2/3PnP2/1Q4P1/PP2P1BP/1R1R2K1 w - - 1 19@@EndFEN@@  19.Bxe4  Black plays  19...fxe4  and threatens to attack again with ...g6-g5.  So White probably needs to play  20.h4  , but then Black can sacrifice a pawn with  20...Qe8  followed by  ...e7-e5 and after dxe5 just play ...Qe6 and start attacking. The engine manages to keep the balance for White, but in a practical game, Black has great winning chances.   19.h4  − now White has to prevent a kingside attack from Black.  19...e5  , a powerful temporary pawn sacrifice. There are many ways for White to go wrong.  20.fxe5  a4  , another pawn sacrifice to put the white pieces offside.  21.Nxa4   21.Qd3  is a solid move, defending the kingside.  21...Bh6  22.Rf1  Qe7  ,  threatening to play ...Nxc5 and after White takes back, Black takes with a check on c5 and then the knight on b6.  23.Rbd1  ,  White prevents Black's idea. After ...Qxc5+ White has Qd4 and remains a piece up because the queen on d4 defends the knight on b6.  23...Rbd8  .   It took me a while to understand this move, but the simple way to explain it is as follows: Black will play ...g6-g5 at some point followed by ...Rg8 and the attack can be very dangerous for White.  White will try to exchange queens and in the endgame, it could cause trouble by playing Nd7 @@StartBracket@@attacking the rook on b8@@EndBracket@@ and after the rook moves, White can often push the e-pawn forward, which is a really annoying passed pawn.  Therefore, Black prevents this whole Nd7 idea by placing the rook on d8.  24.Nxa4  g5  , Black has to play this move to start the kingside attack. I don't think White can hold this position.  25.h5  ,  taking on g5 would be suicide, Black takes back with the queen followed by ...Rg8.   25.Bxe4  , trying to reduce the pressure by taking the knight, but Black is still very active.  25...fxe4  26.Qe3  Qg7  ,  defending the bishop on h6 so that ...gxh4 is now a serious threat.  27.g4  gxh4  28.Qh3  Rg8  , bringing extra pieces to the kingside.  29.Kh1  Qxg4  .  This endgame is favorable for Black.  30.Qxg4  Rxg4  31.Rg1  Rxg1+  32.Kxg1  Be3+  .  The pawn on d4 is weak and if it falls, the pawns on e5 and c5 also become weak.  33.Kh2  Kg7  , activating the king.  34.Kh3  Kf7  35.Kxh4  Rg8  . Black is winning since the rook and king are active while White's rook cannot move.  25...g4  is a strong move, vacating the g5-square for the queen.  26.Nc3  Qg5  . Black has a clear advantage, all the pieces are active,  the h5-pawn can be taken at any time and the white king is not safe.  21...Bh6  22.Qd3  g5  , Black is starting to attack.  23.h5  g4  ,  preventing White from playing g3-g4 while at the same time opening g5 for the black queen.  24.Rf1  Qg5  . Black has a clear advantage: all  the pieces are active and the h5-pawn is about to drop. }
