[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Leningrad Variation 7...Qe8 − Alternative"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 7...Qe8 − Alternative − 8.b3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3
{ It is important to note that White can use various move orders to reach the main position of the Leningrad Dutch. Previously, we saw 2.Nf3 but as the saying goes, 'all roads lead to Rome'. }
2... Nf6 3. Bg2 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 Qe8
{ This used to be the old main line for Black which I have played many times myself. Nowadays most people agree that the7...c6 lines  are safer because that move is almost always useful while the queen is not necessarily needed on e8.   Based on the below analysis Black holds in every line, but especially in the lines with  8.b3  and  8.Nd5  the engine gives a clear advantage for White.  Correspondence games have shown that this advantage is not sufficient for White to win, but it is clear that the 7...Qe8 System involves more risk for Black without more upside. }
8. b3
{ For a long time it was underestimated that with this move White often ends up with an advantage because of the Ba3 possibility. }
8... Na6
{ Numerous games have been played with the logical knight jump to a6, preparing ...c7-c6 followed by ...e7-e5, which works reasonably well if White plays Bb2. }
9. Re1
{ The idea of this move is to attack Black's center by playing e2-e4 and having the rook opposite the queen on e8. One of those situations where the queen will need to lose two more tempi, one to play ...h7-h6 @@StartBracket@@to avoid Ng5@@EndBracket@@ and only then ...Qf7.   As an illustration, after  9.a4  Black can stay in the game with some tactical tricks.  9...Nb4  10.a5  e5  ,  always this push, even though with the rook on f8 and the knight on b4 it may look impossible because of Ba3.  11.Ba3  c5  12.dxe5  dxe5  13.Na4  is the direct approach, but it doesn't give White anything special.   Initially,  13.e4  looked quite promising for White, but a few moves further it is not so clear anymore.  13...Bd7  14.Nd2  f4  ,  Black is playing standard moves, ready for ...g6-g5 and ...Qg6.  15.Nd5  Nfxd5  16.cxd5  Qe7  .  A complex position that is maybe slightly better for White because the pieces are more active and the well-protected passed pawn on d5.  13...e4  14.Ne1  Qe7  15.Nxc5  seems winning but no...  15...Rd8  16.Qb1  Qxc5  17.Nc2  .  And now what?  17...Nfd5  is a great trick after which Black is fine. A sample line:  18.cxd5  Qxc2  19.Bxb4  Qxb1  20.Raxb1  Rxd5  and we have reached an equal endgame with an equal number of pawns and no major weaknesses.   9.Ba3  Besides 9.Re1 I believe this move also gives White some advantage.  9...c6  Black is not only preparing ...e7-e5 @@StartBracket@@more difficult with the bishop on a3 looking at the pawn on d6 and the rook on f8@@EndBracket@@, but also ...b7-b5 to create counterplay on the queenside.  10.Qd3  White is preparing e2-e4.  10...Rb8  11.e4  an improvement over an old game between Koch-Kramnik, Singapore 1990, where White played 11.c5.  11...fxe4  12.Nxe4  Bf5  Taking on e4 results in a very similar type of position as in the main line with ...Bf5. In one line the bishop is on g7, in the other on f6, in all cases, Black lacks counterplay and is therefore suffering.   12...Nxe4  13.Qxe4  Bf5  14.Qe3  Qd7  What else?  White is threatening Rae1, Black doesn't have time for something like ...h7-h6, ...g6-g5, ...Qg6, ...Rf7 and ...Raf8.  15.Rfe1  Rbe8  All Black can do for now is defend everything.  16.Rac1  Nc7  17.Bb2  and Black can only try to hold an inferior position, which in the game Kasimdzhanov-Pruijssers, Germany 2012 he did not succeed in.  13.Nxf6+  White is forced to exchange on f6 but it doesn't help Black considering we cannot take back with the e-pawn.  13...Bxf6  14.Qd2  Qd7   14...Nc7  15.Rae1  Qd7  16.Bb2  is an improvement over 16.h4 as played in Ibragimov-Kramnik, Kherson 1991.  16...b5  17.d5  and White is clearly better.  Black still has a backward pawn on e7 and a hole on e6 and no real counterplay.  15.Rfe1  b5  .  Black's only chance is to generate play on the queenside and find compensation for the backward pawn on e7.  16.Rac1  White is preparing to put pressure on the c6-pawn, but closing the position with ...b5-b4 is not going to help because Black keeps the structural weaknesses on the e-file.  16...bxc4  17.Ng5  Nc7  .  Taking on b3 is even worse, White will take on c6 followed by a check on d5.  18.Rxc4  White is clearly better with the weaknesses on the e-file and the pawn on c6. }
9... e5
{ Black's entire concept of ...Qe8 and ...Na6 is around this break.   9...c6  with the idea to play ...b7-b5 doesn't equalize.  10.Bb2  Ba3 is less effective here because Black is planning ...b7-b5 anyway and then threaten to win a piece with ...b5-b4.  10...b5  Black needs to quickly generate play on the queenside.   10...Rb8  ,  moving the rook away from the g2-bishop, but Black's play is too slow, White is ready to strike in the center.  11.e4  is a break that can put Black under a lot of pressure.  11...Nxe4  12.Nxe4  fxe4  13.Rxe4  Bf5  14.Re3  ,  White will put pressure on the e7-pawn and Black needs to hurry to be in time to defend it. Note that it would be nice to defend it by ...Rf7, but for that Black needs an extra tempo to first play ...h7-h6 so that the rook on f7 cannot be hit by Ng5.    14...Qd7  15.Qe2  Rbe8  16.d5  Instead, Rae1 is also annoying, Black cannot easily disentangle.  16...e5  Black has to play this now because if White gets Rae1 in, Black's e-pawn is not going forward anymore.  17.dxe6  Rxe6  .  Taking with the bishop on e6 loses to exchanging on g7 followed by Rd1.  18.Bxg7  Rxe3  19.Qxe3  Qxg7  20.Rd1  If Black were allowed to play 2 moves in one go we would be okay, but in reality, there are too many weaknesses in the position, with the pawns on a7 and d6 and the offside knight.  11.cxb5  cxb5  12.Ng5  Rb8  13.e4  .  Again White opens the position to show the disadvantages of the fact that Black hasn't completed development yet and the queen is not so great on e8.  13...b4  Black has to gain some space and initiates piece exchanges.   13...h6  is not good.  14.e5  hxg5  15.exf6  Bxf6  16.Nd5  White's active pieces and better pawn structure give yields a clear advantage.  14.Nd5  Nxd5  15.exd5  Nc7  .  We have to defend the e6-square, but it doesn't look pretty.  16.Rc1  Qd8  17.Qe2   17.Qc2  is also an option leading to an advantage for White, but I find 17.Qe2 more forceful.  17...Ne8  18.Qe2  Black's position is passive and needs to look for small tricks.  18...Bh6  19.Ne6  Bxe6  20.Qxe6+  Rf7  21.Rc6  Now the knight from e8 has to be reactivated.  21...Nc7  22.Qe2  Nb5  23.Rc4  Qa5  24.Qc2  White still has a clear advantage with control over the c- and e-files, but Black might be able to generate some play with ...f5-f4 and put the d4-pawn under pressure.  17...Bh6  We really don't want the knight to land on e6 and that White can then take back with the d-pawn. The pawn on e6 would disrupt Black's pieces coordination and fix White's doubled pawns.  18.h4  Bxg5  19.hxg5  Rf7  Black just managed to defend the e7-pawn, but we cannot be very happy here considering that our pieces are all in passive positions. White has a clear advantage. }
10. dxe5
{ Every time White attacks the black center by swapping on e5 and then playing e2-e4. }
10... dxe5 11. Ba3 Rf7 12. e4 f4
{ This move is forced because White threatened to take on f5 and then win the e5-pawn. }
13. gxf4 Nh5
{ In itself a common pawn sacrifice, but here Black cannot create a lot of play. The bishop never reaches g4 and the queen on e8 and the bishop on g7 are not doing a lot either after the text move.   Also not sufficient for Black is  13...Bg4  14.Qc2  Bxf3  15.Bxf3  .  Both the bishop on g7 and the knight on a6 are not very active.  15...Nb8  16.Rad1  Nc6  17.Nd5  White is clearly better with the extra pawn and the more active pieces. }
14. f5 { White is opening the g-file. } 14... gxf5 15. Kh1
{ And ready to put a rook on the g-file. } 15... Nf4 16. Rg1 Kh8 17. Nd5
{ White has a large advantage: the black knight on a6 is completely offside and it is not easy to find a future for the c8-bishop. }
