[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3
{ It is important to note that White can use various move orders to reach the main position of the Leningrad Dutch. Previously, we saw 2.Nf3 but as the saying goes, 'all roads lead to Rome'. }
2... Nf6 3. Bg2 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 Qe8
{ This used to be the old main line for Black which I have played many times myself. Nowadays most people agree that the7...c6 lines  are safer because that move is almost always useful while the queen is not necessarily needed on e8.   Based on the below analysis Black holds in every line, but especially in the lines with  8.b3  and  8.Nd5  the engine gives a clear advantage for White.  Correspondence games have shown that this advantage is not sufficient for White to win, but it is clear that the 7...Qe8 System involves more risk for Black without more upside. }
8. b3
{ For a long time it was underestimated that with this move White often ends up with an advantage because of the Ba3 possibility. }
8... e5
{ It is always a must to analyze the ...e7-e5 break. I found some advantages for White in the following lines, but correspondence games have shown that it is still in the drawing margins, although it is a thin line for Black. }
9. dxe5 dxe5 10. e4
{ This is an essential move, threatening to attack Black's center further with Re1 and stopping Black's idea of ...e5-e4.   Less strong is  10.Ba3  Rf7  11.Qc2  Nc6  and Black's pieces start to coordinate. }
10... Nc6
{ 10...fxe4  11.Ng5  and at some point, there will be a white knight on e4 with a clear advantage. The bishop on g7 doesn't have a good future and Black doesn't have any activity on the kingside. }
11. Nd5 Qd7
{ A strange-looking move, but there is nothing better for Black.   11...Rf7  is a typical move in the Leningrad System, but again  the c8-bishop is being locked in.  12.Ng5  Rd7  13.exf5  . With the strange coordination between Black's pieces, White increases the pressure on Black's center.  13...gxf5  14.Bb2  h6  15.Nxf6+  Bxf6  16.Bd5+  Kg7  17.Nf3  and White had a large advantage in Kasimdzhanov-Miroshnichenko, Konya 2011. }
12. exf5 e4 13. Ng5 { This continuation is not so clear. } 13... gxf5
{ 13...Nxd5  results in an endgame:  14.cxd5  Bxa1  15.dxc6  White is not afraid to exchange queens despite being an exchange down.  15...Qxd1  16.Rxd1  Bg7  17.Bxe4  , taking a pawn and threatening to  win more material on b7.  17...bxc6  18.fxg6  hxg6  19.Ba3  White has a pawn for the exchange,  two powerful bishops, and is ready to take either on g6 or c6. I think in a practical game very few Black players will survive. }
14. Rb1
{ Shankland assesses this position as better for White, but a correspondence game has shown that Black can hold. }
14... h6 { As always, chasing the knight away from g5. } 15. Nh3 Nxd5 16. cxd5
Nb4
{ Targeting the d5-pawn since Black needs to take action. Otherwise, we will suffer for the awkward position of the bishop on c8. }
17. Ba3 a5 18. Nf4 Rd8 { Targeting the pawn on d5 and defending against Ne6. }
19. Ne6 { This move is not clear because Black can sacrifice an exchange. }
19... Qxe6 20. dxe6 Rxd1 21. Rfxd1 Bxe6
{ Black has good compensation for the small material deficit, as proven in the game Marez-Polsterer, ICCF email 2017. }
