{ It is always a must to analyze the ...e7-e5 break. I found some advantages for White in the following lines, but correspondence games have shown that it is still in the drawing margins, although it is a thin line for Black. }
9. dxe5 dxe5 10. e4
{ This is an essential move, threatening to attack Black's center further with Re1 and stopping Black's idea of ...e5-e4.   Less strong is  10.Ba3  Rf7  11.Qc2  Nc6  and Black's pieces start to coordinate. }
10... Nc6
{ 10...fxe4  11.Ng5  and at some point, there will be a white knight on e4 with a clear advantage. The bishop on g7 doesn't have a good future and Black doesn't have any activity on the kingside. }
11. Nd5 Qd7
{ A strange-looking move, but there is nothing better for Black.   11...Rf7  is a typical move in the Leningrad System, but again  the c8-bishop is being locked in.  12.Ng5  Rd7  13.exf5  . With the strange coordination between Black's pieces, White increases the pressure on Black's center.  13...gxf5  14.Bb2  h6  15.Nxf6+  Bxf6  16.Bd5+  Kg7  17.Nf3  and White had a large advantage in Kasimdzhanov-Miroshnichenko, Konya 2011. }
12. exf5 e4 13. Nh4 { A strong move after which Black is in trouble. } 13...
gxf5 14. Nf4
{ Underlining that Black is way behind in development and it will take awhile before the c8-bishop becomes active. }
14... Nd4 15. Bb2 c5 16. f3
{ White continues to put pressure on Black's position, first on the d4-knight, now on the e4-pawn. }
16... Re8
{ The natural move  16...exf3  loses because Black is not yet ready to open the position  with the bishop still on c8.  17.Nxf3  Ne6  18.Qxd7  Bxd7  19.Nxe6  Bxe6  20.Ng5  and Black is in big trouble. }
17. Bxd4 Qxd4+ 18. Kh1
{ And now Black exchanges queens to maximize the power of the e-pawn. } 18...
Qxd1 19. Raxd1 e3 20. Ne2 { White can also first play  20.Rfe1  and then Ne2. }
20... f4
{ Making use of the fact that  21.Nxf4  is not an option because of  21...e2  and Black is not afraid of @@StartFEN@@r1b1r1k1/pp4bp/5n2/2p5/2P2p1N/1P2pPP1/P3N1BP/3R1R1K w - - 0 21@@EndFEN@@  21.gxf4  ,  which locks in the bishop on g2 and also gives little prospect for the knight on h4. }
21. Rfe1 Bh6 22. Bf1 a5
{ Potentially opening the queenside with ...a5-a4 to activate the rook on a8. }
23. Nxf4 Bxf4 24. gxf4 Nh5
{ Continuing to play actively both on the kingside and the queenside. } 25. Ng2
Bh3 { Black's moves are easy to find, we just keep on attacking. } 26. Nxe3
Bxf1 27. Nxf1 Nxf4
{ In this endgame Black has nothing to worry about. Despite the pawn deficit, we have sufficient counterplay with ...a5-a4, the strong knight on f4, and the possibility to activate the king. }
