[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3
{ It is important to note that White can use various move orders to reach the main position of the Leningrad Dutch. Previously, we saw 2.Nf3 but as the saying goes, 'all roads lead to Rome'. }
2... Nf6 3. Bg2 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 Qe8
{ This used to be the old main line for Black which I have played many times myself. Nowadays most people agree that the7...c6 lines  are safer because that move is almost always useful while the queen is not necessarily needed on e8.   Based on the below analysis Black holds in every line, but especially in the lines with  8.b3  and  8.Nd5  the engine gives a clear advantage for White.  Correspondence games have shown that this advantage is not sufficient for White to win, but it is clear that the 7...Qe8 System involves more risk for Black without more upside. }
8. Re1 e5
{ The standard break in the center but a bit risky with White's rook on e1. }
9. e4
{ Immediately exchanging in the center is not so dangerous for Black in this case:  9.dxe5  dxe5  10.e4  Nc6  .  It is important to develop this knight as soon as possible to c6, in many lines the knight jump to d4 saves Black's position.  11.Nd5  ,  attacking c7.  11...fxe4  . Now  12.Nxc7  loses to  12...Qf7  and next Black takes a piece on f3 and then the knight on a8 will be captured.   @@StartFEN@@r1b1qrk1/ppp3bp/2n2np1/3Np3/2P1p3/5NP1/PP3PBP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Ng5  Qd8  13.Nxf6+  Qxf6  14.Nxe4  Qf5  ,  staying on the f-file, in combination with a knight on d4 ready to go to f3.  15.Be3  Nd4  Black has sufficient counterplay in exchange for the fact that the pawn on e5 is securely blocked and the bishop on g7 a bit passive. }
9... Nc6
{ If White now plays  10.d5  , Black will play  10...Nd8  followed by  11.--  Nf7  with a fine position. }
10. exf5 Bxf5 11. h3
{ The standard idea of putting a knight on e4 is not sufficient for White to claim an edge because Black will have counterplay with a knight coming to d4.  11.dxe5  dxe5  12.Ng5  h6  13.Nge4  Nxe4  14.Nxe4  Rd8  .   White is in some trouble − the queen doesn't have a natural square and Black has an active knight coming to d4 in combination with ...Qf7, attacking both the pawn on c4 but also threatening to take on e4 and then on f2. }
11... Qf7
{ Giving up the defense of the e5-pawn but attacking the pawn on c4. } 12. dxe5
Nxe5
{ Taking back with the pawn on e5 is not OK for Black:  12...dxe5  13.Qb3  e4  14.Ng5  and this position is clearly better for White. The e4-pawn is weak, White's pieces are more active and there can always be nasty checks with c4-c5.   A sample line:  14...Qd7  15.Be3  h6  , exchanging the e4-pawn for the pawn on  h3  .  16.Ngxe4  Nxe4  17.Nxe4  Bxh3  .  But now it becomes clear that the b7-pawn will fall.  18.Nc5  Qc8  19.Bd5+  Kh7  20.Nxb7  and White has a large advantage with the extra pawn and the more active position. }
13. Ng5 Qd7 14. g4
{ The black bishop is in trouble, but Black can attack the knight. } 14... h6
15. gxf5 hxg5 { Black's moves are all forced. } 16. fxg6 Nxg6
{ Instead of taking on g6, bringing the a-rook to e8 is likely to transpose and doesn't make a big difference. }
17. Bxg5 Qf5 18. Qd2
{ And White has an extra pawn and I don't believe Black has sufficient compensation. It is not directly winning for White, but without having created any clear weaknesses, I am not sure why we would want to play this with Black. }
