{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 Qe8
{ This used to be the old main line for Black which I have played many times myself. Nowadays most people agree that the7...c6 lines  are safer because that move is almost always useful while the queen is not necessarily needed on e8.   Based on the below analysis Black holds in every line, but especially in the lines with  8.b3  and  8.Nd5  the engine gives a clear advantage for White.  Correspondence games have shown that this advantage is not sufficient for White to win, but it is clear that the 7...Qe8 System involves more risk for Black without more upside. }
8. Qb3
{ The idea of this move is to take control over the light squares, possibly with Ng5 in combination with c4-c5+ and e2-e4 focusing on the squares e6 and f7, and to put pressure on Black's queenside, specifically on the b7-pawn. }
8... Na6 9. Bd2
{ A normal development move, but not something to be scared of with Black. }
9... h6 { Preparing ...g6-g5. } 10. c5+ Kh7 11. cxd6 exd6
{ It is logical to take back with the e-pawn as we immediately get rid of the weak e-pawn. }
12. Rac1 c6
{ Taking control over the d5-square and the pawn is much more stable on c6 than on c7 after Rac1. }
13. Bf4 Qe7 { There is no better way of defending the pawn on d6. } 14. d5 Nh5
{ Chasing away the bishop before White puts a rook on d1 and takes on c6 in order to win the pawn on d6. }
15. dxc6
{ If White plays  15.Bd2  , Black continues with  15...Nc5  without any problems. }
15... Nxf4 16. cxb7 Bxb7 17. gxf4
{ Black has sacrificed a pawn but has now two powerful bishops and the knight is ready to come to c5. }
17... Nc5 18. Qd1 Rad8
{ Black has sufficient counterplay for the sacrificed pawn, all the pieces are active and the white extra pawn is on the f-file, clearly not going anywhere. }
