{ The standard move in the 7...Qe8 system, preparing to attack d5, making sure the knight can come to c7 and the pawn on b7 no longer hangs if Black plays a later ...e7-e5. }
11. dxc6 bxc6 12. b4 { White is threatening b4-b5. } 12... Rc8
{ Black can also play  12...Nxb4  with the idea that after  13.Rxb4  we win back the material with  13...c5  . In this line, Black typically sacrifices an exchange and  gets a passed pawn on c3. Still, I am not convinced it completely equalizes, so I don't recommend it. }
13. b5
{ If White plays the slow approach with  13.Nc2  ,  preventing ...e7-e5 because the d6-pawn would hang, Black simply plays  13...Qf7  ,  attacking the pawn on c4. }
13... cxb5 14. cxb5 Rxc3
{ I don't recommend  14...Nc5  here because White has a nice square on c6 for the knight. }
15. bxa6 e5
{ White can also sacrifice a piece in the hope to promote the a-pawn, which is a dangerous option. }
16. Rb7 exd4 17. Qxd4 Ne4 18. Qxa7 Rf7 19. Be3 Rc8
{ I think White has full compensation for the piece but no more than that. In certain lines Black manages to exchange both pairs of rooks but loses the d6-pawn and with three pawns including the advanced a-pawn White is okay. }
*

