1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3
{ It is important to note that White can use various move orders to reach the main position of the Leningrad Dutch. Previously, we saw 2.Nf3 but as the saying goes, 'all roads lead to Rome'. }
2... Nf6 3. Bg2 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 Qe8
{ This used to be the old main line for Black which I have played many times myself. Nowadays most people agree that the7...c6 lines  are safer because that move is almost always useful while the queen is not necessarily needed on e8.   Based on the below analysis Black holds in every line, but especially in the lines with  8.b3  and  8.Nd5  the engine gives a clear advantage for White.  Correspondence games have shown that this advantage is not sufficient for White to win, but it is clear that the 7...Qe8 System involves more risk for Black without more upside. }
8. d5
{ One of the main moves that has been played by many strong grandmasters. Nowadays no longer seen as the main threat to the Leningrad System. }
8... Na6
{ Preparing a typical setup with ...c7-c6 followed by either ...Nc5-e4 or ...e7-e5. }
9. Nd4 { Preventing ...c7-c6 for now. } 9... Bd7
{ And preparing ...c7-c6 again. } 10. Rb1 { Preparing b2-b4. } 10... c6
{ The standard move in the 7...Qe8 system, preparing to attack d5, making sure the knight can come to c7 and the pawn on b7 no longer hangs if Black plays a later ...e7-e5. }
11. b3 Nc7
{ Maintaining control over the e6-square. Black has a number of plans here: we can take on d5 followed by playing ...b7-b5, although usually not with a knight on d4 that can go to c6. Therefore more likely is ...c6-c5 followed by ...b7-b5 @@StartBracket@@sometimes prepared by ...a7-a6@@EndBracket@@ and ...e7-e5 is also an option, although Black needs to be careful not to end up in a passive position. }
12. Bb2 c5 13. Nc2 g5
{ It is important for Black to combine play on the queenside with play on the kingside. Here White has put the knight on c2 and is well-prepared for Black's actions on the queenside, but the knight is far away too.   13...b5  is a standard approach in these types of positions but it works better if the knight  is on f3, on c2 White tends to be ready for Black's queenside play.  14.cxb5  Nxb5  15.Nxb5  Bxb5  16.b4  and White can probably claim some advantage, Black still has the  weak square on e6 while the action on the queenside has not resulted in any weaknesses on the white side.    13...a6  , this move is a bit slow when  the knight is on c2.  14.b4  cxb4  15.Nxb4  a5  a  typical move to give the knight on c7 a future on c5.  16.Nd3  Na6  and White is a bit better because with the knight on d3 the black knight coming to c5 can be challenged and when Black starts hitting the pawn on c4, we might lose our own pawn on a5. }
14. e3 Qg6
{ And Black's position is fine, we are ready to push ...f5-f4, and if White plays Ne2 to prevent this, Black uses the fact the knight has moved away from the queenside to push ...b7-b5. }
