1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3
{ It is important to note that White can use various move orders to reach the main position of the Leningrad Dutch. Previously, we saw 2.Nf3 but as the saying goes, 'all roads lead to Rome'. }
2... Nf6 3. Bg2 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 Qe8
{ This used to be the old main line for Black which I have played many times myself. Nowadays most people agree that the7...c6 lines  are safer because that move is almost always useful while the queen is not necessarily needed on e8.   Based on the below analysis Black holds in every line, but especially in the lines with  8.b3  and  8.Nd5  the engine gives a clear advantage for White.  Correspondence games have shown that this advantage is not sufficient for White to win, but it is clear that the 7...Qe8 System involves more risk for Black without more upside. }
8. d5
{ One of the main moves that has been played by many strong grandmasters. Nowadays no longer seen as the main threat to the Leningrad System. }
8... Na6
{ Preparing a typical setup with ...c7-c6 followed by either ...Nc5-e4 or ...e7-e5. }
9. Nd4 { Preventing ...c7-c6 for now. } 9... Bd7
{ And preparing ...c7-c6 again. } 10. Rb1 { Preparing b2-b4. } 10... c6
{ The standard move in the 7...Qe8 system, preparing to attack d5, making sure the knight can come to c7 and the pawn on b7 no longer hangs if Black plays a later ...e7-e5. }
11. b3 Nc5 { This is a solid alternative for Black here. } 12. Bb2 e5
{ I don't trust this standard central push in this specific position. } 13.
dxe6 Bxe6
{ Taking with the knight on e6 is also an option but runs into the same problem, Black ends up with a rather passive position and a weak pawn on d6. }
14. Nxe6 Qxe6 15. e3
{ And now what with Black? Yes, we have full control over the e4-square, but we also want to make progress. Typical plans are to either put a knight on e4 followed by playing ...d6-d5 in such a way that we can take back with a piece on d5 and liquidate to an equal endgame; or to advance on the kingside with ...g6-g5 and even the h-pawn, but here that feels more weakening for Black than threatening for White. }
15... Ng4
{ 15...Nce4  doesn't seem to work, the following line is for illustration, but important to get familiar with the concepts because when playing the Leningrad System, we will need to assess these types of positions and know which ones are okay and which ones are not.  16.Qc2  Nxc3  Black's idea is to push ...d6-d5 in such a way that we don't end up with an isolated pawn on d5.    17.Bxc3  d5  18.cxd5  Nxd5  19.Bxg7  Kxg7  20.Bxd5  White doesn't need to take on d5, b3-b4 is also a good option.  20...Qxd5  21.Rfd1  Qe6  22.Qc5  and Black is in trouble, Rd6 followed by Rbd1 is a serious threat and if Black opposes on the d-file we lose the a7-pawn. Often the assessment of these types of positions are all about one or two tempi that make the difference. }
16. Qc2 Rad8 17. h3 Nf6 18. Ne2 Rfe8
{ White had a clear advantage in the correspondence game Gerbich-Freydl, ICCF email 2004. White is ready to play b3-b4-b5 and Black has little counterplay. }
