[White "3. Leningrad Variation 7...Qe8 − Alternative"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 7...Qe8 − Alternative − 8.Qc2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3
{ It is important to note that White can use various move orders to reach the main position of the Leningrad Dutch. Previously, we saw 2.Nf3 but as the saying goes, 'all roads lead to Rome'. }
2... Nf6 3. Bg2 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 Qe8
{ This used to be the old main line for Black which I have played many times myself. Nowadays most people agree that the7...c6 lines  are safer because that move is almost always useful while the queen is not necessarily needed on e8.   Based on the below analysis Black holds in every line, but especially in the lines with  8.b3  and  8.Nd5  the engine gives a clear advantage for White.  Correspondence games have shown that this advantage is not sufficient for White to win, but it is clear that the 7...Qe8 System involves more risk for Black without more upside. }
8. Qc2
{ This move has the idea to prepare e2-e4, but if White wants to play like that, it is better to do so with a rook on e1 opposite the queen on e8. }
8... e5
{ Of course, nothing is stopping Black from playing the central break. } 9.
dxe5 dxe5 10. e4 Nc6
{ It is too early for ...f5-f4, Black has not developed the queenside yet. The knight is well-positioned on c6, in many situations it will jump to d4 now that the white queen is on c2. }
11. Re1 h6
{ Maybe  11...f4  is possible for Black here, it will result in unclear play after  12.gxf4  Bg4  , but there is no need to make it so complex,  Black is fine after ...h7-h6. }
12. Be3 Qf7
{ Threatening to take on c4, but ...f5-f4 also becomes a serious option. } 13.
exf5 Bxf5 14. Qb3 e4 15. Nh4 b6
{ And Black has equalized, has no weaknesses, and more space in the center. The knight can come to e5 and if White exchanges  16.Nxf5  gxf5  ,  the black queen can come to h5 with ...Ng4 and ...Nf3 ideas. }
