[White "3. Leningrad Variation 7...Qe8 − Alternative"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 7...Qe8 − Alternative − 8.Nd5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3
{ It is important to note that White can use various move orders to reach the main position of the Leningrad Dutch. Previously, we saw 2.Nf3 but as the saying goes, 'all roads lead to Rome'. }
2... Nf6 3. Bg2 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 Qe8
{ This used to be the old main line for Black which I have played many times myself. Nowadays most people agree that the7...c6 lines  are safer because that move is almost always useful while the queen is not necessarily needed on e8.   Based on the below analysis Black holds in every line, but especially in the lines with  8.b3  and  8.Nd5  the engine gives a clear advantage for White.  Correspondence games have shown that this advantage is not sufficient for White to win, but it is clear that the 7...Qe8 System involves more risk for Black without more upside. }
8. Nd5 { This is the move that worries me. } 8... Nxd5
{ Black has to take on d5, if we protect the c7-pawn with  8...Na6  , White will play  9.Nxf6+  followed by e2-e4 and Black lacks counterplay. }
9. cxd5 Nd7 10. Ng5 Nb6
{ In practice this move is played more often than ...Nf6, but I believe based on my analysis, that after ...Nb6 Black's task is more difficult than after ...Nf6. }
11. Qc2
{ After  11.a4  , I have not been able to find a clear advantage for White.  11...c6  12.Qb3  .  It looks logical to increase the pressure on the light squares, but Black is in time.   12.dxc6  Taking on c6 always needs to be studied.  12...bxc6  13.Qb3+   13.a5  is not dangerous for Black since the knight wanted to go to d5 anyway.  13...Nd5  14.Qb3  e6  .  This position is about equal, White may continue with Re1 and then e2-e4, Black can play ...h7-h6 and ...Ba6 and then a rook to b8.   13.d5  c5  only move as taking on d5 loses material because of the check on d5 and the rook on a8.  14.Qc2  Rb8  15.Bd2   15.Ne6  is the direct approach, White doesn't wait for ...h7-h6.  15...Bxe6  16.dxe6  Qc8  Black has to start attacking pawns as doing nothing is worse in the long-term because White has a good pair of bishops and more space.  17.Rb1  Qxe6  18.b4  cxb4  .  I prefer to take on b4 so White can forget about ideas with b4-b5 in combination with a4-a5.  19.Rxb4  Rbc8  ,  rooks belong on open files.  20.Qd3  Rc3  21.Qd1  Rc5  Black is a healthy pawn up. For the time being White has compensation with the pair of bishops, but needs to play precisely or may end up worse.  15...h6  .  The engine says that ...Bb7 is a valid alternative, but I don't like to allow a knight on e6 in the Leningrad System.  16.Ne6  Bxe6  17.dxe6  Qc8  ,  threatening to take on e6.  18.a5  Na8  .  Yes, the knight is on an ugly square, but only for one move.  19.Rab1  Nc7  and Black has equalized, with pressure against both the e6-pawn and the b2-pawn which compensates for the pair of bishops White has.  13...e6  I had expected this position to be better for White, but I failed to prove it.  14.e4  is of course the most critical attempt.   14.Bf4  is a normal developing move, but it fails to put Black under real pressure.  14...h6  ,  chasing away the knight on g5 is a good starting move in many positions.  15.Nf3  Qd7  ,  defending the pawn on e6 with the idea to play ...Ba6-c4.  16.Rac1  g5  ,  expanding on the kingside but also limiting the power of White's bishop: on d2 it is more passive.  17.Bd2  Ba6  and we have reached a sharp position with mutual chances.  A sample line:  18.h4  g4  19.Ne1  Nd5  ,  with the idea to play ...f5-f4.  20.Nd3  Rab8  ,  winning the pawn in b2.  21.Qa3  Bxd3  22.Qxd3  Rxb2  Black is one move away from a clear advantage @@StartBracket@@...Nf6@@EndBracket@@ but White comes first.  23.e4  fxe4  24.Bxe4  Ra2  .  Not only attacking the a4-pawn but also preparing a later ...Ra4 to hit the d4-pawn.  25.a5  Ne7  White has compensation for the pawn, but Black is not getting mated any time soon and we can try to win the d4-pawn with Ra4, so it is a complex position with mutual chances.   14.Re1  White is playing the logical plan of Re1 in combination with e2-e4, which makes a lot of sense with the knight on g5 and the queen on b3.  14...h6  Black has to get rid of the annoying knight before White plays e2-e4.  15.Nf3  Nd5  ,  blocking the view of the queen on b3.  16.e4  fxe4  17.Rxe4  Bd7  Black is simply completing development.  18.Qa3  Rb8  .   We have reached a complex position with mutual chances. Be aware that the pawn on d6 is defended. If White takes Black can immediately force a draw.  19.Qxd6  Rxf3  .  This may come as a surprise to the White player.  20.Bxf3  Bf8  and it turns out the white queen has only one square.  21.Qe5  Bg7  with a draw because Black can keep on attacking the queen with ...Bf8-g7.  14...fxe4  15.a5  Nd5  16.Nxe4  Ba6  Black needs to develop with tempo, otherwise, we cannot hold everything together.  17.Re1  Rb8  18.Qd1  and now Black is just in time to become active.  18...Rb4  targeting the pawn on d4.  19.Ra4  Qb8  20.Rxb4  Qxb4  Black continues to put pressure on the d4, a5 and b2-pawns.  21.Bh3  Bc8  22.Bd2  White cannot defend everything.  22...Qxd4  23.Qb3  Nc7  and Black seems to be OK. Many variations result in equal endgames, one sample line:   23...Kh8  might also work.  24.Qb8  Ba6  Black is about to lose all the central pawns so speed is needed.  25.Qxd6  Bd3  .  The knight cannot move because the f2-pawn would fall.  26.Bc3  Nxc3  27.bxc3  Qxd6  28.Nxd6  and Black has sufficient counterplay considering the pawns on c3 and a5 are weak.  24.Bc3  Qd5  ,  an ideal square for the queen, too bad it loses the protection of the pawn on d6.  25.Qxd5  exd5  26.Bxc8  ,  some massive exchanges.  26...Bxc3  27.bxc3  dxe4  .  Taking on c8 would be bad: White takes with the knight on d7 followed by Re7 resulting in a clear advantage.  28.Bd7  c5  29.Rxe4  Kf7  .  We have reached an endgame that is equal but not a draw yet. Black can try to advance the d-pawn and then target White's c- and a-pawns.  12...Nxd5  ,  simply gaining the pair of bishops.  13.Bxd5+  cxd5  14.Qxd5+  Kh8  and Black has no problems. We can kick the knight with ...h7-h6 and after Ne6 there is usually ...Qf7 and there are also lines where ...Qc6 comes in handy. Note that in many endgames Black has better chances because of the pair of bishops. }
11... Qa4
{ White's best option is probably to sacrifice the pawn on d4 after b2-b3 resulting in big complications. }
12. b3 Qxd4 13. Be3 Qb4 14. Qxc7
{ White has managed to get rid of the double d-pawn in exchange for the pawn on c7. The queen is quite annoying on c7, the knight is ready to jump to e6 and after it gets exchanged, the bishop on g2 will be powerful. Meanwhile, the knight on b6 doesn’t have a lot of prospects with the pawn on b3. }
14... f4
{ 14...Bf6  −  because in the main line with 14...f4 I could not find equality, I started looking for alternatives and this move simply defends the pawn on e7.  15.Rac1  Qb5  16.Ne6  Bxe6  ,  Black cannot keep the knight on e6 alive.  17.dxe6  Nd5  . I see no other way for Black to become active.  18.Qd7  Qa5  .  The endgame after taking on d5 and taking the bishop on e3 is not okay for Black. Soon there will be a white rook on c7 and the pawn on d7 is annoying as well.  19.Bxd5  Qxd5  20.Rfd1  Qa5  21.Bh6  , Black is in trouble since the king is not safe and the pieces lack space.  21...Rfd8  22.Qxb7  Rab8  23.Qc7  Qxa2  24.Rxd6  and White has a large advantage.  Black cannot take with the rook on d6 because the rook on b8 would drop and taking with the pawn fails to Qf7+.   Taking the rook cannot be advised, Black will soon be mated:  14...Bxa1  15.Qxe7  Bg7  16.Rc1  ,  White is threatening Rc7 and taking away the c3-square from the black queen.  16...h6  17.a3  Qxa3  18.Bd4  , White sacrifices another rook for a winning attack. After  18...Qxc1  19.Bf1  Black will need to give up all the material to avoid mate. }
15. gxf4
{ My improvement over an important correspondence game.   15.Bxb6  was played in Yefremov-Williamson, ICCF email 2014.  15...Qxb6  16.Rac1  fxg3  17.hxg3  Bf6  .  The position looks suspicious to me, but every time Black seems to escape.  18.Ne6   18.Ne4  was another try from me to improve White's play.  18...Rf7  19.a4  Bg4  20.Qxb6  axb6  21.Rfe1  and White's advantage is not resulting in anything concrete. Black will play something like ...Ra5 followed by ...b6-b5, liquidating the weak queenside.  18...Bxe6  19.dxe6  ,  yes, White is better here, but many lines result in endgames with opposite-colored bishops that Black can hold.  19...Bg5   19...Rab8  ,  this may also hold for Black.  20.Qxb6  axb6  21.Rc7  Rfc8  22.Rfc1  Rxc7  23.Rxc7  b5  24.Bxb7  b4  .  And this seems to me to be a position Black can draw.  20.Rc4   20.Qxb6  is a key alternative with a different type of play than in the game.  20...axb6  21.f4  Bf6  22.a4  b5  23.Bxb7   23.axb5  Bd4+  24.Kh1  Rf5  .  It will take a few moves but Black will succeed in winning the b-pawns.  25.Bxb7  Ra2  26.g4  Rxb5  27.Rc8+  Kg7  28.Rc7  Kf8  29.Be4  d5  30.Bd3  Rxb3  with a likely draw.  bxa4  24.Bxa8  Rxa8  25.bxa4  Rxa4  26.Kg2  Re4  27.Kf3  Rxe6  28.g4  g5  29.e3  h5  .  I don't believe White can win this endgame.  20...Rfc8  21.Qxc8+  Rxc8  22.Rxc8+  Kg7  and eventually this game ended in a draw − Yefremov-Williamson, ICCF email 2014. }
15... Bxa1 16. Rxa1 Re8
{ White has sacrificed an exchange but also has a pawn for it and the dark squares around Black's king are weak. }
17. Qc1 Bd7 18. Bd2 Qc5 19. Qb2
{ White is getting ready for Bc3 and Bh8 with mate. } 19... Rac8 20. Ne4 Qb5
21. Bc3 { Black has to return the exchange. } 21... Rxc3 22. Nxc3 Qb4 23. e3
{ And White has a healthy extra pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Leningrad Variation 7...Qe8 − Alternative"]
[Black "Leningrad Variation 7...Qe8 − Alternative − 8.Nd5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3
{ It is important to note that White can use various move orders to reach the main position of the Leningrad Dutch. Previously, we saw 2.Nf3 but as the saying goes, 'all roads lead to Rome'. }
2... Nf6 3. Bg2 g6
{ This repertoire starts with the moves 1...f5 and 2...Nf6. In most of the lines, you will see that on move three we play  3...g6  followed  by a later ...d7-d6. Considering that in 95% of the repertoire we don’t play ...d7-d5, Black could also first play  3...d6  on move three and on move  4.--  g6  . This will result in a transposition. }
4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6
{ Black has developed the kingside and now starts focusing on one of the most typical plans in the Leningrad System: preparing ...e7-e5. }
7. Nc3 Qe8
{ This used to be the old main line for Black which I have played many times myself. Nowadays most people agree that the7...c6 lines  are safer because that move is almost always useful while the queen is not necessarily needed on e8.   Based on the below analysis Black holds in every line, but especially in the lines with  8.b3  and  8.Nd5  the engine gives a clear advantage for White.  Correspondence games have shown that this advantage is not sufficient for White to win, but it is clear that the 7...Qe8 System involves more risk for Black without more upside. }
8. Nd5 { This is the move that worries me. } 8... Nxd5
{ Black has to take on d5, if we protect the c7-pawn with  8...Na6  , White will play  9.Nxf6+  followed by e2-e4 and Black lacks counterplay. }
9. cxd5 Nd7 10. Ng5 Nf6
{ This is probably Black's best option in the 8.Nd5 line. } 11. Qb3 h6
{ We have to get rid of the knight, otherwise Black cannot develop the pieces. }
12. Ne6 Bxe6 13. dxe6 Rb8 { Just in time to defend the b7-pawn. } 14. Be3
{ This is a strange move from White but the idea is that after d4-d5 the pawn on a7 hangs. Black responds in a normal way. }
14... c6 { Taking control over the d5-square. } 15. Rac1 g5 16. d5 c5
{ Black is a tempo down compared to another line with asimilar position but with the queen already on g6. White's extra tempo in this position doesn't make a big difference, Black is OK. We can play ...b7-b5 like in a Benoni, but Black can also aim for play on the kingside with ...Ng4 followed by ...f5-f4. }
*

