[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Dutch 2.g3 − b4 Systems"]
[Black "Dutch 2.g3 − b4 Systems − 4.b4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ In this overview I will discuss the lines where at some point White plays b2-b4. The big difference is whether there is already a white pawn on c4 or not yet. In general, I recommend a Stonewall setup.  I have also given as an illustration the line where Black plays a setup with ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5, but often my analysis ended in a position that is not fully satisfactory for Black. But in a practical game, you may still want to play that as the chances White will play all the perfect moves are slim. }
4. b4
{ The idea of this move is to play a b4 system with the bishop still on f1. Not often seen in practice, but you need to realize that if you play with ...Nc6 with Black, White may push b4-b5 and if you move then your knight to a5, White can still decide to play e2-e3 and cover the c4-square with the bishop. }
4... Bg7 5. Bb2 d5
{ White still had the possibility to play c2-c4, so Black’s plans with ...d7-d6 followed by ...e7-e5 may result in slightly worse positions. In general, I recommend the ...d7-d5 push in all the b4-lines. }
6. Bg2 a5
{ Black can also castle kingside, but I like to immediately attack the pawn on b4 before White gets the chance to consolidate. }
7. b5
{ If White defends the pawn on b4 with  7.a3  , Black can exchange  7...axb4  8.axb4  Rxa1  9.Bxa1  and continue with  9...Qd6  . White will need to  defend the b4-pawn again and next Black can play ...Ne4 followed by ...e7-e5. In no time, Black has freed the position. }
7... c6 8. bxc6 Nxc6
{ This was Black’s idea by playing 6...a5, we won a tempo to develop the knight on b8. }
9. O-O O-O 10. a4 Ne4
{ White has weaknesses on the c4 and c3-squares and Black would like to make use of that by first preventing White's c2-c4 and then by creating pressure on the queenside. The idea of ...Ne4 is that it prepares ...Be6  (controlling the square c4)  because there is no Ng5 from White anymore and the black knight on e4 could later either go to c3  (if supported by a rook on c8)  or come back to d6 to have more control over the c4-square. }
11. Nbd2 Be6 12. e3 Rc8
{ The engine says it is still equal, but Black’s position is easier to play I think. We are ready to play moves like ...Nb4 and ...Qb6 and White doesn’t have any active plans. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Dutch 2.g3 − b4 Systems"]
[Black "Dutch 2.g3 − b4 Systems − 4.Bg2 Bg7 5.b4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ In this overview I will discuss the lines where at some point White plays b2-b4. The big difference is whether there is already a white pawn on c4 or not yet. In general, I recommend a Stonewall setup.  I have also given as an illustration the line where Black plays a setup with ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5, but often my analysis ended in a position that is not fully satisfactory for Black. But in a practical game, you may still want to play that as the chances White will play all the perfect moves are slim. }
4. Bg2
{ I will discuss first the lines with b2-b4 where the white c-pawn is not yet on c4. }
4... Bg7 5. b4 { White can play b2-b4 before castling kingside. } 5... d5
{ Black immediately plays this move to have control over the c4-square now that b2-b3 is not an option anymore. }
6. O-O O-O
{ I prefer to first bring my king to safety before developing the queenside. }
7. Nbd2 Ne4
{ Normally I would prefer to first develop the queenside but with the knight on e4 Black has two purposes: to control the g5-square so that if we play ...Be6, the bishop won't get hit by Ng5. Also, Black is asking White what to do next so we can optimize the placing of the knight on b8 depending on White’s plans. }
8. c4
{ Sooner or later White has to play this move, otherwise, the position is too passive. }
8... dxc4 9. Nxc4 Nc6
{ This is the advantage of waiting for Black by first playing ...Ne4, now the knight on c6 attacks both d4 and b4. }
10. Bb2 Nxb4 11. Qb3 Nd5
{ The only move for Black as the knight was hanging on b4 and we want to block the queen on b3 from giving check. The position is about equal, next Black can stabilize the knight on d5 by playing ...c7-c6 and prepare the development of the c8-bishop. The only thing to watch out for is that White is hoping for some form of f2-f3 followed by e2-e4 to get a lot of control in the center. }
*

