[White "4. Dutch 2.g3 − b4 Systems"]
[Black "Dutch 2.g3 − b4 Systems − 4.Bg2 Bg7 5.b4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ In this overview I will discuss the lines where at some point White plays b2-b4. The big difference is whether there is already a white pawn on c4 or not yet. In general, I recommend a Stonewall setup.  I have also given as an illustration the line where Black plays a setup with ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5, but often my analysis ended in a position that is not fully satisfactory for Black. But in a practical game, you may still want to play that as the chances White will play all the perfect moves are slim. }
4. Bg2
{ I will discuss first the lines with b2-b4 where the white c-pawn is not yet on c4. }
4... Bg7 5. b4 { White can play b2-b4 before castling kingside. } 5... d5
{ Black immediately plays this move to have control over the c4-square now that b2-b3 is not an option anymore. }
6. O-O O-O
{ I prefer to first bring my king to safety before developing the queenside. }
7. a4 Ne4
{ This move has several ideas: White cannot always simply play Nbd2 because of ...Nc3, Black prepares potential future breaks with ...e7-e5 or ...c7-c5. Also, often in these systems, the bishop from c8 comes to e6, and then we want to rule out Ng5. }
8. Bf4 a5 { Disrupting White's pawn structure. } 9. b5 c5
{ An important move − whenever we have the chance, we try to become active with Black. Considering White has taken control over the square e5, the ...e7-e5 break is not easy to achieve. Similarly, ...g6-g5 is not logical because if Black plays ...h7-h6, there is always h2-h4. }
10. Be5 Nd7
{ Not just attacking the bishop, it is a must to continue developing the pieces. }
11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. e3 Qc7
{ And here Black played  12...c4  in Delizia-Even, ICCF email 2017, which is a good move to reach equality, but it also makes the position a bit dry. If you prefer to keep more tension, 12...Qc7 is a fine move. }
13. c4 { White needs to play this at some point. } 13... dxc4 14. Nbd2 c3
{ Black is in for a complex fight. I don’t fully trust moving the knight to b6 on move 14 because there is a line where White can sacrifice the bishop for three dangerous pawns. }
15. Nxe4 fxe4 16. Ng5 Nf6
{ Simply defending the pawn and threatening to play ...Bf5, when the knight on g5 could get in trouble after ...h7-h6. }
17. Nxe4 Nxe4 18. Bxe4 cxd4
{ Black defends the pawn on c3 even before it is attacked. } 19. exd4 e5
{ Black is fine here having resolved the weak pawn on e7, and is ready to attack f2 after playing ...Bh3, and bring the a-rook to c8, to defend c3. Even if White manages to win back the pawn on c3, there is the chance that Black can create chances on the kingside. And if that doesn’t work, Black still has no worries, the rooks, queen, and bishop on h3 are all active and Black has no weak pawns. }
