[Black "Dutch 2.g3 − b4 Systems − 4.Bg2 Bg7 5.b4 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ In this overview I will discuss the lines where at some point White plays b2-b4. The big difference is whether there is already a white pawn on c4 or not yet. In general, I recommend a Stonewall setup.  I have also given as an illustration the line where Black plays a setup with ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5, but often my analysis ended in a position that is not fully satisfactory for Black. But in a practical game, you may still want to play that as the chances White will play all the perfect moves are slim. }
4. Bg2
{ I will discuss first the lines with b2-b4 where the white c-pawn is not yet on c4. }
4... Bg7 5. b4 { White can play b2-b4 before castling kingside. } 5... Nc6
{ The alternative setup for Black is to play for ...e7-e5 and in these lines, I think Black is fine. There are some setups with the pawn on c4 where I am a bit worried. }
6. c3
{ Yes, this move protects b4, but it doesn't stop Black from preparing ...e7-e5. }
6... d6 7. Qb3 a6
{ Ensuring the knight can no longer be attacked with b4-b5, which is again useful for preparing ...e7-e5. }
8. O-O
{ So far we have been following the game Van Wely-Nijboer, Amsterdam 2004, and now I suggest an improvement. }
8... e5
{ In the game,  8...e6  was played but I see no reason to wait with ...e7-e5. }
9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Rd1 Qe7 11. Ba3
{ Nijboer may have been afraid of this position, but Black has a good solution. }
11... b5
{ Stopping any b4-b5 ideas and that works tactically as White cannot benefit from the knight on c6 and the rook on a8.   If White plays  12.Nxe5  Nxe5  ,  followed by ...Be6 and locking in the bishop on a8 with ...c7-c6. In the end, Black will have a large advantage with two pieces for the rook. }
12. e4
{ If taking on e5 is not possible, White has to go for this central break as otherwise, Black may grab even more space with ...e5-e4. }
12... Be6 13. Qc2
{ Black should not play  13...Nxe4  because of  14.Nfd2  and White will win back the pawn and have the better structure. }
13... O-O
{ Black may claim already some advantage. White's bishop on a3 looks silly, all of Black's pieces are active and we have a nice central duo with f5 and e5. }
