[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Dutch 2.g3 − b4 Systems"]
[Black "Dutch 2.g3 − b4 Systems − 5.O-O O-O 6.b4 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ In this overview I will discuss the lines where at some point White plays b2-b4. The big difference is whether there is already a white pawn on c4 or not yet. In general, I recommend a Stonewall setup.  I have also given as an illustration the line where Black plays a setup with ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5, but often my analysis ended in a position that is not fully satisfactory for Black. But in a practical game, you may still want to play that as the chances White will play all the perfect moves are slim. }
4. Bg2
{ I will discuss first the lines with b2-b4 where the white c-pawn is not yet on c4. }
4... Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. b4 Nc6
{ 6...d5  is atransposition to the lines with 5.b4 and 6.O-O. } 7. a3 d6
{ Black plays for the standard plan of pushing ...e7-e5, making use of possible pins on either the rook on a1 or the bishop on b2, if White takes on e5. }
8. Bb2 e5 9. dxe5 Ng4 10. c4 { A way to gain space on the queenside. } 10...
Ngxe5 11. Qc2 f4 { Our typical advance in the Leningrad. } 12. Nbd2 Qe7
{ Black is ready to take on g3 and play ...Bf5 when e2-e4 is no longer great because of ...Bg4. }
13. b5 { The start of some complications. } 13... Bf5 14. Qc1 Nxf3+ 15. Nxf3
Na5 { It is remarkable to see that the c4-pawn has become weak. } 16. Bxg7 Qxg7
17. Qxf4
{ White won't enjoy the extra pawn for long, Black's pieces are too active. }
17... Nb3 18. Rae1 Rae8 { Threatening ...Re4. } 19. Ng5 Be4
{ Attacking the queen. } 20. Qg4 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Nd2
{ And now after some exchanges we reach an endgame. } 22. Ne6
{ If White plays passively with  22.Rg1  , Black will hit by playing  22...h5  followed by ...Qc3, attacking the queenside pawns. }
22... Qd7 23. Qd4 Qxe6 24. Qxd2 Qxc4
{ White is just in time to exchange queens, otherwise Black might be better with the active queen and rooks. }
25. Qd3 Qxd3 26. exd3 Kf7
{ This endgame is likely to end in a draw. Black's pawn structure is a little better but it doesn't mean much. The big mistake White can make is allowing the black king to come to d5 while its counterpart is still on g2, that would mean trouble for White. }
