[White "4. Dutch 2.g3 − b4 Systems"]
[Black "Dutch 2.g3 − b4 Systems − 4.c4 Bg7 5.b4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ In this overview I will discuss the lines where at some point White plays b2-b4. The big difference is whether there is already a white pawn on c4 or not yet. In general, I recommend a Stonewall setup.  I have also given as an illustration the line where Black plays a setup with ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5, but often my analysis ended in a position that is not fully satisfactory for Black. But in a practical game, you may still want to play that as the chances White will play all the perfect moves are slim. }
4. c4 { These are the systems with b2-b4 with a white pawn on c4. } 4... Bg7 5.
b4
{ I would love to recommend the lines where Black plays with ...d7-d6 followed by ...e7-e5, but in some lines, the evaluation is around 0.5 and not always a lot of active play for Black. So I don't recommend it, but still, give the lines so you can experiment with it in blitz games and decide if you want to give it a try in a standard game. }
5... d6 6. Bb2 e5
{ This is the move I initially wanted to recommend but there are two options for White where I could not find satisfactory play for Black.   Less precise is  6...O-O  7.Bg2  Nc6  8.Qb3  ,  Black is struggling to get ...e7-e5 in.  8...a5  .  Because White has protected the bishop on b2 with the queen, Black cannot sacrifice a pawn on e5 and make use of a pin on the bishop, it only works with an unprotected bishop  @@StartBracket@@or rook on a1@@EndBracket@@.  9.b5  a4  .  Now that there is no ...e7-e5, Black tries to create play on the queenside.  10.Qc2  Na5  11.O-O  c6  12.bxc6  ,  much stronger than taking on a4 when Black plays ...Be6 and the next move takes with the knight on c4 because the queen on a4 hangs.  12...bxc6  13.Nbd2  .  White just defends everything and then picks up the a4-pawn.  13...d5  14.Rfc1  Be6  .  Of course Black can defend the a4-pawn by playing ...Nb7, but it is a sad position after White plays Ne5.  15.cxd5  cxd5  16.Qxa4  ,  with a healthy extra pawn.   6...a5  The idea of this move is to create counter chances on the queenside and don't let White expand for free.  7.b5  a4  ,  stopping a2-a4 and taking away the b3-square from the queen.  8.Bg2  O-O  9.O-O  c6  ,  attacking the most forward pawn on the queenside now that a2-a4 is no longer possible. Black continues to fight on the queenside.  10.bxc6  bxc6  11.Nbd2  .  If Black first plays ...a4-a3 Bc3 and then ...Ne4 we will be hit by a tactical trick, White exchanges on e4, plays Ng5 and after ...d6-d5 White can take on e4 with the knight. In the end, the rook on a8 will hang and cannot move because of Qb3xb8 taking the knight.    11...Ne4  12.Rb1  a3  .  First ...Ne4 and then ...a4-a3 is fine for Black, White doesn't have time to take on e4 and play Ng5 because the bishop on b2 hangs.  13.Ba1  d5  14.Qc2  Qd6  .  It is important to take control over the e5-square with a queen on d6 and a knight on d7 and the bishop can move to a6.  15.Rfc1  Nd7  16.e3  Ba6  .  We have reached a complex position. The engine gives a small edge for White and when I analyzed it further I found that Black can hold the position but it is a narrow path, so I don't recommend it. Simply too many ways to go wrong. }
7. dxe5 Nfd7 8. Bg2
{ Option 1: This is not innocent at all − White is completing development and claims an advantage because of the pawns on c4 and b4 and more space than in the normal Leningrad lines.   Option 2: preventing Black to castle kingside.  8.Qb3  dxe5  9.c5  Qe7  ,  covering the e6-square.  10.Nc3  Nf6  11.e3  .  White believes the bishop has a better future on c4 than on g2.  11...a5  12.a3  Be6  ,  trying to reduce the pressure by exchanging the bishops.   12...axb4  is not okay for Black because there are situations where White can make use of the open a-file.  13.axb4  Rxa1+  14.Bxa1  Nc6   In case of  14...Be6  15.Bc4  Bxc4  16.Qxc4  c6  ,  taking control over the square d5.  17.O-O  Nbd7  ,  getting ready for either ...e5-e4 followed by ...Ne5 or simply ...Qf7 now that the pawn on e5 is defended.  18.Qa2  ,  we have one of those situations where White has a large advantage because of the open a-file.  15.Bc4  e4  16.Nd4  Nxd4  17.exd4  and this is a position I don't trust for Black at all. The c8-bishop is passive and I think White will be quicker in playing d4-d5 and maybe even d5-d6 one day, than Black will be able to push ...f5-f4.  13.Bc4  Bxc4  14.Qxc4  e4  .  What else? Black cannot castle and on ...Nc6 White plays b4-b5.  15.Ng5  Nc6  16.Nb5  .  The knights are annoying, especially if White gets the chance to play Ne6.  16...Nh5  17.Bd4  This is the move I had initially missed in my analysis. White maintains the pressure and the black king is not safe.  17...Bxd4  18.exd4  Ng7  .  Although the knight is not active, at least it protects the e6-square.  19.O-O  h6  .  Not much else Black can do, the pieces cannot really move.  20.Nh3  g5  21.f3  and this position I don't trust for Black. We may need to castle queenside, but that doesn't feel safe to me, the pawn on e4 can become weak and the d-pawn can potentially go all the way to d6. }
8... dxe5 9. O-O O-O 10. e4
{ A crucial move − if Black can get ...e5-e4 in, we won't have problems, and sometimes we can already claim some advantage. The move e2-e4 we also see in other Leningrad systems, when White tries to undermine Black's center. }
10... Nb6 { Keep on attacking to quickly develop pieces. } 11. Nbd2 fxe4
{ Black would prefer to keep the center the way it is with pawns on f5 and e5, but we is too far behind in development to give proper protection to the e5-pawn. }
12. Nxe5
{ Now the pawn on e4 could become weak but Black manages to quickly exchange it. }
12... Qe7 13. f4 exf3 14. Ndxf3 Nc6
{ Taking the pawn with  14...Qxb4  is not an option when being so much behind in development.  15.Qc1  ,  defending the bishop on b2 and preparing c4-c5.  15...Qe7  16.c5  N6d7  .  Black's pieces on the queenside are in passive positions and it will take a long time to activate them all.  17.Qc4+  Kh8  18.Rae1  ,  Black is completely lost. Half of the pieces are not participating and White threatens to win material with Nxg6.   Another option is  14...N8d7  ,  continuing with development.  15.Nxd7  Bxd7  16.Bxg7  Qxg7  17.c5  .  Suddenly, it appears Black is in trouble. On ...Na4 White wins with Qd5+ followed by Ne5.  17...Bb5  ,  exchanging two minor pieces for a rook.  18.cxb6  Bxf1  19.Qxf1  axb6  and now White's pieces quickly find good squares.  20.Qc4+  Kh8  21.Rd1  .  I don't want to play this position with Black. In material terms, a rook and a pawn might be about equal to two minor pieces, but here I see a knight coming to g5, a bishop potentially taking on b7, and no activity for Black. }
15. Nxc6 Qe3+
{ Black has to play this as after  15...bxc6  first,  16.Re1  is unpleasant. }
16. Kh1 Bxb2 17. Re1 Qc3 { Going back to h6 with the queen is not stronger. }
18. Ne7+ Kh8 19. Nxc8 { Removing the rook from a1 would not be right. } 19...
Bxa1 20. Nxb6 axb6 21. Qxa1 Qxa1 22. Rxa1
{ This endgame is not great for Black, White has good winning chances. } *

