[White "4. Dutch 2.g3 − b4 Systems"]
[Black "Dutch 2.g3 − b4 Systems − 4.c4 Bg7 5.Bg2 O-O 6.b4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ In this overview I will discuss the lines where at some point White plays b2-b4. The big difference is whether there is already a white pawn on c4 or not yet. In general, I recommend a Stonewall setup.  I have also given as an illustration the line where Black plays a setup with ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5, but often my analysis ended in a position that is not fully satisfactory for Black. But in a practical game, you may still want to play that as the chances White will play all the perfect moves are slim. }
4. c4 { These are the systems with b2-b4 with a white pawn on c4. } 4... Bg7 5.
Bg2
{ This move often transposes − in most positions, there is a bishop on g2, a pawn on b4, and another bishop on b2; in which sequence White plays these 3 moves doesn't make a big difference. }
5... O-O 6. b4 d6
{ Black prepares ...e7-e5. However, I don't recommend this, Black can easily get in trouble. }
7. Bb2 e5 { Making use of the pin on the b2-bishop. } 8. dxe5 Ng4
{ I don't recommend ...Ng4 in these types of positions.   Another try is  8...Nfd7  preparing ...dxe5, so there is no weak pawn on d6.  9.O-O  dxe5  10.e4  , which is a transposition to a line that I analyze under the move sequence: @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppppp1bp/5np1/5p2/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PP1P/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.b4  d6  6.Bb2  e5  7.dxe5  Nfd7  8.Bg2  dxe5  9.O-O  O-O  10.e4  , which is not great for Black. }
9. Qb3 Nxe5 10. c5+
{ This is a bit of a problem in the lines with a white pawn on c4: White often gets c4-c5, undermining the pawn on d6, so when in doubt, play ...Nfd7 because then we can take back on e5 with the d6-pawn and there is no c5xd6 for White. After ...Ng4, Black can usually not take back on e5 with the d6-pawn because White will play h2-h3 and after the knight moves, the pawn on e5 drops. So that means after ...Ng4 Black needs to take back on e5 with the knight but then White can aim for c4-c5 followed by c5xd6, creating a weak pawn on d6. }
10... Kh8 11. Nbd2 Nbc6 { Black continues developing. } 12. O-O a6
{ Stopping b4-b5. } 13. cxd6 cxd6 14. Rac1
{ White is clearly better because of the weak d6-pawn and the passive bishop on c8. }
