[Round "?"]
[White "4. Dutch 2.g3 − b4 Systems"]
[Black "Dutch 2.g3 − b4 Systems − 4.c4 Bg7 5.Bg2 O-O 6.b4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ In this overview I will discuss the lines where at some point White plays b2-b4. The big difference is whether there is already a white pawn on c4 or not yet. In general, I recommend a Stonewall setup.  I have also given as an illustration the line where Black plays a setup with ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5, but often my analysis ended in a position that is not fully satisfactory for Black. But in a practical game, you may still want to play that as the chances White will play all the perfect moves are slim. }
4. c4 { These are the systems with b2-b4 with a white pawn on c4. } 4... Bg7 5.
Bg2
{ This move often transposes − in most positions, there is a bishop on g2, a pawn on b4, and another bishop on b2; in which sequence White plays these 3 moves doesn't make a big difference. }
5... O-O 6. b4 Ne4
{ I prefer to first play ...Ne4 and decide for a Stonewall setup as late as possible, to keep White guessing whether I play for ...e7-e5 or ...d7-d5. Also, by first playing ...Ne4 it becomes harder for White to put the knight on c3. }
7. Nbd2
{ Not many White players will play like this because it involves a pawn sacrifice. }
7... c6
{ Black doesn't accept the sacrifice. I try to keep the lines as simple as possible, with the same type of strategic ideas. Here we want to play ...Ne4 first and then ...c7-c6 and ...d7-d5.   7...Nc6  is the move to accept the pawn sacrifice.  8.Bb2  Nxb4  9.Nxe4  fxe4  10.Ng5  and there is no good way to defend the pawn on e4.  10...e3  11.fxe3  . At least White's structure is disrupted and castling is not possible, for now.  11...c6  12.Bc3  Na6  13.Nf3  d6  . This position is complex but not something Black has to avoid, I see no reason why we would be worse. }
8. O-O
{ Black doesn’t need to fear  8.Nxe4  from White. We will play  8...fxe4  followed  by ...d7-d5 and enjoy a nice space advantage while White’s knight on g5 will be offside and the pawn on d4 is weak. }
8... d5
{ Stabilizing the black center and the knight on e4. There is no reason to play ...d7-d6 because Black won’t be able to get ...e7-e5 in, any time soon. }
9. e3 Be6
{ The bishop is okay here on e6 because White doesn’t have Ng5 and if White first plays  10.Nxe4  , Black takes back with the d-pawn,  10...dxe4  , forcing White to play  11.Nd2  to protect the pawn on c4 and then Black takes the initiative  with  11...a5  . }
10. a4 Nd7
{ Black should not try to win the pawn on c4 at this stage because if we start with  10...Nxd2  we get surprised by White’s  11.Ng5!  and Black is in trouble. So as usual, simple development is the way to go. }
11. cxd5 cxd5
{ It is important to note that here, Black cannot recapture with the bishop on d5:  11...Bxd5  would allow White to play  12.Nxe4  , which would force the appearance of the doubled pawns on the e-file. Bad would be  12...Bxe4  due to  13.Ng5  Bxg2  and now White has the intermediate  14.Ne6  since ...Qd6 or ...Qc8 are no longer possible with the knight on d7. }
12. a5
{ White is gaining some space on the queenside, but it is one of those rare occasions where it is not clear whether this extra space is useful because it is not easy for White to create anything on the queenside. }
12... Ndf6
{ Black has equalized but is not in any hurry. We can continue with ...Nd6  (if White plays Ng5, the bishop drops back to c8, Black plays ...h7-h6 and then the bishop back to e6 again)  , and then either ...Rc8 and put a knight on c4, or play ...Nfe4 and gain space on the kingside with ...g6-g5. Meanwhile, White may not have a lot of weaknesses but lacks a concrete plan. }
