[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ In this overview I will discuss the lines where at some point White plays b2-b4. The big difference is whether there is already a white pawn on c4 or not yet. In general, I recommend a Stonewall setup.  I have also given as an illustration the line where Black plays a setup with ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5, but often my analysis ended in a position that is not fully satisfactory for Black. But in a practical game, you may still want to play that as the chances White will play all the perfect moves are slim. }
4. c4 { These are the systems with b2-b4 with a white pawn on c4. } 4... Bg7 5.
Bg2
{ This move often transposes − in most positions, there is a bishop on g2, a pawn on b4, and another bishop on b2; in which sequence White plays these 3 moves doesn't make a big difference. }
5... O-O 6. b4 Nc6 { This is also a valid option. } 7. a3
{ Considering White has already a pawn on c4, the focus is on getting d4-d5 in. }
7... d6 8. Bb2 { This move doesn't prevent ...e7-e5. } 8... e5 9. dxe5 dxe5
{ If White plays  10.Nxe5  , after  10...Qxd1+  we have ...Ng4 available, exchanging the knight for the bishop on b2, resulting in a fine position. }
10. Qxd8 Rxd8 11. Nxe5 Nd4
{ Making use of the lead in development. White would like to castle but then the pawn on e2 would fall. }
12. Bxd4 Rxd4
{ If White castles now,  13.O-O  Black will play  13...Ne4  . White needs to defend the knight with  14.f4  Bxe5  15.fxe5  Be6  and Black will soon win back the pawn. }
13. Nd2 Ne4 14. f4 { A temporary piece sacrifice. } 14... Nxd2 15. Rd1 Nb3 16.
Rb1
{ Black can repeat moves here with  16...Nd2  resulting in a draw, but there is no need to end the game so early. }
16... Bxe5 17. fxe5 c6 { Taking away the pressure on b7. } 18. Rxb3 Rxc4 19.
Rd3 Be6
{ Material is equal but I prefer Black with the better pawn structure and more active pieces. Black can continue with ...Kf7 and then either ...Re8, targeting the pawn on e5, or play ...a7-a5, to attack the queenside, and if White plays b4-b5, Black can take on b5 and create a passed b-pawn. }
