[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ In this overview I will discuss the lines where at some point White plays b2-b4. The big difference is whether there is already a white pawn on c4 or not yet. In general, I recommend a Stonewall setup.  I have also given as an illustration the line where Black plays a setup with ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5, but often my analysis ended in a position that is not fully satisfactory for Black. But in a practical game, you may still want to play that as the chances White will play all the perfect moves are slim. }
4. c4 { These are the systems with b2-b4 with a white pawn on c4. } 4... Bg7 5.
Bg2
{ This move often transposes − in most positions, there is a bishop on g2, a pawn on b4, and another bishop on b2; in which sequence White plays these 3 moves doesn't make a big difference. }
5... O-O 6. b4 Nc6 { This is also a valid option. } 7. b5 Na5 8. Qc2
{ This is also a natural option and Black now quickly needs to create play to prove that the knight on a5 is useful. }
8... c6
{ Defending the knight with the queen on d8 and getting ready to open the c-file and/or, after exchanging on b5, to play ...d7-d5 and move the knight to c4. }
9. bxc6 Nxc6 { Now the knight is safe again. } 10. O-O b6
{ If White ever plays d4-d5, Black will return with the knight to a5, and start attacking the c4-pawn with ...Ba6 and ...Rc8. }
11. Ba3 Bb7
{ Stronger than the immediate  11...Ba6  because White can answer with  12.Qa4  . }
12. Nbd2 Rc8 13. Rac1 Na5
{ Note that if Black would have gone for  13...Ba6  instead of Bb7, White usually follows up by playing  14.Qa4  and then Nb3, but in this position,  @@StartFEN@@2rq1rk1/pb1pp1bp/1p3np1/n4p2/2PP4/B4NP1/P1QNPPBP/2R2RK1 w - - 6 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Qa4  doesn't make sense because  of  14...Bc6  .  Only once the white queen has moved to b1, Black can consider putting the bishop on a6. }
14. Qb1 Ba6 15. Qb4 { Attacking the pawn on e7. } 15... Re8 16. Rfd1 Qc7
{ Black continues to put pressure on the c4-pawn and chases the white queen, which doesn't have a good square. }
17. e3 Bf8 18. Bf1
{ With this bishop on f1 White threatens tricks with c4-c5 when Black would need to take on f1 and then, before taking back the bishop, White can take on b6 or sometimes d6 if Black has played ...d7-d6. Considering ...d7-d6 is not great and the black bishop is on f8, it is better for Black to aim for a setup with ...e7-e6 and maybe ...d7-d5 one day than to aim for ...e7-e5. After ...e7-e5, Black will soon have to play ...e5-e4 and the white knight can come to e5 and c4-c5 will follow soon, with a large advantage for White. }
18... e6 19. Qb2 Bb7
{ Black has a flexible pawn structure and good control over the e4-square, chances are about equal. }
