2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. g3 g6
{ In this overview I will discuss the lines where at some point White plays b2-b4. The big difference is whether there is already a white pawn on c4 or not yet. In general, I recommend a Stonewall setup.  I have also given as an illustration the line where Black plays a setup with ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5, but often my analysis ended in a position that is not fully satisfactory for Black. But in a practical game, you may still want to play that as the chances White will play all the perfect moves are slim. }
4. c4 { These are the systems with b2-b4 with a white pawn on c4. } 4... Bg7 5.
Bg2
{ This move often transposes − in most positions, there is a bishop on g2, a pawn on b4, and another bishop on b2; in which sequence White plays these 3 moves doesn't make a big difference. }
5... O-O 6. b4 Nc6 { This is also a valid option. } 7. b5 Na5 8. Qa4
{ The more aggressive option, trying to prove that the knight is misplaced on a5. }
8... b6
{ If Black would have defended the knight by pushing the c-pawn, we would have to play ...b7-b6 anyway after Bd2. }
9. Bd2
{ 9.O-O  Bb7  10.Bb2  a6  and Black is at least equal.  White probably needs to move the queen from a4 soon with the rook on a8, and after Black takes on b5 there are some holes on the light squares in White's camp: e4, d5, and c4. }
9... a6 { Taking benefit of the fact the queen on a4 is misplaced. } 10. Qc2
axb5 11. cxb5 Bb7
{ Trying to make use of the light squares such as e4, d5, and c4. } 12. O-O c5
{ Black needs to continue on the queenside, otherwise, the knight on a5 would not be active. }
13. bxc6 Bxc6 { Threatening ...Be4 followed by ...Rc8 and ...Nc4. } 14. Nc3 Ne4
15. Bf4 Qc8 { There is some real pressure along the c-line. } 16. Rac1 Qa6
{ Putting pressure on the a2-pawn. } 17. Ne5
{ This results in some simplifications. } 17... Nxc3 18. Qxc3 Bxg2 19. Kxg2
Qb7+
{ Although the engine says it is possible to play  19...Qxe2  , I would not advise it because after  20.Nxd7  the pawn on b6 also hangs and we need to play precisely with Black to maintain the balance. }
20. Nf3 Rfc8 21. Qb4 e6
{ Black has no problems, all the pieces are active and while the b6-pawn is a bit weak, the same can be said about the white pawn on a2 @@StartBracket@@and if that is captured, e2 might be hanging as well or there is pressure against the pawn on f2@@EndBracket@@. }
