[White "5. Dutch 2.g3 − 4.c3"]
[Black "Dutch 2.g3 − 4.c3 Bg7 5.Nd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. c3
{ White’s idea is to place the queen on b3 to apply pressure on the light squares in Black’s camp. If Black counters this with ...d7-d5 or ...e7-e6, White sometimes puts a knight on f4 to prepare d4-d5, c3-c4  (with a black pawn on d5)  or h2-h4-h5 to weaken Black’s kingside. }
4... Bg7 5. Nd2 Nc6 6. e4 { Not a dangerous move. } 6... fxe4 7. Nxe4 Nxe4 8.
Bxe4 d5
{ First taking control over the dark squares and then following up with ...e7-e5 to resolve the weak e-pawn and create space for the black pieces. }
9. Bg2 e5 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Nf3 Bg4
{ The white bishop on g2 is potentially stronger than its counterpart on c8, so Black is happy to pin the knight and play for exchanges. }
12. h3 Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3
{ Now Black would like to castle kingside. } 14... Qe7+ 15. Be3 Qf7
{ Black is fine either in the endgame after White exchanges queens on f7, or after White removes the queen and Black castles kingside. }
