[White "5. Dutch 2.g3 − 4.c3"]
[Black "Dutch 2.g3 − 4.c3 Bg7 5.Nd2 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. c3
{ White’s idea is to place the queen on b3 to apply pressure on the light squares in Black’s camp. If Black counters this with ...d7-d5 or ...e7-e6, White sometimes puts a knight on f4 to prepare d4-d5, c3-c4  (with a black pawn on d5)  or h2-h4-h5 to weaken Black’s kingside. }
4... Bg7 5. Nd2 Nc6 6. b4 d5
{ Taking control over the light squares on e4 and c4. } 7. Nh3 O-O 8. O-O Re8
{ The idea of this move is to prepare ...e7-e5. } 9. Qc2 Ne4 10. Nf3 a6 11. Bf4
{ This move prevents ...e7-e5 but at the cost of a misplaced knight on h3 that also wanted to go to f4.   11.a4  fails to  11...e5  and White  has no b4-b5 because the rook on a1 is not protected. }
11... e6
{ Black switches from pushing ...e7-e5 to developing all the pieces and maybe opening a front on the queenside with ...b7-b6 and ...c7-c5.   11...e5  Doesn't really work for Black:  12.Nxe5  Nxe5  13.Bxe5  Bxe5  14.dxe5  Rxe5  .  The pawn on d5 is a bit weak, White is ready to play c3-c4 and the rook on e5 is misplaced.  15.Rfd1  Qe7  16.Nf4  c6  17.Nd3  Re6  18.c4  and White has the more pleasant position.  The d5-pawn can become weak and if Black decides to take on c4, White can combine an attack over the light squares by doubling rooks on the d-file and entering on d8. }
12. a4 Qe7 13. Ne5 a5 { A strong move to create play on the queenside. } 14. b5
{ This move is not precise. } 14... Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Nd6
{ Black has suddenly control over the c4-square and might take over the initiative with ...Nc4, ...Bd7, ...Rac8 and open the c-file with ...c7-c6. Meanwhile, it is not clear what White is going to do. }
