[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Dutch 2.g3 − 4.c3"]
[Black "Dutch 2.g3 − 5.Bg5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. c3
{ White’s idea is to place the queen on b3 to apply pressure on the light squares in Black’s camp. If Black counters this with ...d7-d5 or ...e7-e6, White sometimes puts a knight on f4 to prepare d4-d5, c3-c4  (with a black pawn on d5)  or h2-h4-h5 to weaken Black’s kingside. }
4... Bg7 5. Bg5
{ White can also play these systems with the bishop on c1, but on g5 the idea is that at the right moment White can take the knight on f6, which has control over the light squares d5 and e4. }
5... O-O 6. Qb3+ Kh8 7. Nh3
{ Deploying this knight on f4 via h3 is typical for these lines with Qb3. The knight on f4 can often jump to e6 and makes the advance h2-h4-h5 stronger. }
7... d6 8. Nf4
{ White can take on b7 here, but after exchanging on b7 Black plays ...Nbd7 and has sufficient compensation with the active pieces. }
8... c6
{ Black prepares the advance ...e7-e5, but before playing this, takes control over the square d5. }
9. h4
{ If White could also get h4-h5 in, it would be scary, but first it is Black's turn! }
9... e5
{ Black has to play this now and not something slow like  9...Na6  because then  10.h5  would be annoying. }
10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Ne6 Bxe6 12. Qxe6 Re8
{ We have to get rid of this queen before Black can complete development. } 13.
Qb3 Qc7 { Black has no problems here thanks to the pawn on e5. } 14. Nd2 Na6
{ I don’t like to put my knight on d7 because when I am not looking, I may suddenly get hit by a queen that lands on f7. Both from a6 and d7 the knight can come to c5, so much safer to play it to a6. }
15. e4 f4
{ It is safe for Black to close the kingside and not allow h4-h5 when there is also still tension on the f5-pawn. }
16. O-O-O Ng4
{ The f2-pawn is weak and the bishop on g5 can be attacked with ...h7-h6. White could also have castled kingside, but the structure is a bit weakened because of the pawn on h4. So if Black gets ...f5-f4 in, this could mean trouble. }
