[Black "Dutch 2.g3 − 5.Bg5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. c3
{ White’s idea is to place the queen on b3 to apply pressure on the light squares in Black’s camp. If Black counters this with ...d7-d5 or ...e7-e6, White sometimes puts a knight on f4 to prepare d4-d5, c3-c4  (with a black pawn on d5)  or h2-h4-h5 to weaken Black’s kingside. }
4... Bg7 5. Bg5
{ White can also play these systems with the bishop on c1, but on g5 the idea is that at the right moment White can take the knight on f6, which has control over the light squares d5 and e4. }
5... O-O 6. Bxf6 { The idea is to quickly mate Black, but it doesn't work. }
6... Bxf6 7. Qb3+ Kg7 { Taking the pawn on b7 is quite dangerous for White: }
8. Bxb7 Bxb7 9. Qxb7 c5
{ Black has two ideas: first of all to lock in the white queen and capture it, and secondly to weaken the white pawns on b2, c3, and d4 to either win the rook on a1 or to enter on b2 with decisive effect. }
10. Qxa8 { Taking the rook results in a disaster for White. } 10... Qb6
{ Threatening to take on b2 and win back the rook with interest. } 11. b3 Nc6
{ White is losing the queen. } 12. dxc5 Qb5
{ The black queen must continue watching the b7-square in order to keep the white queen from escaping. }
13. Qxf8+
{ Taking the rook on f8 doesn't help.   Instead of this move, White can play  13.Na3  but this loses  13...Bxc3+  followed by ...Qa6. }
13... Kxf8 14. Nf3 g5 { Threatening ...g5-g4. } 15. O-O Qxe2
{ Black has a winning advantage: the white pieces do not coordinate well and Black is likely to play ...g5-g4 at some point followed by, maybe, ...Qb2 and taking on c3. }
