[White "5. Dutch 2.g3 − 4.c3"]
[Black "Dutch 2.g3 − 5.Qb3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. c3
{ White’s idea is to place the queen on b3 to apply pressure on the light squares in Black’s camp. If Black counters this with ...d7-d5 or ...e7-e6, White sometimes puts a knight on f4 to prepare d4-d5, c3-c4  (with a black pawn on d5)  or h2-h4-h5 to weaken Black’s kingside. }
4... Bg7 5. Qb3 Nc6 6. Nd2 d6
{ The move  6...e6  is also an option with the idea to prepare short castling. If White the plays  7.e4  ,  Black will take on e4, push ...d7-d6 followed by ...e6-e5. I think it is playable for Black, but not in line with the general concept of playing ...d7-d6 followed by ...e7-e5. }
7. Ngf3
{ If White plays  7.d5  , Black is happy to play  7...Ne5  and either exchange the knight on for example f3 or, if it ever gets attacked, drop it back to f7. Black's plan will be to push ....e7-e5. }
7... e6 { Preparing to castle short. } 8. O-O O-O 9. a4 a5
{ Immediately stopping any expansion plans from White on the queenside. } 10.
Re1 d5
{ It would be in the spirit of Black's play if we could aim for ...e6-e5. But unfortunately, White comes first with e2-e4 and would be much better, so Black has to prevent this with ...d7-d5. }
11. Qc2 Ne4
{ Black has reached a solid position, a bit similar to a Stonewall. White doesn't have a lot of play on the queenside yet, and if Black manages to get ...c7-c5 in, we could easily be better. }
*

