{ White’s idea is to place the queen on b3 to apply pressure on the light squares in Black’s camp. If Black counters this with ...d7-d5 or ...e7-e6, White sometimes puts a knight on f4 to prepare d4-d5, c3-c4  (with a black pawn on d5)  or h2-h4-h5 to weaken Black’s kingside. }
4... Bg7 5. Qb3 Nc6 6. Nd2 d6
{ The move  6...e6  is also an option with the idea to prepare short castling. If White the plays  7.e4  ,  Black will take on e4, push ...d7-d6 followed by ...e6-e5. I think it is playable for Black, but not in line with the general concept of playing ...d7-d6 followed by ...e7-e5. }
7. Nh3 e5 8. dxe5 Nxe5
{ 8...dxe5  is not correct because after  9.O-O  Qe7  10.e4  Black is in trouble. We cannot easily castle either side and White is ready to start action in the center. }
9. Nf4 { White wants to take control over e6 and d5. } 9... Qe7 10. O-O c6
{ Taking control back, first with ...Qe7 and now over the square d5 with ...c7-c6. }
11. a4 a5 12. Re1
{ A natural move but here it is not good because the rook on e1 is not protected. }
12... g5
{ A small trick: White cannot play Nd3 because Black would simply take the knight since the rook on e1 is not defended. }
13. Nh3 h6
{ Black might already be a bit better considering Black is ready for ...Be6 and castle kingside and then develop the kingside attack with ...f5-f4. }
