[Round "?"]
[White "5. Dutch 2.g3 − 4.c3"]
[Black "Dutch 2.g3 − 5.Qb3 #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. c3
{ White’s idea is to place the queen on b3 to apply pressure on the light squares in Black’s camp. If Black counters this with ...d7-d5 or ...e7-e6, White sometimes puts a knight on f4 to prepare d4-d5, c3-c4  (with a black pawn on d5)  or h2-h4-h5 to weaken Black’s kingside. }
4... Bg7 5. Qb3 c6
{ Black has an alternative setup that has been played by Nakamura and Vitiugov. I don't recommend it as main line because White has many different ways of playing, but in itself, I believe Black's position is fine. So here is one line as an illustration, in case one day you would like to play something different. }
6. Nf3 d5
{ Going for a Stonewall type of setup where the white queen on b3 might be misplaced considering White would like to advance the queenside pawns. }
7. Bf4 O-O 8. O-O e6 9. c4
{ White has to make this advance sooner or later as on the kingside and in the center, there is not much room for creativity. }
9... Nbd7 10. Nc3 Ne4 11. h4 Nb6
{ Attacking the pawn on c4. Had the white queen been on c2, White would have had a plan with c4-c5 and b2-b4 but here things are more complicated. }
12. cxd5 exd5
{ It is better to keep the pawn on c6, to keep control over the b5-square, and to create a bit of space for the c8-bishop by recapturing with the e-pawn. }
13. Ne5 Kh8 14. Rac1 Nd7 { This knight had no future on the queenside. } 15.
Nxd7 Qxd7 16. Rfd1 Qe7
{ Black has a solid position. The white queen blocks the advance of the b-pawn, so it will not be easy for White to create something tangible here. }
