[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Dutch 2.g3 − 4.h4 & 4.Nc3 Sidelines"]
[Black "Dutch 2.g3 − 4.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nc3
{ This is not a great move because Black can now transpose to a favorable Stonewall because the knight on c3 is blocking the c-pawn. }
4... d5 5. Bf4
{ If White first plays  5.Nf3  , Black can continue developing with  5...Bg7  and only if White plays Bf4 we could consider playing ...c7-c6. }
5... c6
{ The reason I recommend ...c7-c6 here is because White has a positional threat: to play Nb5 and after Black defends with for example ...Na6, White can play c2-c4 and move to a more traditional Stonewall with the pawn on c4. I see no reason to give White this option. }
6. Nf3 Bg7 7. O-O
{ If instead, White plays  7.h4  , Black can still just castle kingside. } 7...
O-O 8. e3 Be6
{ Black is not afraid to exchange this bishop, if White plays  9.Ng5  ,  the bishop will find shelter on f7.  9...Bf7  . }
9. Ne2 Nbd7 10. Nc1 Ne4
{ Black would love to play ...Bf7 with the idea to push ...e7-e5. If White prevents this, expansion on the kingside with ...g6-g5 or on the queenside with ...c6-c5 are valid options. }
11. Nd3 c5
{ The queenside break is more appropriate than playing on the kingside considering White has strong control over the e5-square. }
12. dxc5 Qc8 13. Rc1 Ndxc5 14. Nxc5 Qxc5
{ The position is about equal. Black dreams of playing ...e7-e5, so White needs to try to maintain control over that square but that limits any other actions. Meanwhile, Black can activate the rooks and/or play on the queenside with ...b7-b5 and ...a7-a5. }
