[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Dutch 2.g3 − 4.h4 & 4.Nc3 Sidelines"]
[Black "Dutch 2.g3 − 4.h4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. h4
{ Ten years ago we thought these kind of moves were only played by crazy club players. Nowadays strong engines suggest these moves on a regular basis and we have all gotten used to studying these types of direct attacks. }
4... Bg7
{ After this move White has a forcing line where Black needs to accept a quick draw because of a perpetual check or end up in a worse position. If you want to play for a win with Black, I recommend ...d7-d6 after h2-h4. }
5. h5 Nxh5 6. e4 fxe4
{ 6...e6  is an alternative I analyzed, but I don't trust it for Black:  7.Rxh5  . These types of exchange sacrifices can be dangerous in the Leningrad. Black doesn't have a lot of open lines to use both rooks, so White has a lot of time to put the light pieces in attacking positions.  7...gxh5  8.Qxh5+  Kf8  9.exf5  exf5  10.Ne2  .  Even the simple Qxf5 may result in an endgame with an extra pawn for White.    10...d6  11.Nbc3  Nc6  12.Bh6  Be6  . Black needs to keep developing, but the king will not be safe.  13.Bxg7+  Kxg7  14.O-O-O  Qf6  15.Nf4  Bf7  16.Ncd5  .  An annoying move, Black cannot take on h5 because White will recapture on h5 with a check and only then take the queen, netting a piece.  16...Bxd5  17.Bxd5  Rae8  18.g4  . White has a dangerous attack and I think it is not easy to defend Black's position. }
7. Rxh5 { This is the line that can result in a quick draw. } 7... gxh5 8.
Qxh5+ Kf8 9. Bh6 d5 10. Bxg7+ Kxg7 11. Qg5+ Kf8 12. Qh6+
{ With perpetual check. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Dutch 2.g3 − 4.h4 & 4.Nc3 Sidelines"]
[Black "Dutch 2.g3 − 4.h4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. h4
{ Ten years ago we thought these kind of moves were only played by crazy club players. Nowadays strong engines suggest these moves on a regular basis and we have all gotten used to studying these types of direct attacks. }
4... d6
{ This is the move with which Black gets a game full of complications. } 5. h5
{ The pawn push is possible, followed by an exchange sacrifice, but the difference with the Bg7 line is that Black now has time to vacate the king to d8. }
5... Nxh5 6. Rxh5 gxh5 7. e4
{ White is investing material for a long-term initiative based on the poor location of the black king. }
7... h4 8. Qh5+ Kd7 9. Qxh4
{ After  9.Qxf5  , Black has  9...e6  ,  followed by taking on g3, ...Qe8, and the position is similar to our main line. If White takes on f5 with the e-pawn,  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1b1r/pppkp2p/3p4/5p1Q/3PP2p/6P1/PPP2PB1/RNB1K1N1 w Q - 2 9@@EndFEN@@  9.exf5  Black simply plays  9...Qe8  followed by ...Kd8 and starts developing the pieces. }
9... e6 { Offering a queen swap to reduce the pressure. } 10. Qh3 fxe4
{ Black doesn't want to allow exf5 with the pawn on e6, that would expose the king too much. }
11. Nc3 Qe8
{ Black has a standard plan in this line of putting the queen on e8 followed by ...Kd8 and develop the pieces on the queenside.   Note that defending the pawn on e4 by playing  11...d5  fails to  12.Nxd5  because the queen on h3 pins the pawn on e6. }
12. Nxe4 Kd8
{ White has some compensation for the invested material. The black king will be in the center for a long time, but there are no immediate threats and I think in a practical game I would rank Black's chances higher. White doesn't have a concrete attacking idea while Black's moves are all about developing and offering to exchange pieces. }
