1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. h4
{ Ten years ago we thought these kind of moves were only played by crazy club players. Nowadays strong engines suggest these moves on a regular basis and we have all gotten used to studying these types of direct attacks. }
4... d6
{ This is the move with which Black gets a game full of complications. } 5. h5
{ The pawn push is possible, followed by an exchange sacrifice, but the difference with the Bg7 line is that Black now has time to vacate the king to d8. }
5... Nxh5 6. Rxh5 gxh5 7. e4
{ White is investing material for a long-term initiative based on the poor location of the black king. }
7... h4 8. Qh5+ Kd7 9. e5 e6 { Preventing any ideas connected to e5-e6+. } 10.
exd6 cxd6 11. Nc3 Na6 { Black is ready to play ...Kc7-b8. } 12. Bf4 hxg3 13.
fxg3 Kc7
