[Black "Dutch 2.g3 − 4.Nh3 Systems − 4.Nh3 Bg7 5.Nf4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nh3
{ After this move, there are two separate systems White can play, one with c2-c4 included and one without c2-c4. In both systems, White's strategy is similar: claiming that with a knight on f4, the light squares in the center can be controlled better @@StartBracket@@typically e6 and d5@@EndBracket@@ and sometimes attack g6 by playing h2-h4-h5.  My main recommendation for Black depends on whether White has played an early c2-c4 or not. If White plays it, then I recommend a setup where Black plays ...c7-c6 and ...h7-h6, staying truly flexible. If White leaves the pawn on c2 or plays c2-c3, I recommend a setup with ...d7-d6 and ...Nc6 followed by ...e7-e5. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf4 Nc6
{ My main recommendation, also because if White first plays c2-c3 and then Nf4, I recommend a similar setup with ...Nc6 and ...d7-d6. }
6. d5 { The critical continuation. } 6... Ne5 7. Nc3 c6
{ In these lines Black often wants to exchange the strong pawn on d5, to create more space for our own central pawns and the pieces behind it. The risk is that we might end up with immobile d- and e-pawns. }
8. e4 d6
{ I don't fully trust the immediate capture  8...fxe4  9.Nxe4  Nxe4  10.Bxe4  cxd5  11.Bxd5  . My concern is that the black e- and d-pawns are a bit weak if White plays precisely.  11...e6  12.Bg2  O-O  13.O-O  d5  14.Re1  Re8  15.c3  and it is not clear how Black will ever manage  to get ...e6-e5 in. If we were to succeed, we would have a great position. }
9. O-O O-O 10. exf5 { White's main move, other moves are not critical. } 10...
Bxf5 11. Nce2 { This move was tried in a correspondence game. } 11... Qb6 12.
h3 Nxd5
{ This is my suggested improvement,  12...Bd7  was played in Kuusik-Siigur, ICCF email 2017. }
13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Qxd5+ e6 15. Qb3 d5
{ Black has a solid position with pressure on White's queenside @@StartBracket@@...Rac8 and ...Nc4 come into consideration@@EndBracket@@. }
