[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nh3
{ After this move, there are two separate systems White can play, one with c2-c4 included and one without c2-c4. In both systems, White's strategy is similar: claiming that with a knight on f4, the light squares in the center can be controlled better @@StartBracket@@typically e6 and d5@@EndBracket@@ and sometimes attack g6 by playing h2-h4-h5.  My main recommendation for Black depends on whether White has played an early c2-c4 or not. If White plays it, then I recommend a setup where Black plays ...c7-c6 and ...h7-h6, staying truly flexible. If White leaves the pawn on c2 or plays c2-c3, I recommend a setup with ...d7-d6 and ...Nc6 followed by ...e7-e5. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf4 d6
{ This is a second option that I believe is fully playable. } 6. d5
{ The critical continuation. } 6... c6
{ With the idea to get rid of the annoying d5-pawn. } 7. c4 e5
{ A standard operation in this system, Black plays ...e7-e5 and after White takes  8.dxe6  Na6  and ...Nc5 will follow, to win the pawn back @@StartBracket@@always with the pawn on c6 to control d5@@EndBracket@@. }
8. dxe6 Na6 9. Nc3 Nc5 10. Be3 Nxe6 11. O-O
{ Of course, White can also play  11.Nxe6  Bxe6  12.Bf4  Bxc4  13.Bxd6  Nd5  14.Qa4  Qxd6  15.Qxc4  Nb6  16.Qb3  O-O-O  and after  17.O-O  Rhe8  Black has a comfortable position. }
11... O-O 12. Nxe6 Bxe6 13. b3 Ne4
{ Stronger than ...d6-d5 after which Black is likely to end up with an isolated d-pawn without any active piece play. }
14. Nxe4 fxe4 15. Bd4
{ White can also sacrifice an exchange by taking on e4, but I failed to find any advantage for White. }
15... d5 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. cxd5 cxd5
{ The position is about equal, Black is in time to activate the rooks. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Dutch 2.g3 − 4.Nh3 Systems"]
[Black "Dutch 2.g3 − 4.Nh3 Systems − 5.O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nh3
{ After this move, there are two separate systems White can play, one with c2-c4 included and one without c2-c4. In both systems, White's strategy is similar: claiming that with a knight on f4, the light squares in the center can be controlled better @@StartBracket@@typically e6 and d5@@EndBracket@@ and sometimes attack g6 by playing h2-h4-h5.  My main recommendation for Black depends on whether White has played an early c2-c4 or not. If White plays it, then I recommend a setup where Black plays ...c7-c6 and ...h7-h6, staying truly flexible. If White leaves the pawn on c2 or plays c2-c3, I recommend a setup with ...d7-d6 and ...Nc6 followed by ...e7-e5. }
4... Bg7 5. O-O
{ This move is not so innocent: if Black plays ...e7-e5 too soon, we may be hit by e2-e4, putting a lot of pressure on the center. }
5... d6 6. c3 Nc6
{ Note that this position can also be reached if White first plays c2-c3 and then castles kingside.   Here is an example of playing ...e7-e5 at the wrong moment:  6...e5  7.dxe5  dxe5  8.Qb3  ,  threatening to take on b7.  8...Nc6  9.Nd2  Qe7  10.e4  . Black is under a lot of pressure and without a good way to complete development. }
7. Qb3 e5
{ You may wonder if that is not going to result in exactly the same line as I gave a move ago, where I said that ...e7-e5 was not a good idea. However, there is one subtle difference. }
8. dxe5 Nxe5
{ Here is the difference: Black can take back with the knight, which is much safer than taking with the pawn. }
9. Bxb7 { White cannot really take this pawn. } 9... Rb8 10. Qa4+
{ White's only way to get out of the pin because  10.Bc6+  fails to  10...Nxc6  and the rook on b8 is protected. }
10... Bd7 11. Qxa7 c6
{ White needs to play precisely not to lose material, and ...Qc7 is a big threat here. }
12. Ba6 c5 13. Bd3 O-O 14. Na3 Nxd3 15. exd3 Bc6
{ Black has completed development and is ready to start an attack while White's pieces are scattered around and not effective. My engine says Black is winning. }
