[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nh3
{ After this move, there are two separate systems White can play, one with c2-c4 included and one without c2-c4. In both systems, White's strategy is similar: claiming that with a knight on f4, the light squares in the center can be controlled better @@StartBracket@@typically e6 and d5@@EndBracket@@ and sometimes attack g6 by playing h2-h4-h5.  My main recommendation for Black depends on whether White has played an early c2-c4 or not. If White plays it, then I recommend a setup where Black plays ...c7-c6 and ...h7-h6, staying truly flexible. If White leaves the pawn on c2 or plays c2-c3, I recommend a setup with ...d7-d6 and ...Nc6 followed by ...e7-e5. }
4... Bg7 5. O-O
{ This move is not so innocent: if Black plays ...e7-e5 too soon, we may be hit by e2-e4, putting a lot of pressure on the center. }
5... d6 6. c3 Nc6
{ Note that this position can also be reached if White first plays c2-c3 and then castles kingside.   Here is an example of playing ...e7-e5 at the wrong moment:  6...e5  7.dxe5  dxe5  8.Qb3  ,  threatening to take on b7.  8...Nc6  9.Nd2  Qe7  10.e4  . Black is under a lot of pressure and without a good way to complete development. }
7. Qb3 e5
{ You may wonder if that is not going to result in exactly the same line as I gave a move ago, where I said that ...e7-e5 was not a good idea. However, there is one subtle difference. }
8. dxe5 Nxe5
{ Here is the difference: Black can take back with the knight, which is much safer than taking with the pawn. }
9. Nf4 c6
{ Black takes control over the square d5. Also, White would have taken on b7 had Black played ...Qe7 @@StartBracket@@with the idea to cover the e6-square@@EndBracket@@. The difference with a move ago when Black was winning if White took on b7 is that now White has played Nf4. That means in many lines White can play Nd5, attacking the queen on e7 and exchanging off the knight on f6, after which the bishop on b7 can return home while keeping the extra pawn. }
10. Ne6 Bxe6 11. Qxe6+ Qe7 12. Qxe7+ Kxe7
{ Black has no problems in this position and the only weakness, the pawn on d6, is easy to protect with the king and a rook if necessary. Meanwhile, we are ready to exert pressure on White's queenside with the knight coming to c4 and ...d6-d5, taking control over the central squares, is also likely to be played soon. }
