[White "7. Dutch 2.g3 − 4.Nh3 Systems"]
[Black "Dutch 2.g3 − 4.Nh3 Systems − 5.c3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nh3
{ After this move, there are two separate systems White can play, one with c2-c4 included and one without c2-c4. In both systems, White's strategy is similar: claiming that with a knight on f4, the light squares in the center can be controlled better @@StartBracket@@typically e6 and d5@@EndBracket@@ and sometimes attack g6 by playing h2-h4-h5.  My main recommendation for Black depends on whether White has played an early c2-c4 or not. If White plays it, then I recommend a setup where Black plays ...c7-c6 and ...h7-h6, staying truly flexible. If White leaves the pawn on c2 or plays c2-c3, I recommend a setup with ...d7-d6 and ...Nc6 followed by ...e7-e5. }
4... Bg7 5. c3
{ This move is quite dangerous for Black because of the potential combination of a queen on b3 and a knight on f4 or g5. }
5... Nc6
{ There is not a big difference between playing first ...d7-d6 or first the knight to c6. Black's aim is to push ...e7-e5. }
6. Qb3 d6
{ For the more aggressive players,  6...e5  is an interesting sacrifice that we have already seenhere. }
7. d5 Ne5
{ As usual in the Leningrad System, Black is happy to put the knight on e5. }
8. Ng5 { Aiming for the e6-square. } 8... O-O 9. f4
{ Obviously, this move is not possible if White would have played Nf4 instead of Ng5. }
9... Ned7
{ My suggested improvement over a game between Volokitin and Reinderman, where Black placed the knight on g4. }
10. Ne6 Nc5 { This is the point, otherwise Black would lose material. } 11.
Nxc5 dxc5 12. Be3 Qd6
{ Defending the pawn on c5 with  12...b6  is not an option because of  13.d6+  and the rook on a8 drops. }
13. Nd2 a5 { Putting pressure on the white queen. } 14. Nc4
{ White is winning a pawn, if  14.a4  would be played, Black will become active after  14...e6  . }
14... Qa6 15. Bxc5 a4
{ Chasing the queen to a square where it is not very active. } 16. Qb4 Re8 17.
O-O e6
{ Black has sufficient counterplay for the pawn. White's extra pawn is the one on e2 which is going nowhere and Black has good coordination between the pieces. }
