9. Ne6 Bxe6 10. Qxe6+ Qe7
{ Black has given up a bishop for a knight to get active pieces in return. }
11. Qb3 { Most White players will avoid the queen exchange. } 11... Nd8
{ The pawn on b7 is indirectly defended because White loses material after  12.Bxb7  Rb8  . }
12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Na3 e4 { Trying to reduce the power of the g2-bishop. } 14.
f3 Qe6
{ If White avoids the queen exchange, Black can continue development without any problems. }
15. Nc4 exf3 16. Bxf3 c6
{ Defending the pawn on b7 indirectly, soon the d8-knight can come to f7. } 17.
Bf4 O-O 18. O-O-O Nf7
{ We have a sharp position with mutual chances. Black will try to get ...b7-b5 in to launch an attack against the white king. }
