[Round "?"]
[White "7. Dutch 2.g3 − 4.Nh3 Systems"]
[Black "Dutch 2.g3 − 4.Nh3 Systems − 5.c4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nh3
{ After this move, there are two separate systems White can play, one with c2-c4 included and one without c2-c4. In both systems, White's strategy is similar: claiming that with a knight on f4, the light squares in the center can be controlled better @@StartBracket@@typically e6 and d5@@EndBracket@@ and sometimes attack g6 by playing h2-h4-h5.  My main recommendation for Black depends on whether White has played an early c2-c4 or not. If White plays it, then I recommend a setup where Black plays ...c7-c6 and ...h7-h6, staying truly flexible. If White leaves the pawn on c2 or plays c2-c3, I recommend a setup with ...d7-d6 and ...Nc6 followed by ...e7-e5. }
4... Bg7 5. c4 O-O 6. Nc3
{ In the systems where White plays Nh3 and c2-c4, Black typically plays ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5. If White has played d4-d5, White will take on e6, Black will play ...c7-c6, ...Na6-c5 and recapture the pawn on e6. }
6... d6 7. Nf4
{ Now Black has 2 options, a solid one and one with complications. } 7... c6
{ This results in a complex line. } 8. d5 e5 9. dxe6 Na6
{ A standard way of play for Black: ready to play ...Nc5 and win the pawn back on e6. If White now just castles Black has no problems. }
10. h4 { The only way to put pressure on Black. } 10... Nc5 11. h5 gxh5
{ There is no better alternative, but it is an ugly pawn on h5 and f5 has also become weak. }
12. Bh3 Nxe6 13. Bxf5 Nxf4 { The start of a long forcing sequence. } 14. Bxc8
Ng2+ 15. Kf1 Qxc8 16. Kxg2 Qe6
{ I think Black is OK here and has sufficient active play in exchange for the structural weakness on h5. But be careful, if Black's initiative slows down and the knight on f6 gets exchanged, the h5-pawn is likely to be lost. }
17. Qd3 Rad8 18. Bf4 d5 19. cxd5 Nxd5 20. Nxd5 Rxd5
{ Despite that the knight on f6 was exchanged, I prefer Black here @@StartBracket@@the engine says it is equal@@EndBracket@@. Black has the d-file and will manage to exchange the h-pawn for the white pawn on b2, the majority on the queenside will advance a lot faster and be more dangerous than White's extra pawns on the kingside. }
