[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nh3
{ After this move, there are two separate systems White can play, one with c2-c4 included and one without c2-c4. In both systems, White's strategy is similar: claiming that with a knight on f4, the light squares in the center can be controlled better @@StartBracket@@typically e6 and d5@@EndBracket@@ and sometimes attack g6 by playing h2-h4-h5.  My main recommendation for Black depends on whether White has played an early c2-c4 or not. If White plays it, then I recommend a setup where Black plays ...c7-c6 and ...h7-h6, staying truly flexible. If White leaves the pawn on c2 or plays c2-c3, I recommend a setup with ...d7-d6 and ...Nc6 followed by ...e7-e5. }
4... Bg7 5. c4 O-O 6. Nc3
{ In the systems where White plays Nh3 and c2-c4, Black typically plays ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5. If White has played d4-d5, White will take on e6, Black will play ...c7-c6, ...Na6-c5 and recapture the pawn on e6. }
6... d6 7. O-O
{ If White first plays  7.d5  , Black responds with  7...c6  and after  8.O-O  wetranspose to the main line, while after  8.Nf4  wetranspose to the line with 7.Nf4 and 8.d5. }
7... c6 8. b3 Na6 9. d5
{ 9.Bb2  is not threatening at all.  9...e5  and Black has achieved the main strategic aim, the ...e7-e5 push, while the white knight on h3 is out of play. }
9... cxd5 10. Bxd5+
{ An unusual way of taking back but in this case, it is playable. } 10... Nxd5
11. Qxd5+ e6
{ I prefer taking control over the light squares versus the slightly passive  11...Kh8  . }
12. Qd2 Nc7 13. Bb2
{ White is ready to start putting pressure on the d6-pawn, but Black is just in time to prevent any problems. }
13... d5 14. cxd5 exd5 15. Rad1
{ White can also play  15.Na4  first, but it is likely to be a transposition to our main line. }
15... d4 { A crucial advance, Black doesn't want to sit and wait passively. }
16. Na4 Rf7 { An original way to activate the rook. } 17. Bxd4 Rd7
{ Black's idea is that in return for the sacrificed pawn, gets pressure on the d-file, the pair of bishops, and pressure along the a8-h1 diagonal. }
18. e3 b6 19. Nf4
{ If White plays something like  19.Qb2  , suddenly a nasty pin over the d-file will appear after  19...Ne6  . }
19... Bb7 { The white king doesn't feel safe. } 20. f3 Bxd4 21. exd4 Qf6 22.
Nc3 Rad8
{ The position is equal. If White wants to hang to the extra pawn, that will result in a passive situation without any perspective for progress. Black has good, active pieces and can easily take over the initiative. }
