4... Bg7 5. c4 O-O 6. Nc3
{ In the systems where White plays Nh3 and c2-c4, Black typically plays ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5. If White has played d4-d5, White will take on e6, Black will play ...c7-c6, ...Na6-c5 and recapture the pawn on e6. }
6... d6 7. O-O
{ If White first plays  7.d5  , Black responds with  7...c6  and after  8.O-O  wetranspose to the main line, while after  8.Nf4  wetranspose to the line with 7.Nf4 and 8.d5. }
7... c6 8. d5 h6
{ Preventing the knight jump to g5 and preparing the next move. } 9. Qc2
{ White is preparing e2-e4. } 9... Na6
{ Indirectly defending the pawn on  c6  because if White now takes twice,  10.dxc6  bxc6  11.Bxc6  , White loses the bishop after  11...Nb4  . }
10. Nf4
{ Instead,  10.e4  is not great because Black simply plays  10...Nc5  and  11.exf5  is not good because of  11...Bxf5  . }
10... Qe8 { Defending the pawns on g6 and c6. } 11. Nd3 cxd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13.
cxd5 g5 14. f4 Qg6
{ Here Black played  14...g4  in the game Harabor-Pirs,  ICCF email 2017, after which some exchanges happened on the c-file and on e4, and the game quickly ended in a draw. To keep more tension in the position Black can play the text move, followed by ...Bd7 and ...Rac8. }
