[White "8. Dutch 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bg5"]
[Black "Dutch 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bg5 − 5.Bxf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. Bg5
{ In this system White often takes on f6 followed by playing e2-e4. Black's typical response is to counter with ...d7-d5 and subsequently, we often get good play on the queenside. }
3... e6
{ I prefer this move over ...Ne4 because in general in the opening I want to develop my pieces and not play too often with the same piece. }
4. Nbd2 Be7
{ A sharp continuation from Black − we don't take control over the e4-square despite that White is ready to play e2-e4 and Black could have prevented it with ...d7-d5. }
5. Bxf6
{ White plays for the central break with e2-e4.   If White plays  5.c3  we transpose to the main line after  5...O-O  6.Bxf6  Bxf6  7.e4  d5  . }
5... Bxf6 6. e4 O-O
{ There is no need to take on e4, White wants to take advantage of the light squares, so it is unlikely the pressure against the f5-pawn will be released by playing e4-e5. }
7. Bd3 d6
{ I am not sure about this move. The only way to justify ...d7-d6 is to follow up by playing ...e6-e5 at some point, but I cannot make it work. }
8. c3 Nc6
{ In these types of positions, Black wants to push ...e6-e5 @@StartBracket@@usually after taking on e4@@EndBracket@@ and not play ...c7-c5, so that is why ...Nc6 is a standard move here. }
9. Qc2 fxe4 10. Nxe4
{ White threatens to take on f6 and then win a pawn by taking on h7 with check. }
10... h6 11. O-O e5
{ Now that h7 is no longer hanging and White cannot play a knight to g5, it is time for this advance. }
12. dxe5
{ White is going for a massive exchange operation to prove that the lead in development means something. }
12... Nxe5 13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. Nxe5 Qxe5 15. Rae1
{ White was already one tempo ahead of Black @@StartBracket@@the bishop on c8 hasn't been developed yet@@EndBracket@@ and now White wins a second tempo, meaning the rook is also active. }
15... Qg5 16. Re3
{ White has a clear advantage. The black queen on g5 can easily be chased away, White controls the e-file and can potentially play Re7 @@StartBracket@@after Rfe1@@EndBracket@@ and if Black plays ...Bd7 we need to be careful to not be hit by Qb3+, winning a pawn on b7. }
*

