[Black "Dutch 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bg5 − 5.Bxf6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. Bg5
{ In this system White often takes on f6 followed by playing e2-e4. Black's typical response is to counter with ...d7-d5 and subsequently, we often get good play on the queenside. }
3... e6
{ I prefer this move over ...Ne4 because in general in the opening I want to develop my pieces and not play too often with the same piece. }
4. Nbd2 Be7
{ A sharp continuation from Black − we don't take control over the e4-square despite that White is ready to play e2-e4 and Black could have prevented it with ...d7-d5. }
5. Bxf6
{ White plays for the central break with e2-e4.   If White plays  5.c3  we transpose to the main line after  5...O-O  6.Bxf6  Bxf6  7.e4  d5  . }
5... Bxf6 6. e4 O-O
{ There is no need to take on e4, White wants to take advantage of the light squares, so it is unlikely the pressure against the f5-pawn will be released by playing e4-e5. }
7. Bd3 d5
{ Now that Black has obtained the pair of bishops, it is a good moment to fight for the light squares, even if that means playing a Stonewall structure. }
8. e5 Be7 9. c3 c5
{ Black grabs space on the queenside and keeps the option open to do the same on the kingside with ...g7-g5. }
10. O-O b6
{ With Black's pieces on the queenside not yet developed, it is too early to play ...c5-c4. After retreating the d3-bishop, White will start undermining Black by playing b2-b3 and sometimes a2-a4, while Black still needs to develop. }
11. Re1 Nc6 12. Nf1 Bd7
{ It doesn't make sense to put this bishop on b7 where it is blocked by the d5-pawn. Black can consider playing ...a7-a5 followed by ...Ba6, in the hope to exchange the bishops and take control over the light squares, but this plan does take a lot of time. }
13. h3 Be8
{ I prefer Black, the bishop can come to h5 or g6 and further expansion on the kingside with ...g7-g5 will follow soon. Or Black will try to take space on the queenside with ...c5-c4 followed by ...b6-b5-b4. }
