5. Bxf6
{ White plays for the central break with e2-e4.   If White plays  5.c3  we transpose to the main line after  5...O-O  6.Bxf6  Bxf6  7.e4  d5  . }
5... Bxf6 6. e4 O-O
{ There is no need to take on e4, White wants to take advantage of the light squares, so it is unlikely the pressure against the f5-pawn will be released by playing e4-e5. }
7. Bd3 d5
{ Now that Black has obtained the pair of bishops, it is a good moment to fight for the light squares, even if that means playing a Stonewall structure. }
8. e5 Be7 9. O-O b6
{ Black threatens to play ...Ba6, exchange the bishops and fight for the light squares. }
10. Qe2 c5
{ Undermining White's center who doesn't have time for c2-c4 because Black would first take on c4 and then on d4. }
11. c3 Nc6 12. Rad1 a5
{ Black is ready to advance further on the queenside with ...c5-c4, ...b6-b5-b4 and it is not clear how White will generate counterplay. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Dutch 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bg5"]
[Black "Dutch 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bg5 − 5.Bxf6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. Bg5
{ In this system White often takes on f6 followed by playing e2-e4. Black's typical response is to counter with ...d7-d5 and subsequently, we often get good play on the queenside. }
3... e6
{ I prefer this move over ...Ne4 because in general in the opening I want to develop my pieces and not play too often with the same piece. }
4. Nbd2 Be7
{ A sharp continuation from Black − we don't take control over the e4-square despite that White is ready to play e2-e4 and Black could have prevented it with ...d7-d5. }
5. Bxf6
{ White plays for the central break with e2-e4.   If White plays  5.c3  we transpose to the main line after  5...O-O  6.Bxf6  Bxf6  7.e4  d5  . }
5... Bxf6 6. e4 O-O
{ There is no need to take on e4, White wants to take advantage of the light squares, so it is unlikely the pressure against the f5-pawn will be released by playing e4-e5. }
7. Bd3 d5
{ Now that Black has obtained the pair of bishops, it is a good moment to fight for the light squares, even if that means playing a Stonewall structure. }
8. exf5 { White continues to put pressure on the light squares. } 8... exf5 9.
O-O Nc6
{ The plan with ...b7-b6 followed by ...c7-c5 might be playable, it just seems a bit slow here. }
10. Nb3 { Defending the pawn on d4 while keeping the c2-c4 option open. } 10...
Qd6
{ More active than first ...Bd7 and the queen has no other good square than e7, but there it might not be able to go to because of Re1. }
11. Re1 Bd7 12. c3 b6
{ Taking control over the c5-square and maybe in the far future Black will play ...c7-c5. }
13. Qc2 g6 14. Re2 Rae8
{ Black has to oppose on the e-file, we don't want to allow White to double rooks there without doing anything ourselves. }
15. Rae1 Rxe2 16. Rxe2 Re8 17. Rxe8+ Bxe8
{ The position was equal in Harikrishna-Giri, Germany 2014. Both sides have healthy pawn structures, there is only one open file but all the entry points are defended. It is difficult for both sides to make a lot of progress. }
*

