7. Bd3 d5
{ Now that Black has obtained the pair of bishops, it is a good moment to fight for the light squares, even if that means playing a Stonewall structure. }
8. exf5 { White continues to put pressure on the light squares. } 8... exf5 9.
O-O Nc6
{ The plan with ...b7-b6 followed by ...c7-c5 might be playable, it just seems a bit slow here. }
10. c3 { Trying to limit the power of the f6-bishop. } 10... Qd6
{ First developing the queen and then the bishop to d7. } 11. Re1
{ Was played in Gurevich-Schwartzman, in 1997. } 11... Bd7 12. b4
{ Gaining space on the queenside and hoping to play b4-b5 followed by a knight to e5. }
12... Rae8 { Black maintains sufficient control over the e5-square. } 13. Qc2
g6 14. b5 Nd8 { 14...Ne7  doesn't make sense, the knight has no future on e7. }
15. Nb3 b6
{ Black has no problems. We will follow up with ...Ne6, maybe even ...Nf4 and if we really want to play for a win, we may play ...Rc8 followed by ...c7-c5. If White takes on c6, Black will take back and suddenly the pawn on c3 looks weak. }
