{ There is no need to take on e4, White wants to take advantage of the light squares, so it is unlikely the pressure against the f5-pawn will be released by playing e4-e5. }
7. c3 { Limiting the power of the f6-bishop. } 7... d5
{ Black decided to fight for the light squares now that we have obtained the bishop pair. }
8. e5 Be7 9. Nb3
{ White's idea is to make it harder for Black to play ...c7-c5. } 9... a5 10.
a4 g5
{ In a way, this is aggressive because Black is potentially playing on two sides. We don't want to play ...g5-g4 any time soon, just grab space on the kingside, maybe follow up with ...Qe8-g6, while also keeping the option open of playing ...b7-b6 and ...c7-c5. If you don't like ...g7-g5 you can also go straight for ...c7-c5 with ...b7-b6 first. }
11. Bd3 b6 12. Nc1 c5
{ This position is fine for Black, there is no way White can prove that Black is overextended. Next, Black could play ...Ba6 to exchange the bishops and put the knight on c6 and a rook on c8 before thinking about any further expansion. }
