[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Dutch 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bg5"]
[Black "Dutch 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bg5 − Alternative 4...d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. Bg5
{ In this system White often takes on f6 followed by playing e2-e4. Black's typical response is to counter with ...d7-d5 and subsequently, we often get good play on the queenside. }
3... e6
{ I prefer this move over ...Ne4 because in general in the opening I want to develop my pieces and not play too often with the same piece. }
4. Nbd2 d5
{ This continuation is more solid than  4...Be7  , which is the move I recommend because I play the Leningrad System for exciting positions. However, if you are in the mood for a slow game, or maybe you have an opponent who will go wild anyway, then  4...d5  is a good option. I will show some sample lines/ideas. }
5. e3 Be7
{ The bishop can also go to d6, it doesn't make a big difference. On d6 White can sometimes gain a tempo by playing c4-c5, increasing the space advantage on the queenside, followed by b2-b4-b5. Putting the bishop on d6 sometimes gives Black chances for an attack on White's king, but in this case, it is not so easy. If Black wants that, probably needs to castle short, play ...Qh5, followed by ...h7-h6, and then ...g7-g5-g4. }
6. c4
{ White can play this move also immediately. In general, White will try to create play on the queenside where it is easy to develop a space advantage, while Black will focus on the center and the kingside. }
6... c6 7. Qc2 O-O 8. Bd3 Ne4 { 8...Nbd7  first is also fine. } 9. Bxe7 Qxe7
10. O-O Nd7
{ The plan to fianchetto the bishop to b7 I have played a few times myself in the Stonewall. It can give exciting positions, but in this specific case, Black might just be a bit too much behind in development to make it work.  10...b6  11.Ne5  Bb7  12.cxd5  exd5  . Taking back with the c-pawn will result in long-term weaknesses on the queenside.  White will play a rook to c1 and the queen either to c7 or a4.    13.f4  Rc8  ,  Black would like to develop the knight to d7 and in the future, hopefully, ...c6–c5, but first the pawn on c6 needs to be defended.  14.Nxe4  ,  the start of a surprising way to create a new square for the d3–bishop. Not all of your opponents will find this kind of idea.  14...fxe4  15.Be2  Rc7  .  ...Nd7 was again not possible because of Bg4.  16.Bg4  and Black's position feels awkward, not easy to complete development. }
11. a3 { White plans b2-b4, Black wants to push the g-pawn forward. } 11... a5
{ Black decides that if White pushes b2-b4, he will at least have his rook on the open a-file. }
12. Rab1 g5
{ Although there is no mate in sight @@StartBracket@@Black misses the dark-squared bishop@@EndBracket@@ it is still a good idea to gain space by pushing White's pieces. }
13. b4 axb4 14. axb4 g4 15. Ne5 { 15.Ne1  is a passive alternative. } 15...
Nxe5 16. dxe5 Qg7 17. f4
{ There is no other way for White to defend the pawn on e5 because on  17.Qb2  there is simply  17...Nxd2  followed by ...Qxe5. }
17... gxf3 18. Nxf3 Bd7
{ Black has an active position, the rook can come to a3, the other rook can sometimes go to g8 and if White opens the queenside, the d7-bishop may become strong. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Dutch 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bg5"]
[Black "Dutch 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bg5 − Alternative 4...d5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. Bg5
{ In this system White often takes on f6 followed by playing e2-e4. Black's typical response is to counter with ...d7-d5 and subsequently, we often get good play on the queenside. }
3... e6
{ I prefer this move over ...Ne4 because in general in the opening I want to develop my pieces and not play too often with the same piece. }
4. Nbd2 d5
{ This continuation is more solid than  4...Be7  , which is the move I recommend because I play the Leningrad System for exciting positions. However, if you are in the mood for a slow game, or maybe you have an opponent who will go wild anyway, then  4...d5  is a good option. I will show some sample lines/ideas. }
5. e3 Be7
{ The bishop can also go to d6, it doesn't make a big difference. On d6 White can sometimes gain a tempo by playing c4-c5, increasing the space advantage on the queenside, followed by b2-b4-b5. Putting the bishop on d6 sometimes gives Black chances for an attack on White's king, but in this case, it is not so easy. If Black wants that, probably needs to castle short, play ...Qh5, followed by ...h7-h6, and then ...g7-g5-g4. }
6. Be2 O-O 7. h3
{ The idea of this move is that after ...h7-h6 White can keep the bishop via h4 or f4 and then after ...g7-g5 it can drop back to h2. }
7... Nbd7 8. c4 c6 9. Bf4 Ne4 10. Bh2 b6
{ This move is logical because White is not far ahead in development @@StartBracket@@the dark-squared bishop has lost tempi@@EndBracket@@, so there is no knight on e5, no rook on c1, and no castle yet. }
11. O-O Bb7
{ Black had no opening problems in Vitiugov-Moiseenko, Karlsruhe 2016. We can continue with ...Rc8 and ...c6-c5, perhaps in combination with ...Bf6 and ...Kh8 followed by ...g7-g5, which is also an option. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Hopton Attack 2.Bg5"]
[Black "Hopton Attack 2.Bg5 h6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Bg5
{ The idea of this move is to make Black's development more difficult. If Black is losing too much time, White will generate a lot of play on the white squares by either hitting the e6-square or the pawn on g6 @@StartBracket@@for example with h2-h4-h5@@EndBracket@@ or a central break with e2-e4.  The plan for Black is to develop the bishop to g7, play ...h7-h6 first, and only then play the knight to f6. Subsequently, Black plays ...d6 and usually ...e6 and ...Qe7, with firm control over the e6-square, and is ready to complete development, castle either kingside or queenside and go for the central break ...e6-e5. Especially when White castles queenside, Black will focus on opening the lines of the g7 and e6-bishop and start an attack. }
2... h6
{ A move played by many strong players but I do not recommend it. Based on a game played by Delchev, combined with further engine analysis, I cannot find satisfactory play for Black.   2...Nf6  is not a great move either.  3.Bxf6  exf6  . This lookssimilar to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppppp1pp/8/5p2/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.Bg5  but the difference is that here @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp2pp/5p2/5p2/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ the white knight is  not yet on c3, meaning White can play  4.e3  d5  and now push  5.c4  immediately,  5...Be6  and then follow up with  6.Qb3  and Nc3, creating a lot of pressure on the light squares. }
3. Bh4 g5 4. e3 Nf6 5. Bg3 d6 6. h4
{ White is likely to move the queen to d2 and then lose control over the h5-square. Black could consider playing ...Nh5 then, to swap the bishop on g3 and have a nice pair of bishops. By playing h4 at an early stage, White ensures the h-file will be open and Black can forget about ...Nh5 ideas. }
6... Rg8
{ After  6...g4  White can play  7.Bc4  to ensure the Black e-pawn needs to go to  7...e6  and then continue with  8.Ne2  and Nf4. There will be a lot of pressure on this e6-pawn and I have not been able to find a clear path to equality for Black. }
7. hxg5 hxg5 8. Nc3 e6
{ I was studying these types of positions. Sometimes with h4, ...Rg8 included and pawns are exchanged on g5, and sometimes with pawns on h2 and h6. I prefer a pawn exchange to rule out Nh5 ideas, but both White and Black will likely castle queenside in all cases. White has a little more space, but Black controls a lot of squares around the center and hopes to bury White's bishop on h2 after playing ...f5-f4. }
9. Qd2 Qe7 { Both sides continue to develop so they can castle queenside. } 10.
f3
{ White has more space and would like to gain even more with e3-e4 but also wants to ensure that the bishop on g3 can go back to f2 where it has a lot more potential than on h2. }
10... Nc6 11. O-O-O Bd7 12. e4
{ White is occupying the center and increases the space advantage. } 12... f4
13. Bf2
{ The bishop is a lot more active here than on h2. Potentially, White can start an attack on Black's king after castling, and then the bishop already eyes the a7-square. }
13... a6 14. Nge2
{ A precise move.  14.Bc4  ,  possibly prepared by a3 so the bishop can hide on a2 was the alternative, but White is targeting Black's pawn on f4. Pawns can never move back, if the pawn was still on f7 here, Black would have been more solid. }
14... Bg7 15. g3 e5
{ Black would have preferred to keep this pawn on e6 to keep control over the d5 and f5 squares but after  15...fxg3  16.Nxg3  g4  17.f4  White has gained even more space. }
16. gxf4 gxf4
{ And although White obtained a nice advantage in Delchev-Beerdsen Anogia 2019, he could have gained a decisive advantage here with the text move. }
17. Nd5
{ White is trying to open the e-file considering Black still has the king in the middle of the board. }
17... Nxd5 18. exd5 Nxd4
{ Going back to b8 with the knight would be suicidal, Black is too far behind in development. }
19. Nxd4 exd4 20. Bh4
{ Of course, now it is impossible for Black to castle queenside and cannot offer an exchange of bishops on f6 either as White would play Re1 and win the queen. }
20... Qf8 21. Re1+ Be5 22. Qxd4
{ And White is much better. Black's king is stuck in the center, White threatens Rxe5 and there is no way for Black to escape. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Hopton Attack 2.Bg5"]
[Black "Hopton Attack 2.Bg5 g6 3.h4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Bg5
{ The idea of this move is to make Black's development more difficult. If Black is losing too much time, White will generate a lot of play on the white squares by either hitting the e6-square or the pawn on g6 @@StartBracket@@for example with h2-h4-h5@@EndBracket@@ or a central break with e2-e4.  The plan for Black is to develop the bishop to g7, play ...h7-h6 first, and only then play the knight to f6. Subsequently, Black plays ...d6 and usually ...e6 and ...Qe7, with firm control over the e6-square, and is ready to complete development, castle either kingside or queenside and go for the central break ...e6-e5. Especially when White castles queenside, Black will focus on opening the lines of the g7 and e6-bishop and start an attack. }
2... g6
{ My preferred choice for two reasons: I don't really trust Black's alternatives.Black's play is similar to other key lines in the Leningrad. }
3. h4
{ An aggresive move that we see in many lines of the Leningrad system, White wants to weaken the g6-pawn or chase away the g7-bishop with h5-h6. }
3... Bg7 4. e3 { A quiet option. } 4... h6
{ Let's hit the bishop so that if White ever plays h4-h5, we can answer with ...g6-g5. }
5. Bf4 d6
{ We want to take control over the e5-square as we would love to play ...e7-e5 at some point. }
6. Bc4 Nc6
{ Keep developing, an immediate ...e7-e5 is not yet okay for Black.   6...e5  7.dxe5  dxe5  and now a small trick:  8.Bf7+!  Ke7  9.Qxd8+  Kxd8  Black's king is in  an awkward position and both the g6- and e5-pawns are weak.  10.Bh2  Ne7  , and now after normal developing moves  11.Nc3  Rf8  12.O-O-O+  Bd7  13.Bb3  White has a clear advantage. Black's pieces do not coordinate, they don't threaten anything and the king stands in the way too. }
7. Nc3 Nf6
{ 7...e5  is again too early.  8.dxe5  and now, because Black is not yet developed, has to take back on e5 with the knight.  8...Nxe5   8...dxe5  fails to  9.Qxd8+  Nxd8  10.Nb5  and Black is in trouble.  9.Bb3  and White is a little better. The white squares in Black's  camp are weak and because Black had to take back with the knight on e5, we don't have a lot of central activity. }
8. Nf3
{ Now there is nothing wrong with Black's standard plan: ...e6, ...Qe7, ...Bd7, then castle queenside and play ...e6-e5. }
8... e6
{ 8...Ng4  looks attractive but actually Black is not yet ready for this action.  9.Qe2  Na5  , trying to exchange the white bishop.  10.Bd3!   10.Bb3  was much worse for White in Hoi-Danielsen, Denmark 1997.  10...e5  seems to win a piece, but again Black should first have developed before taking central action.  11.dxe5  dxe5  12.O-O-O  ,  threatening to win material with Bb5+.  12...Qf6  13.e4  , one of those brilliant engine moves!  13...exf4  14.exf5+  Qe7  15.Rhe1  and despite the fact that Black is a piece up, the engine gives a clear advantage for White based on the lead in development.  A sample line:  15...Qxe2  16.Rxe2+  Kf8  17.fxg6  Bxc3  18.bxc3  Nc6  19.Rde1  Bd7  20.Nd4  Rg8  21.Re4  Rxg6  22.Nxc6  Rxc6  23.Bb5  and Black's position collapses. }
9. Qe2 Qe7 10. O-O-O Bd7 11. Bg3 O-O-O
{ Black has developed harmoniously and is ready for central expansion with ...e6-e5. Because White struggles to become active  @@StartBracket@@e3-e4 loses a piece@@EndBracket@@ most humans would prefer to take Black here. }
12. e4 { White would love to play this central break but it backfires. } 12...
fxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 d5 { And White just donated a piece. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Hopton Attack 2.Bg5"]
[Black "Hopton Attack 2.Bg5 g6 3.h4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Bg5
{ The idea of this move is to make Black's development more difficult. If Black is losing too much time, White will generate a lot of play on the white squares by either hitting the e6-square or the pawn on g6 @@StartBracket@@for example with h2-h4-h5@@EndBracket@@ or a central break with e2-e4.  The plan for Black is to develop the bishop to g7, play ...h7-h6 first, and only then play the knight to f6. Subsequently, Black plays ...d6 and usually ...e6 and ...Qe7, with firm control over the e6-square, and is ready to complete development, castle either kingside or queenside and go for the central break ...e6-e5. Especially when White castles queenside, Black will focus on opening the lines of the g7 and e6-bishop and start an attack. }
2... g6
{ My preferred choice for two reasons: I don't really trust Black's alternatives.Black's play is similar to other key lines in the Leningrad. }
3. h4
{ An aggresive move that we see in many lines of the Leningrad system, White wants to weaken the g6-pawn or chase away the g7-bishop with h5-h6. }
3... Bg7 4. e3 { A quiet option. } 4... h6
{ Let's hit the bishop so that if White ever plays h4-h5, we can answer with ...g6-g5. }
5. Bf4 d6
{ We want to take control over the e5-square as we would love to play ...e7-e5 at some point. }
6. Bc4 Nc6
{ Keep developing, an immediate ...e7-e5 is not yet okay for Black.   6...e5  7.dxe5  dxe5  and now a small trick:  8.Bf7+!  Ke7  9.Qxd8+  Kxd8  Black's king is in  an awkward position and both the g6- and e5-pawns are weak.  10.Bh2  Ne7  , and now after normal developing moves  11.Nc3  Rf8  12.O-O-O+  Bd7  13.Bb3  White has a clear advantage. Black's pieces do not coordinate, they don't threaten anything and the king stands in the way too. }
7. c3 { Again, we rely on the system with e6, Qe7 and Bd7. } 7... Nf6 8. Nf3 e6
9. Nbd2 Qe7
{ And now if White castles short, we do the same with Black, if White castles long, Black also goes long. }
10. Qe2
{ If White castles short with  10.O-O  , Black does the same  10...O-O  because preparing castling queenside is dangerous.  With the pawn on c3 White can quickly advance with b2-b4-b5 and if needed, the a-pawn as well. }
10... Bd7 11. O-O-O O-O-O
{ It is much more likely that Black will achieve ...e6-e5 than White achieving e3-e4, which is why I would prefer Black in this position. We are likely to gain space and control over the center. }
*

