[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Hopton Attack 2.Bg5"]
[Black "Hopton Attack 2.Bg5 g6 3.h4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Bg5
{ The idea of this move is to make Black's development more difficult. If Black is losing too much time, White will generate a lot of play on the white squares by either hitting the e6-square or the pawn on g6 @@StartBracket@@for example with h2-h4-h5@@EndBracket@@ or a central break with e2-e4.  The plan for Black is to develop the bishop to g7, play ...h7-h6 first, and only then play the knight to f6. Subsequently, Black plays ...d6 and usually ...e6 and ...Qe7, with firm control over the e6-square, and is ready to complete development, castle either kingside or queenside and go for the central break ...e6-e5. Especially when White castles queenside, Black will focus on opening the lines of the g7 and e6-bishop and start an attack. }
2... g6
{ My preferred choice for two reasons: I don't really trust Black's alternatives.Black's play is similar to other key lines in the Leningrad. }
3. h4
{ An aggresive move that we see in many lines of the Leningrad system, White wants to weaken the g6-pawn or chase away the g7-bishop with h5-h6. }
3... Bg7 4. h5
{ These types of moves always make me nervous behind the board, even when I know it is not a great one. Why? Because I know that if I make one slip, I might lose. }
4... h6 { If possible at all, we really want to play ...h6 and ...g5. } 5. Bd2
g5 6. e3 { Now we start developing with Black in our normal way. } 6... Nf6 7.
Nf3 d6 { Taking away the e5-square from the white knight. } 8. Nc3 e6 9. Qe2
{ White wants to play e3-e4. By developing the bishop to c4 first, White may never get to play e3-e4 since after exchanging on e4, Black will win a piece with ...d6-d5. Bd3 was an alternative for Qe2, but the bishop is on d3 less effective than on c4 @@StartBracket@@after White has played e3-e4@@EndBracket@@ and might get harrassed by Black's ...Nc6-b4. }
9... Nc6 10. e4
{ No panic, White doesn't threaten e4-e5 so we can keep the tension with Black. }
10... O-O 11. O-O-O
{ 11.e5?  dxe5  12.dxe5  Ng4  and the e5-pawn will drop.  But after the text move, we need to be careful with Black. }
11... Ng4
{ We know that White would like to sacrifice on g5, followed by playing ...h5-h6, but there is a simple solution. We protect the g5-pawn and cover the h6-square twice.   11...Bd7?  actually loses in an instructive way.  12.Bxg5!  White's main idea is  12...hxg5  13.h6  Bh8  and although Black doesn't lose immediately, the position is really not okay.  14.exf5  exf5  15.Nxg5  ,  threatening Qc4+.  15...d5  16.h7+  Kg7  17.Qd2  and now a check on h6 is White's idea. The engine can no longer find a defense for Black. }
12. g3 Bd7 13. Kb1 a6
{ It is Black that will start an attack on the queenside with ...b7-b5 next. }
