[Black "Hopton Attack 3.Nd2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Bg5
{ The idea of this move is to make Black's development more difficult. If Black is losing too much time, White will generate a lot of play on the white squares by either hitting the e6-square or the pawn on g6 @@StartBracket@@for example with h2-h4-h5@@EndBracket@@ or a central break with e2-e4.  The plan for Black is to develop the bishop to g7, play ...h7-h6 first, and only then play the knight to f6. Subsequently, Black plays ...d6 and usually ...e6 and ...Qe7, with firm control over the e6-square, and is ready to complete development, castle either kingside or queenside and go for the central break ...e6-e5. Especially when White castles queenside, Black will focus on opening the lines of the g7 and e6-bishop and start an attack. }
2... g6
{ My preferred choice for two reasons: I don't really trust Black's alternatives.Black's play is similar to other key lines in the Leningrad. }
3. Nd2 Bg7 4. e4 fxe4 5. Nxe4 d5 6. Ng3 c5 7. dxc5
{ This move might be slightly inaccurate compared to  7.Nf3  as played by Aronian, which we have seen previously. }
7... Bxb2 8. Rb1 Bc3+
{ Black wants to attack the pawn on c5 as soon as possible and playing ...Bc3+ followed by ...Qa5 is the standard way of doing this. }
9. Bd2 Qa5 10. Nf3 Nf6
{ According to the engine, Black can also take on c5, but I prefer to stick as much as possible to general principles and in these 2.Bg5 lines it is important for Black to complete development before going pawn hunting. }
11. Be2 Bxd2+ 12. Nxd2 Nbd7
{ The difference with the7.Nf3 line is that now Black's queenside knight can still attack the c5-pawn. }
13. O-O Nxc5 14. c4 Be6 15. cxd5 Bxd5 16. Bb5+ Kf7
{ And although the engine gives equality, Black is still a pawn up and has every chance to play for a win. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Hopton Attack 2.Bg5"]
[Black "Hopton Attack 3.Nd2 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Bg5
{ The idea of this move is to make Black's development more difficult. If Black is losing too much time, White will generate a lot of play on the white squares by either hitting the e6-square or the pawn on g6 @@StartBracket@@for example with h2-h4-h5@@EndBracket@@ or a central break with e2-e4.  The plan for Black is to develop the bishop to g7, play ...h7-h6 first, and only then play the knight to f6. Subsequently, Black plays ...d6 and usually ...e6 and ...Qe7, with firm control over the e6-square, and is ready to complete development, castle either kingside or queenside and go for the central break ...e6-e5. Especially when White castles queenside, Black will focus on opening the lines of the g7 and e6-bishop and start an attack. }
2... g6
{ My preferred choice for two reasons: I don't really trust Black's alternatives.Black's play is similar to other key lines in the Leningrad. }
3. Nd2 Bg7 4. e4 fxe4 5. Nxe4 d5 6. Nc5 b6 7. Nb3 Nh6
{ This is played often here, but it doesn't have my preference. First of all, it is easier to remember if Black always places the knight on f6 in the 2.Bg5 line. I once made the mistake to drop it on h6 against Moiseenko @@StartBracket@@see further below@@EndBracket@@ and lost quickly because I mixed up lines. Secondly, 7...Nh6 is typically a move to unbalance the position, but there is no need to do that here.  It is already a dynamic position with the strange knight on b3 and the backward pawn on e7. If Black can play ...e7-e5 at some point, we could easily be better and we can also start chasing the knight on b3 with the idea to weaken White's pawn structure on the queenside. In my view, there is not really a need for more creative moves, but if you feel like it, feel free to study 7...Nh6, I believe Black can also reach a dynamic, balanced position in those lines. A sample line could be: }
8. c3 Nf7
{ This is the idea behind ...Nh6: to place the knight on f7 and prepare ...e7-e5. }
9. Bh4 a5 10. a4 Bf6
{ How else to prepare e7-e5? The pawn on e7 is pinned and the black queen doesn't have a good square to go to.  10...Qd6  is answered by  11.Bg3  . }
11. Bxf6
{ If White doesn't take, Black is ready for ...e7-e5. After the exchange on f6, the black pawn structure is also repaired as there is no longer a weakness on e7. }
11... exf6 12. Bd3 O-O 13. Ne2 Qd6 14. O-O
{ Black will try to take control over the light squares by putting a pawn on f5 and sometimes offering the exchange of bishops via ...Ba6. }
14... f5 15. Re1 Nd7
{ The immediate  15...Ba6  is also an option but after  16.Bxa6  , taking back with the knight  16...Nxa6  means it is a long way from  reaching the f6-square where the knight really belongs.  And taking back with the rook  16...Rxa6  is not an option because White will play  17.Qd2  ,  followed by Nf4 and Re6, controlling the e-file and Black is not in time to counter with ...Re8 because of the silly rook on a6. }
16. c4 dxc4 17. Bxc4
{ White is opening the light squares again and Black needs to watch the e6-square, we don't a white rook or knight to land there. }
17... Nf6 18. Nc3 Bd7 { With dynamic play for both sides. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Hopton Attack 2.Bg5"]
[Black "Hopton Attack 3.Nd2 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Bg5
{ The idea of this move is to make Black's development more difficult. If Black is losing too much time, White will generate a lot of play on the white squares by either hitting the e6-square or the pawn on g6 @@StartBracket@@for example with h2-h4-h5@@EndBracket@@ or a central break with e2-e4.  The plan for Black is to develop the bishop to g7, play ...h7-h6 first, and only then play the knight to f6. Subsequently, Black plays ...d6 and usually ...e6 and ...Qe7, with firm control over the e6-square, and is ready to complete development, castle either kingside or queenside and go for the central break ...e6-e5. Especially when White castles queenside, Black will focus on opening the lines of the g7 and e6-bishop and start an attack. }
2... g6
{ My preferred choice for two reasons: I don't really trust Black's alternatives.Black's play is similar to other key lines in the Leningrad. }
3. Nd2 Bg7 4. e4 fxe4 5. Nxe4 d5 6. Nc5 b6 7. Nb3 Nf6 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be2 Ne4
{ This move is possible because the white knight is not on d2 or c3 but b3. }
10. Bh4 a5 { Not just with the idea to attack the knight on b3 but also... }
11. O-O a4 12. Nbd2 a3 { With the idea to create weaknesses on the queenside. }
13. Nxe4 axb2 14. Rb1 dxe4 15. Bc4+ Kh8 16. Ne5
{ White has a nasty threat on f7, but Black is just in time. } 16... Ba6 17.
Bxa6 Rxa6 18. Rxb2 { And now we have to play an important move. } 18... Bxe5
{ It is not about the beautiful pieces we give up, but about the pieces that remain on the board and the knight is at least as strong as the bishop on h4 and it will be hard for White not to lose the e5-pawn. }
19. dxe5 Nc6
{ With a complex position − according to the engine, it is equal, but there is a lot of play. If the pawn on e4 is attacked, Black can defend with ...Ra4, and the white pawns on a2, c2, and e5 are all weak. In this type of position, the knight can easily become more active than the bishop on h4. }
