3. e4 { Not as crazy as some may think, Black needs to be careful! } 3... fxe4
4. Nc3 Nf6 5. f3 d5 6. fxe4 Nxe4 7. Nxe4 dxe4
{ And now White has two ways of playing, either continuing with brute force or going for the quiet option. }
8. Qd2 Bg7 9. Ne2 Nc6
{ Continuing to hit d4. Black doesn't have time for quiet moves because White will quickly develop a dangerous initiative. }
10. d5 Ne5 11. Nc3 Bf5 12. O-O-O h6 13. Bf4 c6 14. Kb1 Qa5
{ And Black will castle queenside. It remains a dynamic position, but there is always the danger of the pair of bishops. For example, if White hurries to win back the e4-pawn, it may end up in an inferior endgame precisely because of those bishops. }
