[White "9. Hopton Attack 2.Bg5"]
[Black "Hopton Attack 3.Nc3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Bg5
{ The idea of this move is to make Black's development more difficult. If Black is losing too much time, White will generate a lot of play on the white squares by either hitting the e6-square or the pawn on g6 @@StartBracket@@for example with h2-h4-h5@@EndBracket@@ or a central break with e2-e4.  The plan for Black is to develop the bishop to g7, play ...h7-h6 first, and only then play the knight to f6. Subsequently, Black plays ...d6 and usually ...e6 and ...Qe7, with firm control over the e6-square, and is ready to complete development, castle either kingside or queenside and go for the central break ...e6-e5. Especially when White castles queenside, Black will focus on opening the lines of the g7 and e6-bishop and start an attack. }
2... g6
{ My preferred choice for two reasons: I don't really trust Black's alternatives.Black's play is similar to other key lines in the Leningrad. }
3. Nc3 Bg7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bxf6
{ The idea of this move is to play for control over the light squares. The alternative  5.e3  is discussed via the move order4.e3, 5.Nf3. }
5... Bxf6 6. e4 fxe4
{ Whenever White plays e2-e4 in the 2.Bg5 line, Black will take on e4. Allowing e4-e5 is not a good idea because Black would end up with a lack of space when developing pieces will become harder. }
7. Nxe4 O-O
{ I don't recommend withdrawing the bishop:  7...Bg7  8.d5  White first takes away space from Black.  8...O-O  9.h4  and now  White starts an attack on the g6-pawn.  9...h6  10.Bd3  , I feel White has a nasty initiative here with the weakness of the g6-pawn and the lack of space for Black. All of Black's pieces on the queenside still need to be developed while White is using all the minor pieces already. }
8. Nxf6+ exf6
{ Taking back with the rook is not to be recommended. Black would be left with a pawn on e7 that is going nowhere and White can start an attack by combining Bd3 with h2-h4-h5. }
9. Qd2 Re8+
{ Rooks need to go to the open file and it forces White to place the bishop on a suboptimal square since d3 is preferable. }
10. Be2 d5
{ Taking space to develop our pieces. If Black plays ...d7-d6, White may play d4-d5 at some point and Black's position becomes cramped. }
11. O-O-O
{ An aggressive attempt from White, with the idea to generate an attack with h2-h4-h5. }
11... Qd6 { Black wants to take away the f4-square from the white queen. } 12.
h4 Nc6 { This knight can come to e7 to help defend the king if needed. } 13. h5
{ White threatens to take on g6 followed by Qh6. } 13... g5
{ Only move to stop White's attack. } 14. c3
{ With the idea to play Bd3, which if played without c2-c3, would be answered by ...Nb4. }
14... Bf5
{ Black has equalized: all the pieces are developed and White doesn't have any attack. Black can either play ...Re7 followed by ...Rae8 or take more risks and play ...Rab8 and aim for ...b7-b5 to start attacking the white king. }
