[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Hopton Attack 2.Bg5"]
[Black "Hopton Attack 3.Nc3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Bg5
{ The idea of this move is to make Black's development more difficult. If Black is losing too much time, White will generate a lot of play on the white squares by either hitting the e6-square or the pawn on g6 @@StartBracket@@for example with h2-h4-h5@@EndBracket@@ or a central break with e2-e4.  The plan for Black is to develop the bishop to g7, play ...h7-h6 first, and only then play the knight to f6. Subsequently, Black plays ...d6 and usually ...e6 and ...Qe7, with firm control over the e6-square, and is ready to complete development, castle either kingside or queenside and go for the central break ...e6-e5. Especially when White castles queenside, Black will focus on opening the lines of the g7 and e6-bishop and start an attack. }
2... g6
{ My preferred choice for two reasons: I don't really trust Black's alternatives.Black's play is similar to other key lines in the Leningrad. }
3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e3 d5
{ Taking firm control over the light squares.  4...d6  would create too many holes and White could continue with  5.Bc4  .   I don't have ...Nf6 as the main line because White could generate an attack without too much effort:  4...Nf6  5.h4  Ne4  .  If we don't play the knight here, White will go h4-h5 next, happy to sacrifice an exchange on h5 to start chasing the black king.    6.Nxe4  fxe4  7.f3  Black cannot really take on f3 because we would be even further behind in development.  7...d5  8.Qd2  O-O  9.O-O-O  .  In this position, it seems White will be much faster in attack than Black. It is hard to see how Black can threaten anything on the queenside, and moving forward the a- and b-pawn is not easy and not even scary for White. }
5. Nf3 { White wants to keep the e5-square under control. } 5... Nf6
{ 5...Nh6  is an alternative I don't fully trust because it is hard for Black  to get ...e7-e5 in, first of all because the queen from d8 is on the same diagonal as the bishop on g5 @@StartBracket@@or h4 after Black plays ...Nf7@@EndBracket@@ and secondly because White can start putting pressure on the pawn on d5 with c2-c4. }
6. h4 O-O
{ I try to avoid plans with a quick ...Ne4 because it will only make it easier for White to start an attack with g2-g4. }
7. Bxf6
{ White plays for attacking chances. The bishop can go back to f4, but this would effectively mean a loss of tempo. }
7... Bxf6 8. Qd2 e6
{ Black is preparing counterplay with ...c7-c5 and for that, the pawn on d5 needs to be well supported. }
9. Ne2 c5 10. Nf4 Qd6
{ And Black is fine, we will play next ...Nc6, maybe ...Bd7 and one day ...e6-e5. If White ever plays h4-h5, Black will react with ...g6-g5.   A sample line for illustration:  10...Qd6  11.c4  White is immediately putting pressure on the black center despite being behind in development.  11...cxd4  12.exd4  dxc4  13.Bxc4  ,  with the two exchanges in the center it has become clear that both sides have a weak pawn, e6 and d4.  13...Nc6  14.O-O  b5  .   Taking on d4 could result in loss of material as there are always tricks with Nxe6 at some point.  15.Bb3  a5  , Black keeps chasing the white bishop.  16.Rac1  a4  17.Bxe6+  White will win back the material because of the move d4-d5, attacking the queen and knight.  17...Bxe6  18.Nxe6  Qxe6  19.d5  Qd7  20.Rxc6  , White is a pawn up but there is a forced sequence to liquidate to a drawish endgame.   20...Rad8  21.Rd1  ,  the only way to defend the pawn on d5; after Rc5, ...Be7 would have been strong.  21...Qxc6  22.dxc6  Rxd2  23.Rxd2  Rc8  24.Rc2  and now it turns out that White cannot defend the pawn on b2 and the pawn on c6 at the same time, and if b2-b3, Black will play ...Bc3 and win the c6-pawn.    24...b4  25.Kf1  b3  26.axb3  axb3  27.Rc4  Bxb2  Black has won the pawn back, and although we may lose the b-pawn, the king is so close that White will lose the c-pawn.  28.Nd2  Kf7  29.Nxb3  Ke6  , and a draw is not far away since the c-pawn will drop. }
