[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Hopton Attack 2.Bg5"]
[Black "Hopton Attack 3.Nc3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Bg5
{ The idea of this move is to make Black's development more difficult. If Black is losing too much time, White will generate a lot of play on the white squares by either hitting the e6-square or the pawn on g6 @@StartBracket@@for example with h2-h4-h5@@EndBracket@@ or a central break with e2-e4.  The plan for Black is to develop the bishop to g7, play ...h7-h6 first, and only then play the knight to f6. Subsequently, Black plays ...d6 and usually ...e6 and ...Qe7, with firm control over the e6-square, and is ready to complete development, castle either kingside or queenside and go for the central break ...e6-e5. Especially when White castles queenside, Black will focus on opening the lines of the g7 and e6-bishop and start an attack. }
2... g6
{ My preferred choice for two reasons: I don't really trust Black's alternatives.Black's play is similar to other key lines in the Leningrad. }
3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e3 d5
{ Taking firm control over the light squares.  4...d6  would create too many holes and White could continue with  5.Bc4  .   I don't have ...Nf6 as the main line because White could generate an attack without too much effort:  4...Nf6  5.h4  Ne4  .  If we don't play the knight here, White will go h4-h5 next, happy to sacrifice an exchange on h5 to start chasing the black king.    6.Nxe4  fxe4  7.f3  Black cannot really take on f3 because we would be even further behind in development.  7...d5  8.Qd2  O-O  9.O-O-O  .  In this position, it seems White will be much faster in attack than Black. It is hard to see how Black can threaten anything on the queenside, and moving forward the a- and b-pawn is not easy and not even scary for White. }
5. h4
{ White wants to start attacking the pawn on g6 with h4-h5 and bring the knight to f4 or bishop to d3, followed by g2-g4. }
5... c6 6. Bd3 Nh6
{ Playing ...Nf6 is less precise because it doesn't stop White from the h4-h5 push and sacrifice the exchange on h5 for a dangerous attack. The idea of ...Nh6 is to place the knight on f7. }
7. h5 Nf7 8. Bf4 { The bishop takes away the f4-square from a white knight. }
8... Nd7 9. hxg6
{ If White plays  9.g4  , Black will respond with  9...g5  ,  followed by taking on g4. If White then recaptures with the queen on g4, Black plays ...Nf6 and is already a bit better thanks to the lead in development. }
9... hxg6 10. Rxh8+ Bxh8 11. Nf3
{ White is not in time to stop Black's main central break. } 11... e5 12. dxe5
Ndxe5
{ And Black has equalized. Next, we will prepare queenside castling and we may also decide to take the bishop on d3 and continue with the bishop pair. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Hopton Attack 2.Bg5"]
[Black "Hopton Attack 3.Nc3 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Bg5
{ The idea of this move is to make Black's development more difficult. If Black is losing too much time, White will generate a lot of play on the white squares by either hitting the e6-square or the pawn on g6 @@StartBracket@@for example with h2-h4-h5@@EndBracket@@ or a central break with e2-e4.  The plan for Black is to develop the bishop to g7, play ...h7-h6 first, and only then play the knight to f6. Subsequently, Black plays ...d6 and usually ...e6 and ...Qe7, with firm control over the e6-square, and is ready to complete development, castle either kingside or queenside and go for the central break ...e6-e5. Especially when White castles queenside, Black will focus on opening the lines of the g7 and e6-bishop and start an attack. }
2... g6
{ My preferred choice for two reasons: I don't really trust Black's alternatives.Black's play is similar to other key lines in the Leningrad. }
3. Nc3 Bg7 4. h4 Nh6
{ I made this mistake myself against Moiseenko, a player much stronger than me. }
5. Qd2 Nf7 6. Nf3 d6 { I thought I was playing all the normal moves. } 7. O-O-O
h6
{ To make sure that if White plays h4-h5 Black can play ...g6-g5, also to break the pin on the queen so that ...e7-e5 can be inserted later on. }
8. Bf4 Nc6 9. e4
{ White is not threatening anything, so I continued my development. } 9... O-O
10. Bd3 { And now as we have learned, the central break follows. } 10... e5 11.
dxe5 dxe5 12. Be3
{ Suddenly I realized I have a lost position. White threatens h4-h5 with a large advantage and if I prevent this with ...f5-f4 I am also much worse. }
12... f4
{ 12...b6  13.h5  .  Now ...g6-g5 is not possible as the f5-pawn would be hanging.  13...f4  14.hxg6  Nd6  15.Qe2  fxe3  .  If Black doesn't accept the piece, we will simply be a pawn down with a bad position. Accepting the piece gives White a winning attack:  16.Bc4+  Kh8  17.Bd5  Bb7  18.Qxe3  ,  threatening Rxh6 with mate and there is no defense anymore.  18...Rf4  19.g3  , Black can resign. }
13. Bc5 Re8 14. Bc4
{ The black pieces lack coordination and Black is not threatening anything. It is really a sad position. }
14... Be6 { And now White wins either the a7- or c7-pawn. } 15. Bxe6 Rxe6 16.
Qxd8+ Rxd8 17. Rxd8+ Ncxd8
{ 17...Nfxd8  18.Nd5  is winning for White as well. } 18. Bxa7
{ Sadly, we cannot lock in the bishop and win it too. } 18... b6 19. Nd5 Nc6
20. Nxc7 Rd6 21. Bxb6 Nb4 22. Ba5 { And Black is three pawns down. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Hopton Attack 2.Bg5"]
[Black "Hopton Attack 3.Nc3 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Bg5
{ The idea of this move is to make Black's development more difficult. If Black is losing too much time, White will generate a lot of play on the white squares by either hitting the e6-square or the pawn on g6 @@StartBracket@@for example with h2-h4-h5@@EndBracket@@ or a central break with e2-e4.  The plan for Black is to develop the bishop to g7, play ...h7-h6 first, and only then play the knight to f6. Subsequently, Black plays ...d6 and usually ...e6 and ...Qe7, with firm control over the e6-square, and is ready to complete development, castle either kingside or queenside and go for the central break ...e6-e5. Especially when White castles queenside, Black will focus on opening the lines of the g7 and e6-bishop and start an attack. }
2... g6
{ My preferred choice for two reasons: I don't really trust Black's alternatives.Black's play is similar to other key lines in the Leningrad. }
3. Nc3 Bg7 4. h4 h6
{ It is important to play this move before developing the knight to f6. If first  4...Nf6  and then  5.--  h6  , White may  decide to take  6.Bxf6  ,  winning 1-2 tempi @@StartBracket@@usually the bishop needs to return to g7 to protect the h6-pawn before Black can castle@@EndBracket@@ and use that to either break in the center with e2-e4 or with h4-h5, in both cases trying to weaken the light squares around Black's king.   The alternative  4...d5  is also playable, but in the Leningrad  repertoire I try to aim for structures with ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5 as often as possible, but there are lines where ...d7-d5 is a better move and those cases will be indicated. }
5. Bf4 Nf6
{ White can also prepare queenside castling by choosing the d2-square for the queen. }
6. Qd2 d6 { Black continues to aim for ...e7-e5. } 7. O-O-O Nc6
{ Black is not afraid of  8.d5  since  8...Ne5  can be played. } 8. e3 Bd7
{ Preparing e7-e5 which was not yet possible because White would have taken on d8 and then the e5-pawn will fall. }
9. Nh3 e5 10. Bh2 Qe7
{ It is a good idea to first give an extra cover of the e6-square and only then castle kingside. If Black would have castled immediately  10...O-O  , White can go for  11.Bc4+  ,  take on e5, followed by Ng5. }
11. Kb1 O-O
{ Black has completed development and has no problems. We managed to play ...e7-e5 and can start thinking about queenside expansion with ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5 to chase away the knight on c3 and increase the central control. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Hopton Attack 2.Bg5"]
[Black "Hopton Attack 3.Nc3 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Bg5
{ The idea of this move is to make Black's development more difficult. If Black is losing too much time, White will generate a lot of play on the white squares by either hitting the e6-square or the pawn on g6 @@StartBracket@@for example with h2-h4-h5@@EndBracket@@ or a central break with e2-e4.  The plan for Black is to develop the bishop to g7, play ...h7-h6 first, and only then play the knight to f6. Subsequently, Black plays ...d6 and usually ...e6 and ...Qe7, with firm control over the e6-square, and is ready to complete development, castle either kingside or queenside and go for the central break ...e6-e5. Especially when White castles queenside, Black will focus on opening the lines of the g7 and e6-bishop and start an attack. }
2... g6
{ My preferred choice for two reasons: I don't really trust Black's alternatives.Black's play is similar to other key lines in the Leningrad. }
3. Nc3 Bg7 4. h4 h6
{ It is important to play this move before developing the knight to f6. If first  4...Nf6  and then  5.--  h6  , White may  decide to take  6.Bxf6  ,  winning 1-2 tempi @@StartBracket@@usually the bishop needs to return to g7 to protect the h6-pawn before Black can castle@@EndBracket@@ and use that to either break in the center with e2-e4 or with h4-h5, in both cases trying to weaken the light squares around Black's king.   The alternative  4...d5  is also playable, but in the Leningrad  repertoire I try to aim for structures with ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5 as often as possible, but there are lines where ...d7-d5 is a better move and those cases will be indicated. }
5. Bf4 Nf6 6. Qd3
{ This is a move with independent value as White's idea is to attack the g6-pawn with the queen. }
6... d6 7. Qg3 { Black cannot defend this pawn, but that is not the end. } 7...
O-O 8. Qxg6 Ng4
{ Locking in the white queen, which could easily get lost, and Black also needed to defend against White's threat of Bxh6. }
9. Nf3
{ The idea of Nf3 is the same as if White would have played Nh3, the knight wants to go to g5 to deliver mate on h7 and if Black takes the knight with ...hxg5, the h-file will be open and the rook from h1 joins the attack, either by making Qh7+ possible or by playing Rh7. }
9... Rf6 10. Qh5 Bd7 { Black is threatening to win the queen after ...Be8. }
11. Nd5 Rf8 12. Qg6 e6
{ It is important to attack the knight and to have the queen cover the f6-square. I do not recommend chasing the knight away with ...c7-c6.   12...c6  13.Bxh6  Nxh6  14.Ng5  ,  threatening mate on h7, Black has only one move.  14...Rf6  15.Nxf6+  exf6  .  This shows the difference with 12...e6, the move I recommend. After 12...c6 Black needs to capture on f6 with the pawn, while after 12...e6 we can take with the queen on f6 and get to a slightly favorable endgame.    16.Qh7+  Kf8  17.Nh3  and this position is better for White. In terms of material,  the position is about equal, but Black's king hasn't found a safe place yet and White will soon play Nf4 and then either Nh5 or Ng6+ and Rh3-Rg3 is also an attacking idea. }
13. Ng5
{ If White would have played  13.Bxh6  , Black takes back with the knight  13...Nxh6  and after  14.Ng5  plays  14...Rf6  and Black is a little better according to the engine. }
13... hxg5 14. Bxg5
{ If Black wants to continue fighting we need to return some material. } 14...
Rf6
{ After  14...Nf6  White can force a draw by repetition.  15.Bh6  Ne8  16.Bg5  Nf6  .  Black defends against mate, White threatens the queen with Bg5, after ...Nf6 White plays Bh6 again and we can repeat forever. }
15. Nxf6+ Nxf6 16. h5
{ White has alternatives such as  16.g4  , when Black will take  16...fxg4  followed by  17.--  Qe8  , or @@StartFEN@@rn1q2k1/pppb2b1/3ppnQ1/5pB1/3P3P/8/PPP1PPP1/R3KB1R w KQ - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.e3  after which Black can also play  16...Qe8  . }
16... Qe8 { This is an essential part of Black's defense. } 17. Qxe8+ Bxe8 18.
h6 Bh8
{ It is hard to assess this position. My engine gives 0.00 in several different lines but I don't think that is useful information. Important factors are: White has a passed h-pawn, but it is not going anywhere, also there are no open lines where the white rooks can become active. Black should have no problem in playing ...Nc6 and then try to exchange one or two minor pieces and maximize the activity of the remaining forces. }
