[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Bg5
{ The idea of this move is to make Black's development more difficult. If Black is losing too much time, White will generate a lot of play on the white squares by either hitting the e6-square or the pawn on g6 @@StartBracket@@for example with h2-h4-h5@@EndBracket@@ or a central break with e2-e4.  The plan for Black is to develop the bishop to g7, play ...h7-h6 first, and only then play the knight to f6. Subsequently, Black plays ...d6 and usually ...e6 and ...Qe7, with firm control over the e6-square, and is ready to complete development, castle either kingside or queenside and go for the central break ...e6-e5. Especially when White castles queenside, Black will focus on opening the lines of the g7 and e6-bishop and start an attack. }
2... g6
{ My preferred choice for two reasons: I don't really trust Black's alternatives.Black's play is similar to other key lines in the Leningrad. }
3. Nc3 Bg7 4. h4 h6
{ It is important to play this move before developing the knight to f6. If first  4...Nf6  and then  5.--  h6  , White may  decide to take  6.Bxf6  ,  winning 1-2 tempi @@StartBracket@@usually the bishop needs to return to g7 to protect the h6-pawn before Black can castle@@EndBracket@@ and use that to either break in the center with e2-e4 or with h4-h5, in both cases trying to weaken the light squares around Black's king.   The alternative  4...d5  is also playable, but in the Leningrad  repertoire I try to aim for structures with ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5 as often as possible, but there are lines where ...d7-d5 is a better move and those cases will be indicated. }
5. Bf4 Nf6 6. Qd3
{ This is a move with independent value as White's idea is to attack the g6-pawn with the queen. }
6... d6 7. Qg3 { Black cannot defend this pawn, but that is not the end. } 7...
O-O 8. Qxg6 Ng4
{ Locking in the white queen, which could easily get lost, and Black also needed to defend against White's threat of Bxh6. }
9. f3 { A natural option for White is to attack the knight on g4. } 9... Rf6
10. Qh5 Be6 { Black is trying to win the queen on h5. } 11. e4
{ White needs to create a miracle to stay in the game, because ...Bf7 is a big threat. }
11... Bf7 12. Bc4 e6
{ The engine gives some crazy lines after ...Bxc4 ending in a 0.00 evaluation. With 12...e6 Black continues to fight for a full point. }
13. Bxe6 Bxe6 14. exf5 Rxf5 15. Qxg4
{ White has saved the queen, but only temporarily! } 15... Re5+ 16. Bxe5 Bxg4
17. Bxg7
{ White has to take on g7; if White takes  17.fxg4  , Black will play  17...dxe5  and claim a large advantage. }
17... Qe7+ 18. Nge2 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Kxg7
{ Black might be a little better, but it is not easy. White will castle queenside, Black will play ...Nd7 and activate the rook @@StartBracket@@or even exchange a pair of rooks@@EndBracket@@ and hide the king on h7. White has two potential weak pawns, h4 and f3, and that might be exactly what Black needs.  The strange balance in material is not sufficient for Black to win, we need to create additional weaknesses, win for example the pawn on h4 and then start running with our own h-pawn. It will be a long journey, which is an indication of how small Black's advantage is. }
