6... d6 7. Qg3 { Black cannot defend this pawn, but that is not the end. } 7...
O-O 8. Qxg6 Ng4
{ Locking in the white queen, which could easily get lost, and Black also needed to defend against White's threat of Bxh6. }
9. Bg5 Qe8
{ Black has to try to exchange queens as soon as possible to reduce White's initiative. }
10. Qxe8 Rxe8 11. f3
{ White can also play  11.Bd2  after which Black takes  11...Bxd4  . } 11...
Bxd4 12. fxg4 hxg5 13. hxg5 fxg4
{ The black pawn on g4 is strong because it is defended by the bishop on c8 and limits the knight on g1. The white pawn on g5 is a bit weak, undefended, and Black might be able to pick it up later. }
14. e3 Bxc3+
{ If Black plays  14...Bxe3  instead, we will be in big trouble after  15.Nd5  Bb6  16.Bc4  . }
15. bxc3 Nc6 16. Bd3 Ne5
{ The engine says the position is equal, but I have a slight preference for Black. We can take the bishop on d3 and claim that our bishop is stronger than the knight and in the future, we can try to pick up the pawn on g5. }
