{ Taking control over the e5-square, at some point we would like to play ...e7-e5. }
7. Qf3
{ Not such a strange move, White develops the queen, preparing e3-e4 and sometimes Qg3 while also being ready to castle queenside. }
7... O-O 8. Bc4+ e6 { You always have these crazy attackers: } 9. h5 Nxh5
{ Black has to take on h5 since  9...g5  fails to a sacrifice on g5:  10.Bxg5  followed by h5-h6 and Qxf5 and White has a winning attack. }
10. Rxh5 gxh5 11. Qxh5 Qe8
{ A queen exchange would be good for Black as we are an exchange up. } 12. Qh2
Rf6
{ After  12...Qg6  White also generates a dangerous attack with  13.O-O-O  ,  Bg3 and Nge2-f4. }
13. O-O-O Nc6
{ Although Black is an exchange up, the kingside has long-term weaknesses and the position is highly unclear. }
