[White "10. Staunton Gambit 2.e4"]
[Black "Staunton Gambit 2.e4 fxe4 3.Nd2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. e4
{ The Staunton Gambit − the main line with 4.Bg5 was first played by Staunton against Horwitz in London 1846. I used to think this move would lead to an advantage for Black, but I had to change my mind. It is a dangerous option and if both sides know what they are doing, chances are probably balanced. }
2... fxe4 3. Nd2 { This is a rare sideline. } 3... Nf6 4. g4
{ We will see the move g2-g4 in many of the 2.e4 lines. It is aimed at driving away the knight on f6, taking control over the f5-square, and potentially the bishop can go to g2. }
4... h6 5. h3 d5 6. Ne2 c5
{ A crucial move, Black wants to become active as soon as possible. } 7. dxc5
e5 { Black has a nice center and the bishop would have a great future on c5. }
8. Nb3
{ White has to protect c5, otherwise, Black would already be much better. }
8... Nc6 9. g5 hxg5 10. Bxg5 Be6
{ Protecting the pawn on d5 so that if White ever takes on f6, Black can take back with the queen. }
11. Nc3 Qd7 12. Bg2 O-O-O
{ I believe Black has a large advantage. The king is much safer, we have a powerful center and White's pawn structure has a lot of weaknesses. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Staunton Gambit 2.e4"]
[Black "Staunton Gambit 2.e4 fxe4 3.f3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. e4
{ The Staunton Gambit − the main line with 4.Bg5 was first played by Staunton against Horwitz in London 1846. I used to think this move would lead to an advantage for Black, but I had to change my mind. It is a dangerous option and if both sides know what they are doing, chances are probably balanced. }
2... fxe4 3. f3
{ White is offering a permanent pawn sacrifice, one that in the Leningrad System Black almost never accepts. The standard defense is to protect the pawn on e4. }
3... d5 4. fxe4 dxe4 5. Nc3 Nf6
{ There is not a big difference between first developing the knight or protecting the pawn with  5...Bf5  . }
6. Bc4 Nc6
{ This is an important move. Even more important than the idea to attack the pawn on d4 is to start chasing the white bishop because Black's light squares are a bit weak. }
7. Nge2 Na5 { Step 1. } 8. Bb5+ c6 { Step 2. } 9. Ba4 b5
{ And step 3, the bishop will not survive. } 10. Bb3 Bf5
{ There is no rush to take on b3, but taking immediately is also fine. } 11.
Ng3 e6 12. Bg5
{ A typical pin to win back the pawn on e4. Usually, White does need to give up the bishop for the knight on f6 and in the resulting positions, Black's bishop pair can be strong. }
12... Nxb3 13. axb3 Be7
{ White was threatening to take on e4 because of the pinned knight on f6. } 14.
Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Ncxe4 Bxd4
{ The king is in trouble and White needs to quickly escape to an endgame. } 16.
c3 Be5
{ The bishop can also go back to b6, but it is logical to prevent Nd6+. } 17.
Qxd8+ Rxd8 18. Rxa7 O-O
{ And Black has all the chances. Even if one of the bishops gets traded off, the resulting bishop will be stronger than the knight. Even more worrying for White is that the king is still in danger. After castling, Black may decide to trade the knight on g3 and enter with the rook on d2. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Staunton Gambit 2.e4"]
[Black "Staunton Gambit 2.e4 fxe4 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.g4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. e4
{ The Staunton Gambit − the main line with 4.Bg5 was first played by Staunton against Horwitz in London 1846. I used to think this move would lead to an advantage for Black, but I had to change my mind. It is a dangerous option and if both sides know what they are doing, chances are probably balanced. }
2... fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. g4
{ This move prepares g4-g5 and a bishop sortie to g2. } 4... h6 5. Qe2 d5 6. g5
hxg5 7. Bxg5
{ In these types of positions Black usually protects the pawn on e4 with ...Bf5, develops the queen's knight and the queen to quickly castle queenside. On the kingside, the king is less safe with the gap on g6 and it also takes a bit longer to find a good square for the bishop on f8. }
7... Nc6 8. O-O-O Bf5 9. f3 Qd7 10. Bg2 O-O-O
{ Black is just in time for White's plans in the center. } 11. fxe4 dxe4
{ Taking with the knight on e4 is, in this particular case, also a valid option. Considering there are many lines where White exchanges on e4 at an earlier moment when ...dxe4 is the only good option, I prefer to stick with the same choice here as well. }
12. d5 Ne5
{ When in doubt where to go if the knight on c6 is attacked: a5 is a good square if it means we can swap the white bishop on c4 or b3, but in most other cases the knight is better off on e5. }
13. h4 Bg4
{ Threatening to take the rook on d1, there is only one defense for White. }
14. Bh3 Bxe2 15. Bxd7+ Rxd7 16. Ngxe2
{ Most complications are over, Black just needs to develop the f8-bishop. }
16... g6 17. Nf4 Bh6
{ Black is still a pawn up and although we may lose the e4-pawn, we usually get the pawn on d5 in return. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Staunton Gambit 2.e4"]
[Black "Staunton Gambit 2.e4 fxe4 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.f3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. e4
{ The Staunton Gambit − the main line with 4.Bg5 was first played by Staunton against Horwitz in London 1846. I used to think this move would lead to an advantage for Black, but I had to change my mind. It is a dangerous option and if both sides know what they are doing, chances are probably balanced. }
2... fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3
{ A typical move that can also transpose to the lines with first Bg5 included. I give here a different variation for Black than in theBg5 line, but in general, the plans are quite similar with good chances for Black. }
4... d5
{ Do not take on f3! White will develop quickly and the light squares on Black's kingside are seriously weakened after capturing on f3. }
5. fxe4 dxe4
{ Note that taking with the knight on e4 is not an option. After  5...Nxe4  White would take the knight  6.Nxe4  dxe4  , followed by  7.Qh5+  g6  and  8.Qe5  . }
6. Bg5 Bf5 7. Nge2
{ White can also play for the pawn on e4 and leave the bishop on f1 a bit longer. }
7... e6 8. Ng3 Be7
{ There is no need to put the bishop on g6, White almost never takes on f5 to improve our structure. }
9. Qd2
{ If Black plays the standard  9...Nc6  , the complications after  10.d5  must be calculated because we cannot take with the pawn as the bishop on f5 would be hanging.  The easier solution is to play @@StartFEN@@rn1qk2r/ppp1b1pp/4pn2/5bB1/3Pp3/2N3N1/PPPQ2PP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Nbd7  , which also has the advantage that if White  takes on f6, we can take back with the knight, and the e4-pawn is still protected. }
9... Nbd7 10. O-O-O h6 11. Be3
{ If White takes on f6, Black takes back with the knight, develops the queen, and castles queenside. }
11... Nb6 12. d5
{ It is not so easy for Black to castle queenside here @@StartBracket@@the normal plan in these lines@@EndBracket@@ because after ...Qd7 there is an annoying Bb5. At the same time, short castling is a better option than in other lines because, with the pawn on e6 and the bishop on f5, Black actually has good control over the light squares. This is also due to the fact that the bishop on f1 has trouble becoming active. All these reasons make short castling a sound move. }
12... O-O 13. dxe6
{ White liquidates to an endgame to win back the pawn on e4. There was not a clear alternative for White to improve further. }
13... Qxd2+ 14. Bxd2 Bxe6 15. Re1 Rae8
{ The e-file will soon be opened, so it makes sense to develop the rook to e8. }
16. Ngxe4 Nxe4 17. Rxe4 Bf5
{ White has won the pawn back, but it took a lot of effort and Black is a bit better. We are ahead in development, the rook could potentially invade on f2 and the bishops are more active. White hasn't equalized yet and to fight for a draw means going through a lot more complications. }
