[White "10. Staunton Gambit 2.e4"]
[Black "Staunton Gambit 2.e4 fxe4 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.f3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. e4
{ The Staunton Gambit − the main line with 4.Bg5 was first played by Staunton against Horwitz in London 1846. I used to think this move would lead to an advantage for Black, but I had to change my mind. It is a dangerous option and if both sides know what they are doing, chances are probably balanced. }
2... fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3
{ A typical move that can also transpose to the lines with first Bg5 included. I give here a different variation for Black than in theBg5 line, but in general, the plans are quite similar with good chances for Black. }
4... d5
{ Do not take on f3! White will develop quickly and the light squares on Black's kingside are seriously weakened after capturing on f3. }
5. fxe4 dxe4
{ Note that taking with the knight on e4 is not an option. After  5...Nxe4  White would take the knight  6.Nxe4  dxe4  , followed by  7.Qh5+  g6  and  8.Qe5  . }
6. Bg5 Bf5 7. Bc4 { If the bishop shows up, Black needs to attack it. } 7...
Nc6 { Getting ready to chase away the bishop from c4. } 8. Nge2
{ Defending the pawn on d4 and creating the option of playing Ng3 to win back the pawn on e4. }
8... e6
{ This move closes the line of the c4-bishop, which is a common reaction in most of these lines where there is a white bishop on c4. }
9. Bxe6
{ White is playing for a small trick with this temporary piece sacrifice, but Black's moves are easy to find. }
9... Bxe6 10. d5 { Winning back the piece. } 10... h6
{ Forcing the exchange of the g5-bishop as after  11.Bh4  Black can play  11...g5  followed by taking on d5 with the knight. }
11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. dxc6
{ 12.dxe6  is not a good option because Black will play  12...Rd8  followed by ...Bc5, threatening mate on f2. }
12... bxc6
{ Had Black played  12...Rd8  here, White would have sacrificed the queen with  13.cxb7  . }
13. Nxe4 Qe5
{ A powerful outpost for the queen and White needs to resolve this as soon as possible. }
14. Qd4 Qxd4 15. Nxd4 Bd5 { A nice central square for the bishop. } 16. O-O-O
{ Black cannot win a piece with  16...Bxe4  because White will play  17.Rhe1  . }
16... O-O-O
{ Black has a clear advantage thanks to the pair of bishops in this open position. Yes, we have weak double pawns on the c-file, but they are easy to protect with ...Kb7 and White cannot increase the pressure any further. }
