2... fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3
{ A typical move that can also transpose to the lines with first Bg5 included. I give here a different variation for Black than in theBg5 line, but in general, the plans are quite similar with good chances for Black. }
4... d5
{ Do not take on f3! White will develop quickly and the light squares on Black's kingside are seriously weakened after capturing on f3. }
5. fxe4 dxe4
{ Note that taking with the knight on e4 is not an option. After  5...Nxe4  White would take the knight  6.Nxe4  dxe4  , followed by  7.Qh5+  g6  and  8.Qe5  . }
6. Bg5 Bf5 7. Bc4 { If the bishop shows up, Black needs to attack it. } 7...
Nc6 { Getting ready to chase away the bishop from c4. } 8. Nge2
{ Defending the pawn on d4 and creating the option of playing Ng3 to win back the pawn on e4. }
8... e6
{ This move closes the line of the c4-bishop, which is a common reaction in most of these lines where there is a white bishop on c4. }
9. O-O Be7 { It is always a good idea to break the pin from the bishop on g5. }
10. Qe1
{ White would like to use the queen in an attack, but Black comes first! }
10... Ng4 { The start of a forcing sequence. } 11. Bf4
{ 11.Bxe7  is not challenging for Black.  11...Qxe7  12.Qg3  O-O-O  .  Black is a pawn up and has active pieces while the king is safe. White doesn't have sufficient compensation. Black is threatening to take on d4, can  decide to play ...Na5 to exchange the bishop on c4 and play ...Rhf8. }
11... g5 { A powerful move, the bishop cannot go to g3.  12.Bg3  Ne3  . } 12.
h3 gxf4 13. hxg4 Bh4 { Forcing the white queen to go to a suboptimal square. }
14. Qc1 Bg6
{ Much better to keep on defending the pawn on e4 than to take on g4. } 15.
Qxf4 Bg5 { Black is dominating the dark squares. } 16. Qg3 Qe7
{ Preparing queenside castling and defending the pawn. } 17. Nf4 Bxf4
{ Black has to take, there is no good way to defend the pawn on e6. } 18. Qxf4
O-O-O 19. Nxe4 Rxd4 20. Bd3 Nb4
{ Black is clearly better. We have the more active pieces and White is almost a pawn down due to the double g-pawns. In any endgame, Black will pretty much have an 'extra' e-pawn. }
*

