[White "10. Staunton Gambit 2.e4"]
[Black "Staunton Gambit 2.e4 fxe4 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.f3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. e4
{ The Staunton Gambit − the main line with 4.Bg5 was first played by Staunton against Horwitz in London 1846. I used to think this move would lead to an advantage for Black, but I had to change my mind. It is a dangerous option and if both sides know what they are doing, chances are probably balanced. }
2... fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3
{ A typical move that can also transpose to the lines with first Bg5 included. I give here a different variation for Black than in theBg5 line, but in general, the plans are quite similar with good chances for Black. }
4... d5
{ Do not take on f3! White will develop quickly and the light squares on Black's kingside are seriously weakened after capturing on f3. }
5. fxe4 dxe4
{ Note that taking with the knight on e4 is not an option. After  5...Nxe4  White would take the knight  6.Nxe4  dxe4  , followed by  7.Qh5+  g6  and  8.Qe5  . }
6. Bg5 Bf5 7. Bc4 { If the bishop shows up, Black needs to attack it. } 7...
Nc6 { Getting ready to chase away the bishop from c4. } 8. d5 Na5 9. Be2 e6
{ Black wants to increase the control over the light squares. } 10. Nh3
{ White has to be creative to complete development. } 10... h6 11. Bh4
{ Because of the move ...h7-h6, White needs to think twice before playing Nf4 due to ...g7-g5. }
11... Be7 { Getting rid of the pin and threatening to take on d5. } 12. O-O O-O
{ Black could not yet take on d5 because of the hanging piece on f5. } 13. g4
Bh7 14. Nf4
{ Threatening to take on e6 and attack the queen, so g7-g5 doesn't make sense. }
14... Nxd5 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. Ncxd5 Qc5+
{ An important check because on c5 the queen defends the knight on a5. If Black would have taken directly  16...exd5  , White would play  17.Qxd5+  and pick up next move the knight on a5. }
17. Kg2 exd5 18. Qxd5+
{ White would have ended up losing after the greedy  18.Ne6  because Black has  18...Rxf1  . }
18... Qxd5 19. Nxd5 Rad8
{ Black has no problems, we are fully developed and if given a chance, we may bring the king to the center or even on a lucky day, put a rook on d2. }
