[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. e4
{ The Staunton Gambit − the main line with 4.Bg5 was first played by Staunton against Horwitz in London 1846. I used to think this move would lead to an advantage for Black, but I had to change my mind. It is a dangerous option and if both sides know what they are doing, chances are probably balanced. }
2... fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 g6 { My main recommendation. } 5. f3 d5 6. fxe4
Nxe4 { Taking with the knight means there is no more Bxf6. } 7. Nxe4 dxe4 8.
Bb5+ Nc6 { The move  8...c6  is also fine for Black. } 9. d5
{ Black doesn't lose a piece because of the two pawn moves that are relevant in several Leningrad System lines. }
9... a6 10. Ba4 b5 11. Bb3
{ The pin on the knight is gone so now it can move to e5. } 11... Ne5 12. Ne2
{ Black needs to complete development and castle. } 12... Bg7 13. O-O h6 14.
Bh4 Qd6 15. Bg3 Bf5 16. Nd4 O-O
{ Black is OK − the pin on the knight on e5 can easily be solved by moving the queen @@StartBracket@@to c5, for example@@EndBracket@@. There is a big hole on e6 and, normally, Black will respond with ...Bf6 after Ne6, or sometimes we will take on e6 with the f5-bishop. White will then win back the pawn on e4, but Black will have sufficient counterplay with the bishop on g7. }
