[White "10. Staunton Gambit 2.e4"]
[Black "Staunton Gambit 2.e4 fxe4 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Bg5 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. e4
{ The Staunton Gambit − the main line with 4.Bg5 was first played by Staunton against Horwitz in London 1846. I used to think this move would lead to an advantage for Black, but I had to change my mind. It is a dangerous option and if both sides know what they are doing, chances are probably balanced. }
2... fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 g6 { My main recommendation. } 5. f3 exf3
{ A rare occasion when taking on f3 is also possible. } 6. Nxf3 Bg7
{ 6...d5  immediately is also a sound option:  7.Bd3  Bg7  8.O-O  O-O  9.Qd2  Nc6  ,  Black has an extra pawn. White has some compensation because of the weak e-pawn and the squares e6 and e5 but is certainly not better. There are no direct attacking chances.  Still, from all the lines against 2.e4, I try to avoid these positions with Black because they feel a bit passive. I prefer positions with equal material where Black can quickly become active. }
7. Bc4 c6
{ Black has to fight for the light squares, a direct  7...d5  fails to  8.Bxf6  . }
8. Bd3 d5
{ It is important to get ...d7-d5 in to limit the power of the white bishop. Still, even on d3 in combination with h2-h4-h5, it can be dangerous. }
9. O-O O-O 10. Qe1 { White is setting up a big attack. } 10... Na6
{ The knight has no future on d7, while from a6 it can either try to exchange the bishop on d3 after ...Nb4 or protect the e6-square with ...Nc7. }
11. Ne2 Bg4 12. Qh4 Bxf3 13. Rxf3 Nb4
{ White's initiative is really dangerous and Black is just in time to keep the balance. It is a scary line, especially if we have to find this over the board. }
14. Nf4 Qd7 { We want to create the option of swapping queens with ...Qg4. }
15. Bh6 Bxh6 16. Qxh6 Nxd3 17. Nxg6 { Ouch... } 17... Rf7
{ No panic!  17...hxg6  would be losing to  18.Qxg6+  Kh8  19.Raf1  . There is not much Black can do against the  threat of Qh6+ followed by Rg3+.  Note that @@StartFEN@@r4r1k/pp1qp3/2p2nQ1/3p4/3P4/3n1R2/PPP3PP/R5K1 w - - 1 19@@EndFEN@@  19.Rh3+  first doesn't work yet because of a pin along the g-file:  19...Qxh3  20.gxh3  Rg8  and Black wins being two pieces up. }
18. Rg3 Ng4
{ A nice intermediate move − Black manages to swap the knight on g4 for the one on g6. }
19. Qh4 hxg6 20. Rxg4 Qd6 21. cxd3 Kg7
{ The big complications are over and Black has maintained the balance. Still, I prefer not to have these types of lines in my repertoire because the chances are high that I won't remember the exact details behind the board. That is why in general my advice is not to take on f3 in any line, even when the engine says it is okay. }
