{ The Staunton Gambit − the main line with 4.Bg5 was first played by Staunton against Horwitz in London 1846. I used to think this move would lead to an advantage for Black, but I had to change my mind. It is a dangerous option and if both sides know what they are doing, chances are probably balanced. }
2... fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 g6 { My main recommendation. } 5. Bc4 c6
{ Black is forcing White to play d4-d5, otherwise Black would succeed in playing ...d7-d5 with a clear advantage. }
6. f3
{ This is a standard pawn sacrifice but in this situation, it is not effective. }
6... d5 7. Bb3 exf3 8. Nxf3
{ Both sides will now focus on completing their development and castling. White is seeking compensation for the pawn. }
8... Bg4 9. Qd2 Bg7 10. O-O-O O-O 11. Rde1 Nbd7
{ I believe Black is already a bit better. The bishop on b3 is not only out of play, it even helps Black in the attack with ...b7-b5 and ...a7-a5-a4. }
