1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. e4
{ The Staunton Gambit − the main line with 4.Bg5 was first played by Staunton against Horwitz in London 1846. I used to think this move would lead to an advantage for Black, but I had to change my mind. It is a dangerous option and if both sides know what they are doing, chances are probably balanced. }
2... fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 g6 { My main recommendation. } 5. Bc4 c6
{ Black is forcing White to play d4-d5, otherwise Black would succeed in playing ...d7-d5 with a clear advantage. }
6. d5 Bg7 7. Nge2 e6 8. d6
{ This move seriously hinders Black's development so we have to analyze it. }
8... O-O 9. Nxe4 Qa5+ 10. Bd2 Qe5 { First Black gets rid of the knight on e4. }
11. Nxf6+ Qxf6
{ We want to keep the queen close to the king − at some point, White will launch a kingside attack. }
12. f4 Qxb2 13. Rb1 Qf6 14. h4 b6
{ Black plans to exchange the poor c8-bishop. } 15. h5 Ba6 16. Bxa6 Nxa6
{ I prefer Black although the engine disagrees and says it is still equal. I think Black has the healthier pawn structure and the safer king and we can create serious pressure if we manage to get ...e6-e5 in. }
