{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. e4
{ The Staunton Gambit − the main line with 4.Bg5 was first played by Staunton against Horwitz in London 1846. I used to think this move would lead to an advantage for Black, but I had to change my mind. It is a dangerous option and if both sides know what they are doing, chances are probably balanced. }
2... fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 g6 { My main recommendation. } 5. h4
{ With the aggressive idea of h4-h5. } 5... d5 6. h5
{ White is going all out. This type of play with quickly advancing the h-pawn is quite popular in blitz games, but for a game with standard time control, it is actually also a serious option. }
6... Bf5
{ Simply defending the pawn on g6 and developing a piece.   The alternative  6...Bg7  @@StartBracket@@played a few times in practice@@EndBracket@@ is a move I don't trust after  7.h6  .  I would not advise to take on h5:  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1p2p/5np1/3p2BP/3Pp3/2N5/PPP2PP1/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nxh5  7.Rxh5  gxh5  8.Qxh5+  Kd7  9.Nxd5  and White is winning. }
7. Bxf6 exf6 8. g4
{ White is winning a pawn, but Black has compensation with all the holes behind the advanced white pawns. }
8... Be6 9. hxg6 Qd7
{ Simply defending the pawn on h7 and getting ready for queenside castling. }
10. g5
{ White can also defend the pawn with  10.Be2  , but Black will play  10...Nc6  , castle queenside, and have a clear advantage because of the lead in development. }
10... fxg5 11. Qh5 { White threatens g7+. } 11... Qg7 12. Qxg5 c6
{ Defending the pawn on d5. } 13. Nge2 { Now it is time to open the position. }
13... hxg6 14. Nf4
{ White can also take  14.Rxh8  Qxh8  and then  15.Qxg6+  with check but after  15...Bf7  Black will castle queenside and have the better position because of the two strong bishops. }
14... Rxh1 15. Nxe6 Qe7
{ My improvement over a game between Trent-Anton Guijarro, Caleta 2015 where  15...Qh6  was played and the game was soon drawn.  It turns out Black can allow the check on c7 in order to reach a favorable endgame. }
16. Qxe7+ Bxe7 17. Nc7+ Kd8 18. Nxa8 Nd7
{ Black will pick up the knight on a8 and has a clear advantage with the extra pawn and active rook. }
*

