2... fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 g6 { My main recommendation. } 5. h4
{ With the aggressive idea of h4-h5. } 5... d5 6. h5
{ White is going all out. This type of play with quickly advancing the h-pawn is quite popular in blitz games, but for a game with standard time control, it is actually also a serious option. }
6... Bf5
{ Simply defending the pawn on g6 and developing a piece.   The alternative  6...Bg7  @@StartBracket@@played a few times in practice@@EndBracket@@ is a move I don't trust after  7.h6  .  I would not advise to take on h5:  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1p2p/5np1/3p2BP/3Pp3/2N5/PPP2PP1/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nxh5  7.Rxh5  gxh5  8.Qxh5+  Kd7  9.Nxd5  and White is winning. }
7. Bxf6 exf6 8. g4
{ White is winning a pawn, but Black has compensation with all the holes behind the advanced white pawns. }
8... Be6 9. hxg6 Qd7
{ Simply defending the pawn on h7 and getting ready for queenside castling. }
10. g5
{ White can also defend the pawn with  10.Be2  , but Black will play  10...Nc6  , castle queenside, and have a clear advantage because of the lead in development. }
10... fxg5 11. Qh5 { White threatens g7+. } 11... Qg7 12. Qxg5 c6
{ Defending the pawn on d5. } 13. f3 hxg6
{ Black is offering the pawn on g6 after a rook swap on h8. } 14. Rxh8 Qxh8 15.
Qxg6+ { White wins back the pawn but that doesn't bring anything special. }
15... Bf7 16. Qg3 Qxd4
{ Taking an essential pawn − White needs to play precisely to maintain the balance. }
17. fxe4 Qg7 18. Qxg7 Bxg7
{ Black's bishops could become dangerous but White is just in time to neutralize them. }
19. exd5 Bxc3+
{ Black has to take because after  19...cxd5  the bishop on f7 would be passively defending the isolated d-pawn. }
20. bxc3 Bxd5
{ Black can try to play for more than a draw with the better pawn structure. }
