[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Staunton Gambit 2.e4 − 4.Bg5 Nc6 Alternative"]
[Black "Staunton Gambit 2.e4 − 4.Bg5 Nc6 Alternative − 5.f3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. e4
{ The Staunton Gambit − the main line with 4.Bg5 was first played by Staunton against Horwitz in London 1846. I used to think this move would lead to an advantage for Black, but I had to change my mind. It is a dangerous option and if both sides know what they are doing, chances are probably balanced. }
2... fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Nc6
{ This is the old move and it is still played frequently but according to my analysis, one of the main lines is no longer playable. Therefore, Black needs to go for an alternative where we must defend a passive position for quite a long time, not the kind of chess most players are interested in. }
5. f3 d5
{ We just don't want to take on f3. It is not that Black is lost then, but it is exactly what White wants, to sacrifice a pawn and quickly develop. I see no reason to cooperate. }
6. fxe4 dxe4 7. Nge2 Nb4
{ Taking control over the d5-square.   The standard  7...Bf5  is not so good here because White wins a lot of tempi:  8.d5  Ne5  9.Ng3  Bg6  10.Qd4  and White has a clear advantage. }
8. a3 Nbd5 9. Nxd5 Qxd5
{ Taking with the queen is stronger than with the knight because Black gains a tempo by attacking the bishop on g5 and also prepares a later queenside castling. }
10. Qd2 Bf5 { Protecting the e4-pawn while preparing to castle queenside. } 11.
Nc3 Qd7 12. d5
{ If White doesn't play this pawn push, Black is ready to castle queenside and take over the initiative. The pawn on d5 cramps Black's position so we resolve that immediately. }
12... e6 13. O-O-O c6 { Now White has to exchange the pawn on d5. } 14. dxe6
Qxd2+
{ It is a good idea to exchange queens considering the black king is stuck in the middle of the board for now. }
15. Rxd2 Bxe6 16. Kb1
{ Prophylaxis − if White plays  16.Bxf6  gxf6  17.Nxe4  will be hit with  17...Bh6  , losing an exchange. }
16... Be7 { Keeping both options open on which side to castle. } 17. Bxf6 Bxf6
18. Nxe4 Be7
{ Setting a small trap: if White plays the logical  19.Nd6  , Black will take  19...Bxd6  20.Rxd6  and lock in the rook with  20...Bd5  which results in an unpleasant position for White. }
19. Bd3 O-O-O
{ Short castling is also an option in these types of endgames. Black is a little better because of the pair of bishops. Especially if White decides to quickly exchange the rooks, the endgame will be in our favor. }
*

