[White "11. Staunton Gambit 2.e4 − 4.Bg5 Nc6 Alternative"]
[Black "Staunton Gambit 2.e4 − 4.Bg5 Nc6 Alternative − 5.d5 Ne5 6.Qd4 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. e4
{ The Staunton Gambit − the main line with 4.Bg5 was first played by Staunton against Horwitz in London 1846. I used to think this move would lead to an advantage for Black, but I had to change my mind. It is a dangerous option and if both sides know what they are doing, chances are probably balanced. }
2... fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Nc6
{ This is the old move and it is still played frequently but according to my analysis, one of the main lines is no longer playable. Therefore, Black needs to go for an alternative where we must defend a passive position for quite a long time, not the kind of chess most players are interested in. }
5. d5 { The start of the critical line. } 5... Ne5 6. Qd4
{ This move looks similar to putting the queen on e2, but the difference is that with the queen on e2 there are threats against the black king after a future Nxe4. }
6... Nf7
{ Whenever the e5-knight is attacked in the Leningrad System, it will usually go back to f7. }
7. h4
{ I am not sure how much this move helps White. It is clear that Black is unlikely to ever take on g5 after this move, but how beneficial it is to have the pawn on h4 is unclear, considering White often plays Bxf6 anyway. }
7... e5 { Again, Black tries to exchange queens. } 8. Qa4
{ Trying to keep the pressure on Black's position. } 8... Nd6
{ Simply defending the pawn on e4. } 9. O-O-O h6 10. Be3
{ White cannot win the e4-pawn in the usual way because a piece will be lost in return.  10.Bxf6  Qxf6  11.Nxe4  Qf4+  . }
10... Be7 { Completing development and castling. } 11. Nge2 O-O 12. Ng3 Ng4
{ Black has to give up the pawn on e4 but is putting pressure on f2. } 13.
Ncxe4 b5 { A sharp pawn sacrifice to open lines against the white king. } 14.
Bxb5 Nxb5 15. Qxb5 d6 16. h5 a5
{ Black has sufficient compensation for the sacrificed pawn. we may follow up with either ...Ba6 or ...Bd7 and taking on e3 also comes into consideration. White doesn't have any attacking chances, so Black can slowly develop the initiative on the queenside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Staunton Gambit 2.e4 − 4.Bg5 Nc6 Alternative"]
[Black "Staunton Gambit 2.e4 − 4.Bg5 Nc6 Alternative − 5.d5 Ne5 6.Qd4 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. e4
{ The Staunton Gambit − the main line with 4.Bg5 was first played by Staunton against Horwitz in London 1846. I used to think this move would lead to an advantage for Black, but I had to change my mind. It is a dangerous option and if both sides know what they are doing, chances are probably balanced. }
2... fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Nc6
{ This is the old move and it is still played frequently but according to my analysis, one of the main lines is no longer playable. Therefore, Black needs to go for an alternative where we must defend a passive position for quite a long time, not the kind of chess most players are interested in. }
5. d5 { The start of the critical line. } 5... Ne5 6. Qd4
{ This move looks similar to putting the queen on e2, but the difference is that with the queen on e2 there are threats against the black king after a future Nxe4. }
6... Nf7
{ Whenever the e5-knight is attacked in the Leningrad System, it will usually go back to f7. }
7. h4
{ I am not sure how much this move helps White. It is clear that Black is unlikely to ever take on g5 after this move, but how beneficial it is to have the pawn on h4 is unclear, considering White often plays Bxf6 anyway. }
7... c6
{ This is another standard reaction that results in sharp play. In some of the lines, Black needs to play quite accurately, including sacrificing a pawn at the right moment. It is playable, I just believe that the line I recommend is more fun. }
8. O-O-O Qb6 9. Qd2
{ An aggressive attempt to keep the queens on the board and launch an attack.   White can also win the e4-pawn while giving up the pawn on f2, hoping to benefit from the lead in development:  9.Bxf6  gxf6  10.Qxe4  Qxf2  11.Nf3  f5  , a necessary pawn sacrifice to win some time for development.  12.Qxf5  Qe3+  13.Kb1  d6  14.Qh5  Qh6  . Black really wants to exchange queens as otherwise, the king will be in danger.   15.Qxh6  Bxh6  16.Bd3  Bg7  . Black wants to have the possibility to  play ...Ne5 to block the e-file.  17.Rhe1  Bg4  18.Ne4  ,  White threatens to take the d6-pawn because the e7–pawn is pinned by the rook on e1.  18...Ne5  19.Be2  Bxf3  20.gxf3  Bh6  and the engine says it is about equal, but it feels to me Black still needs to be accurate, the position doesn't play on autopilot. }
9... Qa5 10. Bc4
{ Initially, I thought this position is a bit scary for Black, but it turns out that White doesn't get the chance to attack. }
10... b5
{ Black has to push immediately, otherwise White will gain a large advantage because of the lead in development. }
11. Bxf6 bxc4 12. Bg5 cxd5
{ A simple move after which it is hard for White to avoid an exchange of queens. }
13. Nxd5
{ After  13.Qxd5  there will be a few exchanges.  13...Qxd5  14.Nxd5  Nxg5  15.hxg5  .  If White doesn't take back but plays Nc7+, Black plays ...Kd8, locking in the knight, next ...Nf7, and then will pick up the knight on a8.  15...Kf7  16.Nc3  e6  17.Nxe4  d5  , Black has created a harmonious pawn structure.  18.Nc3  Bc5  and the engine gives equality, but I prefer Black with the bishop pair and the central pawns. }
13... Qxd2+ 14. Bxd2 Rb8 { Only move,  14...Kd8  loses to  15.Ba5+  . } 15.
Nc7+ Kd8 16. Ba5 Rb7 17. Rd4
{ Keeping the game alive. Funny enough, White cannot win material with a discovered check. A draw can be achieved by playing  17.Ne6+  Ke8  and  18.Nc7+  again. }
17... d6 18. Na6+ Ke8 19. Rxc4 Bf5 { Finally developing this bishop. } 20. Bc3
Rg8 { Getting ready to develop the other bishop. } 21. Ne2 g6
{ We have reached a balanced position with mutual chances. Black may aim for a later ...d6-d5, followed by ...e7-e5 to create a strong center, but first, we want to activate the f8-bishop. }
*

