2... fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Nc6
{ This is the old move and it is still played frequently but according to my analysis, one of the main lines is no longer playable. Therefore, Black needs to go for an alternative where we must defend a passive position for quite a long time, not the kind of chess most players are interested in. }
5. d5 { The start of the critical line. } 5... Ne5 6. Qd4
{ This move looks similar to putting the queen on e2, but the difference is that with the queen on e2 there are threats against the black king after a future Nxe4. }
6... Nf7
{ Whenever the e5-knight is attacked in the Leningrad System, it will usually go back to f7. }
7. Nh3
{ This is a strange square for the knight, but the players who employ this system against the Leningrad tend to be creative! }
7... e5
{ Exchanging queens with the idea that White will need to give up the bishop pair in the endgame, in order to win back the e4-pawn. }
8. dxe6 dxe6 9. Qxd8+ Nxd8 10. O-O-O Nf7
{ The f7-square is a nice place for the knight and White was threatening to play Nxe4 anyway since the knight on d8 would have been hanging. }
11. Bc4 Nd6 12. Bb3 Be7
{ I do not recommend  12...h6  13.Bxf6  gxf6  14.Nf4  Kf7  15.Rhe1  h5  16.Nxe4  although the engine thinks Black is fine. I just look at the position and see all White's pieces being active while Black is far away from completing development. }
13. Rhe1 e5 { Creating space for the c8-bishop. } 14. f3 Bxh3
{ The fastest way to get the king to safety. } 15. gxh3 O-O-O 16. Nxe4 Ndxe4
17. fxe4 Rxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Rf8
{ And this endgame is equal, although if White is not looking, we may either take on e4 one day or put a rook on f3 or f2. }
