{ This is the old move and it is still played frequently but according to my analysis, one of the main lines is no longer playable. Therefore, Black needs to go for an alternative where we must defend a passive position for quite a long time, not the kind of chess most players are interested in. }
5. d5 { The start of the critical line. } 5... Ne5 6. Qd4
{ This move looks similar to putting the queen on e2, but the difference is that with the queen on e2 there are threats against the black king after a future Nxe4. }
6... Nf7
{ Whenever the e5-knight is attacked in the Leningrad System, it will usually go back to f7. }
7. Bxf6 exf6 8. Nxe4
{ A common continuation where Black is OK after standard moves. } 8... f5
{ A common move in the Leningrad System, often followed by a later ...g7-g6 to activate the f8-bishop. }
9. Ng3 g6 10. O-O-O
{ While still dreaming of a kingside attack, White's position may already be a bit worse here. }
10... Bh6+ { A check to enable kingside castling with tempo. } 11. f4 O-O 12.
Nf3 Bg7 { A beautiful bishop − Black can already start an attack. } 13. Qa4 Qe7
14. Kb1 Qc5
{ The pawn sacrifice  14...b5  also comes into consideration.  White should probably take with the queen on b5, but it looks so scary with a rook coming to b8 in combination with the bishop on g7 and potentially the queen on f6, b4, or even a3. In a practical game, I would prefer Black. }
15. c3 Nd6 16. Qc2 b5
{ Black has a clear advantage: the attack has started while White has no idea yet on how to reach the black king. The pair of bishops is strong and the a-pawn may run all the way from a7 to a3, to soften White's structure. }
