[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Staunton Gambit 2.e4 − 4.Bg5 Nc6 Alternative"]
[Black "Staunton Gambit 2.e4 − 4.Bg5 Nc6 Alternative − 5.d5 Ne5 6.f4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. e4
{ The Staunton Gambit − the main line with 4.Bg5 was first played by Staunton against Horwitz in London 1846. I used to think this move would lead to an advantage for Black, but I had to change my mind. It is a dangerous option and if both sides know what they are doing, chances are probably balanced. }
2... fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Nc6
{ This is the old move and it is still played frequently but according to my analysis, one of the main lines is no longer playable. Therefore, Black needs to go for an alternative where we must defend a passive position for quite a long time, not the kind of chess most players are interested in. }
5. d5 { The start of the critical line. } 5... Ne5 6. f4 { A rare move. } 6...
Nf7 7. Qd4 e5
{ Offering a queen swap if White takes on e6, after which White's initiative is over.   7...c6  is probably too slow.  8.Bxf6  gxf6  9.Qxe4  e6  10.O-O-O  f5  11.Qe1  cxd5  12.g4  . White's initiative is dangerous, Black has fallen too far behind in development. }
8. fxe5
{ If  8.dxe6  dxe6  and we reach a position without queens that is similar to other lines where Black is fine. }
8... Nxg5 9. exf6 Qxf6 { Offering a queen swap to reduce White's initiative. }
10. Qxf6 gxf6 11. h4 Nf7 12. Nxe4
{ White has won the pawn back, but Black still has a pair of bishops and White doesn't have much initiative anymore. }
12... Bg7 13. O-O-O d6
{ It makes Black's life easier to prevent White's d5-d6, which is why I suggest ...d7-d6 before castling. }
14. Nf3 O-O 15. Bd3 Bg4
{ The position is about equal, Black has a nice pair of bishops but the f-pawn is a bit weak and we don't want to have a white knight on the f5-square either. A potential dream scenario for Black would be to play ...Ne5 and White would take on e5. Black would then recapture with the d-pawn and advance the f-pawn to f5. Then Black would have a massive center combined with a pair of bishops. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Staunton Gambit 2.e4 − 4.Bg5 Nc6 Alternative"]
[Black "Staunton Gambit 2.e4 − 4.Bg5 Nc6 Alternative − 5.d5 Ne5 6.Qe2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. e4
{ The Staunton Gambit − the main line with 4.Bg5 was first played by Staunton against Horwitz in London 1846. I used to think this move would lead to an advantage for Black, but I had to change my mind. It is a dangerous option and if both sides know what they are doing, chances are probably balanced. }
2... fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Nc6
{ This is the old move and it is still played frequently but according to my analysis, one of the main lines is no longer playable. Therefore, Black needs to go for an alternative where we must defend a passive position for quite a long time, not the kind of chess most players are interested in. }
5. d5 { The start of the critical line. } 5... Ne5 6. Qe2
{ Again the most critical move, the queen on e2 is in one line with the king on e8 and this can easily result in trouble for Black. }
6... Nf7
{ This move is okay for Black, but it can result in an endgame that is not much fun. }
7. Bxf6
{ White's most aggressive option.   The developing move  7.Nh3  is not dangerous for Black.  7...d6  8.Bxf6  exf6  9.Nxe4  Be7  was fine for Black in Rawlings-Wenzel, ICCF email 2019. }
7... exf6 8. Nxe4
{ If White takes with the queen, Black is happy to play ...Qe7 and liquidate to an endgame where we can try to benefit from the pair of bishops. }
8... Qe7
{ Black can also play  8...Bb4+  9.c3  Be7  , but White will sacrifice a pawn with  10.d6  and after  10...cxd6  White will have long-term compensation because the pieces are more active than Black's. }
9. d6 { An essential pawn sacrifice. } 9... Nxd6 10. Nxd6+ cxd6 11. O-O-O
{ White is threatening to avoid the queen swap with Qf3 and make use of the lead in development. }
11... Qxe2 12. Bxe2 Rb8 13. Nf3 a6
{ The position is about equal and eventually, a draw was agreed in Dobrov-L'Ami, Wijk aan Zee 2017. Still, I don't think this line is a lot of fun to play for Black, the pawn on d6 limits the Black's activity, and putting it on d5 is not going to help. }
*

