[White "11. Staunton Gambit 2.e4 − 4.Bg5 Nc6 Alternative"]
[Black "Staunton Gambit 2.e4 − 4.Bg5 Nc6 Alternative − 5.d5 Ne5 6.Qe2 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. e4
{ The Staunton Gambit − the main line with 4.Bg5 was first played by Staunton against Horwitz in London 1846. I used to think this move would lead to an advantage for Black, but I had to change my mind. It is a dangerous option and if both sides know what they are doing, chances are probably balanced. }
2... fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Nc6
{ This is the old move and it is still played frequently but according to my analysis, one of the main lines is no longer playable. Therefore, Black needs to go for an alternative where we must defend a passive position for quite a long time, not the kind of chess most players are interested in. }
5. d5 { The start of the critical line. } 5... Ne5 6. Qe2
{ Again the most critical move, the queen on e2 is in one line with the king on e8 and this can easily result in trouble for Black. }
6... c6 { This move is played a lot in practice. } 7. O-O-O Nxd5
{ A less popular move than  7...cxd5  . This may change because according to my analysis,  White has a dangerous line against the 7...cxd5 option. }
8. Nxe4 Qc7 { This might be the only move for Black in this position. } 9. Nf3
{ If White plays  9.c4  Nf6  is fine for Black.  And if White takes the knight with the bishop and follows up with Qh5+, there is always ...Ng6. }
9... Nf7 10. c4 Nf6 11. Bxf6 Qf4+
{ An important check because if Black immediately takes  11...gxf6  , White can just take the pawn with  12.Nxf6+  . }
12. Kb1 gxf6 13. g3 Qh6
{ If we want to keep on defending the pawn on f6, there is no other square. }
14. Nh4 { Threatening Nf5. } 14... d6 { A pawn sacrifice. } 15. Rxd6 Bg7
{ By playing ...d7-d6 and sacrificing a pawn, Black has defended the f5-square and now we can continue developing.   15...exd6  just loses to  16.Nxd6+  . }
16. f4 O-O
{ Black has an okay position. The pawn structure is a bit weak and we will need to play ...f6-f5 at some point in order to activate the queen again, but our king is safe and we have a pair of bishops. }
