{ And Black has a solid position and is ready to activate the c8-bishop after, for example, ...d7-d5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Staunton Gambit 2.e4 − 4.Bg5 Nc6 Alternative"]
[Black "Staunton Gambit 2.e4 − 4.Bg5 Nc6 Alternative − 5.d5 Ne5 6.Qe2 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. e4
{ The Staunton Gambit − the main line with 4.Bg5 was first played by Staunton against Horwitz in London 1846. I used to think this move would lead to an advantage for Black, but I had to change my mind. It is a dangerous option and if both sides know what they are doing, chances are probably balanced. }
2... fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Nc6
{ This is the old move and it is still played frequently but according to my analysis, one of the main lines is no longer playable. Therefore, Black needs to go for an alternative where we must defend a passive position for quite a long time, not the kind of chess most players are interested in. }
5. d5 { The start of the critical line. } 5... Ne5 6. Qe2
{ Again the most critical move, the queen on e2 is in one line with the king on e8 and this can easily result in trouble for Black. }
6... c6 { This move is played a lot in practice. } 7. O-O-O cxd5
{ It is more logical to take with the pawn and keep the pawn on e4 defended, for now, limiting White's options. }
8. Bxf6 gxf6 9. f4
{ This move has not been played in practice yet, but it is quite dangerous for Black. }
9... exf3 10. Nxf3 Nf7 11. g4 e6 12. Nxd5
{ Only possible because the pawn on e6 is pinned by the queen on e2. } 12...
Bh6+ 13. g5 { White is taking the most aggressive approach. } 13... fxg5 14.
Qe4 g4+ { Making use of the check to drive the f3-knight to a passive square. }
15. Nd2 Qa5 16. Bb5 { Threatening Qxe6+. } 16... Kd8 17. Nc3 a6
{ Chasing away the annoying bishop. } 18. Be2 Qe5
{ A queen swap would be great for Black. } 19. Qxg4 d5
{ White has compensation for the sacrificed pawn, but whether that can be translated to an advantage remains to be seen. The black king can hide on b8 and after a future ...b7-b5, the rook on a8 can be activated via a7. I don't see any direct refutation. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5"]
[Black "Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5 d5 4.e3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nc3 { White wants to play e2-e4. } 2... Nf6 3. Bg5
{ White wants to take on f6 to create doubled pawns. White could then either try to benefit from the weak pawn on f5 or play for c2-c4, claiming that if Black takes on c4, a white bishop on c4 will be very powerful now that there are no longer pawns on either f7, e6, or d5 to stop this bishop. }
3... d5 4. e3
{ A strange move, White has first played for e2-e4, when Black prevented that White played for disrupting Black’s pawn structure and now forgets about all that and just starts developing pieces. Of course, White is not worse by taking this approach, there is nothing wrong with developing, but this plan misses a bit of focus so it is not threatening for Black. }
4... e6 5. Bd3 c5 6. g4
{ Doesn't work so well because White can never play Nge2 since the bishop will be trapped after ...c5-c4. }
6... fxg4 7. h3 g3
{ This is a very typical reaction for Black in the Leningrad System if faced with g2-g4: take on g4 and then give the pawn back on g3, so that the light squares don't become too weak @@StartBracket@@which would happen after ...gxh3@@EndBracket@@. Moreover, by forcing fxg3, White's structure is weakened  (the pawns on g3 and e3)  and Black can create pressure on the dark squares. }
8. fxg3 Bd6 9. Qf3 O-O
{ I prefer Black because the pawns on g3, e3, and d4 are weak, and if White castles queenside, Black can play ...c5-c4, ...Qa5 and ...b7-b5, with a quick attack. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
