[Round "?"]
[White "12. Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5"]
[Black "Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5 d5 4.e3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nc3 { White wants to play e2-e4. } 2... Nf6 3. Bg5
{ White wants to take on f6 to create doubled pawns. White could then either try to benefit from the weak pawn on f5 or play for c2-c4, claiming that if Black takes on c4, a white bishop on c4 will be very powerful now that there are no longer pawns on either f7, e6, or d5 to stop this bishop. }
3... d5 4. e3
{ A strange move, White has first played for e2-e4, when Black prevented that White played for disrupting Black’s pawn structure and now forgets about all that and just starts developing pieces. Of course, White is not worse by taking this approach, there is nothing wrong with developing, but this plan misses a bit of focus so it is not threatening for Black. }
4... e6 5. Nf3
{ White is planning a setup where the pieces get developed first and then either Ne5 will be played, followed by f2-f4, or the knight will be rerouted from c3, followed by c2-c4. }
5... a6 6. Bd3 c5
{ This advance with the c-pawn is an essential way of putting pressure on the white center. Because there is a knight on c3, it is not possible for White to stabilize the center with c2-c3. }
7. O-O c4
{ Normally, we would first develop the f8-bishop and castle, but here if we move the bishop Black may lose a tempo if White takes on c5 when we will have to recapture with the bishop. }
8. Be2 Bd6
{ This is one of those rare cases where Black can delay development without being punished. We can actually play ...b7-b5 before White stops this with a2-a4. White's best option is then to put a knight on e5 supported by f2-f4 and we have a position with about equal chances. }
9. a4 O-O 10. b3
{ If White doesn't play this soon, Black will play ...Nc6, ...Rb8 and support the c-pawn with ...b7-b5. }
10... cxb3 11. cxb3 Nc6
{ I have a slight preference for Black due to the extra space. We can put a knight on e4  @@StartBracket@@while for White it is not so easy to occupy the e5-square@@EndBracket@@ and even the pawn on b3 is slightly weak if Black plays something like ...Qb6, possibly followed by ...Bb4 and/or ...Na5. }
*

