[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nc3 { White wants to play e2-e4. } 2... Nf6 3. Bg5
{ White wants to take on f6 to create doubled pawns. White could then either try to benefit from the weak pawn on f5 or play for c2-c4, claiming that if Black takes on c4, a white bishop on c4 will be very powerful now that there are no longer pawns on either f7, e6, or d5 to stop this bishop. }
3... d5 4. f3 Nc6 5. Qd3
{ This is an alternative given by the engine, but it is not too threatening. }
5... e5 { Black immediately takes action in the center. } 6. dxe5 Nxe5 7. Qe3
Qe7
{ The only way to defend the knight and to prevent losing a piece because of the pin with f3-f4. }
8. Bxf6 gxf6 { Taking with the queen  8...Qxf6  is bad because of  9.Nxd5  . }
9. Nxd5 Qf7 10. Nxf6+
{ If White plays  10.Nc3  , Black has ample compensation for the pawn by playing  10...Be6  ,  followed by ...Nc4 while White is suffering from a lack of coordination between the pieces. }
10... Qxf6 11. f4 Bg7 12. Qxe5+ Qxe5 13. fxe5 Bxe5
{ Black has sufficient compensation for the pawn with the pair of bishops and the lead in development. Given the chance, Black will play ...f5-f4 to lock up White's pieces. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5"]
[Black "Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5 − 4.f3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nc3 { White wants to play e2-e4. } 2... Nf6 3. Bg5
{ White wants to take on f6 to create doubled pawns. White could then either try to benefit from the weak pawn on f5 or play for c2-c4, claiming that if Black takes on c4, a white bishop on c4 will be very powerful now that there are no longer pawns on either f7, e6, or d5 to stop this bishop. }
3... d5 4. f3 Nc6 5. Qd2 e6 { Creating space to develop the f8-bishop. } 6. e4
dxe4
{ We take first with the d-pawn so that the pawn on d4 hangs.   I looked at the  6...fxe4  option, but feel that White is slightly better in an endgame, so I don't recommend it.  7.fxe4  Bb4  8.e5  . Now the only way not to lose a piece is by trading queens.  8...Ne4  9.Bxd8  Nxd2  10.Kxd2  Nxd8  11.Nf3  O-O  12.Bd3  Be7  13.Ne2  c5  14.c3  . This endgame feels to me as slightly better for White, all the pieces are active and have more space. }
7. fxe4 Qxd4 8. Qxd4 Nxd4 9. O-O-O e5
{ Going back  9...Nc6  is not good because of  10.exf5  and White gets a dangerous initiative. }
10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Nd5
{ A sharp line where Black temporarily sacrifices a rook. } 11... Bh6+ 12. Kb1
c6
{ One of those rare occasions where we have to know the exact move order in the Leningrad. Black can only sacrifice a rook if the following lines are known. }
13. Nc7+ Ke7 14. Nxa8
{ This knight can go to c7 but even there it cannot get out. } 14... fxe4
{ Two pawns for the rook and more to come! } 15. Ne2 Nf5
{ Only move, the knight was attacked and e3 is a nice square. } 16. Nc3 Ne3 17.
Re1 f5
{ 17...Bf5  is also possible, but advancing the pawn first and then winning the knight is stronger. }
18. h3 Bd7 19. Nc7 Kd6 20. Na6
{ Note that White can also give back the knight on b5, but it doesn't change the assessment of the position. }
20... bxa6 { Black has ample compensation for the exchange. } 21. g4
{ White wants to undermine Black's center because the f- and e-pawns could become dangerous. }
21... Rb8 22. gxf5 Bxf5 23. Nd1
{ What else? White can barely move the pieces. } 23... Nxf1 24. Rhxf1 Ke6
{ Black has the advantage as the two bishops and the e4-pawn more than compensate for the small material deficit. The rook can get activated via the d- or g-file, sometimes pick up the h-pawn and all White can do is defend. }
