3... d5 4. f3 Nc6 5. Qd2 e6 { Creating space to develop the f8-bishop. } 6.
O-O-O { Now that pawn on d4 is defended, White is ready for e2-e4. } 6... Bb4
{ An alternative setup for White starts with } 7. Nh3 O-O 8. a3
{ It is not clear where the bishop is better positioned, e7 or a5, both seem to be okay. }
8... Be7 9. Kb1 a6 { Black is preparing ...b7-b5 so White needs to be quick. }
10. e4 dxe4
{ Taking with the d-pawn is often seen in these systems because Black increases the pressure on the d4-pawn. That makes it easier to play ...e6-e5 since the pawn on f5 is defended by the bishop on c8. }
11. fxe4 e5
{ It is essential for Black to immediately break free and not end up in a cramped position. }
12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. d5 Nd4
{ There is no reason to go back to the passive e7-square. } 14. exf5 Bxf5
{ Threatening to take on c2 so White's answer is obvious. } 15. Bd3 Qd7
{ I prefer defending the bishop on f5 over taking on h3. Yes, White would have an ugly pawn on h3, but the half-open g-file would increase the attacking chances and the bishop on d3 could become powerful with Black's light-squared bishop gone. }
16. Nf2 b5
{ White has obtained control over the e4-square but Black is ready to attack on the queenside thanks to the target on a3. It is a complex position where it seems that Black's moves like ...Rab8 followed by ...b5-b4 are a bit easier to find/play compared to White's plans. }
