{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nc3 { White wants to play e2-e4. } 2... Nf6 3. Bg5
{ White wants to take on f6 to create doubled pawns. White could then either try to benefit from the weak pawn on f5 or play for c2-c4, claiming that if Black takes on c4, a white bishop on c4 will be very powerful now that there are no longer pawns on either f7, e6, or d5 to stop this bishop. }
3... d5 4. f3 Nc6 5. Qd2 e6 { Creating space to develop the f8-bishop. } 6.
O-O-O { Now that pawn on d4 is defended, White is ready for e2-e4. } 6... Bb4
{ Pinning the knight to make e2-e4 more difficult. } 7. e3
{ White can also first play  7.a3  and then  7...Ba5  8.e3  . } 7... Bd7
{ Black is preparing to castle queenside as well, a safe strategy considering White did the same. }
8. Bd3 Qe7 9. Nge2 h6
{ This move can also be played later. The idea is that Black can gain space with ...g7-g5 after castling queenside, or even better, push the e-pawn to e5 without losing d5 and for that, we need to get rid of the pin on the f6-knight. }
10. Bf4
{ If White plays  10.Bh4  Black will also castle queenside and keep the option open of playing ...g7-g5 later. Taking on f6 is not dangerous for us as we'll get the bishop pair. }
10... O-O-O
{ Both sides would like to push their e-pawn. It seems Black is a little faster. }
11. a3 Ba5 12. Kb1 a6
{ Pushing the e6-pawn to e5 requires a tactical justification in that the white queen doesn't have a lot of squares. The idea of ...a7-a6 is that the b5-square is no longer available for the white queen.   Immediately pushing the e-pawn doesn't work yet:  12...e5  13.dxe5  Nxe5  14.Nxd5  and White has won a pawn. }
13. Bg3 e5
{ Now the same trick with taking on d5 is no longer winning because the e3-pawn is not defended by the bishop on f4 anymore. }
14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Qxa5 Nc6 17. Qd2
{ Note that White cannot play  17.Qxd5  because of  17...Be6  and White loses the queen.  The b5-square is also taken because of the small move ...a7-a6. }
17... Nxe3
{ This is a nicely centralized knight. There are some lines where White sacrifices the pawn on g2 and later wins back the pawn on g7, but in practice, most players would just defend the g2-pawn. }
18. Rdg1 Rhe8 19. Nc3 Qf7
{ The position is equal, Black has compensation with the powerful knight on e3 for White's two bishops. Black would like to keep the knight on e3, but as soon as we play...f5-f4, White will occupy the e4-square with the knight or bishop. So it is likely that at some point Black will play ...Ne3-c4 and White may need to give up the d3-bishop for the knight. }
*

