[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nc3 { White wants to play e2-e4. } 2... Nf6 3. Bg5
{ White wants to take on f6 to create doubled pawns. White could then either try to benefit from the weak pawn on f5 or play for c2-c4, claiming that if Black takes on c4, a white bishop on c4 will be very powerful now that there are no longer pawns on either f7, e6, or d5 to stop this bishop. }
3... d5 4. f3 c5
{ A second option I recommend. The main difference is that in the lines with  4...Nc6  , the result is often a complex middlegame, while in the  4...c5  lines there is a higher chance of a queen swap resulting in a complex endgame. Most correspondence players prefer the 4...c5 system, but I have a slight preference for the 4...Nc6 system for over-the-board play. I find it easier to understand the logic behind the moves and therefore easier to remember/play the correct moves in an actual game. }
5. e4 Nc6 6. Nge2 dxe4
{ To keep things simple, I recommend that in these f3 lines to first take with the d-pawn on e4 and only later with the f-pawn, so that we first put pressure on the d4-pawn. }
7. d5 exf3
{ Only move as moving the knight to e5 is not good because White will take on e4 followed by Ng3, winning the pawn on e4, with a clearly better position. }
8. gxf3 Ne5
{ The normal square in these lines for the knight, with the option to drop back to f7 if needed. }
9. Nf4 Qb6 { Protecting the e6-square and attacking b2. } 10. Qe2 Nf7 11. Bxf6
gxf6
{ Taking with the g-pawn is better than taking with the queen because Black has the option of Bh6 now, effectively preventing White to castle queenside. }
12. Qb5+ Bd7
{ I prefer Bd7 over taking on b5 because then we have to know two lines, one after Bxb5 and one after Nxb5. }
13. Ne6 Rc8
{ I prefer this move over  13...Bxb5  because after  14.Bxb5+  Black needs to give up the queen anyway and the a7-pawn is likely to be lost at some point. }
14. Qxb6 axb6 15. Nb5 Ne5
{ The black king can now escape via f7 and, although the engine thinks White has sufficient compensation for the sacrificed pawn, I think in a practical game it is not easy for White to prove anything. }
