[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nc3 { White wants to play e2-e4. } 2... Nf6 3. Bg5
{ White wants to take on f6 to create doubled pawns. White could then either try to benefit from the weak pawn on f5 or play for c2-c4, claiming that if Black takes on c4, a white bishop on c4 will be very powerful now that there are no longer pawns on either f7, e6, or d5 to stop this bishop. }
3... d5 4. f3 c5
{ A second option I recommend. The main difference is that in the lines with  4...Nc6  , the result is often a complex middlegame, while in the  4...c5  lines there is a higher chance of a queen swap resulting in a complex endgame. Most correspondence players prefer the 4...c5 system, but I have a slight preference for the 4...Nc6 system for over-the-board play. I find it easier to understand the logic behind the moves and therefore easier to remember/play the correct moves in an actual game. }
5. e4 Nc6 6. Bb5 fxe4
{ Taking with the d-pawn is not an option because of d4-d5. } 7. dxc5 d4
{ Defending the d5-pawn with  7...Be6  is not great, White can play  8.Qe2  and castle queenside and Black is too far behind in development. }
8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Nxe4 Qd5 { Threatening to take the bishop after ...Nxe4. } 10.
Qe2 Nxe4 11. Qxe4 e5
{ 11...Qxg5  is of course not possible because of  12.Qxc6+  , but @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p3p1pp/2p5/2Pq2B1/3pQ3/5P2/PPP3PP/R3K1NR b KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qxc5  is a valid alternative.  I prefer the text move because it helps with developing the f8-bishop. }
12. Qxd5 cxd5 13. O-O-O Bxc5 14. Re1 O-O
{ Defending the e5-pawn with  14...Bd6  is not going to help. White simply plays  15.Bf4  , making use of the pin along the e-file. }
15. Rxe5 Rf5 { An original way of defending the d5-pawn. } 16. Rxf5 Bxf5
{ Black has sufficient compensation with the pair of bishops and the game Rulfs-Marten, ICCF email 2019 soon ended in a draw. Black’s idea is to place the rook on the open e-file and activate the bishops by playing ...d4-d3. }
