[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5"]
[Black "Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5 − 4.f3 #16"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nc3 { White wants to play e2-e4. } 2... Nf6 3. Bg5
{ White wants to take on f6 to create doubled pawns. White could then either try to benefit from the weak pawn on f5 or play for c2-c4, claiming that if Black takes on c4, a white bishop on c4 will be very powerful now that there are no longer pawns on either f7, e6, or d5 to stop this bishop. }
3... d5 4. f3 c5
{ A second option I recommend. The main difference is that in the lines with  4...Nc6  , the result is often a complex middlegame, while in the  4...c5  lines there is a higher chance of a queen swap resulting in a complex endgame. Most correspondence players prefer the 4...c5 system, but I have a slight preference for the 4...Nc6 system for over-the-board play. I find it easier to understand the logic behind the moves and therefore easier to remember/play the correct moves in an actual game. }
5. e4 Nc6 6. Bb5 fxe4
{ Taking with the d-pawn is not an option because of d4-d5. } 7. fxe4 Nxe4
{ 7...dxe4  still fails to  8.d5  . } 8. Nxe4 dxe4
{ Now there is no d4-d5 because Black is first: we threaten to win a piece with ...Qa5+. }
9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. dxc5 Qxd1+
{ Exchanging queens is the best way to reduce White's pressure.   I don't trust  10...Qd5  in a practical game. It was played with decent results in some correspondence games though.  11.Be3  e5  ,  making space for the f8-bishop.  12.Nh3  Be7  13.O-O  Bxc5  .  White cannot take on d5 because Black would first take the bishop with a check and then capture the queen, ending up with an extra piece.    14.Bxc5  Qxc5+  15.Kh1  .  This is the position I don't trust despite the engine saying 0.00. In a practical game, I would be worried about the fact that Black's king is stuck in the center and cannot castle for the foreseeable future. }
11. Rxd1 g6
{ Note that if Black would have advanced the e-pawn, Rd8+ would have been annoying, the bishop on f8 would be pinned and White could generate a strong attack with Ne2 and Rf1+. }
12. Ne2 Bg7 13. Nd4 Rf8
{ We have reached a complex endgame with mutual chances. Black has a pair of bishops in an open, dynamic position and that compensates for the weaknesses in the pawn structure.  Black is likely to prepare queenside castling by playing ...Bd7, ...h7-h6 and if Bh4, also ...g6-g5. There are some situations where Black could even sacrifice the pawn on e7 and simply castle queenside and generate a lot of activity with the passed pawn on e4 supported by the two bishops. But if we don’t need to sacrifice it  (by playing ...h7-h6)  why would we? }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5"]
[Black "Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5 − 4.Bxf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nc3 { White wants to play e2-e4. } 2... Nf6 3. Bg5
{ White wants to take on f6 to create doubled pawns. White could then either try to benefit from the weak pawn on f5 or play for c2-c4, claiming that if Black takes on c4, a white bishop on c4 will be very powerful now that there are no longer pawns on either f7, e6, or d5 to stop this bishop. }
3... d5 4. Bxf6 exf6
{ In its most simple form, this system is about White trying to prove the weakness of Black's doubled f-pawns and Black making maximum use of the pair of bishops. Over the years, new developments have occurred and White players now often aim for the c2-c4 push in order to weaken the light squares from g8 to c4.  Black usually counters this idea with a timely ...b7-b5. Regardless of whether White pushes for c2-c4 or chooses a more traditional approach, in all cases, Black tries to reroute the knight to e4 in the hope that White needs to take this strong knight and the black pawn structure is repaired while keeping the pair of bishops. }
5. e3 Be6
{ Black starts by developing this bishop, so if needed we can protect the f5-pawn with ...Qd7, or if White puts a knight on f4, the bishop can drop back to f7. }
6. Qf3 Nc6 7. Bb5
{ The alternative  7.Bd3  is discussed as part of themove order  with 6.Bd3 first and then Qf3. }
7... Qd6
{ It is important to not put the queen on d7 because the knight would be pinned. In many lines, the black knight moves via a5 to c4. On the other hand, if White doesn't put the bishop on b5, Nb5 can still be played, so sometimes that prevents Black from playing ...Qd6 and we will have to play ...Qd7. }
8. Nge2
{ White wants to put the knight on f4. The disadvantage is that the bishop can no longer drop back to e2.   Note that if White plays  8.Nh3  to keep e2 open for the bishop, Black will play  8...g5  threatening to win a piece with ...g5-g4. }
8... a6
{ A great move! The bishop would normally go to d3, but here it will be attacked by ...Nb4, and White's beautiful bishop will be exchanged. }
9. Ba4 O-O-O 10. Nf4 Na5
{ This line is for illustration, in general, I recommend playing  10...Bf7  whenever there is a knight on f4, but in this particular case, swapping on e6 will not bring White anything special. }
11. h3 Kb8
{ Always a good idea to step away with the king from c8 so if White ever takes the pawn on f5 with the queen, it will not come with a check. }
12. O-O-O Bf7 13. g4 g5 { Pushing the knight to a passive square. } 14. Nfe2
fxg4
{ This move works for Black because White cannot occupy the f5-square with the knight. }
15. hxg4 Bg6 { Maintaining control over the f5-square. } 16. Ng3 Qe6 17. Bb3
{ White could not play  17.Nf5  because Black responds with  17...h5  and White's position collapses. }
17... Nxb3+ 18. axb3 Bb4
{ Black was better in Brodsky-Ikonnikov, Hoogeveen NED 2006. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5"]
[Black "Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5 − 4.Bxf6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nc3 { White wants to play e2-e4. } 2... Nf6 3. Bg5
{ White wants to take on f6 to create doubled pawns. White could then either try to benefit from the weak pawn on f5 or play for c2-c4, claiming that if Black takes on c4, a white bishop on c4 will be very powerful now that there are no longer pawns on either f7, e6, or d5 to stop this bishop. }
3... d5 4. Bxf6 exf6
{ In its most simple form, this system is about White trying to prove the weakness of Black's doubled f-pawns and Black making maximum use of the pair of bishops. Over the years, new developments have occurred and White players now often aim for the c2-c4 push in order to weaken the light squares from g8 to c4.  Black usually counters this idea with a timely ...b7-b5. Regardless of whether White pushes for c2-c4 or chooses a more traditional approach, in all cases, Black tries to reroute the knight to e4 in the hope that White needs to take this strong knight and the black pawn structure is repaired while keeping the pair of bishops. }
5. e3 Be6
{ Black starts by developing this bishop, so if needed we can protect the f5-pawn with ...Qd7, or if White puts a knight on f4, the bishop can drop back to f7. }
6. Qf3 Nc6 7. Bb5
{ The alternative  7.Bd3  is discussed as part of themove order  with 6.Bd3 first and then Qf3. }
7... Qd6
{ It is important to not put the queen on d7 because the knight would be pinned. In many lines, the black knight moves via a5 to c4. On the other hand, if White doesn't put the bishop on b5, Nb5 can still be played, so sometimes that prevents Black from playing ...Qd6 and we will have to play ...Qd7. }
8. Nge2
{ White wants to put the knight on f4. The disadvantage is that the bishop can no longer drop back to e2.   Note that if White plays  8.Nh3  to keep e2 open for the bishop, Black will play  8...g5  threatening to win a piece with ...g5-g4. }
8... a6
{ A great move! The bishop would normally go to d3, but here it will be attacked by ...Nb4, and White's beautiful bishop will be exchanged. }
9. Ba4 O-O-O 10. Nf4 Bf7
{ When White plays Nf4, Black normally responds with ...Bf7. } 11. h4 g5
{ The move  11...h5  is also okay for Black, but long term, Black hopes to play ...g7-g5 to create space for the bishops. Here it can be done directly, so why would we wait? }
12. Nd3 Ne7
{ The knight is on its way to either d6 or b6, to defend the f5-pawn. } 13.
O-O-O Kb8 14. Kb1 g4
{ It is not easy to protect the pawn on f5 and to play ...Nc8-Nd6 because on  14...Be6  there is always  15.Nc5  and if the bishop then drops back  15...Bc8  ,  the knight struggles to get to d6. }
15. Qe2 Nc8
{ Black's position is fine, with no big weaknesses and the knight is likely to end on e4. If White prevents this by playing f2-f3, the e-pawn will become weak with a rook on e8 and the bishop on h6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
