[Round "?"]
[White "12. Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5"]
[Black "Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5 − 4.Bxf6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nc3 { White wants to play e2-e4. } 2... Nf6 3. Bg5
{ White wants to take on f6 to create doubled pawns. White could then either try to benefit from the weak pawn on f5 or play for c2-c4, claiming that if Black takes on c4, a white bishop on c4 will be very powerful now that there are no longer pawns on either f7, e6, or d5 to stop this bishop. }
3... d5 4. Bxf6 exf6
{ In its most simple form, this system is about White trying to prove the weakness of Black's doubled f-pawns and Black making maximum use of the pair of bishops. Over the years, new developments have occurred and White players now often aim for the c2-c4 push in order to weaken the light squares from g8 to c4.  Black usually counters this idea with a timely ...b7-b5. Regardless of whether White pushes for c2-c4 or chooses a more traditional approach, in all cases, Black tries to reroute the knight to e4 in the hope that White needs to take this strong knight and the black pawn structure is repaired while keeping the pair of bishops. }
5. e3 Be6
{ Black starts by developing this bishop, so if needed we can protect the f5-pawn with ...Qd7, or if White puts a knight on f4, the bishop can drop back to f7. }
6. Qf3 Nc6 7. Bb5
{ The alternative  7.Bd3  is discussed as part of themove order  with 6.Bd3 first and then Qf3. }
7... Qd6
{ It is important to not put the queen on d7 because the knight would be pinned. In many lines, the black knight moves via a5 to c4. On the other hand, if White doesn't put the bishop on b5, Nb5 can still be played, so sometimes that prevents Black from playing ...Qd6 and we will have to play ...Qd7. }
8. h4 h5 9. Nh3
{ Now this move makes sense after the inclusion of h2-h4, ...h7-h5 because there is no immediate ...g7-g5. Once the knight is on f4, the pawn on h5 will be attacked. }
9... O-O-O 10. Nf4 Bf7
{ The h5-pawn was hanging and Black also wants to avoid Ng6. } 11. Nd3 g6 12.
a3
{ Not only preparing b2-b4 to support a white knight on c5, but also ensuring the white bishop can drop back to a2 and will not be swapped for a knight on b3. }
12... a6 { Preparing to put a knight on c4. } 13. Ba4 Na5 14. Nc5 Nc4 15. b4
{ Not just defending the knight on c5 but also with the idea of b4-b5, to start an attack against the black king. }
15... c6 { Ensuring that White cannot play b4-b5 quickly. } 16. Bb3 Qc7
{ If White wants to attack on the queenside with a3-a4 and then b4-b5, the h1-rook needs to join the party. It turns out that this takes too much time and Black will obtain a clear advantage. }
17. Ke2 Nd6 { Rerouting the knight to e4. } 18. a4 a5
{ Stopping White's expansion on the queenside. } 19. b5 Ne4 20. N5xe4 dxe4 21.
Qh3 { The white queen is completely offside. } 21... Bb4
{ And there is not much left of White's attack. } *

