8. h4 h5 9. Nh3
{ Now this move makes sense after the inclusion of h2-h4, ...h7-h5 because there is no immediate ...g7-g5. Once the knight is on f4, the pawn on h5 will be attacked. }
9... O-O-O 10. Nf4 Bf7
{ The h5-pawn was hanging and Black also wants to avoid Ng6. } 11. Nd3 g6 12.
a3
{ Not only preparing b2-b4 to support a white knight on c5, but also ensuring the white bishop can drop back to a2 and will not be swapped for a knight on b3. }
12... a6 { Preparing to put a knight on c4. } 13. Ba4 Na5 14. Nc5 Nc4 15. b4
{ Not just defending the knight on c5 but also with the idea of b4-b5, to start an attack against the black king. }
15... c6 { Ensuring that White cannot play b4-b5 quickly. } 16. Bb3 Qc7 17.
Bxc4 { It would have been better for White to first bring the king to safety. }
17... dxc4 18. g3 { A blunder from White. } 18... Bxc5 { Black wins material. }
19. dxc5 { 19.bxc5  fails to  19...Qa5  . } 19... Qe5
{ The white knight is pinned either from a5 or from e5. } 20. e4 fxe4 21. Qe3
Rd3 { A winning combination. } 22. cxd3 Qxc3+
{ And after  23.Ke2  ,  White didn't wait for Black's move and resigned in Pyda-Jakubiec, Zakopane 2000. Taking on d3 with either pawn wins the house. }
