[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5"]
[Black "Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5 − 4.Bxf6 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nc3 { White wants to play e2-e4. } 2... Nf6 3. Bg5
{ White wants to take on f6 to create doubled pawns. White could then either try to benefit from the weak pawn on f5 or play for c2-c4, claiming that if Black takes on c4, a white bishop on c4 will be very powerful now that there are no longer pawns on either f7, e6, or d5 to stop this bishop. }
3... d5 4. Bxf6 exf6
{ In its most simple form, this system is about White trying to prove the weakness of Black's doubled f-pawns and Black making maximum use of the pair of bishops. Over the years, new developments have occurred and White players now often aim for the c2-c4 push in order to weaken the light squares from g8 to c4.  Black usually counters this idea with a timely ...b7-b5. Regardless of whether White pushes for c2-c4 or chooses a more traditional approach, in all cases, Black tries to reroute the knight to e4 in the hope that White needs to take this strong knight and the black pawn structure is repaired while keeping the pair of bishops. }
5. e3 Be6
{ Black starts by developing this bishop, so if needed we can protect the f5-pawn with ...Qd7, or if White puts a knight on f4, the bishop can drop back to f7. }
6. Nge2 Nc6
{ Black sticks to the natural way of development: knight to c6, bishop to f7, queen to d6 or d7, and usually queenside castling while sometimes kingside is also a valid option. }
7. Nf4 Bf7 8. h4 { After h2-h4, Black usually plays ...h7-h5, stopping h4-h5. }
8... h5 9. Qf3 Ne7
{ Not only defending the pawn on d5 but also having the idea to play ...Nc8-d6. }
10. Qg3 Qd7
{ Placing the queen on d6 doesn't make sense if White has the option of Nb5. }
11. Bb5 c6 12. Be2 Nc8
{ It is better to do this before castling as otherwise, the king would be in the way. }
13. Na4
{ Note that  13.Ng6  is not good because Black would play  13...Bd6  and the knight needs to return to f4 to not lose a piece. }
13... b6 { Defending against Nc5 before playing ...Nd6. } 14. b3 Nd6
{ White may continue with Rc1 and Nb2 and then c2-c4 but it all takes a lot of time and doesn't feel too threatening. Meanwhile Black is ready for ...Ne4 and then possibly ...g7-g5 and the white queen may get lost after ...g5-g4. I prefer Black here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5"]
[Black "Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5 − 4.Bxf6 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nc3 { White wants to play e2-e4. } 2... Nf6 3. Bg5
{ White wants to take on f6 to create doubled pawns. White could then either try to benefit from the weak pawn on f5 or play for c2-c4, claiming that if Black takes on c4, a white bishop on c4 will be very powerful now that there are no longer pawns on either f7, e6, or d5 to stop this bishop. }
3... d5 4. Bxf6 exf6
{ In its most simple form, this system is about White trying to prove the weakness of Black's doubled f-pawns and Black making maximum use of the pair of bishops. Over the years, new developments have occurred and White players now often aim for the c2-c4 push in order to weaken the light squares from g8 to c4.  Black usually counters this idea with a timely ...b7-b5. Regardless of whether White pushes for c2-c4 or chooses a more traditional approach, in all cases, Black tries to reroute the knight to e4 in the hope that White needs to take this strong knight and the black pawn structure is repaired while keeping the pair of bishops. }
5. e3 Be6
{ Black starts by developing this bishop, so if needed we can protect the f5-pawn with ...Qd7, or if White puts a knight on f4, the bishop can drop back to f7. }
6. Nf3 { White's idea is to continue later on with Nd2 and c2-c4. } 6... c6
{ Because of White's c2-c4 plan, it is a good idea for Black to respond with ...c7-c6. However, the standard setup with ...Nc6 is still an option. }
7. g3
{ This rare move was played in a game between Ippolito and Zang in Calicut, 1998. }
7... Nd7 8. Bg2 Nb6
{ Black has two options for the knight: c8 and then d6, or c4 and if needed later, d6. }
9. Ne2 Nc4 10. b3 Nd6 11. Nd2 Ne4
{ The knight has found a beautiful spot. Do note that Black can delay developing because White's position with the knights on e2 and d2 is not threatening at all. }
12. c3 g6 13. O-O h5 { Suddenly, Black is organizing an attack. } 14. Qc2 h4
{ Black had already obtained a dangerous initiative. We can still decide to castle queenside, but maybe the king sits better on f7 or g7 while the rook on h8 helps in the attack. I think most White players will struggle to defend this position. }
*

