{ White wants to take on f6 to create doubled pawns. White could then either try to benefit from the weak pawn on f5 or play for c2-c4, claiming that if Black takes on c4, a white bishop on c4 will be very powerful now that there are no longer pawns on either f7, e6, or d5 to stop this bishop. }
3... d5 4. Bxf6 exf6
{ In its most simple form, this system is about White trying to prove the weakness of Black's doubled f-pawns and Black making maximum use of the pair of bishops. Over the years, new developments have occurred and White players now often aim for the c2-c4 push in order to weaken the light squares from g8 to c4.  Black usually counters this idea with a timely ...b7-b5. Regardless of whether White pushes for c2-c4 or chooses a more traditional approach, in all cases, Black tries to reroute the knight to e4 in the hope that White needs to take this strong knight and the black pawn structure is repaired while keeping the pair of bishops. }
5. e3 Be6
{ Black starts by developing this bishop, so if needed we can protect the f5-pawn with ...Qd7, or if White puts a knight on f4, the bishop can drop back to f7. }
6. Nf3 { White's idea is to continue later on with Nd2 and c2-c4. } 6... c6
{ Because of White's c2-c4 plan, it is a good idea for Black to respond with ...c7-c6. However, the standard setup with ...Nc6 is still an option. }
7. Bd3 Nd7 8. Ne2 g6 9. Nd2 Nb6
{ Again, with the idea to move the knight to d6 and maybe even to e4, either via c4 or c8. }
10. b3 Be7 { Black is ready to castle, but White takes action. } 11. c4 c5
{ An important move, although not standard at all for this line. White was threatening to play c4-c5 and get a grip on the queenside while Black doesn't have a lot on the kingside yet  @@StartBracket@@notice how the knight on e2 helps to protect against Black's plans with ...f5-f4@@EndBracket@@. }
12. Nf4 Bf7 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Qxd5
{ By taking with the queen Black puts pressure on the d4-pawn that is currently pinned because of the bishop on d3. }
15. O-O cxd4 16. Bc4 Qd8
{ The position was equal in Eingorn-Kindermann, Vienna 2003. Black may keep an extra pawn, but that extra pawn sits on f6 and doesn't mean much while White can claim that the king is a bit safer than Black's @@StartBracket@@which is likely to go to f7 and then maybe to g7@@EndBracket@@. }
*

