[White "12. Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5"]
[Black "Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5 − 4.Bxf6 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nc3 { White wants to play e2-e4. } 2... Nf6 3. Bg5
{ White wants to take on f6 to create doubled pawns. White could then either try to benefit from the weak pawn on f5 or play for c2-c4, claiming that if Black takes on c4, a white bishop on c4 will be very powerful now that there are no longer pawns on either f7, e6, or d5 to stop this bishop. }
3... d5 4. Bxf6 exf6
{ In its most simple form, this system is about White trying to prove the weakness of Black's doubled f-pawns and Black making maximum use of the pair of bishops. Over the years, new developments have occurred and White players now often aim for the c2-c4 push in order to weaken the light squares from g8 to c4.  Black usually counters this idea with a timely ...b7-b5. Regardless of whether White pushes for c2-c4 or chooses a more traditional approach, in all cases, Black tries to reroute the knight to e4 in the hope that White needs to take this strong knight and the black pawn structure is repaired while keeping the pair of bishops. }
5. e3 Be6
{ Black starts by developing this bishop, so if needed we can protect the f5-pawn with ...Qd7, or if White puts a knight on f4, the bishop can drop back to f7. }
6. h4
{ If White plays h2-h4, Black almost always wants to play ...h7-h5. Black needs a pawn on g6 to defend the f5-pawn and we don't want that pawn to be attacked by h4-h5. Moreover, h7-h5 reduces the chance White can play the break g2-g4 successfully. }
6... h5 7. Nh3 c6 8. Qd3
{ A rare move with the idea to quickly castle queenside and push e3-e4. } 8...
g6 9. O-O-O { If White castles queenside, Black almost always mirrors this. }
9... Nd7 10. f3 Qe7
{ Preparing queenside castling and if White pushes e3-e4, Black can open the position, play ...Bh6+ and have the better game because of the bishop pair. }
11. Nf4 Bf7 12. Kb1 O-O-O
{ Black is maybe already a bit better if the position is opened. The bishops will be strong and, as long as it stays closed, we can improve our position by playing ...Kb8, ...Nb6-c8-d6. }
