[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13. Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 − Alternative 2...d5"]
[Black "Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 − Alternative 2...d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nc3 { White wants to play e2-e4. } 2... d5
{ This is an alternative way of playing for Black. I recommend it as a backup system because I believe Black's setup is more solid, but also a bit more boring. I play the Leningrad for a win and the system I recommend with  2...Nf6  often quickly becomes unbalanced. I think  2...d5  is also a sound system and not everyone wants to play with doubled f-pawns, so below I give the main lines that one needs to know if playing this. }
3. Bg5
{ Now  3...Nf6  wouldtranspose to the system with 2...Nf6. However, I assume Black played 2...d5 to avoid these systems with a double f-pawn, so the lines below are based on the idea that Black doesn't want to transpose. }
3... c6 4. e3 g6 { This move seems playable for Black. } 5. h4
{ Black needs to be careful when White plays h2-h4 in the Leningrad System. As a general rule, Black never takes on h5. We either allow h4-h5 and then taking on g6 @@StartBracket@@or h5-h6@@EndBracket@@ or we play ...h7-h6 so that after h4-h5 we can close the position with ...g6-g5. }
5... Bg7 6. Bd3 Nf6 7. h5 Ne4 8. Bxe4
{ Initially, my engine gave White an advantage with this strange move but when I analyzed further, I felt Black is OK. }
8... fxe4 9. hxg6 hxg6 10. Rxh8+ Bxh8
{ Considering both sides will probably castle queenside, it is clear Black is behind in development compared to White and therefore needs to be fast. }
11. f3 Qd6 { Threatening to win a piece with ...Qg3+. } 12. Nge2 exf3 13. gxf3
Qh2 { Disrupting White's development. } 14. Kd2 Bg7 15. Qh1 Qxh1 16. Rxh1 Kf7
{ White doesn't have any entry points, so Black has time to complete development and equalize. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13. Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 − Alternative 2...d5"]
[Black "Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 − Alternative 2...d5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nc3 { White wants to play e2-e4. } 2... d5
{ This is an alternative way of playing for Black. I recommend it as a backup system because I believe Black's setup is more solid, but also a bit more boring. I play the Leningrad for a win and the system I recommend with  2...Nf6  often quickly becomes unbalanced. I think  2...d5  is also a sound system and not everyone wants to play with doubled f-pawns, so below I give the main lines that one needs to know if playing this. }
3. Bg5
{ Now  3...Nf6  wouldtranspose to the system with 2...Nf6. However, I assume Black played 2...d5 to avoid these systems with a double f-pawn, so the lines below are based on the idea that Black doesn't want to transpose. }
3... c6 4. e3 g6 { This move seems playable for Black. } 5. h4
{ Black needs to be careful when White plays h2-h4 in the Leningrad System. As a general rule, Black never takes on h5. We either allow h4-h5 and then taking on g6 @@StartBracket@@or h5-h6@@EndBracket@@ or we play ...h7-h6 so that after h4-h5 we can close the position with ...g6-g5. }
5... Bg7 6. Bd3 Nf6 7. h5 Ne4 8. Bf4 Nd7
{ Black cannot play  8...g5  because White first plays  9.h6  and then has the possibility to play Qh5+, with a large advantage. }
9. Nf3 Bf6 { Black is threatening ...g6-g5, so White decides to take on g6. }
10. hxg6 hxg6 11. Rxh8+ Bxh8 12. Ke2
{ For Black it is also an option to keep the king in the center, besides castling queenside of course. }
12... Nf8
{ Black creates space for the c8-bishop and defends the g6-pawn. That pawn can easily be attacked with a knight on e5 or a queen on h6. }
13. Qh1 Bf6 14. Ne5 Be6
{ Not only developing the bishop but also creating the option to give the g6-pawn extra protection with ...Bf7. }
15. f3 Nd6
{ Maybe White is a little better but in a practical game, this is just a complex position with all three results possible. Black can activate the queen and castle queenside.   My Stockfish 13 gives White +0.64 after the moves  16.Bh6  Nd7  and now the bishop goes back  17.Bf4  again.  It is one of those rare occasions that I fail to understand how to translate the engine’s score into something concrete. I really believe Black’s position is fine. If we manage to castle queenside, our king will be even safer than White’s. }
