{ This is a more aggressive attempt than  4...g6  but also seems playable for Black. }
5. Na4 Qa5+ 6. c3 Nf6
{ The move played by a top grandmaster, so it deserves serious attention. Based on my analysis, I don't recommend it but I think it gives a nice illustration of what we need to watch out for as a Black player. }
7. Nc5 Qb6 8. Nd3 Nbd7
{ This move is necessary, to be able to play the e-pawn and develop the bishop from f8. Without the knight on d7, White would take on f6 after Black has played ...e7-e6 and Black is forced to take back with the g-pawn and that would result in a really bad structure around the king. }
9. Nf3 Ne4 10. Bf4 e6
{ Slowly, Black is creating a kind of Stonewall structure. } 11. Nfe5 Ndf6 12.
Be2 Be7 13. O-O O-O
{ Black has secured the king, but the bishop on c8 is still a problem piece. }
14. f3 Nd6 15. Bg3 Qd8 16. b3 g5
{ Black is grabbing some space on the kingside, but unfortunately, there is no kingside attack in sight. }
17. c4
{ Not only does White have a nice advantage, but it is also difficult to see how Black can generate counterplay: ...f5-f4 is unlikely to happen and ...g5-g4 is not threatening anything. If White is scared, even f3-f4 can be played. Despite having 250 rating points less and playing against someone who qualified for the FIDE Candidates, White made a comfortable draw in Hambleton-Wang, Edmonton 2015. }
