[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13. Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 − Alternative 2...d5"]
[Black "Anti-Dutch 2.Nc3 − Alternative 2...d5 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nc3 { White wants to play e2-e4. } 2... d5
{ This is an alternative way of playing for Black. I recommend it as a backup system because I believe Black's setup is more solid, but also a bit more boring. I play the Leningrad for a win and the system I recommend with  2...Nf6  often quickly becomes unbalanced. I think  2...d5  is also a sound system and not everyone wants to play with doubled f-pawns, so below I give the main lines that one needs to know if playing this. }
3. Bg5
{ Now  3...Nf6  wouldtranspose to the system with 2...Nf6. However, I assume Black played 2...d5 to avoid these systems with a double f-pawn, so the lines below are based on the idea that Black doesn't want to transpose. }
3... c6 4. e3 Qb6
{ This is a more aggressive attempt than  4...g6  but also seems playable for Black. }
5. Na4 Qa5+ 6. c3 e5
{ Using a small trick: White cannot play  7.dxe5  because after  7...b5  , the  knight can no longer go to c5 and also has no other squares. }
7. Nf3 Nd7
{ Defending the pawn on e5 is the only option for Black. Playing ...e5-e4 would be asking for trouble with White having developed three light pieces and Black none. }
8. b4 Qc7 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Qxe5 11. Be2 Nf6
{ Black needs to finish development as soon as possible, priority is on the pieces on the kingside to enable castling. Castling queenside is not a good option with White's bishop coming to f4 in combination with the b-pawn and potentially Nc5... }
12. Bf4 Qe6
{ We need to block one of the bishops with the queen, but it is more important to develop the f8-bishop and then castle, which is why ...Qe6 is preferred over ...Qe7. }
13. O-O Be7 14. Nc5 Qf7
{ Taking on c5 would be a disaster for the dark squares, even if Black would be lucky enough to win the pawn on c5. }
15. Qc2 O-O
{ Black has almost completed development, only the c8-bishop needs to find a proper place. }
16. c4 Bxc5
{ Maybe it is not nice to take with a bishop, but the knight on c5 is quite powerful and what is important, are the pieces that remain on the board: the c8-bishop can now become active. }
17. bxc5 dxc4 18. Bxc4 Be6
{ Black has a solid position, only one minor weakness @@StartBracket@@the pawn on b7@@EndBracket@@ and good pieces. }
