[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nc3 { White wants to play e2-e4. } 2... d5
{ This is an alternative way of playing for Black. I recommend it as a backup system because I believe Black's setup is more solid, but also a bit more boring. I play the Leningrad for a win and the system I recommend with  2...Nf6  often quickly becomes unbalanced. I think  2...d5  is also a sound system and not everyone wants to play with doubled f-pawns, so below I give the main lines that one needs to know if playing this. }
3. Bf4 a6
{ There are some games where Black allows White to play Nb5, but I think it is much easier to prevent it. }
4. e3 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 { Now White can choose where to put the bishop: d3 or e2. }
6. Bd3 c5 { It is essential for Black to become active as soon as possible. }
7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. O-O O-O 9. Ne2
{ A standard idea to prepare an attack on the black center with c2-c4. } 9...
Qe7
{ Black can also try to gain the pair of bishops with  9...Nc6  10.c4  .  White can keep the pair of bishops by playing a2-a3 or c2-c3, but speed is more important here, to put Black under pressure.  10...Nb4  11.a3  Nxd3  12.Qxd3  .  Black has the bishop pair, but the bishop on c8 is rather passive.    12...Bd7  13.Rfd1  Rc8  .  The real problem for Black is the pawn on e6. White can attack this pawn from d4, f4 and/or g5, and also the e5-square is weak.  14.Rac1  Ba7  15.Ned4  and White  has a small but lasting advantage because of the better pawn structure and better piece coordination with the rooks on d1 and c1. }
10. c4 Nc6
{ Black continues to develop and would love to improve the structure by playing ...e6-e5. }
11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Bg5 Nf6 13. Rc1 h6
{ Playing  13...e5  fails tactically. White would reply with  14.Bxf6  and then Bxf5 winning a pawn because there is always Qd5 check winning the bishop on c5. }
14. Bxf6 Rxf6 15. Qb3 b6
{ Black needs to develop the bishop, a plan with ...Kh8, ...e6-e5 and then ...Be6 is too slow. }
16. Rfd1 Bb7 17. Nf4 { White is putting pressure on the e6-pawn. } 17... Na5
{ Black needs to get rid of the pin on the e6-pawn. } 18. Qa4 e5
{ Resolving the issues with the e6-pawn and gaining important space in the center. }
19. Nh5 Rf7
{ Black has equalized by playing a few precise moves to get rid of the weak pawn on e6. We have sufficient space and all the pieces are active.   Black is threatening to win a piece with ...e5-e4, but do note that if White plays something like  20.Bb1  , Black should not play  20...Bxf3  21.gxf3  Qg5+  22.Ng3  and try to win a piece with  22...f4  , because White has  23.Qe4  , with a winning position in view of mating threats.  Instead, Black can consolidate after Bb1 with something  like @@StartFEN@@r5k1/1b2qrp1/pp5p/n1b1pp1N/Q7/4PN2/PP3PPP/1BRR2K1 b - - 3 20@@EndFEN@@  20...g6  . }
