[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nc3 { White wants to play e2-e4. } 2... d5
{ This is an alternative way of playing for Black. I recommend it as a backup system because I believe Black's setup is more solid, but also a bit more boring. I play the Leningrad for a win and the system I recommend with  2...Nf6  often quickly becomes unbalanced. I think  2...d5  is also a sound system and not everyone wants to play with doubled f-pawns, so below I give the main lines that one needs to know if playing this. }
3. Bf4 a6
{ There are some games where Black allows White to play Nb5, but I think it is much easier to prevent it. }
4. e3 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 { Now White can choose where to put the bishop: d3 or e2. }
6. Be2 c5 7. O-O Nc6
{ Although this has been played in practice a few times, I don't trust it for Black. }
8. Na4 c4 9. b3 Be7 10. Ne5 Nxe5 11. Bxe5
{ Ivan Sokolov has played  11.dxe5  , but I think taking back with the bishop is much stronger. }
11... O-O
{ 11...Qa5  with the idea to control the c5-square from the white knight doesn't work so well.  12.Bh5+  g6  13.Qe1  Qxe1   Black should avoid the queen swap.  13...Bb4  14.c3  Be7  and  Black is just worse with all the pawns on light squares and the bishop on c8.  14.Rfxe1  gxh5  15.Nb6  and White is winning material and has a large advantage. }
12. bxc4 dxc4 13. Nc5
{ And White has in almost all lines a clear advantage, except when Black sacrifices an exchange.   White cannot play  13.Bxc4  because of  13...b5  . }
13... b6 14. Bf3 Ra7 15. Bb8 Rc7 16. Bxc7 Qxc7 17. Na4
{ My engine says that Black has compensation, my brain says that in a practical game I would always prefer White. Black doesn't even have a pawn for the exchange and I think in the long run, it just plays easier with White. }
