1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. c4
{ Sometimes White wants to go for a setup with Nc3, Qc2, Bd3, and Nge2. Against the Leningrad System, this is usually not so threatening.   The move  2.e3  is also an option but  transposes to lines where e2-e3 is played at a later stage and where the knight from g1 either moves to f3 or to e2 @@StartBracket@@after Bd3@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Nf6 3. Nc3 d6 4. Bg5
{ As in other lines with Bg5, White's main idea is to take on f6 and go for a quick e2-e4. There is also a second point behind White's setup: to first develop all the pieces on the queenside for a quick castle on the queenside followed by a kingside attack. }
4... Nbd7
{ Preventing White's plan, Black can take back with the knight if White will capture on f6. }
5. Qc2 { Combining two ideas: e2-e4 and queenside castling. } 5... g6
{ Black continues with the normal setup. } 6. h4
{ Expanding on the kingside and preparing a future attack. } 6... Bg7 7. O-O-O
c6
{ It is important to take control over the d5-square before pushing ...e7-e5. }
8. Nh3 e5
{ Standard reaction: push in the center, especially considering White's attacking plans. }
9. e3 h6 { Gaining the pair of bishops. } 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. g4
{ An aggressive move, White hopes to take on f5 and open the g-file. } 11...
exd4 12. g5
{ This move is not threatening for Black because it reduces White's chances for a potential pawn break on the kingside. }
12... hxg5 13. hxg5 Qd8
{ I don't like  13...Qe7  here,  the queen may need to move later again when White puts a rook on e1, and in the long-term, the queen belongs on the queenside @@StartBracket@@e.g. a5@@EndBracket@@ to help in the attack. }
14. exd4 Kf7
{ The king is completely safe here considering White has closed the kingside by playing g4-g5. The advantage of the king move over castling is that the rook can stay on h8  (an open file)  and that the pawn on g6 is protected @@StartBracket@@in case White plays Nf4 at some point@@EndBracket@@. }
15. Bg2 Nf8 { Giving the knight a new future, on d7 it was not active. } 16.
Rhe1 Ne6
{ Black has a fine position, the king is safe, the pawn structure is better @@StartBracket@@on White's side, the pawns on g5 and d4 are weak@@EndBracket@@ and Black can continue with moves like ...Bd7, ...Qb6 or ...Rab8 followed by ...b7-b5. }
