2. c4
{ Sometimes White wants to go for a setup with Nc3, Qc2, Bd3, and Nge2. Against the Leningrad System, this is usually not so threatening. }
2... Nf6 3. Nc3 d6 4. Bg5
{ As in other lines with Bg5, White's main idea is to take on f6 and go for a quick e2-e4. There is also a second point behind White's setup: he's first developing all his pieces on the queenside so he can quickly castle queenside and start a kingside attack. }
4... Nbd7
{ Preventing that Black needs to take back with a pawn on f6 if White were to capture the knight. }
5. Qc2 { Combining the two ideas of e2-e4 and preparing queenside castling. }
5... g6 { Black continues with his normal setup. } 6. O-O-O
{ This line is not necessarily very different from the lines where White starts with h2-h4 or e2-e4, but there are different ways for Black to respond and it is good to illustrate these plans. }
6... Bg7 7. h4 c6
{ In nearly all cases, Black needs this move to take control over the d5-square. }
8. Nh3 e5
{ Immediately taking control over the center before White gets the chance to play Nf4. }
9. dxe5 Nxe5
{ Taking back with the pawn is not great for Black. After  9...dxe5  White will react with  10.e4  ,  with the idea of taking on f5, and the pawn on e5 will become weak. }
10. e3 h6 { Clarifying the bishop's intentions. } 11. Bf4
{ Taking on f6 will give Black a powerful pair of bishops. } 11... Ne4
{ White was threatening to win a piece with Bxe5 given the pin on the d-file. }
12. Nxe4 fxe4 13. Be2
{ Taking the pawn is not a good idea:  13.Qxe4  Bf5  14.Qd4  Nd3+  and White loses the queen. }
13... O-O
{ Black has a fine position. We can play ...d6-d5 in the future because White can not really take with the c-pawn on d5 as that will open the c-file against the king on c1. The black bishop on g7 is also very powerful. Black can use it in an attack with ...b7-b5, combined with a rook on b8 and a queen on a5, to mate the white king. }
