Bg7
{ It is important to keep on developing pieces, otherwise Black may quickly get in trouble. }
9. Nf3 Nf6
{ Not just attacking the queen but also opening the way for the bishop on c8, and the knight on f6 is a good defender of the king. }
10. Qc2 O-O 11. Bd3
{ White would like to attack g6 by playing h2-h4-h5. Piece sacrifices on g6 almost never work because Black has the options of Qe8 and Rf7. }
11... Bg4 12. Nh4
{ White doesn't want to allow Black to take on f3. Black would play Nh5 and the double f-pawns would be seriously weak and there will be no more dynamic attacking options for White. }
12... c5 { Opening the key diagonal for the g7-bishop. } 13. d5
{ If White takes on c5, Black first plays ...Qa5+ check before taking back on c5. }
13... e5
{ Normally, I am not a big fan of these types of moves because the bishop on g7 becomes passive. But here White has no easy way of controlling the e4-square @@StartBracket@@the situation would be different if the knight would have been on d2@@EndBracket@@. }
14. h3 Bd7 15. O-O b5
{ Black is putting pressure on White from multiple sides. There are ideas with ...e5-e4, taking on c4 and Black is happy to increase the pressure with ...Rb8. It is clear that the white knight on h4 is completely offside and Black is at least equal here. }
