[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Rare Setups"]
[Black "Rare Setups − 2.c4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. c4
{ Sometimes White wants to go for a setup with Nc3, Qc2, Bd3, and Nge2. Against the Leningrad System, this is usually not so threatening.   The move  2.e3  is also an option but  transposes to lines where e2-e3 is played at a later stage and where the knight from g1 either moves to f3 or to e2 @@StartBracket@@after Bd3@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. f3
{ If White delays Nf3, the option of playing with f2-f3 is still on the table. If you want to play precisely with Black, I recommend 3...d6 instead of 3...g6 so that after White goes f2-f3, Black can counter with ...e7-e5. However, I realize that we don't always play so precisely and before you know it, we have played our g-pawn instead of the ...d7-d6 push. No worries, Black is still fine and I give here both a line after 3...d6 and after 3...g6. }
4... d6
{ White now gets the e2-e4 push for free, but Black can still maintain the balance. }
5. e4 fxe4 6. fxe4 Bg7 { We continue with simple development. } 7. Nf3
{ White can also start with first  7.Be2  and then 8.Nf3, it just transposes to the same position. }
7... O-O 8. Be2 c5
{ An important break. It is similar to a Benoni setup and it helps to increase the activity of the bishop on g7. }
9. d5 Nbd7 { There is a nice square on e5 for a black knight. } 10. O-O Ng4 11.
h3 Nge5
{ By occupying this square with the knight Black makes it hard for White to create any activity. }
12. Be3 Nxf3+
{ Black has one extra knight since both knights want to be on e5, so it makes sense to exchange one. }
13. Rxf3 Ne5 14. Rxf8+ Qxf8
{ Black can also take back with the bishop on f8, but taking with the queen involves a positional threat. }
15. Qd2
{ The only good move for White as Black was threatening ...Bh6 and after exchanging the dark-squared bishops it becomes clear that Black's knight and bishop are stronger than White's. }
15... Bd7
{ The position is about equal. Black has a great knight on e5 and the next moves will be aiming to play for the ...b7-b5 break via ...a7-a6 and perhaps ...Rb8 and if really needed even ...Qe8. The ...b7-b5 break could bring Black a nice advantage due to the weakness of the c4-pawn and the threat of creating a strong initiative on the queenside supported by the bishop on g7. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Rare Setups"]
[Black "Rare Setups − 2.c4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. c4
{ Sometimes White wants to go for a setup with Nc3, Qc2, Bd3, and Nge2. Against the Leningrad System, this is usually not so threatening.   The move  2.e3  is also an option but  transposes to lines where e2-e3 is played at a later stage and where the knight from g1 either moves to f3 or to e2 @@StartBracket@@after Bd3@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. h4
{ This aggressive move is the main reason that I prefer to play first ...d7-d6 if White starts with d4, c4, and Nc3. }
4... d6 5. h5 Nxh5
{ Instead, playing  5...Bg7  is not attractive because of  6.h6  . } 6. Rxh5
gxh5 7. e4 { White is playing for a quick attack against Black's king. } 7...
fxe4
{ This move could result in a quick draw but Black can also deviate.   7...Bg7  is sound for Black although White has realistic hopes for a small advantage. It is a different question whether something small is relevant when it is such a big mess!  8.Qxh5+  Kf8  9.Bh6  Rg8  .  I think it is important to defend the bishop on g7. My engine initially gives alternatives for Black but after a few seconds the evaluation increases in White's favor.    10.e5  .  Instead White can also play something like Nh3. Black will then respond with ...Qe8 and the position remains unclear.  10...dxe5  11.dxe5  Qe8  .  It is important to offer the queen swap, which White will reject of course, because the queen can help in the defense from e8.  12.Qh2  Nc6  13.Nd5  Qg6  ,  the only move for Black. We have to push White back or force some exchanges as White was threatening to take on c7 and win more material.  14.Bf4  Be6  .  Black has to use all the pieces, the pawn on c7 is less relevant.    15.Nxc7  Rc8  16.Be2  ,  a tricky move, White threatens to win Black's queen with Bh5. If White would have taken on e6, Black could have taken back with the queen and have had an advantage. All the pieces work together and White's initiative is gone. So Be2 is not only a tricky move, it is also the only move for White!    16...Bf7  17.e6  White wants to distract Black from h5.  17...Be8  .  Taking on e6 would lose to Bh5 first and then after ...Qf6 White wins material with Bg5!  18.Nf3  Rxc7  Black returns material to free up the position.  19.Bxc7  Qxe6  .   Material is equal but White's king looks a bit safer @@StartBracket@@for example on f1, queenside castling might be risky because of ...Qf6@@EndBracket@@. I think the entire line is complex and messy and this final position is not clear at all. Black will @@StartBracket@@as usual@@EndBracket@@ try to get ...e7-e5 in at some point to take control of a lot of central squares. Note that in this final position White doesn't win with Ng5 because of ...Qh6 and Black may take over. }
8. Qxh5+ Kd7 9. Qg4+ Ke8
{ This results in a draw by perpetual check after Qh5+.   9...e6  ,  with this move Black keeps the game going but it also involves some risk.  10.d5  ,  threatening mate in one with Qxe6.  10...Qe8  11.Bg5  Be7  ,  making sure that d8 is available for the king.  12.dxe6+  Kd8  ,  Black tries to win back the pawn on e6.  13.c5  White is using brute force to open the position and create squares for the f1-bishop.  13...Bxe6  ,  taking back the pawn by using the fact that the bishop on g5 will hang.    14.Qxe6  Bxg5  15.Qd5  .  This is still scary for Black: the bishop on g5 is attacked and the queen threatens to take on b7, while cxd6 is an option as well.  15...h6  16.Qxb7  e3  ,  Black is desperately seeking counterplay.  17.Nd5  Qc6  .  Without queens, most of the danger will be gone.  18.Ba6  exf2+  19.Kxf2  Qxb7  ,  Black gives up the rook on a8 but plans to win back the bishop so in total, it counts as an exchange sacrifice.  20.Bxb7  dxc5  21.Bxa8  c6  ,  attacking the knight and closing the way back for the bishop on a8.    22.Nc3  Kc7  ,  taking away the b7-square from the bishop and defending the pawn on c6 so the knight from b8 can come out.  23.Nf3  Na6  ,  finally the bishop on a8 is gone.  24.Bxc6  Kxc6  25.Nxg5  hxg5  .  It has been a long, complex line but we end with an equal endgame. A draw is a likely result considering the reduced material. Black should continue with bringing both the knight and rook to the center and prepare to attack the pawns on b2 and g2 because White can target the black pawn on g5. }
