[Black "Rare Setups − 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3
{ In this overview we will discuss systems that are linked to the London and Colle setups. In many of these lines, Black prepares the pawn push to e5 and then continues with ...g6-g5-g4, creating a dangerous kingside attack. One of the advantages of playing the Leningrad System is that there is no easy life for White in these setups compared to the Slav and all the Indian Defenses. This chapter also includes all the lines that can arise when White starts with d2-d4, c2-c4, and Nc3. }
2... Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. e3 g6 4. c4 { A rather rare continuation. } 4... Bg7 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Be2
{ The bishop is here better placed than on d3, but the move is not having any independent value, it will quickly become a position that is similar to another line in this chapter. }
6... a5
{ Preventing b2-b4 from White. Allowing b2-b4 could result in an exact transposition to the line with 4.b4, but I suggest we stop the white b-pawn for now. }
7. O-O b6
{ We continue to play in a similar fashion as if the pawn was on b4  (seethe other line)  and play a setup with ...b7-b6 and ...e7-e6. }
8. b3 Bb7 9. Bb2 e6
{ This position is an improved version for Black over the line with 4.b4. Here, White's pawn is only on b3, and therefore it will take a lot longer for White to create an initiative on the queenside. Meanwhile, Black's play is the same as in the other line: ...Qe7, ...d7-d6, and ...Nbd7 followed by either ...Ne4 or ...e6-e5. }
