[Black "Rare Setups − 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e3 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3
{ In this overview we will discuss systems that are linked to the London and Colle setups. In many of these lines, Black prepares the pawn push to e5 and then continues with ...g6-g5-g4, creating a dangerous kingside attack. One of the advantages of playing the Leningrad System is that there is no easy life for White in these setups compared to the Slav and all the Indian Defenses. This chapter also includes all the lines that can arise when White starts with d2-d4, c2-c4, and Nc3. }
2... Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. e3 g6 4. b4
{ This move doesn't happen often, but maybe it is a bit underestimated because Black needs to play precisely to maintain the balance. White's idea is to put one bishop on b2 and make it hard for Black to play ...e7-e5. The other bishop is going to e2, stating that from there it is more effective in White's queenside operations than on g2. Meanwhile, White has already grabbed space on that side with b2-b4. }
4... Bg7 5. Bb2 O-O 6. c4 b6
{ An alternative setup for Black I don't fully trust is  6...d6  7.Nbd2  Kh8  .  The idea of this move is to place the c8-bishop on g8, but it is quite passive.  8.Qc2  c6  ,  ensuring White cannot play d4-d5 when the bishop moves to e6.  9.a4  Be6  10.Be2  Nbd7  . Black has developed the pieces, but it is not clear how we can become active.  11.O-O  Bg8  12.b5  and White was clearly better in Peng-Nijboer, Enschede 2006. White has made clear progress on the queenside while Black hasn't achieved anything in the center nor on the kingside. }
7. Be2 Bb7
{ In many lines the bishop is not well placed on b7. The main purpose of playing ...b7-b6 is to hinder the white c-pawn. The rest of this line is an illustration of the issues Black faces after putting the bishop on b7. }
8. O-O e6
{ 8...c5  is a move you would like to play from a strategic point of view but after  9.bxc5  bxc5  10.d5  , White has a nice space advantage. }
9. Nc3 Qe7 { Black is preparing ...d7-d6 followed by ...e6-e5. } 10. Qb3 d6 11.
d5
{ Blocking the bishop on b7.   11.c5  is a standard advance but here it is less convincing:  11...Nbd7  12.cxd6  cxd6  .  It is not entirely clear what White has achieved by playing c4–c5.  13.Bc4  Rfe8  14.Rfc1  Kh8  .  A plan with ...h7-h6 first, ...Kh7, and then ...e6-e5 is a bit slow. White can put pressure on Black by playing Nc7, threatening to win an exchange.  15.Nb5  Nd5  and Blacks holds everything together thanks to the beautiful knight on d5.  It will be difficult for both sides to make a lot of progress, but Black can start pushing away the knight on b5 by playing ...a7-a6. Then it would be nice if we can also play ...b6-b5 followed by ...N7b6, so White may prevent this by playing a2-a4. }
11... e5 12. c5 bxc5
{ This is what Black should have played in a blitz game between Inarkiev-Cheparinov, Riyadh 2017. }
13. bxc5 Ba6
{ Black is just in time to exchange bishops and develop the knight before it would get locked in. }
14. c6 Bxe2 15. Nxe2 Na6
{ The last square left, but on its way to the beautiful c5-square. } 16. Ba3
Ne4 { Black really wants a knight on c5 and not a double pawn. } 17. Qc4 Nac5
{ White is better, especially after chasing away the knight on e4 with f2-f3, but the game is far from over. }
