2... Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. e3 g6 4. b4
{ This move doesn't happen often, but maybe it is a bit underestimated because Black needs to play precisely to maintain the balance. White's idea is to put one bishop on b2 and make it hard for Black to play ...e7-e5. The other bishop is going to e2, stating that from there it is more effective in White's queenside operations than on g2. Meanwhile, White has already grabbed space on that side with b2-b4. }
4... Bg7 5. Bb2 O-O 6. c4 e6
{ Because White has put maximum pressure on the e5-square, it makes sense to play for the light squares with ...e7-e6 and put the bishop on b7. After a later ...Qe7 and ...Nbd7, Black can still aim for ...e6-e5. }
7. Be2 Qe7
{ The idea to prepare ...e6-e5 is not great for Black.   And the natural move  7...a5  only helps White in gaining more space on the queenside:  8.b5  d6  9.O-O  Nbd7  10.Nc3  b6  11.Rc1  h6  12.Ba3  Re8  13.c5  . It feels like White has made more progress than Black. }
8. O-O d6 9. Nc3 Nbd7
{ Black has put everything in place for ...e6-e5 and White is ready for c4-c5. }
10. c5 e5 { And now White starts with two exchanges to open the position. } 11.
cxd6 cxd6 12. dxe5 dxe5 { Next, White starts playing for the light squares. }
13. Qb3+ Kh8 14. Ng5 { Threatening Ne6 and Black has only one way to defend. }
14... Nb6 15. Ba3
{ With a large advantage for White, threatening b4-b5 and the black pieces struggle to find good squares. The difference in the number of developed pieces between White and Black is a decisive factor. }
