{ This move doesn't happen often, but maybe it is a bit underestimated because Black needs to play precisely to maintain the balance. White's idea is to put one bishop on b2 and make it hard for Black to play ...e7-e5. The other bishop is going to e2, stating that from there it is more effective in White's queenside operations than on g2. Meanwhile, White has already grabbed space on that side with b2-b4. }
4... Bg7 5. Bb2 O-O 6. c4 e6
{ Because White has put maximum pressure on the e5-square, it makes sense to play for the light squares with ...e7-e6 and put the bishop on b7. After a later ...Qe7 and ...Nbd7, Black can still aim for ...e6-e5. }
7. Be2 b6
{ The idea of this move is to make c4-c5 less attractive for White, especially after ...d7-d6 is played, and potentially, to put the bishop on b7. }
8. Nc3 Qe7
{ We will first focus on playing for ...e6-e5, but  8...Bb7  is a valid alternative. }
9. Qb3 Nc6
{ This move is now possible because the knight has the d8-square. Sometimes even ...a5 is an option because, with the gain of tempo by attacking the queen, Black gets time to create play against the c4-pawn, for example by playing d7-d5 after ...Na5. }
10. Ba3 d6 11. O-O a6
{ In case White plays  12.b5  ,  the swap on b5 will result in increased activity for the rook on a8. }
12. Rac1 Nd8
{ A typical move for the Leningrad − this knight often ends up on f7. } 13. c5
b5
{ Considering White has blocked the a-pawn, meaning a2-a4 will take some time, this is a good move. }
14. d5 e5
{ It is a tense situation, Black is ready to play ...e5-e4 and/or ...f5-f4. }
15. Bb2 Nf7 { Preparing ...g6-g5. } 16. a4 bxa4 17. Nxa4 Rb8
{ Not only putting pressure on the b4-pawn but also ensuring there is no Nb6 from White after pawns are exchanged on d6. }
18. cxd6 cxd6
{ The position is a bit similar to a King's Indian, with sharp play for both sides. }
19. Rc6 Bb7 20. Rfc1 Bh6
{ Advancing the g-pawn is also an alternative but the greedy  20...Bxc6  is not advisable. After  21.dxc6  , White's passer on the  c-file is way too powerful and the pawn on a6 is hanging too.  Defending it with  21...Qa7  would not bring any relief since White has  22.Ng5  available, with more than enough compensation for the exchange. In fact, Black is close to losing. }
21. R1c2 f4
{ It is a messy situation but in a practical game, I think Black's chances are quite good, one mistake and the white king will be mated. }
