1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3
{ In this overview we will discuss systems that are linked to the London and Colle setups. In many of these lines, Black prepares the pawn push to e5 and then continues with ...g6-g5-g4, creating a dangerous kingside attack. One of the advantages of playing the Leningrad System is that there is no easy life for White in these setups compared to the Slav and all the Indian Defenses. This chapter also includes all the lines that can arise when White starts with d2-d4, c2-c4, and Nc3. }
2... Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. c4 d6 4. Nc3 g6 5. Bf4
{ White is going for a standard setup with bishops on f4 and e2 and in most cases, also with h2-h3. I will discuss also the lines where White refrains from h2-h3. }
5... Bg7 6. e3 O-O 7. Be2 Nc6 { Black is preparing ...e7-e5. } 8. d5
{ An aggressive move that is rarely seen because White players who go for this type of setup normally prefer more quiet play. Still, it is good to know how to respond with Black. }
8... e5 9. dxe6 Bxe6 10. c5
{ White has to be quick. If Black gets the chance to consolidate, we will probably have the better piece coordination. }
10... Nh5
{ An aggressive move to go after the pair of bishops, justified by the fact that Black is ahead in development.  10...dxc5  is playable but after  11.Ng5  Qe8  12.Bxc7  Rc8  13.Nxe6  Qxe6  14.Bg3  White might have a tiny edge. }
11. cxd6 Nxf4 12. exf4 Qxd6 13. Qxd6 cxd6 14. O-O h6
{ Chances are about equal, Black's bishops compensate for the weak d-pawn. Please note that this d-pawn could become strong if it can reach d4. }
