Rc1 Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 e5 { This was played in Aronian-Kamsky, Saint Louis 2013. }
14. dxe6 c6
{ Taking control over the square d5 and protecting the b7-pawn before recapturing on e6. }
15. b4 g5
{ Chasing away the bishop from f3 before there is a lot of pressure on the c6-pawn. }
16. b5 g4 17. Be2 Bxe6 18. bxc6 bxc6
{ White had a nice advantage, especially after continuing with the text move. }
19. Bd3 { In the game,  19.Qa4  was played. } 19... Rc8 20. Ne2
{ Putting pressure on the e6-bishop in combination with the pawn on f5. } 20...
Be5 21. Qc2 Qf6 22. Nf4 Rf7
{ Black has been able to hold the f5-pawn, but now White strikes on the other side. }
23. c5 d5 24. Qa4
{ White is clearly better, Black has some weaknesses on the queenside and the e6-bishop is passive. }
