[White "14. Rare Setups"]
[Black "Rare Setups − 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bf4 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3
{ In this overview we will discuss systems that are linked to the London and Colle setups. In many of these lines, Black prepares the pawn push to e5 and then continues with ...g6-g5-g4, creating a dangerous kingside attack. One of the advantages of playing the Leningrad System is that there is no easy life for White in these setups compared to the Slav and all the Indian Defenses. This chapter also includes all the lines that can arise when White starts with d2-d4, c2-c4, and Nc3. }
2... Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. Bf4 d6 4. e3 g6 5. h3
{ White creates a safe haven for the f4-bishop. These types of systems are common among amateur players who prefer similar setups with White regardless of how Black responds. }
5... Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O e6
{ Black starts preparing for ...e6-e5, but this is easier to accomplish with a queen on e7, so that's why we first push ...e6. }
8. Bh2 Nc6 9. Nbd2 Qe7 10. c3
{ Black has prepared everything for ...e6-e5 and we could have played that now with interesting play. However, in a top-level game, Black decided to play less straightforwardly. But it is sound so that is why I show it here. }
10... b6 11. b4 a5
{ Grabbing some space on the queenside. The move ...a7-a6 would not have helped because White has a2-a4 and soon the a-file will be open which is to White's advantage. }
12. Qb3
{ If White plays b4-b5, Black is happy to reroute the knight via d8 to f7. }
12... Bb7 13. a3
{ So far we have been following a rapid game between Aronian-Caruana, Zürich 2014, but here I prefer the text move. }
13... Nd8
{ Caruana played  13...h6  ,  which feels like a loss of tempo because once the d8-knight is on f7, we don't need ...h7-h6 to play ...g6-g5. }
14. c4
{ Without this advance, it is difficult to see how White can become active. }
14... Nf7 15. Rac1 axb4 16. axb4 g5
{ Again this advance, threatening to start attacking the white king. Next, Black can play ...Kh8, ...Ne4 and ...g5-g4 to start a serious attack. The engine says it is equal, but Black's position seems easier to play. }
*

