1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Nf3
{ In this overview we will discuss systems that are linked to the London and Colle setups. In many of these lines, Black prepares the pawn push to e5 and then continues with ...g6-g5-g4, creating a dangerous kingside attack. One of the advantages of playing the Leningrad System is that there is no easy life for White in these setups compared to the Slav and all the Indian Defenses. This chapter also includes all the lines that can arise when White starts with d2-d4, c2-c4, and Nc3. }
2... Nf6
{ I prefer to first develop the knight and take control over the e4-square and play ...d7-d6 later. }
3. Bf4 d6 4. e3 g6 5. h3
{ White creates a safe haven for the f4-bishop. These types of systems are common among amateur players who prefer similar setups with White regardless of how Black responds. }
5... Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O e6
{ Black starts preparing for ...e6-e5, but this is easier to accomplish with a queen on e7, so that's why we first push ...e6. }
8. Bh2 Nc6 9. Nbd2 Qe7 10. c3
{ Black has prepared everything for ...e6-e5 and we could have played that now with interesting play. However, in a top-level game, Black decided to play less straightforwardly. But it is sound so that is why I show it here. }
10... Kh8
{ An alternative with a similar type of play is ...Kh8, stepping aside from the a2-g8 diagonal where either a white queen or bishop could be bothering the black king. }
11. b4 Nd8 { On its way to f7 where it supports both ...e6-e5 and ...g6-g5. }
12. c4 Nf7 13. c5
{ It is remarkable that White is worse in many lines if c4-c5 is not played. But not many players may play like this in a practical game because why would they advance the c-pawn if they have first lost a tempo by playing c2-c3 instead of c2-c4? In my experience, White players who play a setup with c2-c3 prefer to keep that pawn on c3 for a long time, to support the pawn on d4. }
13... g5 14. Rc1 e5
{ This type of position, with a knight on f7 and pawns on g5 and e5, is a common theme. Black is fine here. }
