1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. h3
{ Preparing g2-g4. Some lines transpose to the2.g4 lines with a later h2-h3. }
2... Nf6 3. g4 d5 4. c4
{ This is almost always answered by either  4...c6  or  4...e6  . The latter is not good here because of  5.gxf5  . }
4... c6 5. Nc3 fxg4 6. Bf4 g3
{ Taking on h3 would weaken the light squares too much in Black's camp. } 7.
Bxg3 Qb6 8. Qd2 Bf5 9. Nf3 e6 10. c5
{ Ensuring there is no more ...Bb4 for Black. } 10... Qd8 11. Nh4 Be7
{ It can look a bit scary to keep the bishop on f5, but in fact, after White takes, Black has still great control over the e4-square. }
12. Nxf5 exf5 13. Bg2 O-O 14. O-O Nbd7 15. Qc2 g6
{ And Black is completely fine as all our pieces will find good squares. The knight can come to e4 almost forcing the bishop to drop back to h2 because if Black can take there that would yield a weak pawn on g3. After the bishop is on h2, Black can play ...Bh4, ...Qg5 and the d7-knight can be rerouted to f6, resulting in a dangerous kingside attack.  If White decides to take the knight on e4 with the knight on c3, Black will play ...fxe4, offer a bishop exchange on h4, and again the queen can come to h4 or g5 and the d7-knight to f6. }
*

