1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. h3
{ Preparing g2-g4. Some lines transpose to the2.g4 lines with a later h2-h3. }
2... Nf6 3. g4 d5 4. g5 { A rare move and Black has a great counter. } 4... Ne4
5. Bf4 { A natural move which fails here. } 5... h6 6. gxh6 g5
{ Another punch. } 7. Bh2 c5 { And again Black attacks White's position. } 8.
e3 Rxh6
{ Much stronger than taking with the bishop. The rook keeps an eye on the h3-pawn and prevents Qh5+. }
9. f3 Qa5+ { The main idea is to protect the pawn on c5. } 10. c3 Nd6
{ Look how handy the rook on h6 is, protecting the knight on d6 and ready to recapture if White would play Bxd6. }
11. Bd3 Nc6 12. Nd2 Qb6 13. Qc2
{ The knight on g1 can still not be developed, it needs to keep an eye on the h3-pawn. }
13... c4 14. Bf1 e5
{ It feels like colors reversed: Black has gained a lot of space and soon will castle queenside and continue the central attack. Black has a clear advantage. }
*

