1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. h3
{ Preparing g2-g4. Some lines transpose to the2.g4 lines with a later h2-h3. }
2... Nf6 3. g4 d5 4. g5 { A rare move and Black has a great counter. } 4... Ne4
5. Nf3 c5 { Immediately putting White under pressure. } 6. Bg2 cxd4
{ Taking on d4 before White can take back with a pawn is a sensible idea. Black has good chances now to push ...e7-e5. }
7. O-O Nc6 8. Nxd4 e5 9. Nxc6 bxc6
{ I would always prefer Black here: what is that pawn on g5 doing anyway? } 10.
c4 { White's only chance is to quickly generate some activity. } 10... Be6 11.
cxd5 cxd5 12. Qa4+ Kf7 { The king is comepletely safe here. } 13. Nc3 Bc5
{ Creating ideas with ...Nxf2 or ...Ng3 in combination with ...Qb6. } 14. Nxe4
fxe4 15. h4 Qe7
{ Black is better in many ways − we can attack the pawn on g5 with ...h7-h6 while the rooks can be centralized. We can also create a passed d-pawn with ...d5-d4-d3. Another plan involves placing a rook on f8, moving the king to g8, and start attacking f2. }
*

