1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. h3
{ Preparing g2-g4. Some lines transpose to the2.g4 lines with a later h2-h3. }
2... Nf6 3. g4 d5 4. Bf4 c5 5. e3
{ White is trying to maintain the center under control, but now the g4-pawn becomes a liability. }
5... Nc6
{ Black makes it unattractive for White to take on c5 because ...e7-e5 would be strong. }
6. Nc3 cxd4 7. exd4 fxg4
{ White would like to put the knight on f3 and then jump to e5, but as long as there is a black pawn or bishop on g4, this will be hard to achieve. }
8. Qd2 g6
{ The bishop can be quite strong on g7 because it is not easy for White to defend the pawn on d4. }
9. O-O-O Bg7 10. hxg4 Bxg4
{ White doesn't have time to create anything on the light squares with a bishop on d3 and a knight on e5. That plan is just too slow. }
11. f3 Bf5 12. Bh3 Qd7
{ Ensuring that the queen can take back on f5 to maintain control over the light squares. }
13. Be5 O-O-O 14. Kb1 Ne8 15. Bxf5 Qxf5 16. f4 h5
{ Black is a pawn up and has a passed h-pawn which will be dangerous in any endgame. }
*

