[White "15. Korchnoi Attack 2.h3"]
[Black "Korchnoi Attack 2.h3 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. h3
{ Preparing g2-g4. Some lines transpose to the2.g4 lines with a later h2-h3. }
2... Nf6 3. g4 d5 4. Qd3
{ Although this position has arisen quite a few times in practice, the engine disapproves and gives Black already some advantage. }
4... c5
{ This direct attack on the white center is stronger than  4...Nc6  , but even that move promises Black an edge. }
5. Bf4 Nc6
{ Black could also have played  5...Qb6  ,  but I find it more natural to first develop the knight. Moving the f6-knight to e4 is likely to transpose to the line with 5...Nc6 and then 6...Ne4. }
6. e3 Ne4 7. Nc3 c4 8. Qd1 e5
{ We see the same idea, in combination with ...Bb4. } 9. dxe5 Bb4 10. Ne2 fxg4
{ 10...Qa5  11.Bg2  is not good for Black because the pin on the c3-knight doesn't bring anything. The white king simply moves away to f1 and the pawn on d5 gets under heavy pressure.    11...Nxc3  12.bxc3  Bxc3+  13.Nxc3  Qxc3+  14.Kf1  and Black is in trouble. The pawn on d5 will be lost soon.  Note that  14...Be6  is answered by  15.gxf5  and our king is in danger. On top of that, White's bishop pair is stronger than Black's two minor pieces. }
11. a3 Ba5 12. Bg2 gxh3
{ A rare occasion when taking on h3 is a good idea. Black ends up with an extra pawn. White cannot create any play on the light squares, the bishop on g2 will be traded and the white queen cannot do any harm at the moment. }
13. Bxh3 Bxh3 14. Rxh3 Qd7
{ Keep on attacking, speed is important here in order to take advantage of Black's lead in development! }
15. Rh1
{ 15.Rh2  g5  16.Bg3  h5  , Black is winning. The bishop is in trouble, the king cannot find safety and White has no constructive moves. }
15... g5 16. Bh2 Rf8
{ And Black is winning. White is out of moves, cannot complete development, and the king cannot hide either, while Black has ideas like ...Qh3-g2. }
