[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Qd3
{ Maybe not fashionable but it does have some venom. White wants to prove that Black has weakened the light squares by playing 1...f5 and the idea is that by first playing Qd3, White keeps the option open to continue with either e2-e4, g2-g4, or even first h2-h3 and then g2-g4. }
2... e6
{ I don't fully trust this move.   Also after  2...g6  , White can already claim some advantage, a sample line:  3.h4  Nf6  4.h5  Bg7  , Black is not doing much against White's plan of attacking  the pawn on g6.  5.hxg6  hxg6  6.Rxh8+  Bxh8  7.Qg3  and White has already a clear advantage.  Black can only defend the g6-pawn by playing ...Kf7, but the king is quite vulnerable there.   2...Nc6  is rarely played and it could be used as a surprise weapon. I give one line that illustrates the most critical setup from White's side:  3.Bg5  ,  preventing ...Nf6 because a double f-pawn would not be great for Black in this position.  3...d6  ,  threatening ...e7-e5.  4.Nc3  h6  5.Bd2  e5  6.d5  Nce7  7.g4  . This pawn sacrifice is the most critical way of playing this position.   7...fxg4  8.h3  Nf6  ,  giving back the pawn with ...g4-g3, a standard option in many of these lines, is not correct because White plays fxg3 and at some point, g3-g4, limiting the power of the c8-bishop.  9.hxg4  Bxg4  10.Bg5  .  Black was planning to play ...g7-g6, which is now prevented.  10...Rg8  11.Bxf6  gxf6  12.O-O-O  and this position is a little better for White. It is not so easy for Black to castle queenside because after  12...Qd7  ,  the bishop on g4 may get in trouble after f2-f3. }
3. g4 fxg4 4. h3 g3 5. Qxg3
{ I feel Black's position has more weaknesses than White's. } 5... Nc6 6. Nf3
Nf6 7. Rg1 d5
{ Blocking the center to slow down White's initiative, but the pawn on e6 is not great and is seriously limiting the power of the c8-bishop. }
8. Nc3 Ne4 { Black is going for complications. } 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Bg5 Qd5
{ Only move as  10...Be7  would be met by  11.Bxe7  Qxe7  12.Nd2  Nxd4  13.O-O-O  , Black is behind in development and with many weaknesses to look after. }
11. Nd2 Nxd4 { 11...Bd6  is answered by  12.Bf4  . } 12. Qxc7 Bd7 13. c4 Qc6
{ Black has to exchange queens to reduce the pressure. } 14. Qxc6 Bxc6 15.
O-O-O
{ Black is suffering due to the weaknesses in the pawn structure and the king is not safe either. }
*

