[White "16. Manhattan Variation 2.Qd3"]
[Black "Manhattan Variation 2.Qd3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Qd3
{ Maybe not fashionable but it does have some venom. White wants to prove that Black has weakened the light squares by playing 1...f5 and the idea is that by first playing Qd3, White keeps the option open to continue with either e2-e4, g2-g4, or even first h2-h3 and then g2-g4. }
2... d5
{ Black maintains control over the e4-square and goes for a Stonewall type of setup. Note that if White now plays  3.g4  , wetranspose to the line with 2.g4 followed by 3.Qd3. }
3. g3 { A rather slow move after which we get some form of the Stonewall. }
3... Nf6 4. Bg2 e6 5. c4 Bd6 { 5...c6  first is also fine. } 6. Nf3 O-O 7. O-O
c6 8. b3 Nbd7
{ Preventing the bishop exchange on a3 with  8...Qe7  is also a valid option. If White then plays  9.a4  , Black can still prevent the exchange by  9...Na6  ,  with the option of playing ...Nb4. }
9. Ba3
{ Many players try hard to exchange the dark-squared bishop, but I am not convinced it will bring White anything. In an old article in one of Dvoretsky's books, Vladimir Kramnik already noted that White's 'good' bishop on g2 is in fact not so great because it bites on granite with the pawn on d5. }
9... Bxa3 10. Nxa3 Qe7 11. Nc2 b6
{ In many Stonewall lines, the c8-bishop ends up on a6 or b7. } 12. cxd5 cxd5
13. Nce1 a5 14. Qd2 Ba6 15. Nd3 Rfc8
{ Black has no problems, all the pieces are active and the only weakness, the e6-pawn, cannot be touched by White. }
