1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. Qd3
{ Maybe not fashionable but it does have some venom. White wants to prove that Black has weakened the light squares by playing 1...f5 and the idea is that by first playing Qd3, White keeps the option open to continue with either e2-e4, g2-g4, or even first h2-h3 and then g2-g4. }
2... d5
{ Black maintains control over the e4-square and goes for a Stonewall type of setup. Note that if White now plays  3.g4  , wetranspose to the line with 2.g4 followed by 3.Qd3. }
3. c4 e6 { A standard move, protecting the pawn on d5. } 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. g3 Be7
{ An alternative setup, but  5...c6  followed by ...Bd6 is also fine for Black. }
6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Ne4
{ The idea is to first block the g2-bishop and then continue with ...b7-b6 to create space for the c8-bishop. }
8. Nc3 b6
{ Always an option when the white bishop is on g2 − the one thing to watch out for is that we don't want White to put a rook quickly on c1 and a knight on e5 and then move that knight to c6. Here, this would take too much time with the bishop still on c1 and the knight on c3 in the way. }
9. Ne5 Bb7 10. Bf4 Nd7
{ Developing the knight to d7 is more natural than to a6 where after a2-a3 it would be misplaced. }
11. Rfd1 g5
{ Gaining space on the kingside is a standard plan for Black in these types of Stonewall setups. }
12. Nxd7 Qxd7 13. Be5 Bd6
{ We have reached a complex position where Black has sufficient counterplay. We threaten to take on e5 and attack the pawn with ...Qg7, and if White takes on d6 we can recapture with the queen and aim for ...c7-c5 next. }
*

