[Black "Krejcik Gambit 2.g4 d5 3.g5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g4
{ An aggressive pawn sacrifice that cannot be underestimated. Some variations transpose to the 2.h3 lines. }
2... d5 { Taking on g4 is also asound option and it is discussed later on. } 3.
g5 { The idea of this move is to cramp Black's position. } 3... c5
{ Black needs to play actively to compensate for the lack of space on the kingside. }
4. dxc5 e6 5. a3 Bxc5 { Black has to take before White can play b2-b4. } 6. b4
Bd6 7. Nf3
{ White needs to first protect the pawn on g5 before developing the bishop on b2. }
7... Ne7
{ Black is just completing development by placing the knights on e7 and c6, followed by short castling. }
8. Bb2 O-O 9. c4
{ White has to attack the black center, otherwise, the position is too passive. }
9... Nbc6 10. Nbd2
{ Black has one problematic piece and that is the bishop on c8. A good option is to play ...a7-a6, take on c4 if the bishop from f1 moves to g2, and play later ...b7-b5 after having played ...Bd6-c7.  If White plays e2-e3 and protects the pawn on c4 with the bishop, Black should not take on c4 because with a bishop on c4, the pawn on e6 would be weak. So instead of taking on c4 Black can consider playing ...b7-b6 and putting the bishop on b7. }
10... a6 11. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Much stronger than taking back with the pawn on d5 after which Black's structure with the isolated pawn on d5 and the pawn on f5 blocking the bishop on c8 would be far from ideal. }
12. Rc1 Bd7
{ Considering White has opened the c-file, it is not easy for Black to play ...b7-b5 followed by ...Bb7. }
13. h4 b5
{ And Black is clearly better because the white king cannot find safety. } *

