[White "17. Krejcik Gambit 2.g4"]
[Black "Krejcik Gambit 2.g4 d5 3.Qd3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g4
{ An aggressive pawn sacrifice that cannot be underestimated. Some variations transpose to the 2.h3 lines. }
2... d5 { Taking on g4 is also asound option and it is discussed later on. } 3.
Qd3 { Increasing the pressure on f5. } 3... g6
{ Further on, I am offering analternative for Black,  3...e5  , which lands on unexplored territory but, according to my analysis, it is fully playable. }
4. gxf5
{ This is an old line where nowadays, thanks to the engines, we know Black will be better if White takes the pawn on b7. }
4... Bxf5 5. Qb5+ Nc6 6. Qxb7
{ This pawn capture is just bad but we have to know the right sequence for Black. }
6... Nxd4 7. Na3 Rb8 8. Qxa7 e5
{ Black is not playing for a direct refutation but claiming that the lead in development combined with a strong pawn center and more active pieces will gain a large advantage. }
9. Nf3 Nc6
{ It is much stronger to keep the pieces on the board and not take on f3 or c2. In this way, Black defends the pawn on e5, attacks the queen, and keeps the option of a later ...e5-e4 open. }
10. Qa4 Bd7 11. Bg5 Nf6
{ Black prefers to develop the knight and only then the bishop. If we put the bishop on e7, White is happy to exchange, while now White would have to take on f6, giving up the pair of bishops. }
12. c3 Bd6
{ Black has many good moves here including taking on b2, but there is nothing wrong with continuing to develop pieces. }
13. Bh3
{ I don't think a lot of players will find this move, based on the fact that if Black takes on h3, the knight on c6 gets lost. }
13... O-O 14. Bxd7 Qxd7 15. Bxf6 Rxf6
{ And Black has fantastic compensation. A sample line:  16.b4  e4  17.Nd4  Be5  18.Nac2  Qh3  , getting closer to the white king.  19.e3  Bxd4  20.cxd4  Nxb4  . Accidents were waiting to happen!  21.Nxb4  Rxf2  22.Kxf2  Rf8+  23.Ke2  Qg2+  and game over. }
