1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g4
{ An aggressive pawn sacrifice that cannot be underestimated. Some variations transpose to the 2.h3 lines. }
2... d5 { Taking on g4 is also asound option and it is discussed later on. } 3.
Qd3 { Increasing the pressure on f5. } 3... g6
{ Further on, I am offering analternative for Black,  3...e5  , which lands on unexplored territory but, according to my analysis, it is fully playable. }
4. g5 { Again, White is trying to cramp Black's position. } 4... Bg7 5. h4 c5
{ Black has to counterattack, we cannot just sit and wait while White gains space on the kingside. }
6. h5 Nc6 7. dxc5 e5
{ If White now plays h5-h6, the bishop returns to f8, threatening to take on c5. Meanwhile, Black has a nice center. }
8. Nc3
{ If White takes  8.hxg6  , Black first plays  8...e4  and  only after the white queen moves, Black recaptures on g6. The reason is that if Black first takes back on g6, White will swap rooks on h8, and if then later Black attacks the white queen with ...e5-e4, this queen can go to h3 with tempo because it attacks the bishop on h8. By first playing ...e5-e4 and only then recapturing on g6, Black eliminates this option for White. }
8... e4 9. Qd2 Nge7
{ According to the engine, this is still about equal, but in a practical game it feels like Black is on top with the lead in development and space advantage. }
