1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g4
{ An aggressive pawn sacrifice that cannot be underestimated. Some variations transpose to the 2.h3 lines. }
2... d5 { Taking on g4 is also asound option and it is discussed later on. } 3.
Qd3 { Increasing the pressure on f5. } 3... e5
{ This is a second alternative that I give, which is fully playable. It has hardly been played in practice and the following lines are all my own analysis. If you like unexplored territory, then you may prefer this line over established theory. }
4. dxe5 Nc6 5. gxf5 { White will have temporarily an extra pawn on f5. } 5...
Nxe5 6. Qg3 Nf7
{ The square f7 is almost always a logical square for the knight in the Leningrad System, but here even more so. Later on, White cannot take with the queen on g7 because, after Rg8, the queen cannot escape via h6 due to the f7-knight. }
7. Bh3
{ If White doesn't defend the pawn on f5, Black will take it at some point. }
7... Nf6 8. Nc3 c5 { Taking space before White can stabilize the position. } 9.
Bd2 Bd6 10. Qg2
{ White cannot take  10.Qxg7  because after  10...Rg8  , the queen is lost. }
10... d4 11. Ne4 O-O 12. O-O-O Bd7
{ It is okay to give up the pair of bishops in order to complete development and win back the f5-pawn. }
13. Nxd6 Nxd6 14. Nf3 Bxf5
{ Black has won back the pawn and what remains is a sharp position. White quickly needs to develop an initiative along the g-file in combination with targeting the d4-pawn @@StartBracket@@by playing e2-e3@@EndBracket@@ because long-term, Black has the better chances with the healthy pawn structure and space advantage, }
