1. d4 f5
{ This course is based on 1...f5. Depending on your lines against 1.e4, you could also follow most of our repertoire with  1...d6  and  2.--  f5  . It means that against 1.e4 it is OK to play for example the Modern Defense or the Pirc or certain variations of the Philidor. }
2. g4
{ An aggressive pawn sacrifice that cannot be underestimated. Some variations transpose to the 2.h3 lines. }
2... fxg4
{ Taking on g4 is also a sound option, but always with the idea to return the pawn on g3 once White plays h2-h3. }
3. h3 g3 4. fxg3
{ And now Black wants to develop the pieces and castle, preferably queenside, where the king is safer than on the kingside. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 d5
{ It is important to prevent White from playing e2-e4, so ...d7-d5 would also have been played if White would have gone Bg2 instead of Nc3. }
6. Bg5 Nc6 7. e3 e6 8. Nge2
{ White needs to watch the pawn on g3 because after Black's ...Bd6 it is not easy to defend g3. If White would drop back the bishop to f4 we can always hit it by ...g7-g5, either directly or after ...h7-h6. }
8... Bd7 { Preparing queenside castling. } 9. Nf4
{ Note that Black should not play  9...h6  because White will play  10.Bxf6  followed by Qh5+. }
9... Qe7 10. Qd2 O-O-O 11. O-O-O Kb8
{ Black is OK and is likely to play ...Be8 followed by ...h7-h6, gaining the pair of bishops. Once d5 is sufficiently protected, the advance ...e6-e5 is a serious option. }
