[Result "*"]

1. g3 f5
{ Many other moves are possible, but we want to stick to typical Leningrad System play, if possible. }
2. Bg2 Nf6 3. d3
{ White is preparing e2-e4 and Black normally responds by taking on e4 @@StartBracket@@to lock in the bishop on g2@@EndBracket@@ and play ...e7-e5 to grab some space in the center. }
3... d6 4. c4
{ White decided on a typical setup from the English opening and this position can also arise from the 1.c4 move order. }
4... g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. e3
{ This is a modest move with the intention to increase the central pressure with d3-d4 at a later stage. }
6... O-O 7. Nge2 c6
{ There are different ways of playing this position with Black, but I try to stay close to the plans we know from the main lines of the Leningrad System. }
8. O-O a5
{ Considering White 'forgot' to play b2-b4 before castling, we may as well block this option for now. }
9. b3 e5 { Grabbing space in the center is always a good idea. } 10. Ba3 Na6
{ This knight can go to b4 in certain lines, reducing the pressure on d6. } 11.
Qd2 Nb4 12. Rad1 Qe7
{ It is important to put the queen on e7: White often wants to play d3-d4-d5 followed by Nf4 and then Ne6. With the queen on e7, white must sacrifice a pawn to place the knight on e6. }
13. d4 e4
{ This is the standard reaction when White plays d3-d4. The alternative of maintaining the tension in the center is usually not advisable because White will take on e5 followed by Qd6, infiltrating in Black's position. }
14. d5 c5
{ The position is still equal but could easily slip in Black’s favor if White doesn’t play precisely. Black is ready to occupy more space with ...g6-g5 followed by action on the kingside, but we can even consider in the medium term to play ...Bd7 followed by ...a5-a4. }
15. Nf4 g5 16. Ne6
{ Not a blunder, White will get compensation for the sacrificed pawn because of the weak pawn on d6. }
16... Bxe6 17. dxe6 Qxe6 18. Qxd6 { A greedy pawn capture. } 18... Qxd6 19.
Rxd6 Ne8
{ White loses material with the double attack on the rook and knight. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. English &  Réti Setups"]
[Black "English Setups − 1.g3 with 4.c4 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. g3 f5
{ Many other moves are possible, but we want to stick to typical Leningrad System play, if possible. }
2. Bg2 Nf6 3. d3
{ White is preparing e2-e4 and Black normally responds by taking on e4 @@StartBracket@@to lock in the bishop on g2@@EndBracket@@ and play ...e7-e5 to grab some space in the center. }
3... d6 4. c4
{ White decided on a typical setup from the English opening and this position can also arise from the 1.c4 move order. }
4... g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. e3
{ This is a modest move with the intention to increase the central pressure with d3-d4 at a later stage. }
6... O-O 7. Nge2 c6
{ There are different ways of playing this position with Black, but I try to stay close to the plans we know from the main lines of the Leningrad System. }
8. O-O a5
{ Considering White 'forgot' to play b2-b4 before castling, we may as well block this option for now. }
9. b3 e5 { Grabbing space in the center is always a good idea. } 10. Ba3 Na6
{ This knight can go to b4 in certain lines, reducing the pressure on d6. } 11.
Qd2 Nb4 12. Rad1 Qe7
{ It is important to put the queen on e7: White often wants to play d3-d4-d5 followed by Nf4 and then Ne6. With the queen on e7, white must sacrifice a pawn to place the knight on e6. }
13. d4 e4
{ This is the standard reaction when White plays d3-d4. The alternative of maintaining the tension in the center is usually not advisable because White will take on e5 followed by Qd6, infiltrating in Black's position. }
14. d5 c5
{ The position is still equal but could easily slip in Black’s favor if White doesn’t play precisely. Black is ready to occupy more space with ...g6-g5 followed by action on the kingside, but we can even consider in the medium term to play ...Bd7 followed by ...a5-a4. }
15. Nf4 g5 16. Ne6
{ Not a blunder, White will get compensation for the sacrificed pawn because of the weak pawn on d6. }
16... Bxe6 17. dxe6 Qxe6 18. Nb5 Rad8 19. f3
{ White has to be quick, if Black gets the chance to consolidate, we will be a real pawn up. }
19... d5
{ Of course Black wants to get rid of the weak d6-pawn and support the pawn on e4. }
20. Bxb4 axb4 21. Nc7
{ A funny attack to increase the pressure on the d5-pawn. } 21... Qe5 22. Nxd5
Nxd5 23. cxd5 { White has won the pawn back. } 23... exf3 24. Rxf3
{ But Black has an eye on the new weakness − the pawn on e3. } 24... g4 25. Rf2
{ On  25.Rf4  Black would also have played  25...Bh6  . } 25... Bh6 26. Kh1
Bxe3 { Only capturing a pawn, but an important one! } 27. Re2
{ White doesn't lose an exchange. } 27... Bxd2 28. Rxe5 Bc3 29. Re6 Kg7
{ Black is a pawn up and although the position is still close to equal because of the opposite-colored bishops, it is not a draw yet. Black can play on two sides: prepare ...f5-f4 or play for ...b7-b5 followed by ...c5-c4. And if White plays passively, Black can even attack the a2-pawn with ...Ra8. }
