[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. English &  Réti Setups"]
[Black "English Setups − 1.g3 with 4.c4 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. g3 f5
{ Many other moves are possible, but we want to stick to typical Leningrad System play, if possible. }
2. Bg2 Nf6 3. d3
{ White is preparing e2-e4 and Black normally responds by taking on e4 @@StartBracket@@to lock in the bishop on g2@@EndBracket@@ and play ...e7-e5 to grab some space in the center. }
3... d6 4. c4
{ White decided on a typical setup from the English opening and this position can also arise from the 1.c4 move order. }
4... g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. e4
{ The so-called Botvinnik setup in the English, a system that a lot of White players who play the English will follow. }
6... fxe4
{ A standard response − we want to take early so that White is inclined to take the pawn back with the d-pawn and not with a piece, locking in the bishop on g2. If Black waits, White may take on f5, opening the long diagonal for the g2-bishop. }
7. dxe4 O-O 8. Nge2 c5
{ Black wants to have the pawns on c5 and e5 and then play ...Nd4. If we start with ...e5 and then play ...c5 Black gets attacked by Nb5 and there is no ...Nd4 because the knight is still on b8. So the way to go is first ...c5, then ...Nc6 and then ...e5. }
9. O-O Nc6 10. h3 a6
{ Immediately playing  10...e5  followed by ...Nd4 is also fine. The idea of ...a7-a6 is to prevent Nb5 and prepare a later ...b7-b5, but the move order can be reversed. }
11. Be3 e5 { Full control over the d4-square. } 12. Nd5 Nd4 13. Nec3 Nxd5
{ The knight on f6 is not very active and by exchanging on d5 it becomes easier for Black to push ...b7-b5. }
14. Nxd5
{ White can also take with a pawn on d5, but it doesn’t make a big difference for Black: the bishop on g2 is not becoming active anytime soon and Black will still continue to prepare ...b7-b5. }
14... b5 15. b3 Be6
{ Black has reached a comfortable position. The only minor thing is that the bishop on g7 is not active, but maybe Black can exchange it in the future with ...Bf6-g5 @@StartBracket@@no problem if White takes with the knight on f6 because exchanging minor pieces can mean White will end up with a silly bishop on g2@@EndBracket@@, or with ...h7-h5 followed by ...Kh7 and ...Bh6. }
