[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. English &  Réti Setups"]
[Black "Réti Setups − 1.g3 without c4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. g3 f5
{ Many other moves are possible, but we want to stick to typical Leningrad System play, if possible. }
2. Bg2 Nf6 3. d3
{ White is preparing e2-e4 and Black normally responds by taking on e4 @@StartBracket@@to lock in the bishop on g2@@EndBracket@@ and play ...e7-e5 to grab some space in the center. }
3... d6 4. e4
{ A rare move − the characteristics of the position will resemble a 1.e4 e5 opening soon with a strange bishop on g2 and Black being happy to have exchanged the f-pawn so later we can start action on the f-file. }
4... fxe4 5. dxe4 e5 { Blocking the bishop on g2 behind the e4-pawn. } 6. Ne2
Be7
{ Black continues to develop and castle kingside. Castling queenside is normally not a good idea in these lines because White can easily push the queenside pawns forward and generate a dangerous attack. }
7. O-O O-O 8. Nbc3 c6
{ Preventing White's knight jumps to d5, which would yield a nice space advantage. }
9. h3 Be6 { Black continues with normal development. } 10. f4 Nbd7 11. Be3
{ Important to notice is that after  11.f5  , Black has  11...Bc4  . } 11... b5
{ The position is about equal. White may want to expand on the kingside, Black on the queenside, but even if White moves forward with the f- and g-pawns, there is no mate in sight so no need for Black to be scared. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. English &  Réti Setups"]
[Black "Réti Setups − 1.g3 without c4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. g3 f5
{ Many other moves are possible, but we want to stick to typical Leningrad System play, if possible. }
2. Bg2 Nf6 3. d3
{ White is preparing e2-e4 and Black normally responds by taking on e4 @@StartBracket@@to lock in the bishop on g2@@EndBracket@@ and play ...e7-e5 to grab some space in the center. }
3... d6 4. e4
{ A rare move − the characteristics of the position will resemble a 1.e4 e5 opening soon with a strange bishop on g2 and Black being happy to have exchanged the f-pawn so later we can start action on the f-file. }
4... fxe4 5. dxe4 e5 { Blocking the bishop on g2 behind the e4-pawn. } 6. Ne2
Be7
{ Black continues to develop and castle kingside. Castling queenside is normally not a good idea in these lines because White can easily push the queenside pawns forward and generate a dangerous attack. }
7. O-O O-O 8. Nbc3 c6
{ Preventing White's knight jumps to d5, which would yield a nice space advantage. }
9. h3 Be6 { Black continues with normal development. } 10. f4 Nbd7 11. a4 h6
{ And now the advance of the g-pawn, even all the way to g4, could be really bad for White. Black may take on f4  (or even if White has played f4-f5 at some point, Black will still try to get the bishop to g5)  followed by ...Bg5, for example by playing ...Ne5, ...Nfd7 and ...Bg5, taking control over the dark squares. }
12. Be3 Qc7 13. Qd2 Rad8
{ Protecting the pawn on d6 so that the bishop on e7 can move and maybe someday Black can play ...d6-d5. }
14. a5 b5
{ A strong counter on the queenside, we don't want to give White more space. }
15. axb6 axb6 16. g4 Nh7
{ Black is at least equal. If White becomes too ambitious by, for example, playing f4-f5, the square g5 will be weak and if White isn't careful, Black will play ...d6-d5 and have a massive center. }
