1. Nf3 f5 2. d3
{ This line became popular because Magnus Carlsen won convincingly against a much stronger opponent in only 19 moves. Many years since then have passed and nowadays it is not a big problem for Black anymore. }
2... d6
{ I like this move a lot better than  2...Nc6  after which White can play the tricky  3.d4  .  After 2...d6 it doesn't make sense for White to play d3-d4, because that would transpose to a main line of the Leningrad while being a full tempo down. }
3. e4 e5
{ The standard reaction, when White plays e2-e4, Black usually plays ...e7-e5. Because the white bishop is still on f1, Black doesn't take on e4 first. We would only do that if the bishop is on g2, so the bishop would be locked behind the e4-pawn. }
4. Nc3 Nc6
{ 4...Be7  is not great because Black doesn't take control over the square d4.  5.d4  fxe4  6.Nxe4  d5  ,  at least Black should have played ...Nf6 here, but even then White has a clear advantage.  7.Neg5  Black is in big trouble with the exposed king.  7...exd4  8.Bd3  Qd6  9.Nxd4  and White was winning in Svidler-Bu, Tbilisi 2017. Black's king is not safe and the pieces don't coordinate well. }
5. exf5 Nge7
{ A key move.  5...Bxf5  was played in the famous game between a young Magnus Carlsen and Dolmatov, which resulted in a crushing win for White.  6.d4  Nxd4  7.Nxd4  exd4  8.Qxd4  Nf6  9.Bc4  c6  10.Bg5  b5  11.Bb3  Be7  12.O-O-O  Qd7  13.Rhe1  Kd8  14.Rxe7  Qxe7  15.Qf4  Bd7  16.Ne4  d5  17.Nxf6  h6  18.Bh4  g5  19.Qd4  1-0 Carlsen-Dolmatov, Moscow 2004. }
6. g4 { A strange move but it defends the pawn on f5, so we need to check it. }
6... h5 { We don't want to keep the pawn on f5 alive for too long. } 7. gxh5
Nxf5
{ 7...Bxf5  is also an option, but I  prefer to keep control over the square d4. }
8. Rg1 Be7
{ Another advantage of ...Nxf5 is that the knight defends the pawn on g7, so ...Be7 is possible. }
9. Nd5 Be6 10. Bh3 Rf8
{ Not just defending the knight, the half-open f-file could become a problem for White. }
11. Nxe7 Qxe7 12. c3
{ White immediately wants to take control over the d4-square. } 12... Nh4
{ A tricky move, attacking both the knight on f3 and the bishop on h3. } 13.
Nxh4 Qxh4 { Black is threatening mate on f2. } 14. Rg3 Qf6
{ Threatening mate in f2 again.   14...Bxh3  is not good for Black because after White's  15.Bg5  , the queen is lost. Black can then still escape to an endgame, but the position is clearly worse. }
15. Be3
{ Now that f2 is protected, White is threatening to win a piece with Rg6, so Black has to take on h3. }
15... Bxh3 16. Rxh3 O-O-O
{ The black king is finding a safe space on the queenside and White will do the same. }
17. Qg4+ Kb8 18. O-O-O
{ White is threatening to win an exchange with Bg5, so Black has to move the queen away from f6. }
18... Qf7 { Gaining a tempo by attacking the pawn on a2. } 19. a3
{ White can also play Kb1, Black's reaction will be the same. } 19... d5
{ This position is about equal. Yes, White has an extra pawn, but the pawn is on h2 and not going anywhere. White probably will try to swap the h5-pawn with h5-h6 after which both h2 and f2 are weak. Moreover, Black is planning to gain more space in the center with ...d5-d4 and if White prevents this with d3-d4, the bishop on e3 will become passive and Black can start an attack by playing ...Na5 followed by either ...Nc4 or even ...Nb3. }
