1. Nf3 f5 2. d3
{ This line became popular because Magnus Carlsen won convincingly against a much stronger opponent in only 19 moves. Many years since then have passed and nowadays it is not a big problem for Black anymore. }
2... d6
{ I like this move a lot better than  2...Nc6  after which White can play the tricky  3.d4  .  After 2...d6 it doesn't make sense for White to play d3-d4, because that would transpose to a main line of the Leningrad while being a full tempo down. }
3. e4 e5
{ The standard reaction, when White plays e2-e4, Black usually plays ...e7-e5. Because the white bishop is still on f1, Black doesn't take on e4 first. We would only do that if the bishop is on g2, so the bishop would be locked behind the e4-pawn. }
4. Nc3 Nc6
{ 4...Be7  is not great because Black doesn't take control over the square d4.  5.d4  fxe4  6.Nxe4  d5  ,  at least Black should have played ...Nf6 here, but even then White has a clear advantage.  7.Neg5  Black is in big trouble with the exposed king.  7...exd4  8.Bd3  Qd6  9.Nxd4  and White was winning in Svidler-Bu, Tbilisi 2017. Black's king is not safe and the pieces don't coordinate well. }
5. exf5 Nge7
{ A key move.  5...Bxf5  was played in the famous game between a young Magnus Carlsen and Dolmatov, which resulted in a crushing win for White.  6.d4  Nxd4  7.Nxd4  exd4  8.Qxd4  Nf6  9.Bc4  c6  10.Bg5  b5  11.Bb3  Be7  12.O-O-O  Qd7  13.Rhe1  Kd8  14.Rxe7  Qxe7  15.Qf4  Bd7  16.Ne4  d5  17.Nxf6  h6  18.Bh4  g5  19.Qd4  1-0 Carlsen-Dolmatov, Moscow 2004. }
6. Nh4
{ This may look strange but White is trying to get the queen to h5 as quickly as possible. }
6... Nxf5 7. Qh5+ g6
{ Black has to sacrifice this pawn and then chase White's queen away. } 8. Nxg6
Ng7 9. Qh4 { White is offering a queen swap. } 9... Qxh4 10. Nxh4 Nd4
{ Ensuring White loses the right to castle because there is no other way to defend c2. }
11. Kd1 Be7 12. Nd5 { White is trying to do the same as Black by hitting c7. }
12... Bxh4
{ My engine says that after  12...Bd8  the position is also equal. However, Black is still a pawn down and it is not so obvious how Black can generate some initiative, so for a practical game, I don't recommend it. }
13. Nxc7+ Kd8 14. Nxa8 Bg4+
{ Black wants to win the knight on a8 as quickly as possible and putting the white f-pawn on f3 limits the power of the f1-bishop. Especially if it comes to g2, White will need to spend another tempo on f3-f4. }
15. f3 Be6
{ The bishop can also come to d7, but the e6-square is perhaps a bit more active. }
16. c3 Nc6 17. g3 Be7 18. f4 Kd7 { Black is ready to capture the knight. } 19.
fxe5 dxe5 20. Bg2 Rxa8
{ We have reached a position that is hard to assess. From a material point of view, White is slightly better with two pawns and a rook for the two knights. On the other hand, these two pawns are not moving forward any time soon, there is a weak pawn on d3 and the white king is far away from a safe square @@StartBracket@@a1 or g1@@EndBracket@@. The engine says it is equal in many different lines, which is a good indication that the position is balanced and that the strongest player will win. }
