{ A key move.  5...Bxf5  was played in the famous game between a young Magnus Carlsen and Dolmatov, which resulted in a crushing win for White.  6.d4  Nxd4  7.Nxd4  exd4  8.Qxd4  Nf6  9.Bc4  c6  10.Bg5  b5  11.Bb3  Be7  12.O-O-O  Qd7  13.Rhe1  Kd8  14.Rxe7  Qxe7  15.Qf4  Bd7  16.Ne4  d5  17.Nxf6  h6  18.Bh4  g5  19.Qd4  1-0 Carlsen-Dolmatov, Moscow 2004. }
6. d4 exd4 { I don't trust  6...Bxf5  . } 7. Nxd4 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Nxf5
{ Black is trying not to fall behind in development, which could be dangerous with the disappearance of the f- and e-pawns. }
9. Qe4+ { Not a sharp move. } 9... Qe7 10. Bd3 Qxe4+ 11. Nxe4 d5
{ Black needs to create some space and develop the pieces and all will be fine as there are no weaknesses. }
12. Ng3 g6 { Taking on g3 would have resulted in problems after hxg3. } 13. Bf4
c6 14. O-O Bd6 { Black is ready to castle. } 15. Rae1+ Kf7
{ Okay so no castling, but here the king is also safe. } 16. Bxd6 Nxd6 17. f3
Bd7
{ With an equal position − Black has no weaknesses and the drawing margin is quite large because all rooks can be exchanged on the e-file and it is difficult for both sides to create a passed pawn.  Black’s next moves are probably ...Rae8 and ...Kf6  (so that it becomes really hard for White to push the f-pawn to f5)  and then Black can try to advance the majority on the queenside with ...c6-c5 and create a passed pawn. }
