[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. English &  Réti Setups"]
[Black "Réti Setups - 1.Nf3 without c4 #14"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 f5 2. d3
{ This line became popular because Magnus Carlsen won convincingly against a much stronger opponent in only 19 moves. Many years since then have passed and nowadays it is not a big problem for Black anymore. }
2... d6
{ I like this move a lot better than  2...Nc6  after which White can play the tricky  3.d4  .  After 2...d6 it doesn't make sense for White to play d3-d4, because that would transpose to a main line of the Leningrad while being a full tempo down. }
3. e4 e5
{ The standard reaction, when White plays e2-e4, Black usually plays ...e7-e5. Because the white bishop is still on f1, Black doesn't take on e4 first. We would only do that if the bishop is on g2, so the bishop would be locked behind the e4-pawn. }
4. Nc3 Nc6
{ 4...Be7  is not great because Black doesn't take control over the square d4.  5.d4  fxe4  6.Nxe4  d5  ,  at least Black should have played ...Nf6 here, but even then White has a clear advantage.  7.Neg5  Black is in big trouble with the exposed king.  7...exd4  8.Bd3  Qd6  9.Nxd4  and White was winning in Svidler-Bu, Tbilisi 2017. Black's king is not safe and the pieces don't coordinate well. }
5. exf5 Nge7
{ A key move.  5...Bxf5  was played in the famous game between a young Magnus Carlsen and Dolmatov, which resulted in a crushing win for White.  6.d4  Nxd4  7.Nxd4  exd4  8.Qxd4  Nf6  9.Bc4  c6  10.Bg5  b5  11.Bb3  Be7  12.O-O-O  Qd7  13.Rhe1  Kd8  14.Rxe7  Qxe7  15.Qf4  Bd7  16.Ne4  d5  17.Nxf6  h6  18.Bh4  g5  19.Qd4  1-0 Carlsen-Dolmatov, Moscow 2004. }
6. d4 exd4 { I don't trust  6...Bxf5  . } 7. Nxd4 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Nxf5
{ Black is trying not to fall behind in development, which could be dangerous with the disappearance of the f- and e-pawns. }
9. Qg4 c6
{ The difference with the Carlsen-Dolmatov game is clear: the black knight is better positioned on f5 than on f6 and with ...c7-c6 and ...d6-d5 next, Black can take control over the light squares. }
10. Bd3 Qe7+
{ Maybe  10...g6  is also possible,  but I don't like to create weaknesses on the side where White is already attacking. White could try to attack g6 with h2-h4-h5 and it is not clear how to defend. }
11. Ne2 Qf7
{ This was the idea of ...Qe7+. Black is defending the knight without moving any pawns, has developed the queen and moved it away from a dark square where it could be attacked by Bg5. }
12. Bg5 h6
{ Now that the queen on f7 covers the g6-square, Black can allow this weakening pawn move to get rid of the bishop. }
13. Qe4+ Be7 14. Bxe7 d5
{ A nice intermediate move, Black is taking control of some central squares. }
15. Qb4
{ 15.Qe5  is also possible and after the queens are exchanged on e7, we have reached an equal endgame where Black can hope for some advantage by pushing the pawn majority on the queenside, while for White it will be harder to do this on the kingside because it could expose the king after short castling. }
15... Qxe7 16. Qc3 O-O
{ The position is equal and Black has no problems. Next, we can play ...Bd7 and ...Rae8, maybe move the queen to g5 although it is unlikely we will be able to create a real attack. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. English &  Réti Setups"]
[Black "Lisitsin Gambit #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 f5 2. e4
{ This gambit was probably first played by Georgy Lisitsin against Riumin in the USSR Championship in Moscow 1931 and the gambit was named after him. He also played it against Korchmar, Botvinnik, and Korchnoi and he also experimented with 2.d3 and then 3.e4 against Krogius. }
2... fxe4
{ As part of our repertoire, it is recommended to take on e4 instead of trying to hold on to the pawn. In this way, Black avoids White's main idea in this gambit: to initiate a quick attack over the light squares  (d3 to h7, d1 to h5, and c4 to f7)  with queen and bishop.   Note that Black can also transpose to the Latvian Gambit by playing  2...e5  , which is typically reached after the moves @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  f5  . }
3. Ng5 Nf6
{ I don't think there is anything wrong with  3...d5  but to make it easier to remember, I try to recommend similar types of setups across all the different systems. For that reason,  I recommend here a setup with ...Nf6 and the pawn on e5. }
4. d3 e5
{ I don't like the look of taking on d3 and giving White a huge lead in development and dangerous attacking possibilities via the light squares.   4...e3  was played in what I think is the original game of this gambit Lisitsin-Riumin, Moscow 1931. }
5. Nxe4 { Taking back with the knight on e4 gives Black an easy game. } 5... d5
{ This is the most straightforward way to go, immediately occupying the center. }
6. Nxf6+ Qxf6 7. Be2 Nc6
{ Black can develop the pieces to good squares and choose whether to castle kingside or queenside. Both are valid options, but in the spirit of fighting for the initiative in the Leningrad System, I prefer castling queenside. }
8. Nc3 Be6 9. O-O O-O-O
{ Black might already be a bit better because the pieces occupy more active squares and Black also has more space in the center. Next, we can play something like ...a7-a6 followed by ...Bc5 to put pressure on f2 @@StartBracket@@perhaps by also putting a rook on f8@@EndBracket@@. If White prevents this by playing a2-a3 and b2-b4 in time, Black can play ...g7-g5 followed by ...Rg8 and ...g5-g4 and then ...h7-h5, to launch a quick kingside attack. }
