[White "18. English &  Réti Setups"]
[Black "Lisitsin Gambit #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 f5 2. e4
{ This gambit was probably first played by Georgy Lisitsin against Riumin in the USSR Championship in Moscow 1931 and the gambit was named after him. He also played it against Korchmar, Botvinnik, and Korchnoi and he also experimented with 2.d3 and then 3.e4 against Krogius. }
2... fxe4
{ As part of our repertoire, it is recommended to take on e4 instead of trying to hold on to the pawn. In this way, Black avoids White's main idea in this gambit: to initiate a quick attack over the light squares  (d3 to h7, d1 to h5, and c4 to f7)  with queen and bishop.   Note that Black can also transpose to the Latvian Gambit by playing  2...e5  , which is typically reached after the moves @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  f5  . }
3. Ng5 Nf6
{ I don't think there is anything wrong with  3...d5  but to make it easier to remember, I try to recommend similar types of setups across all the different systems. For that reason,  I recommend here a setup with ...Nf6 and the pawn on e5. }
4. d3 e5
{ I don't like the look of taking on d3 and giving White a huge lead in development and dangerous attacking possibilities via the light squares.   4...e3  was played in what I think is the original game of this gambit Lisitsin-Riumin, Moscow 1931. }
5. dxe4 h6
{ We have to get rid of this annoying knight before we can continue with our development. }
6. Nf3 Nc6
{ Simply defending the pawn on e5. Black has no intent to take on e4 any time soon as it would give White too much compensation on the b1-h7 diagonal. }
7. Bc4 Bc5
{ A good, active square for the bishop − with the f-file being open for Black, there are future chances against the pawn on f2. }
8. O-O d6
{ Black cannot castle kingside at the moment so first, the c8-bishop needs to be developed. There are two choices: a solid one, by trying to remove the bishop from c4 @@StartBracket@@for example with ...Na5@@EndBracket@@ and then castle kingside, or play for the initiative and castle queenside immediately. Note that the idea of playing ...Qe7 followed by ...Be6 looks solid, but is usually not okay because White can play Nc3-Nd5, attacking the queen. }
9. h3 { The idea of this move is to prevent Black's bishop from coming to g4. }
9... Na5
{ Black takes the chance to chase away the c4-bishop and castle kingside. } 10.
Bd3 O-O 11. Nc3 Be6
{ Simple development, the move  11...a6  was played in a high-level blitz game: Bu-Zhang, Beijing 2008. }
12. Qe2 Nc6
{ Considering the knight could not go to c4 anymore, it is normal to return to c6 from where ...Nd4 becomes an option again.  Black's ideas in this position are: ...Qd7 followed by ...Nd4 and ...c7-c6 and ...d6-d5. Or, and I like this even more, ...Qe8, then ...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@note that immediately ...Nh5 often fails to Nxe5@@EndBracket@@ followed by ...Nf4. White is almost forced to take the knight because otherwise there will soon be a mate on g2, but after taking on f4, Black has a powerful pair of bishops and there are still chances for a mating attack by doubling rooks on the f-file followed by ...Qg6 or ...Qh5. }
