[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. English &  Réti Setups"]
[Black "English Setups − 1.Nf3 with 5.c4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c4
{ We have transposed to an English opening that could also have started with 1.c4. Also, at any point, White can decide to play d2-d4 and transpose to a main line of the Leningrad System. }
5... O-O 6. Nc3 d6 7. Rb1 Nh5
{ This move is not accurate because White hasn't put the d-pawn on d3 yet, so d4 can be played in one go, transposing to a main line of the Leningrad System. In those main lines, we don't usually play ...Nh5 at such an early stage. }
8. d4 e5 { That is the way to justify ...Nh5, but it doesn't equalize. } 9.
dxe5 dxe5 10. Qd5+ Kh8
{ White is making use of the fact that if Black takes on d5,  10...Qxd5  , the position is lost after  11.Nxd5  and there is no good way to defend  the pawn on c7 because after  11...Rf7  12.Ng5  followed by Ne6 is killing. }
11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Ng5
{ Now it becomes clear why White played Qd5+ first. With Black's king on h8, there is now the threat of Nf7+. }
12... Rd7 13. Ne6 c6 { At least taking control over the d5-square. } 14. Nxg7
Kxg7 15. b3
{ White has a clear plus with the pair of bishops and lead in development with the rook being wrongly placed on d7. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. English &  Réti Setups"]
[Black "English Setups − 1.Nf3 with 5.c4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c4
{ We have transposed to an English opening that could also have started with 1.c4. Also, at any point, White can decide to play d2-d4 and transpose to a main line of the Leningrad System. }
5... O-O 6. Nc3 d6 7. Rb1 e5 { Now we are in a main line of the English. } 8.
d3
{ In this system, there are many different move orders. In general, White will advance on the queenside, Black on the kingside, and sometimes Black can break in the center with ...e5-e4 or, after ...c7-c6, create a big center with ...d6-d5. I will give two lines with typical ideas for Black. }
8... h6
{ 8...Nc6  is not a bad move but White has now an additional option: exchanging the c1-bishop on f6 to increase the control over the square d5.  9.Bg5  h6  10.Bxf6  Qxf6  11.Nd5  Qf7  12.b4  Nd8  .  First ...g6-g5 and only after b4-b5 from White, putting the knight on d8 is also fine.  13.b5  Ne6  14.Nd2  g5  15.e3  Kh8  16.Nb4  Nc5  17.a4  f4  . This complex position was reached in Ragozin-Vyzmanavin, Helsinki 1992, in which Black had a dangerous kingside initiative. }
9. b4 Nc6
{ In general, I recommend putting the knight on c6 and advance on the kingside with ...h7-h6 followed by ...g6-g5. }
10. b5
{ White is playing all the standard moves from one of the main lines in the English. }
10... Ne7 11. a4 Be6
{ Black keeps on developing and if White does nothing special, Black will continue with a combination of ...Qd7, ...g6-g5, ...f5-f4, and ...Bh3, generating a dangerous kingside initiative. }
12. Nd2 Rb8
{ It is better to defend this pawn than playing ...c7-c6, which would create new targets for White on the queenside.   I don't like  12...c6  because we are opening lines for White, the rook might come to b7, the bishop to a3 and I don't think Black will be able to get ...d6-d5 in any time soon @@StartBracket@@if that would be the case, ...c7-c6 might actually be a good move@@EndBracket@@. }
13. a5 g5
{ 13...Qd7  first transposes to Black's position after the next move. } 14. Ba3
Qd7 15. Qa4 { White may want to play b5-b6, but Black blocks in time. } 15...
b6
{ Black is ready for further expansion with ...g5-g4 followed by ...f5-f4, which is probably more effective than ...h6-h5-h4 as played in Spangenberg-Onischuk, Halle 1995, although even there Black was OK. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. English &  Réti Setups"]
[Black "English Setups − 1.Nf3 with 5.c4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c4
{ We have transposed to an English opening that could also have started with 1.c4. Also, at any point, White can decide to play d2-d4 and transpose to a main line of the Leningrad System. }
5... O-O 6. Nc3 d6 7. d3
{ This was White's final chance to make it a 1.d4 opening. } 7... Nc6
{ In all these English lines I like the knight on c6. Placing the knight on a6 is less logical in these types of positions because after the knight moves to c5 there is a pawn on d3 preventing a future knight jump to e4. }
8. Rb1 a5
{ Black can also play without the inclusion of ...a7-a5 and a2-a3, but I feel that opening the a-file benefits Black. }
9. a3 Nh5
{ The pawn push b2-b4 is not working because the knight on c3 would be hanging, thus Black is preparing ...f5-f4. }
10. d4
{ A rarely played move but dangerous. Luckily, most English players don't like to put this pawn on d4 in one go, they like to lose a tempo with d2-d3! }
10... f4 { The main idea behind playing ...Nh5. } 11. b4 axb4 12. axb4 Bg4
{ Developing the bishop doesn't work here, White obtains a clear advantage in all lines. }
13. b5 Na5 { 13...Nb8  would be too passive. } 14. Nd5 e6
{ Exchanging the pawn on f4 for the pawn on c4.   The alternative with  14...fxg3  15.hxg3  and then grabbing the pawn  15...Nxc4  is not the way to go for Black.  16.Qd3  Nb6  17.Ng5  and Black is in serious trouble. }
15. Nxf4 Nxf4 16. Bxf4 Nxc4
{ Black's bishop on g4 feels awkward, it can easily get trapped now that the way back is blocked by the e6-pawn and the pawn on b7 is also weak. }
17. Nd2 g5
{ Black needs to use these types of moves, simply taking on d2 would result in a large advantage for White. }
18. Nxc4 gxf4 19. Bxb7
{ It's always this g2-bishop in the English that strikes. } 19... Ra2 20. Bf3
Qg5
{ Black is trying to become active but doesn't have any chance for a kingside attack. }
21. b6
{ I don't think Black has sufficient compensation for the pawn deficit. At some point White will play Rb2, limiting the power of the a2-rook, and it is not clear how Black can further improve the position. }
