20... fxg3 21. hxg3 Rxf2 { That's the kind of move we like! } 22. Kxf2 Bxg3+
23. Kg1 Bh2+
{ And another piece sacrifice − the best way to make a draw through perpetual check. }
24. Kxh2 Qh4 { White cannot defend against the series of checks. } 25. Qxc7+
Bd7+ 26. Kg1 Qg3+ 27. Kf1 Qh3+
{ After all these complications, we end with a draw by perpetual check as there is no way Black can play for mate. }
