1. Nf3 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c4
{ We have transposed to an English opening that could also have started with 1.c4. Also, at any point, White can decide to play d2-d4 and transpose to a main line of the Leningrad System. }
5... O-O 6. Nc3 d6 7. d3
{ This was White's final chance to make it a 1.d4 opening. } 7... Nc6
{ In all these English lines I like the knight on c6. Placing the knight on a6 is less logical in these types of positions because after the knight moves to c5 there is a pawn on d3 preventing a future knight jump to e4. }
8. Rb1 a5
{ Black can also play without the inclusion of ...a7-a5 and a2-a3, but I feel that opening the a-file benefits Black. }
9. a3 Nh5
{ The pawn push b2-b4 is not working because the knight on c3 would be hanging, thus Black is preparing ...f5-f4. }
10. Bd2 { White wins the queen but Black gets three minor pieces in return. }
10... f4 11. Ng5 { Has been played in a few games, but is not that scary. }
11... e6 { Simply attacking the knight and taking control over d5. } 12. Nge4
d5 { Continuing to chase the knight. } 13. cxd5 exd5 14. Nxd5 Qxd5 15. Nf6+
Nxf6 16. Bxd5+ Nxd5
{ My engine says Black has a slight advantage but I believe that in a practical game, Black has serious winning chances. It is much easier to play with the three minor pieces, especially because the white queen doesn’t have a lot of active possibilities.  The one thing Black needs to watch out for is a pin with Qb3  (which for the moment fails to ...Be6)  , but other than that the next moves will probably involve developing the bishop from c8, bringing the rook from a8 to e8, and then start putting pressure on White’s position with moves like ...Bg4 or ...Bh3 and ...Bd4. The pawns on f2 and e2 are quite weak and the position is not easy to defend for a human. }
