9. a3 Nh5
{ The pawn push b2-b4 is not working because the knight on c3 would be hanging, thus Black is preparing ...f5-f4. }
10. Bd2 f4 11. Ne4
{ Probably the most critical attempt − White is trying to slow down Black on the kingside while being ready for b2-b4-b5 and/or c4-c5. }
11... Bg4
{ One of the key ideas of the setup with the black e-pawn still on e7 is to gain time to put pressure on the light squares by moving the bishop to g4, the queen to d7, and a knight to d4. }
12. b4 axb4 13. axb4 Qd7 { Black takes control over some light squares. } 14.
b5 Nd4 { There is no reason to go back to the passive d8-square. } 15. Bc3 Bxf3
{ Taking on f3 with the knight is maybe less precise:  15...Nxf3+  16.exf3  Bf5  17.Re1  and White will probably manage to play d3-d4 and activate the bishop again via f1. But Black can still play this position by starting with ...Nf6 and then ...c7-c6 and sometimes ...d6-d5 to challenge the knight on e4. }
16. exf3 { The most ambitious continuation. } 16... Be5
{ Creating space for the knight on h5. } 17. Re1 Ng7 18. Nc5 Qc8
{ I don't see how White can be better with such a passive bishop on g2. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. Nimzo-Larsen 1.b3 f5 − Dutch-style"]
[Black "Nimzo-Larsen 1.b3 f5 − Dutch-style #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3 f5 { If we can play this on the first move, we will! } 2. Bb2 Nf6
{ There is no reason to be afraid of Bxf6 in this position. Black would take back with the e-pawn, play ...d7-d5 next, and develop in the same way as in the 2.Nc3 line: ...Be6, ...Nc6, ...Qd7 and castle queenside. }
3. c4 e6
{ I prefer this move over ...d7-d6. In many lines, White has the option to take on f6 and Black needs to take back with the e-pawn as long as that pawn is still on e7. In itself, that is fine for Black but then the continuation should be with a ...d7-d5 setup. If ...d7-d6 has been played first, that would yield a loss of tempo. So I prefer not to play ...d7-d6 as long as the pawn is still on e7. }
4. d4 d5
{ I like this transposition to a Stonewall when White plays a setup with the bishop on b2 and the pawn on d4. It feels to me that compared to a normal Stonewall, White has lost at least two tempi: by putting the bishop on b2, it will take an extra tempo to exchange these dark-squared bishops on a3, and secondly, the pawn on b3 means a loss of tempo when later White wants to expand on the queenside @@StartBracket@@in the Stonewall, White typically gains space on the queenside and Black in the center and on the kingside@@EndBracket@@. }
5. Nf3 c6
{ Preparing to play ...Bd6 so that if White would play c4-c5 the bishop can drop back to c7. Also, Black can now recapture with the c-pawn if White would ever exchange on d5. }
6. g3 Bd6 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O b6
{ I like the idea of putting the bishop on b7 in the Stonewall but there is nothing wrong with the alternative, more traditional plan of playing ...Nbd7 followed by ...Ne4 and ...Ndf6 and then ...Bh5 via d7 and e8. }
9. Nc3 Bb7 10. cxd5 exd5
{ In this particular situation,  10...cxd5  is less good because White has the option of  11.Nb5  followed by Rc1, increasing the pressure on the queenside. }
11. Qc2 g6 12. e3 Nbd7
{ Black has a fine position where the ideas are ...Ne4, ...Ndf6, ...Rc8, ...Rd8  (and the queen on e7)  and then play ...c6-c5 and Black has significant pressure and control in the center. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. Nimzo-Larsen 1.b3 f5 − Dutch-style"]
[Black "Nimzo-Larsen 1.b3 f5 − Dutch-style #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3 f5 { If we can play this on the first move, we will! } 2. Bb2 Nf6
{ There is no reason to be afraid of Bxf6 in this position. Black would take back with the e-pawn, play ...d7-d5 next, and develop in the same way as in the 2.Nc3 line: ...Be6, ...Nc6, ...Qd7 and castle queenside. }
3. c4 e6
{ I prefer this move over ...d7-d6. In many lines, White has the option to take on f6 and Black needs to take back with the e-pawn as long as that pawn is still on e7. In itself, that is fine for Black but then the continuation should be with a ...d7-d5 setup. If ...d7-d6 has been played first, that would yield a loss of tempo. So I prefer not to play ...d7-d6 as long as the pawn is still on e7. }
4. Nf3
{ The idea of this move is to keep the options open for White in the next few moves. White can either play d2-d4 later, or d2-d3 followed by e2-e4. Note that a setup of pawns on d3 and e3 doesn't have any independent value because at a later stage one of the pawns needs to move to the fourth rank and White has just lost a tempo. }
4... g6 5. g3
{ The alternative setup with d2-d4 is discussed as an option on move four instead of 4.Nf3. }
5... b6
{ Because Black has the pawns on e6 and f5, there is little future for the light-squared bishop on c8 which is much better placed on b7. The idea to remember is that as soon as White plays g2-g3, Black answers with ...b7-b6, just in time to oppose the bishop on g2. }
6. Nc3 Bb7 7. Bg2 Bg7
{ Black continues to develop and plans to castle kingside. } 8. O-O O-O 9. d4
{ White could also have played this move earlier and only then play Bg2 and castle kingside. There are many move transpositions but they all result in this position: both sides have castled kingside and fianchettoed their bishops and the white d-pawn is on d4. }
9... a5
{ Black is preparing to put the knight on a6. If White will then ever play d4-d5  (a typical idea in this position)  , the knight can go to c5 with good control over the e4-square, and thanks to the pawn on a5 White cannot chase away the knight with b3-b4. }
10. d5
{ An aggressive follow-up. White can also play quietly with  10.e3  , but then Black simply plays  10...Na6  and ...Qe7 and has no problems. We can then continue with ...h7-h6  (so White can forget about Ng5 ideas in combination with d4-d5)  followed by preparing ...e6-e5 with ...d7-d6. }
10... Na6 11. Rb1 Nc5
{ Black has nothing to worry about. We have full control over the e4-square and after a later ...Nfe4, there is pressure on White's pawn on d5 @@StartBracket@@so don't play ...e6-e5 too soon because you release the pressure on White's center and the bishop on b7 would become passive@@EndBracket@@. Typical next moves for Black either before or after ...Nfe4 are ...Qe7 and ...Rae8. }
*

