3. c4 e6
{ I prefer this move over ...d7-d6. In many lines, White has the option to take on f6 and Black needs to take back with the e-pawn as long as that pawn is still on e7. In itself, that is fine for Black but then the continuation should be with a ...d7-d5 setup. If ...d7-d6 has been played first, that would yield a loss of tempo. So I prefer not to play ...d7-d6 as long as the pawn is still on e7. }
4. Nf3
{ The idea of this move is to keep the options open for White in the next few moves. White can either play d2-d4 later, or d2-d3 followed by e2-e4. Note that a setup of pawns on d3 and e3 doesn't have any independent value because at a later stage one of the pawns needs to move to the fourth rank and White has just lost a tempo. }
4... g6 5. g3
{ The alternative setup with d2-d4 is discussed as an option on move four instead of 4.Nf3. }
5... b6
{ Because Black has the pawns on e6 and f5, there is little future for the light-squared bishop on c8 which is much better placed on b7. The idea to remember is that as soon as White plays g2-g3, Black answers with ...b7-b6, just in time to oppose the bishop on g2. }
6. Nc3 Bb7 7. Bg2 Bg7
{ Black continues to develop and plans to castle kingside. } 8. O-O O-O 9. d3
{ This type of setup is often favorable for Black but has to be aware of one particular idea. }
9... c5
{ If White is planning to play e2-e4, Black has an eye on the d4-square thanks to the move ...c7-c5. }
10. Qc2 Qe7
{ The black queen is moving out of the d-file to avoid the influence of a white rook on d1. }
11. e4
{ This was White's idea when playing d2-d3. Of course, White can also play e2-e3, but then d3-d4 will be played anyway at some point, which would cause a loss of tempo compared to playing d2-d4 in one go. }
11... fxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxg7 Qxg7 14. dxe4 Nc6
{ Black is increasing the control over the d4-square. } 15. Rad1 Rad8 16. Rd2
e5
{ The final move of Black's plan. We are ready to put the knight on d4 with an active position. The bishop on b7 is more active than the white bishop on g2 and if White ever takes the knight on d4, Black will have a strong passed pawn on d4 that is defended by the pawn on e5. }
