[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. Nimzo-Larsen 1.b3 f5 − Dutch-style"]
[Black "Nimzo-Larsen 1.b3 f5 − Dutch-style #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3 f5 { If we can play this on the first move, we will! } 2. Bb2 Nf6
{ There is no reason to be afraid of Bxf6 in this position. Black would take back with the e-pawn, play ...d7-d5 next, and develop in the same way as in the 2.Nc3 line: ...Be6, ...Nc6, ...Qd7 and castle queenside. }
3. d4
{ This can transpose to many other Leningrad lines that start with 1.d4. Here I show one rare line. }
3... g6 4. e3 Bg7 5. Be2
{ The combination of an early Bb2 with Be2 is not often seen. } 5... O-O 6. Nf3
{ The more solid developing move results in quiet play. } 6... b6
{ Black decides on a double fianchetto. Considering White has put the bishop on e2, there is a case for Black to take control over the e4-square. }
7. O-O Bb7 8. c4 e6
{ First playing  8...d6  would be illogical because White can go for  9.d5  ,  reducing the power of the b7-bishop. }
9. Nc3 Qe7
{ 9...d6  is not a good option.  10.d5  e5  11.Ng5  and White is clearly better because of the knight coming to e6. }
10. a3 a5 { Stopping White's expansion on the queenside. } 11. Qc2 d6 12. Nd2
{ White can play  12.b4  but it doesn't do much. Black will continue with  12...Nbd7  and it is hard for White to create anything on the queenside. }
12... Nbd7 13. Bf3 Bxf3 { Black is forced to exchange. } 14. Nxf3 e5
{ Black has done all the preparations and is now ready for this central push. }
15. dxe5 dxe5 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. cxd5 Bf6 18. e4
{ If White takes  18.Qxc7  , Black will play  18...Rfc8  followed by ...Qd6 and White needs to ply precisely to maintain the balance, one mistake and the queen will get lost. }
18... Nc5
{ Black has no problems, the weakness on c7 is compensated by the active pieces, the weak pawn on b3, and the power of the pawns on e5 and f5. }
