[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Leif Johannessen vs. Hikaru Nakamura, Oslo 2010"]
[Result "*"]

{ Nakamura was one of the first players to popularize the c6-lines in the Leningrad at the top level. He has played it many times with great success. Here we look at one of his wins in a blitz game. Despite the limited time, the game is quite instructive, and in a game with standard time control, I would be happy to reach the level that Nakamura displays in this game! }
1. d4 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. Nc3 d6
{ First the move ...d6 and then later ...g6 is more precise so that if White wants to push for a quick e2-e4, Black can respond with ...e7-e5. }
4. Nf3 g6 5. g3 Bg7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O c6
{ We have reached the main line of the Leningrad. In myrepertoire, I explain why I prefer the move ...c7-c6 over ...Qe8 @@StartBracket@@which I have played myself many times@@EndBracket@@ and ...Nc6. }
8. d5 e5 9. dxe6 Bxe6 10. b3 Ne4
{ Black can also opt for  10...Na6  followed by ...Nc7, with a fine position, and soon will soon be able to play ...d6-d5. }
11. Nxe4 fxe4
{ After  11...Bxa1  White would take  12.Nxd6  and next on b7. With two pawns for the exchange and the weak pawn on c6 White would have a large advantage. }
12. Nd4 Bf7
{ In the c6-lines the bishop often drops back to f7 from where it supports the move ...d6-d5. }
13. Rb1 d5 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. Ba3 Re8 16. e3
{ I am not sure this is a great move by White, but it is a move that many players would make automatically. Why wouldn't White want to support the beautiful knight on d4 that limits the power of the g7-Leningrad-bishop? But what has happened to me a few times is that only after White has played the move e2-e3, will realize a gap has been created on d3 for a black knight. }
16... Nd7
{ Of course not Nc6 because White would take the knight and then never have to worry about a knight coming to d3 anymore AND the c6 pawn would be weak: White would play Bc5-Bd4 and double rooks on the c-file. This would be serious trouble for Black. }
17. Qe2 Rc8
{ Don't ever forget to use all the pieces! The Leningrad is a dynamic opening where often the side with best-positioned pieces has the advantage. }
18. Rfc1 Qa5 19. Bb2 Ne5
{ The engine says the position is equal and that White's best move is to protect the pawn on a2 by playing Ba1. In practice, White players also want to make active moves and don't play like engines. }
20. Qb5 Qxa2
{ Oops, White forgot that Black can take this pawn and there is no way to win the black queen. In fact, Black threatens to win further material by playing ...Rxc1, and either the rook on b1 or the bishop on b2 drops. }
21. Ba1 Nd3 { And there is the knight! White needs to protect f2. } 22. Rf1 Re7
{ Even with an hour on the clock it is not easy to see that Nakamura is preparing to catch the white queen! He starts by taking away the d7-square and in the process, also protecting the pawn on b7. The engine says White should have played Qa4, but after the queen exchange, Black will also soon win the a-pawn. With two pawns Nakamura would have had an easily winning endgame. }
23. f3
{ White is dreaming of taking on e4 twice and then capturing the knight on d3. }
23... Rc5 { The white queen has only one square to go to. } 24. Qa4 Qd2
{ Threatening to take on e3 with check, but there is also another idea... } 25.
fxe4 Ra5
{ And White resigned as the queen is lost. A great game by Nakamura. He played the c6-Leningrad, then converted his weak pawn on d6 into a great center with pawns on e4 and d5. Next, he activated all his pieces @@StartBracket@@...Rc8!@@EndBracket@@ and combined a knight jump to d3 with his queen attacking the a2-pawn. White played healthy chess, but lost in 25 moves! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Dagur Ragnarsson vs. Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, Reykjavik 2015"]
[Result "*"]

{ Mamedyarov is one of those extremely sharp, dangerous players, always full of tactical tricks. Here he plays the main line of the Leningrad. }
1. c4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. d4 d6 7. Nc3 c6
{ As recommended in the repertoire. } 8. d5 e5 9. dxe6 Bxe6
{ This is the same position as in Nakamura's game, but there White played b2-b3, which was answered by ...Ne4. }
10. Bf4
{ This move is not dangerous for Black, but White players often use it when they want to make a draw against a much higher-rated player. }
10... Bxc4 11. Bxd6 Re8 12. Qd4 Ba6 { 12...Be6  was also an option. } 13. Qb4
Qb6
{ White, 400 points lower rated than his esteemed opponent, is happy to see Black is offering an exchange of queens. He thinks, mistakenly, that it will bring him closer to a draw. }
14. Rfd1 Nbd7 { Develop all your pieces! } 15. e3 Ne4
{ Black is becoming active and giving White a lot of choices in what to play. And the more choices, the higher the chance your opponent will make a mistake. Here White should have taken on e4 to maintain the balance. }
16. Na4
{ Forcing the queen exchange and protecting the pawn on b2, but the engine is quick to point out this is actually the losing move! }
16... Qxb4 17. Bxb4 Nb6
{ A strong move. If White now plays  18.Nc3  , the bishop is being kicked with  18...c5  and after  19.Ba3  White loses a pawn on c3.  @@StartFEN@@r3r1k1/pp4bp/bnp3p1/5p2/NB2n3/4PNP1/PP3PBP/R2R2K1 w - - 1 18@@EndFEN@@  18.Nc5  is also not an option because Black will exchange  18...Nxc5  and simply take the pawn on b2. That leaves White with one option, which is the game move. }
18. Nxb6 axb6 19. Ba3
{ White had an alternative in  19.Rab1  Bc4  ,  Black creates maximum pressure with the two bishops on White's queenside pawns.  20.a3  c5  21.Be1  Re7  .  Making sure that White cannot become active with Rd7. In fact, White has no good moves here. For example, after  22.Nd2  Be2  23.Rdc1  Nxd2  24.Bxd2  Bd3  ,  White is lost. If the rook moves, Bxb2 wins, and if not, Black will play ...Bxb1. }
19... Be2 20. Re1 Bc4 21. Rad1 b5 { Setting a small trap. } 22. Rd7
{ And White falls for it. } 22... c5
{ Oooops, the bishop on a3 is in trouble, b2-b3 is not possible and ...b5-b4 is not far away. }
23. Rc1
{ Trying to prevent ...b5-b4 because the bishop on c4 would be hanging, but Black is not in a hurry, he first protects the pawn on c5. }
23... b6 24. Rb7 Bxa2 { Not only taking the pawn but preparing ...b5-b4. } 25.
Rxb6 b4 { And the a3-bishop is dead. } 26. Bxb4 cxb4 27. Rxb4 Reb8 28. Rxb8+
Rxb8
{ White resigned, he will lose the b-pawn as well and doesn't have compensation for the piece. Mamedyarov was faced with a much lower-rated player and decided to use the main line of the Leningrad, to play for a win. White went for one of the most drawing lines and still lost quickly. He completely underestimated the issues on the queenside caused by Black's two bishops. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Panneerseluam Iniyan vs. Daniil Dubov, Abu Dhabi 2018"]
[Result "*"]

{ Another top player who has many chess fans around the world because of his wonderful, creative play: Daniil Dubov. He makes playing the Leningrad look really easy! }
1. d4 f5 2. Bg5
{ This is an aggressive system for White. It would be a mistake to play ...Nf6 now, so we first go ...g7-g6. }
2... g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. h4
{ Many White players love to push their h-pawn, Black almost always responds in the same way. White also often tries to play for the light squares by a combination of e2-e4 and when Black plays ...Nf6, White will capture with the bishop. }
4... h6
{ An important move as after a future h4-h5, Black will have the option of ...g6-g5. }
5. Bf4 Nf6 6. e3 d6 7. Qf3
{ White is preparing to castle queenside in combination with putting pressure on the light squares. }
7... O-O 8. Bc4+ e6
{ I do not recommend moving the king to the h-file as White can play Nh3 followed by Ng5, making use of the pin on the h-file. }
9. O-O-O Qe8
{ It is more precise to put the queen on e8 than on e7 because there are some attacking lines for White where the black queen moves to g6. }
10. Nh3
{ White could also have sacrificed a piece:  10.h5  g5  11.Bxg5  hxg5  12.h6  Bh8  13.h7+   13.Nh3  is a valid alternative because now after ...g5-g4, White plays Qg3, pinning the g-pawn.  13...Nh7  14.g4  Bf6  15.gxf5  Kh8  .  Black has returned a second pawn for the piece but his king is quite safe on h8.  16.Rdg1  d5  17.Bd3  c6  ,  according to the engine Black is a little better. In a practical game, I think it is hard to maintain the balance with White.  13...Kg7  14.Qg3  Qg6  .  This is one of the reasons why Black played ...Qe8 and not ...Qe7.  15.Nf3  Ng4  and Black has stopped White's attack. Because of the silly bishop on h8 White might be able to escape with a draw, but that is not in the spirit of most White players who sacrifice on g5. }
10... Nc6 11. d5
{ A natural break in the center but probably a mistake. White should have focused on the kingside with h4-h5 and if Black takes with the knight, play g2-g4. }
11... Nb4
{ 11...Na5  would also have given Black the advantage, but the game move is fine. Isn't it great that in the Leningrad after 11 moves we can already have a serious advantage with Black? }
12. dxe6 Bxe6 13. Bb3 Bxb3
{ A direct attack with  13...a5  is a serious alternative either on this move or the next. }
14. axb3 Ne4 15. Nxe4
{ The losing move − White had the last chance to block with Rd4, but even then Black would have been clearly better. }
15... fxe4 16. Qe2
{ And now it is time to attack and make maximum use of the g7-Leningrad-bishop and the knight on b4. }
16... a5 17. f3 b5
{ White's knight on h3 and the bishop on f4 are not very effective. } 18. c3
Nd3+ 19. Kc2 a4 { The engine gives +6 for Black in all the lines! } 20. fxe4
Nc5
{ Initially in this game White was trying to take control over the light squares, but look at how weak b3 and e4 are now. }
21. b4 Qxe4+ 22. Kd2 a3 23. Nf2
{ If White takes with  23.bxa3  ,  mate will follow soon.  23...Bxc3+  24.Kxc3  Rxa3+  25.Kb2  Qxb4+  26.Kc1  Qc3+  27.Qc2  Ra1  . }
23... Nb3+ 24. Ke1 Qxg2
{ White resigned since Black has many threats. The main one is to take on f4 and then play ...axb2, threatening to play ...Ra1 and White cannot capture with the queen on b2 because of ...Re8+. A fantastic attacking game by Dubov, already after 11 moves he had a clear advantage and he executed the attack flawlessly. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Luka Oboladze vs. Mihail Kobalia, Batumi 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5
{ This line is one of the most positional/strategic setups White can choose. }
3... d5 4. Bxf6 exf6 5. e3
{ Black will normally place the bishop on e6 or f7, put the pawns on g6 and h5, a knight to c6 and queen to d7 or d6, and castle queenside. }
5... Be6 6. Bd3 g6 7. Nge2 Bf7 8. a3
{ The idea of a2-a3 is to prevent Black from gaining the pair of bishops after a future ...Nc6-b4. }
8... Qd7 9. Qd2 Nc6 10. b4 Ne7
{ The knight on c6 prefers to be on d6. Sometimes Black starts with this rerouting before castling queenside because the c8-square is still available for the knight, so it can go e7-c8-d6 before a black king lands on c8 after queenside castling. }
11. Nc1 Nc8 12. Nb3 b6
{ Black pretty much never wants to allow White to be able to play Nc5. Of course, the move ...b7-b6 weakens the light squares a bit, but if needed Black can go ...c7-c6. }
13. O-O Nd6 14. f3
{ Taking away the e4-square from Black, but the disadvantage is that the pawn on e3 becomes weak. }
14... Bh6 15. Qf2 O-O
{ Yes, Black can also castle kingside, especially considering White has already played b2-b4 and put both knights on the queenside. Castling on that side has become less attractive for Black. The disadvantage of kingside castling is that if Black moves forward with the g- and f-pawns, the king might get exposed, but in the current situation everything looks pretty safe. We have played 15 moves and the engine already gives Black a clear advantage! }
16. f4 { This is an ugly move, nothing else I can say about it! } 16... Rfe8
17. Rfe1 Bf8 { The bishop had no role on h6 anymore. } 18. h3 Qc6 19. Ne2 Nc4
20. Bxc4 dxc4
{ Black has gained the pair of bishops. Is that a big deal? Well, the position is still closed, but at the same time with all the pawns still on the board, Black has multiple chances to create pawn breaks, open the position and swap one bishop for a knight to gain control over the position. White's play makes a passive impression, trying to play solid but really waiting for Black to take action. }
21. Nd2 a5
{ Tension point 1: whenever Black likes, he can take on b4 and open the position a bit. }
22. c3
{ We now get to a phase in which Black tries to improve the pieces while maintaining control over the position. There are a number of ideas: taking on b4 and then running with the c-pawn, or doubling on the a-file with the rooks to ensure White needs to recapture axb4. Black could also consider playing ...g6-g5 at some point, double rooks on the e-file to put pressure on e3, and then activate the f7-bishop. The exact order of these plans is less relevant. }
22... Qa4 23. Rec1 Bd5 24. Nf1 { All White can do is defend passively. } 24...
Ra7 25. Rcb1 Qd7 26. Qe1 Be4 27. Rc1 Qd5 28. Qf2 Bd3 29. Neg3 Rea8
{ Black threatens to take on b4 because the rook on a1 is not sufficiently protected. }
30. Qb2 { But now White let's go of the defense of the pawn on e3. } 30... Bd6
31. Nh1 Qe6 { Threatening to take on f1 and then on e3. } 32. Re1 g5
{ Full pressure on the a-file and Black decides to create a second front on the kingside. White's position is collapsing. }
33. fxg5 fxg5 34. Nf2 Bxf1 35. Rxf1
{ Taking back with the king on f1 would have made it a bit more difficult for Black to win, but he has a strong attack with ...g5-g4, and the pawns on a3 and e3 remain weak, so eventually he will get the full point. }
35... axb4 36. cxb4 Qxe3
{ This is game over, White has lost an important pawn, the pawn on a3 is still weak and the c-pawn is ready to advance. And oh yes, Black can also threaten mate with ...Qg3. }
37. Qc2 Rxa3 38. Rxa3 Rxa3 39. Qxf5
{ White could also have taken  39.Qxc4+  but after  39...Kg7  Black is still a pawn up, has a passed c-pawn, and a strong attack. }
39... Ra2 40. Kh1 Qf4 41. Qe6+ { White is hoping for a perpetual check. } 41...
Kg7 42. Qd7+ Qf7 { All endgames are easily winning for Black. } 43. Qxf7+ Kxf7
44. Ne4+ Ke7 45. Nxg5 c3
{ And White resigned, the c-pawn cannot be stopped. A great strategical win by Kobalia, he had a nice advantage after 15 moves, he hadn't done anything special for that, and he was never in danger afterwards. He kept on torturing his opponent with the pair of bishops and the potential to break both on the queenside @@StartBracket@@with ...a5@@EndBracket@@ and on the kingside @@StartBracket@@with ...g5@@EndBracket@@. Although it took a few moves to convert the won position into a full point, the engine confirms that Black had a large advantage early on. }
