[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Tobias Koelle vs. Mateusz Bartel, Titled Tuesday 2020"]
[Result "*"]

{ Bartel is a strong 2600+ player from Poland who has also been working as a second in team Carlsen. He is known for his attacking chess. }
1. d4 f5 2. e4 { The Staunton Gambit. } 2... fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 c6
{ Myrepertoire choice is to play  4...g6  here, but the ideas in this game are similar to the lines in the course. }
5. f3 d5
{ Defending the pawn on e4. Yes, White can win it back but has to take on f6 for that, giving up the pair of bishops in what is likely to become a sharp position. }
6. Qd2 Bf5
{ Not only defending the pawn on e4 but also preparing the option to castle queenside @@StartBracket@@kingside castling is also a valid alternative@@EndBracket@@. }
7. O-O-O
{ In the spirit of the Staunton Gambit, White is only thinking about attacking. }
7... Nbd7 8. h4 h6 9. g4
{ White is pushing all his pawns forward in the hope to open the position and mate Black. }
9... Bg6 10. Bf4 e6
{ Making space for the bishop to come out. The Leningrad is all about piece power, the more pieces you use and the more active they are, the likelier Black will gain the advantage. }
11. h5 Bh7 12. fxe4 Bb4
{ A powerful move, the knight on c3 is in a nasty pin. } 13. Bg2
{ Continuing to take with  13.exd5  fails to  13...Ne4  14.Qe3  Bxc3  15.bxc3  Qa5  and Black has a winning attack. }
13... Bxe4 14. Nf3 Qa5
{ All of Black's pieces have become active, even the knight on d7 is ready to join the attack. }
15. Kb1 Bxc3 16. bxc3
{ Exchanging queens won't help:  16.Qxc3  Qxc3  17.bxc3  O-O  ,  threatening to win a piece on the f-file.  18.Nh4  Bxg2  19.Nxg2  Nxg4  .  Black is two pawns up and the pawns on h5 and c3 are weak. Black is completely winning. }
16... Nb6
{ Only 16 moves played and Black has already a winning attack. The knight threatens to come to c4 or a4 followed by a queen check on the b-file and mate on b2. }
17. Ne5 Bxg2 18. Qxg2 Na4 19. Rd3 Ne4
{ Taking away the d2-square from the white king and the pawn on c3 will soon be captured. }
20. Bd2
{ And White lost, either because he resigned or lost on time. Anyway, he won't survive the attack. Black can check on b6 or b5 with the queen, followed by a check on b2, and then take maybe on c3 with a knight. Mate is not far away.  A great game by Bartel who made the Staunton Gambit look inferior. In the repertoire lines, I show that White can maintain the balance, but in a practical game, there are so many ways White can go wrong. In this game, White intended to quickly generate an attack, but Black took over and the game was already decided before it had really started. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Igor Efimov vs. Marc Santo Roman, Nice 1994"]
[Result "*"]

{ Marc Santo Roman was a creative French player who played the Leningrad quite often. }
1. d4 f5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. e4 fxe4 4. g4
{ The Staunton Gambit in its sharpest form, with g2-g4. } 4... h6 5. f3 d5
{ We don't want to give up the pawn on e4 that easily, White needs to work for it, so for now we just protect it with ...d7-d5. Taking on f3 is not really an option, it only helps White to accelerate development. }
6. Bf4 c5
{ In many of these lines the key to success for Black is to be able to play ...e7-e5 and for that, it helps if there is no more white pawn on d4, either because it took on c5 or because Black took on d4. }
7. Nb5 Na6 8. dxc5 e5
{ Mission accomplished: Black returns the extra pawn in order to break free. }
9. Bxe5 Bxc5
{ Just look at all the weak dark squares in White's camp. The engine concludes Black has a winning advantage and we have only played 9 moves! }
10. h3 O-O 11. f4 Qb6
{ Threatening to take the knight on g1 and a nasty check on f2, possibly followed by ...Qe3+ or even mate. }
12. Bd4 Bd7
{ Black is way ahead in development and his king is safe, whereas the white king is in danger. }
13. Bxc5 Nxc5 14. Nd4 Nd3+
{ Black could also have played the simple  14...Qb4+  followed by ...Qxb2. }
15. cxd3 Qxd4 16. Ne2 Qxb2 17. dxe4 Nxe4
{ Of course Black takes with the knight, he wants to put a rook on the e-file and mate the white king. }
18. Qxd5+ Kh8 19. Qd4
{ Note that the rook on a1 was hanging and that is why White didn't take the knight on e4. }
19... Qa3 20. Bg2 Ng3
{ White is completely lost, if he takes on g3, Black will take back with the queen and mate is not far away. }
21. Qc3 Qxc3+ 22. Nxc3
{ White has managed to reach an endgame, but he will have a serious material deficit. }
22... Nxh1 23. Bxh1 Rxf4 24. Bxb7 Re8+ 25. Kd2 Rd4+ 26. Kc2 Re3
{ Black continues to capture more material and is now threatening ...Rc4 to win the knight on c3. White resigned but basically was already lost on move 9.  These lines with g2-g4 in the Staunton Gambit initially may look dangerous to Black players, but if you know about the central break ...e7-e5 that you need to aim for and you keep focused on developing your pieces, it is likely you will emerge with a large advantage from the opening. }
