[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Marco Frohberg vs. Romuald Mainka, Bremen 1998"]
[Result "*"]

{ Mainka is a grandmaster from Germany who played many games in the Leningrad before it became popular. }
1. d4 f5 2. h3
{ The systems with 2.h3 are a bit similar in nature to the Staunton Gambit. White tries to quickly seize control over the light squares, but in this case without sacrificing a pawn. }
2... Nf6 3. g4 d5
{ When White plays g2-g4, Black either takes on g4 and then plays ...d7-d5 or like here, immediately plays ...d7-d5 @@StartBracket@@my mainrecommendation in the repertoire@@EndBracket@@, to maintain control over the light squares. }
4. Qd3 e6 { Black could also have played  4...g6  followed by ...Bg7. } 5. Bg5
Be7 6. Nc3 O-O 7. f3 { This move weakens the white pawn structure. } 7... c5
{ Of course, Black wants to open the position to make use of his lead in development. The move ...c7-c5 is a typical way of breaking things up that comes back in many Leningrad positions. }
8. gxf5 cxd4 { With this exchange, Black will win a few tempi. } 9. Qxd4 Nc6
10. Qd2 d4
{ Black keeps on attacking the white pieces and they can only move backwards, not a good sign. }
11. Nd1 Nd5
{ White has weaknesses on the dark squares so it makes sense for Black to exchange White's main defender of these squares, the dark-squared bishop. }
12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. e4 dxe3 14. Nxe3 Nxe3
{ Black could already have obtained a winning position with the following line:  14...Qh4+  15.Qf2  Qf4  ,  ensuring that after the knight exchange on d5, White cannot castle queenside.  16.Nxd5  exd5  17.Bd3  Bxf5  18.Bxf5  Rxf5  19.Ne2  .  And now Black can also play ...Re8 with a large advantage, but there is nothing wrong with picking up a pawn.  19...Qb4+  20.c3  Qxb2  and White's position is hopeless: a pawn down, the king is not safe in the center. But also after short castling, Black plays ...Raf8 and ...Ne5, with a winning attack. }
15. Qxe3 Qb4+ 16. Kf2 Qh4+ 17. Kg2 e5
{ Taking the pawn on f5 with the rook would also have resulted in a large advantage, but the game move is fine. Black has a serious lead in development and the white king is not safe. }
18. Bb5 Nd4 19. Ne2 Nxb5
{ White wins back the piece but ends up in a lost position. } 20. Qb3+ Kh8 21.
Qxb5 Bxf5
{ All of Black's pieces are becoming active and he is ready to open the position up further around White's king. }
22. Ng3 e4 23. f4
{ Taking on e4 results in mate:  23.fxe4  Bxe4+  24.Nxe4  Qxe4+  25.Kg3  Qf4+  26.Kg2  Qf2  . }
23... Rad8
{ White would love to play Rad1, but then Black takes on d1 followed by Bxh3+ and mate will follow soon. }
24. Rae1 e3 25. Qe5 Rd2+
{ And White resigned. After  26.Kf3  Black will play  26...Rf2+  followed by ...Qxg3. A nice attacking game by Mainka who showed how to take advantage with ...c7-c5 and opening the position if White neglects the dark squares. Already after 7 moves, the engine gives a clear advantage for Black! }
