[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Adalberto Villavicencio Martinez vs. Kevin Spraggett, Las Palmas 1998"]
[Result "*"]

{ Kevin Spraggett is a strong grandmaster from Canada who even made it to the candidate matches for the World Championship. The Leningrad has been one of his main weapons for many years. }
1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nh3
{ The systems with Nh3 have their own characteristics and Black needs to pay attention whether White plays this system with or without c2-c4 @@StartBracket@@see therepertoire@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf4 Nc6
{ The idea of ...Nc6 followed by ...e7-e5 is a standard idea against Nh3. } 6.
h4 e5 7. dxe5 Nxe5 8. h5
{ In these Nh3 systems Black normally doesn't play ...g6-g5 after White pushes h4-h5 because White would first play h5-h6 and only after ...Bf8 withdraw the knight from f4. The pawn on g5 would then be weak, there is a nice square for White on h5 to give a check with the queen and White is also ahead in development. }
8... c6 9. Nd2 d5
{ Taking control over the light squares just before White was going to play e2-e4, which would have been uncomfortable for Black. }
10. Nf3 Nfg4 { Black wants to keep a knight on e5 to defend the pawn on g6. }
11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Nd3 Be6 13. c3 Nc4
{ Now this knight can move because after Nf4, attacking the pawn on g6, Black has ...Bf7. }
14. Qc2 Qe7
{ Black keeps both options open, castling kingside or queenside, and with that approach, can mirror what White is doing. }
15. b3 Nd6 { 15 moves played and the engine prefers Black! } 16. Bb2 Ne4 17. c4
d4 18. O-O-O O-O-O
{ There was no reason to castle kingside because White could still launch an attack there. On the queenside, this is much harder for White, because by advancing the queenside pawns, the king gets exposed. }
19. Kb1 g5
{ Black has now obtained a space advantage with the pawns on d4, g5, and f5. }
20. h6 Bf6 21. Rhe1 Kb8 22. e3
{ Black decides to take the pair of bishops and create a dangerous pawn on c3. }
22... Nc3+ 23. Bxc3 dxc3 24. e4 fxe4 25. Bxe4 Rhe8
{ Don't forget, the Leningrad is an opening where piece power is essential, so do play with all your pieces, including rooks. }
26. f3 Bh8 27. g4 Qf6
{ If Black can play ...c3-c2, it could suddenly be mate on a1. } 28. Qh2+ Ka8
29. Kc2
{ The king is usually not a good piece to stop a passed pawn in the middlegame. }
29... Bg8 30. Qc7 Rc8 31. Qh2 Qf8
{ A beautiful move, backward queen moves are often missed. Black's idea is to go to a3. }
32. Bf5 Qa3 33. Kb1 Rcd8 34. Qc2 Qd6
{ Suddenly it turns out that the pawn on h6 is weak. } 35. Rxe8 Rxe8 36. Nf2
Qxh6
{ Black has a healthy extra pawn, the only problem is that it is on h7 and not going anywhere. }
37. Ne4 a6 38. Qf2 Qg7
{ White always needs to watch these tricks with ...c3-c2 followed by ...Qb2+ or ...Qa1+. }
39. Kc2 Qc7
{ A strange mistake, perhaps it was time trouble. White could now have played  40.Nxc3  with equal play. }
40. Rd7 Qa5 { Now Black is on top again. } 41. Kb1 h5
{ Oops, White missed that one of the ideas of ...Qa5 was to attack the bishop on f5 and as a result, Black can now push ...h7-h5, which is a big improvement. The passed h-pawn is becoming dangerous. }
42. a4 h4 43. Qc5
{ Black is happy to exchange queens with the dangerous pawns on c3 and h4. }
43... Qxc5 44. Nxc5 h3 { White has no time to take on b7. } 45. Rd1 h2 46. Ne4
Ka7 47. Rh1 Be5
{ White is completely tied down to Black's h- and c-pawns and Black can simply open the position on the queenside. }
48. Kc2 Bf4 { The immediate  48...b5  would have been even stronger. } 49. Kxc3
b5 50. axb5 cxb5 51. b4
{ I don't know if this move was actually played, but White is lost anyway. Black was threatening to exchange on c4 followed by ...Rc8.  Spraggett played a very strategic game: he made sure that against this Nh3 system the pawn on g6 was well protected, he then went on to gain space with the pawn on d4, win the pair of bishops and create a passed pawn. White was already much worse when he dropped the h-pawn and allowed Black to play ...h7-h5-h4. Spraggett made it look really easy! }
