[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Sabri  Abdul Moula vs. Mateusz Bartel, Turin 2006"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this game I want to show some typical endgame play. } 1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6
3. Bg2 g6 4. Nh3
{ The opening play is similar to the game played by Spraggett. } 4... Bg7 5.
Nf4 Nc6 6. h4 e5 7. dxe5 Nxe5 8. h5 c6 9. hxg6
{ This is the deviation from Spraggett's game. The White player is looking for exchanges in the hope to make a draw against a much higher-rated player. }
9... hxg6 10. Rxh8+ Bxh8 11. Qd6 Qe7 12. Qxe7+ Kxe7
{ White has managed one of his objectives: straight out of the opening a pair of rooks and the queens have been exchanged. And yes this position is equal, but it is not even close to any kind of drawish endgame, there is a lot of play left. }
13. b3 Ne4 { Opening the diagonal for the g7-bishop. } 14. c3 d5 15. Bb2 Kf7
{ The game move is not bad, but the engine gives Black already a significant advantage after  15...g5  16.Nd3  Be6  .  Black has more space, the more active pieces, and the possibility to create play on the queenside with ...a7-a5-a4. }
16. Nd2 Bf6 17. Nxe4
{ White keeps exchanging pieces but it only helps Black: he has a strong center and the bishop on g2 has become ineffective. }
17... fxe4 18. O-O-O Bg4 19. Kd2 g5 20. Nh3
{ This knight is poorly placed on h3. } 20... a5
{ With a knight on h3 and a bishop on g2 that are offside it totally makes sense for Black to open a second front on the queenside. }
21. a4 b5 22. axb5 cxb5
{ Black is ready to push ...a5-a4 with a strong passed pawn. } 23. c4 bxc4 24.
Bxe5 Bxe5 25. bxc4
{ Black has only one objective from here on: pushing his pawn to a1. } 25...
Bxh3 { Ensuring the knight cannot create any troubles. } 26. Bxh3 a4
{ Step 1. } 27. cxd5 a3 { Step 2. } 28. Be6+ Kf6 29. Ke3 a2
{ Step 3. And although the database gives 2 more moves, they look so weird that I wonder if White didn't resign here, the engine gives +7 for Black.  Bartel was facing an opponent who was looking for a draw by quickly exchanging pieces. The game shows how easy it is in the Leningrad to create play. Black was already clearly better on move 15, he created a passed pawn on the a-file that was supported by the rook and the g7-Leningrad-bishop decided the game. }
