[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Luis Aguirre Lorenzo vs. Emanuel Berg, Santa Cruz de La Palma 2005"]
[Result "*"]

{ Emanuel Berg is a grandmaster from Sweden who used to have a rating above 2600. He has played many games in the Dutch, both the Leningrad as well as the Classical Variation. }
1. Nf3 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. c4 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. Nc3 d6 7. d3
{ White could have switched to a 1.d4 Leningrad, but he decided to stick with the English. }
7... Nc6 8. Rb1 a5 9. a3 e5
{ 9...Nh5  would have been more in line with our repertoire, but the themes stay the same. }
10. b4 axb4 11. axb4 h6
{ While White expands on the queenside, Black will gain space in the center and on the kingside. This move prepares both ...g6-g5 and ...Be6 @@StartBracket@@there is no more Ng5 from White@@EndBracket@@. }
12. b5 Ne7 13. c5 Be6 14. Bb2 Nd7
{ This move clarifies the situation with the white c-pawn and protects the pawn on e5 so that Black is ready for ...d6-d5. }
15. cxd6 cxd6 16. Nd2 d5
{ White has to take action, otherwise Black will continue to gain space, and White's position becomes cramped. }
17. e4 d4 18. Nd5 Nc5
{ Not just attacking the pawn on d3, the real intent becomes clear on the next move. }
19. Nc4 fxe4
{ White needs to take back with the d-pawn on e4, locking in the bishop on g2. }
20. dxe4 Nxd5 21. exd5 Bf5
{ Black's pieces are more active than White's, has a strong pawn center and a clear advantage.   Black can take the pawn on d5 and then lose an exchange:  21...Bxd5  22.Bxd5+  Qxd5  23.Nb6  Qe4  24.Nxa8  Rxa8  .  Black has compensation for the small material deficit but there is no advantage. }
22. Ba3 Rxa3 { A strong exchange sacrifice from Black. } 23. Nxa3 e4 24. g4 Bc8
25. Nc4 Qxd5
{ After this move, Black has only a small advantage.   Black had a much stronger option:  25...Qh4  26.h3  h5  27.f3  e3  .  Black is completely winning with the central pawns and the kingside attack. }
26. Nb6 Qe5 27. Nxc8 Rxc8 28. Rc1 Qf4 { Black should have played  28...d3  . }
29. Re1 Kh7 30. Rxe4 { Possible because the rook on c8 is not protected. }
30... Nxe4 31. Rxc8 Qxf2+ 32. Kh1 Qe3 33. Bxe4
{ White should have played  33.Qf3  and a draw via perpetual check starting with ...Nf2+ is likely. }
33... Qxe4+ 34. Kg1 d3 35. Rc7 Qd4+ 36. Kh1 d2 37. Kg2
{ 37.Rf7  was the only move and White has good survival chances. } 37... Qe4+
{ White resigned. On  38.Kg1  Qe1  decides and on @@StartFEN@@8/1pR3bk/6pp/1P6/4q1P1/8/3p2KP/3Q4 w - - 2 38@@EndFEN@@  38.Kf2  Qf4+  wins  the rook on c7. Black didn't play very precisely and at several moments he let the advantage slip to obtain it back a few moves later. But what is clear is that he had no problems out of the opening, he quickly gained space and after the exchange sacrifice, he had a nice advantage based on the power of the central pawns. }
