[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Model Games"]
[Black "Magdalena Kludacz vs. Karen Movsziszian, Copenhagen 2008"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d6 2. c4 f5 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 g6 5. b4
{ A dangerous system for Black, where therepertoire gives different ideas based on whether the c-pawn is on c2 or c4. }
5... Bg7 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Bg2 c6
{ In the repertoire this is mentioned as not the recommended path because it can result in a passive position for Black. }
8. O-O Qe8 9. Nbd2 Kh8 10. Qc2
{ White could have claimed the advantage after  10.Re1  with the idea of a quick e2-e4. The rook on e1 is well-positioned against the black queen on e8. }
10... Be6 11. Ne1 Nbd7 12. Nd3 Bg8 13. b5
{ A poor move, giving away the control over the d5-square. White should first have played a2-a4 so that after a later b4-b5, White can always take back with the a-pawn on b5. }
13... cxb5 14. cxb5 Nd5
{ A beautiful square for the knight, although first  14...Bd5  was also fine. }
15. Rfc1 g5
{ Advancing the g-pawn is a common motive in the Leningrad. It helps Black to play ...f5-f4 and also enables the queen to come to g6 or h5. }
16. e4
{ The right move for White but it should have been played a few moves earlier with a rook on e1. }
16... fxe4 17. Nxe4 Qg6 18. Qd2 g4
{ Stronger than defending the pawn on g5 with ...h7-h6. The pawn on f2 has now become a weakness and Black can start thinking about doubling rooks on the f-file. }
19. Rc2 Rf5 20. a4 Raf8 21. Qa5
{ White misses a tactical trick, but in general, it is strange to play your queen to a5 if your opponent is building up a kingside attack. One would think that White should keep some pieces close to the king, to help defend it. }
21... Rf3
{ A very nice, unusual, tactical trick. Suddenly there are two white pieces hanging, the knight on d3 and the knight on e4. }
22. Bxf3 Rxf3 23. Re1 Rxd3
{ Black has won two pieces for the rook and has a winning position because his pieces are much more active. }
24. Qxa7 Ne3 { Another tactical motive White must have missed. } 25. fxe3 Qxe4
26. Rc8 Rd2
{ White resigned, it is hard to avoid mate in a reasonable way. Movsziszian played a great game. In the first 12 moves, he developed his pieces in a bit of passive fashion, and then in the next 14 moves, he completely blew away his opponent. First, the control over the d5-square and then the attack with ...g6-g5 and doubling rooks on the f-file are typical for many Leningrad positions. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. Bloopers"]
[Black "Alexander Moiseenko vs. Michiel Abeln, Ohrid 2009"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this chapter, I will show you a number of bloopers I have made while playing the Leningrad System. I think it is instructive to see and understand these human mistakes and also in some cases, things still turned out OK. Miracles do happen in the Leningrad, lost games can still be saved because in most positions Black has active piece play against White’s king. }
1. d4 f5 2. Bg5 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. h4 Nh6
{ Not a great move,  4...h6  would have been the standard approach. } 5. Qd2
Nf7 6. Nf3 d6 7. O-O-O h6
{ The idea of this move is that if White later plays h4-h5, Black can respond with ...g6-g5. }
8. Bf4 Nc6 9. e4 O-O
{ The natural ...e7-e5 break is not great here:  9...e5  10.dxe5  dxe5  11.Qe1  ,  the black queen is in trouble because White is ready for Nd5.   This is not the right time for Black to play for small tricks:  9...Nxd4  10.Nxd4  e5  .  Black may think he wins back his piece, but in the meantime, White will develop a huge attack.  11.exf5  exf4   11...exd4  12.fxg6  dxc3  13.gxf7+  Kf8  14.bxc3  ,  White is two pawns up but more importantly, is ready to continue the attack while Black has no counterplay.  12.Bb5+  Kf8  13.fxg6  Ne5  14.Nd5  ,  Black's king is in big danger and he is not even up in material. }
10. Bd3 e5
{ Probably Black's best option.   Taking the pawn on d4 is not OK:  10...Nxd4  11.Nxd4  Bxd4  12.exf5  gxf5  13.Bc4  .  Black will lose the important h6-pawn.   10...Nb4  is too slow.  11.Bc4  Kh7  12.e5  and White has a large advantage. }
11. dxe5 dxe5
{ First taking with the knight was probably Black's best option.  11...Ncxe5  12.Nxe5  dxe5  13.Be3  .  White has still a clear advantage, but at least Black is still alive and the swap of the knights helps with the lack of space. }
12. Be3 { White threatens now to play h4-h5. } 12... Nd6
{ A very bad move. After  12...f4  13.Bc5  Re8  14.Nd5  ,  White is better but not yet winning.   12...Nd4  normally, it makes sense to occupy this central square, but with the rook on d1 and the queen on d2, the knight on d4 is not yet sufficiently stable and Black has not completed development yet.  13.Nxd4  exd4  14.Bc4  .  Because of the double pin on the a2-g8 diagonal and on the d-file, Black cannot take on c3 or e3.  14...fxe4  15.Bxd4  Qxd4  16.Qxd4  Bxd4  17.Rxd4  White has a winning endgame: he will soon cash the pawn on e4 while still being ahead in development. }
13. Bxh6
{ Oops, Nd6 simply dropped a pawn, basically it is game over: White has a better position, more active pieces and an extra pawn. }
13... f4 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Bb5 Bg4 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. Nxe5
{ This can hardly be called a sacrifice: yes, White gives up the exchange but he has already two pawns for it and Black has so many weak pawns. }
17... Bxd1 18. Qxd1 Nb7 19. Nxc6 Qd6 20. Qd5 f3 21. g3 Qxd5 22. Nxd5 Rae8
{ Black is completely desperate due to lack of counterplay. } 23. Re1 Re6 24.
Nd4 Re5 25. Nxc7 { Four pawns already for the exchange. } 25... Rc8 26. Nce6+
{ Black had enough and resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. Bloopers"]
[Black "Robert Hartoch vs. Michiel Abeln, Haarlem 2005"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d6 2. d4 f5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 g6 5. b3
{ This may look like a passive move but actually, it is just a transposition to one of the main lines. }
5... Bg7 6. Bb2 O-O 7. O-O Qe8 8. c4 c6
{ Instead of ...c6 the move  9...Na6  leads to a position that has occurred a lot in practice. In itself, ...c7-c6 is not bad, but next White plays a rare move and Black quickly loses the plot. }
9. Re1
{ Planning e2-e4 at some point and therefore Black should have played ...Ne4 here. If White exchanges knights on d2 or c3, Black is in time to play ...e7-e5. }
9... Na6 10. Nc3 Nc7
{ It may look like a standard move, but it is too slow, Black had to play  10...b5  . }
11. e4 fxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Rxe4 Bf5 14. Re3 Qd7
{ A bit passive.   Objectively best for Black was to play  14...Bh6  15.Re2  .  Of course, the rook can also go to e1, but it will be hard for White to put a lot of pressure on e7.  15...Bg4  and now there is a move repetition:  16.Re4  Bf5  17.Re2  resulting in a draw. }
15. Qe2 Bf6
{ It would have been more logical to defend with  15...Rae8  so that the rook also participates in the game. }
16. Re1 Rf7 17. d5 cxd5 18. Bxf6 exf6 19. Nd4
{ Black is in big trouble, he has lost control over the e-file. White can often take the bishop on f5 and enter with the rook on e7, while the bishop on g2 can take the pawn on b7. }
19... dxc4 20. Bxb7 Bd3
{ It is important to keep fighting and play intermediate moves. After all, it is a game between humans. }
21. Qf3 Raf8 22. Bc6
{ It would have been stronger to play  22.Bd5  Nxd5  23.Qxd5  with a winning advantage for White. }
22... Qh3 23. Qf4 f5 24. bxc4 Bxc4 25. f3
{ The position still looks horrible for Black.   White can play for a trick but it only results in an equal position.  25.Nxf5  Bd5  .  It is a complex position, on Ne7+ Black can take on e7.  26.Bxd5  Nxd5  27.Nh6+  .  This looks like winning for White, but it is not.  27...Kg7  ,  the only square.  28.Qd4+  ,  Black is just in time to take on h6, the knight back to f6 simply loses to Nxf7.  28...Kxh6  and now White cannot capture the knight on d5 because he will be mated after ...Rxf2.  29.Re4  ,  threatening mate with Rh4 and although ...Nf6 prevents the mate, Black would still lose the queen.  29...Nf4  ,  the only way to prevent Rh4+.  30.gxf4  with an equal position. }
25... Bd5 { It would have been stronger to play  25...Nd5  . } 26. Qxd6
{ The white rook to e8 or e7 was even stronger, but this is still winning. }
26... f4 { Black is trying to swindle. } 27. Bxd5
{ And it works, simply  27.gxf4  was winning, now the position is not so clear anymore. }
27... Nxd5 28. Re8 Nf6
{ A really bad move.   Black should have played  28...Ne3  29.Rxf8+  Rxf8  30.Qe6+  Qxe6  31.Nxe6  with a drawish endgame. Black was afraid he would be lost because of losing the f-pawn, but the engine points out Black has sufficient play after  31...Rc8  32.Nxf4  Rc3  . }
29. Rxf8+ Rxf8
{ White can play  30.Ne6  followed by Qc7, threatening mate, and Black is completely lost. }
30. Qxf4
{ A draw was offered, which Black of course accepted. Black is not immediately lost, but he is a pawn down without any form of compensation. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. Bloopers"]
[Black "Gediminas Sarakauskas vs. Michiel Abeln, La Fère 2003"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 f5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 g6 4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. Nc3 Qe8
{ Not ourrepertoire, but the type of position in this game is still relevant for the themes we study. }
8. b3 a5
{ I could not remember theory... maybe because of the stress of playing for @@StartBracket@@shared@@EndBracket@@ tournament victory? Both  8...e5  and  8...Na6  are main lines. }
9. Bb2 Na6 10. Qd2 c6 11. Rfe1 Nc7
{ Perhaps Black should have played the ...e7-e5 break.  11...e5  12.dxe5  dxe5  13.e4  but  13...f4  is not really a valid option here, so Black does have some problems  with the e5-pawn. }
12. Qc2
{ Instead, White could have stabilized his advantage by playing the natural  12.e4  . }
12... e5
{ Finally, but a bit late.   Black should have played  12...b5  and after  13.e4  fxe4  14.Nxe4  Bf5  15.Nxf6+  Bxf6  16.Qd2  Qf7  .  White has some advantage, Black doesn't have a lot of counterplay, but the game is also far from over. }
13. dxe5 dxe5 14. e4 Nh5 { Defending the pawn on e5 and dreaming of ...f5-f4. }
15. exf5
{ The engine says that putting pressure on the e5-pawn by playing  15.Na4  was even stronger. }
15... Bxf5 16. Ne4
{ The black e-pawn is securely blocked, the bishop on g7 is powerless and Black has some weak squares like d6, c5, and b6. Black's dream is to put a knight on d4, in some form of ...Ne6 and ...Bg4, without dropping the pawn on e5, would be ideal. }
16... Qe7 { An immediate  16...Bg4  drops the  pawn on e5 after  17.Nd6  . }
17. Qc3 Rfe8 18. Rad1 Bg4
{ Pretending Black is threatening something, but the engine knows no mercy and shows that even  19.h3  would have resulted in a large advantage for White. }
19. Qc1 Ne6 20. Ba3 c5 { The black queen has almost no good square to go to. }
21. Rd5 Bxf3 22. Bxf3 b6
{ Black is still hoping to escape by putting the knight on d4. } 23. Qd1 Nd4
{ The pawn on h5 is lost because  23...Nf6  fails to simply  24.Rxe5  . } 24.
Bxh5 gxh5 25. Qxh5 Rf8
{ Black could have won a piece, but still lost the game.  25...Nc2  26.Red1  Nxa3  27.Rd7  Qf8  28.Ng5  ,  threatening mate on h7.  28...h6  29.Rf7  hxg5  30.Rxf8+  Rxf8  31.Rd7  ,  with a winning attack. }
26. Rd1
{ Black has the knight on d4, but is a pawn down, has an inactive bishop on g7 and the king is vulnerable as well. }
26... Rf5 27. Qg4 Raf8 { Blundering a piece. } 28. R1xd4
{ Oooops! The c-pawn is pinned by the bishop on a3 and the e-pawn is pinned by the rook on d5 that would happily take the rook on f5. }
28... h5 29. Qg6 Rxf2 30. Rd7
{ Black had enough of this disappointing final round game. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. Bloopers"]
[Black "Oleg Romanishin vs. Michiel Abeln, Aosta 2004"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. b3 d6 7. Bb2 Qe8
{ Black could also have played  7...c6  . } 8. c4 c6 9. d5 Bd7 10. Nc3 Na6 11.
Rc1 Rc8 12. Nd4
{ After this game, I looked at this variation in-depth and I believe that  12.Ne1  is far better than  12.Nd4  . In fact, after  12.Ne1  I think White has a nice advantage, which is one of the reasons why I don't trust the Leningrad as much as when I started playing it a year ago. }
12... Nc7
{ Kramnik played in his younger  12...Qf7  and maybe that is more precise.  The standard plan of taking on d5, putting a knight on e4, and playing ...b7-b5 is not effective.  @@StartFEN@@2r1qrk1/pp1bp1bp/n1pp1np1/3P1p2/2PN4/1PN3P1/PB2PPBP/2RQ1RK1 b - - 6 12@@EndFEN@@  12...cxd5  13.Nxd5  and White has some annoying pressure because taking on d5 is not possible due to Bxd5+ and the pawn on b7 drops and if Black plays  13...Nc5  White has the strong  14.Nb5  . }
13. Qd2 c5 14. Nc2 b5
{ Maybe it was stronger to play first  14...a6  so that Black can always recapture on b5 with a pawn without giving up control over the c4-square.  15.Rfe1  b5  ,  Black has sufficient counterplay. }
15. cxb5 Nxb5 16. Nxb5 Bxb5 17. Na3 Bd7 18. Nc4
{ White is slightly better with a nice knight on c4 and no weaknesses. The main problem is that it is not so easy for Black to become active. }
18... Qf7 19. f4
{ Stopping any ...f5-f4 ideas from Black, but it is a bit too drastic and Black had a good chance to equalize. }
19... Rb8
{ Not bad, but Black had a stronger option.   The first part is easy to see:  19...Ne4  20.Qd3  Bxb2  21.Nxb2  but only here you start to realize that after  21...Nf6  White doesn't have any concrete plan anymore, Black is fine. }
20. Ne5 { Missed by Black, but luckily not a disaster. } 20... Qe8 21. Nxd7
Qxd7
{ White has obtained the pair of bishops, but it doesn't mean much here, it is hard for White to activate the bishop on g2. }
22. Rc4 Rb5 { A strange move, it prevents Qa5 but that was not a threat. } 23.
Re1 Rfb8
{ Black is doing nothing, which is not good. The rooks on the b-file are not threatening much. }
24. Bc3 { And now ...Rb4 is no longer an option for Black. } 24... R8b7 25. Qd3
Ne8 26. Bd2
{ White doesn't exchange bishops because he would lose control over the square b4. }
26... Nf6 27. Bf3
{ We now get to a phase where both sides are not doing much. } 27... R5b6 28.
e3 Ra6 29. Rc2 Rab6 30. Re2 Kf8 31. Rc4 Rb5 32. Ra4
{ This would have been a good moment for White to start the action with h2-h3, Rg2, and g3-g4, Black is so passive that he will end up with a lost position. }
32... R5b6 33. Kg2 Qc8 34. Ba5 Rb5 35. Bc3 Ne8 36. Be1 Nf6 37. h3 Qd7 38. Kh2
R5b6 39. Rg2 { Finally White has found the winning plan. } 39... Rb8 40. g4
R6b7 41. gxf5 Qxf5
{ Taking back with the pawn on f5 makes the black king vulnerable for a white attack after Bc3 and e3-e4. }
42. Qxf5 gxf5 43. Rg5 { The pawn on f5 is doomed. } 43... Bh6 44. Rxf5 Kg7 45.
Rc4 Kg6 46. e4 { Black had suffered enough for the day. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. Bloopers"]
[Black "Igor Naumkin vs. Michiel Abeln, Capelle la Grande 2007"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. c4 O-O 6. Nc3 d6 7. d5
{ This was a new move for me. } 7... c6 8. Nd4 Bd7
{ A serious alternative was to take on d5:  8...cxd5  9.cxd5  Na6  10.O-O  Nc5  and Black doesn't have any major problems. }
9. O-O c5
{ I am not sure about the combination of ...c6-c5 and ...Bd7. If I wanted to play ...c5, I should have played it instead of 8...Bd7 as there is no guarantee that the bishop is well-placed on d7. }
10. Nc2 Na6 11. h3 { A slow move, Black wasn't threatening ...Ng4. } 11... Nc7
12. a4 { Blocking ...b7-b5. } 12... Rb8 13. Re1 a6
{ There was an alternative:  13...b6  .  In this way Black can usually get ...b5 in after first ...b7-b6, then ...a7-a6 and then finally ...b6-b5, but it takes three moves, so it is a slow approach. Still, it seems that Black had the time here to do it.  14.e4  ,  the only way for White to prove that Black is too slow.  14...Nxe4  15.Nxe4  fxe4  16.Rxe4  a6  .  Black continues with his ...b5 plan.  17.Bg5  Rf7  18.Qe2  Bf6  19.Bxf6  exf6  and Black is okay, he can next play ...f6-f5, maybe ...Qf6 and one day throw in ...b6-b5. }
14. a5 Qe8
{ Not a great move, the queen is now opposite the rook on e1, and if it moves later to f7 it is still not too threatening because the d5-pawn is well-defended by the c4-pawn.   If you say A, you also have to say B: Black had to play  14...b5  15.axb6  Rxb6  16.Ra2  Qb8  and maybe White has a tiny edge because after playing e2-e4, he can create some pressure against the e7-pawn, but Black can defend that pawn quite easily. }
15. e4 fxe4 16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. Rxe4 Qf7 18. Re2 b5
{ At least there is some logic in Black's play: first, put pressure on f2, and then play on the queenside. }
19. axb6 Rxb6 20. Ne3
{ A somewhat strange move, the simple  20.Qe1  followed by Ra3 and possibly later Ra3-e3 or Ra3-f3 could create quite some pressure. }
20... Rfb8 21. Ra2 Bd4
{ Maybe first playing  21...Rb4  so that the white queen needs to defend c4 was stronger. }
22. Qe1 h5
{ Preventing ...Ng4 ideas, but a pawn never moves back, so this is quite a commitment on Black's kingside.   Black had a real opportunity to free himself here:  22...e5  23.dxe6  Bxe6  and we have a complex position that is maybe a little better for White but it is not a lot. Black can either try to win the c-pawn or play for ...d6-d5 at some point. }
23. Nd1 Bf6
{ 23...e5  was still good here, but I was afraid of a tactical trick:  24.dxe6  Bxe6  25.Rxe6  Nxe6  26.Bd5  and wins for White I thought, but no, Black also has a trick.  26...Kh7!  How cool, don't defend the piece, just step away with the king.  27.b4  ,  White's idea is to play Re2.   Taking the piece immediately is not good:  27.Qxe6  Qxe6  28.Bxe6  Re8  and Black wins back the piece because if the bishop moves to d5 there is a rook check on e1.  27...Re8  28.Re2  .  White wins the piece after all, but it is not the end yet.  28...Rxb4  29.Rxe6  Rxe6  30.Bxe6  Qe8  .  White's bishop is in a pin and Black is threatening to win material with Rb1.  31.Qe4  ,  defending the b1-square.  31...d5  and another trick. If White takes now with the bishop on d5, Black will swap queens and take the pawn on c4 with the rook. The resulting endgame is about equal.  32.cxd5  Bxf2+  ,  winning a queen against three minor pieces.  33.Nxf2  Rxe4  34.Nxe4  Qa4  .   And that is the final trick of this line: from a material point of view White is doing great, probably winning with the three minor pieces and passed d-pawn @@StartBracket@@which is a lot faster than Black's a-pawn@@EndBracket@@. The problem is that after ...Qa4, White has to accept a perpetual check with a draw or he will lose material @@StartBracket@@e.g. Nf2 is answered by ...Qa1@@EndBracket@@ and the game. }
24. Bd2 Bf5
{ There is not a lot Black can do, he has two weaknesses, e7 and a6, that he needs to defend. The good thing is that for White it is also hard to improve the position and he also needs to watch the pawns on b2 and h3. }
25. Ba5 R6b7 26. Ra3 Ne8
{ The knight wasn't great on c7, but on the kingside, there is also no great future. }
27. Rae3 Kf8 28. Bc3 Bxc3 29. Qxc3 Nf6
{ It would have been more logical to fight for the dark squares with  29...Qf6  . }
30. f3
{ Finally White is going for it. On the queenside, he cannot make any progress, so first exchanging the dark-squared bishops and now this advance is the only real winning attempt. }
30... Ng8
{ It is such a complex position, it would have been best to play  30...g5  but I did not consider this move at all, I was afraid to give up the e6-square.  31.g4  Bh7  and the position is about equal. If White ever wants to push f3-f4 Black can play ...Ke8 and ...Nd7, and after taking on f4 play ...Ne5. There is no attack for White. }
31. g4 Bc8 32. Qc2 Qf6 33. Re4 Kg7
{ Black had a nice idea of bringing the knight to e5 via h6 and f7. } 34. Qc1
Kh8 35. Nc3 Rb4 36. Rf4 Qg7 37. Bf1 Nf6
{ Not a good move because now White could have played  38.Ne4  and Black cannot take that knight since the e7-pawn would be lost. This is the disadvantage of putting the king on h8 − too far from f8 to help defend the weak e-pawn. }
38. g5 Nd7 39. Rfe4 Ne5
{ I am not sure I realized what I was doing here. Black is fine, but the position is also dangerous! }
40. Rxe5
{ A clear error.   40.f4  was the way to go.  40...Nf3+  is the only move! I am not sure if in my calculations I realized that taking on c4 with the knight results in a lost position for Black after Rxe7. It is not easy to assess/calculate, but the engine has no doubt.  41.Kf2  ,  also the only move! Any other square for the king loses for White.  41...Nd4  42.Rxe7  Nxe2  43.Qe3  ,  an incredible move and this is the reason why Kf2 was the only move. With the king on g2, Black would now play ...Nxf4+.  43...Nxc3  44.bxc3  R4b7  45.Rxg7  Kxg7  .  The engine says it is equal, but I would still prefer Black with the long-term chances based on the a-pawn. }
40... dxe5 41. Ne4 a5
{ Not a bad move, but Black could have played more actively with either  41...Bf5  or  41...Qf8  . }
42. Rf2 a4 { Black is threatening ...a4-a3 followed by ...Rb1. } 43. Qc3
{ After  43.Nxc5  Black has  43...e4  followed by ...Rxb2. } 43... Rb3 44. Qa5
a3
{ Black has played a series of strong moves but here he completely forgets about this back rank. Simply playing  44...Bf5  so that White would never have a  check on d8 would have resulted in a win. }
45. bxa3 Rb1
{ A blunder, losing the game. The check on d8 had to be prevented, so again  45...Bf5  was called for. }
46. Qd8+ Kh7 { If Black plays  46...Qg8  , the game is lost after  47.Qxe7  . }
47. d6
{ Completely missed by Black who was dreaming of ...Bxh3. Soon White will play Nf6+ so Black resigned. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. Bloopers"]
[Black "Gert Ligterink vs. Michiel Abeln, Groningen 2004"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. g3 O-O 6. Bg2 d6 7. O-O c6 8. d5 Bd7
{ A sideline that results in similar play as in the main line with  8...e5  . }
9. Rb1 a5 10. Nd4 Qb6
{ Black's main idea is to slow White down in his actions on the queenside. }
11. e3
{ Not very challenging. The reason I don't trust this line for Black is  11.Be3  @@StartBracket@@I didn't know before the game@@EndBracket@@. }
11... Na6 12. b3 Nc5 13. Bb2 Rad8
{ Black plays for the standard plan with ...e7-e5. Perhaps it would have been better to maintain central tension with  13...Nce4  . }
14. Qc2 e5 15. dxe6 Nxe6 16. Nxe6 Bxe6
{ I thought Black would be OK here, he can defend the pawn on d6 and prepare ...d6-d5, but the engine believes White has a clear advantage. }
17. Rfd1 Rf7 18. Rd2 Rfd7 19. Rbd1
{ White could have played  19.Na4  and after  19...Qc7  , the move  20.Bd4  , threatening to win an exchange, is annoying. A lesson learned for me after the game,  to be careful with playing ...a7-a5 in the Leningrad because it weakens the b6-square. }
19... Qa6 20. Ne2 a4
{ Trying to create some counterplay, but this is more logical with a rook on a8 than a queen. If Black exchanges on b3, the move Ra2 could be strong, while the queen can always be chased away with Ra1. }
21. Bd4 Ne8 22. Bxg7 Nxg7 23. Qc3 axb3 24. axb3 Qb6
{ Black has zero counterplay, it is really sad. } 25. Nf4 Bf7 26. h4 Ne6
{ Moving the knight back to e8 to protect the f6-square was relatively best, but even then White has a large advantage. }
27. Nxe6 Bxe6 28. Qf6 { Oops, someone comes visiting! } 28... Bf7 29. h5 Qxb3
{ Fully realizing Black's position is lost, Black activates the queen in the hope to swindle. }
30. hxg6
{ Not the right route,  30.e4  to bring the bishop into the attack was the way to proceed. }
30... hxg6
{ This is so bad, Black missed that the h-file needs to stay closed so taking with the bishop was the only move. }
31. Rd4
{ White misses a really nice move:  31.Bd5!  with the idea to play Kg2 and Rh1 with mate. }
31... Be8
{ Black could have made it a little harder for White to win by pinning the rook with  31...Qc3  . }
32. Bf3 Ra8 33. Rh4 { White is completely winning. } 33... Rg7 34. Kg2 g5 35.
Rh6 { White could have forced mate with Rh8 followed by Qf8+ and Rh1+. } 35...
g4 36. Bd5+ { Black resigned, mate will follow soon after Rdh1. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. Bloopers"]
[Black "Robert Zysk vs. Michiel Abeln, Deizisau 2005"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. Nf3 g6 4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. Nc3 c6 8. d5 e5
9. dxe6 Bxe6 10. Bf4
{ This move is rarely played, theory has established that Black has no problems. }
10... Bxc4 11. Bxd6 Re8 12. Ne5 Be6 13. Rc1 Nbd7
{ So far Black's moves were pretty obvious. } 14. Nd3 Ng4
{ A bit of a strange move, not bad, but it would have been simpler to play  14...Nb6  with  the idea of ...Nc4 or ...Nbd5. }
15. Ba3 Nge5
{ Black is threatening ...Nc4 and the bishop on a3 would be in trouble, so White prevents the knight jump. }
16. b3 Nxd3
{ Both knights want to be on e5 so it makes sense to exchange one and the other one can come to e5. An additional benefit is that the diagonal of the g7-bishop is now open. }
17. Qxd3 Qa5
{ Playing  17...Ne5  was also okay, but Black didn't want to exchange queens and looks for more active play. }
18. Bb2 Rad8
{ Easy move to make, bring your rook to an open file, opposite the white queen. }
19. Qc2 Nf6
{ The position is a bit boring because both sides are very solid, so it is hard to come up with a constructive plan. It makes sense to remove the knight from d7 so the rook has an open file. The knight can come to e5 but with the pawns on e2 and b3, there is not a lot of potential for the e5-knight. From f6 at least the knight controls e4 @@StartBracket@@in case White wants to play e2-e4, there will be a lot of exchanges@@EndBracket@@ and the knight can come to d5. }
20. a3
{ White is preparing a minority attack with his pawns on the queenside, dreaming of b3-b4 and then b4-b5 at some point, and create a weak c-pawn on Black's side. }
20... Qc7 21. Nb5
{ A blunder, White loses material after this move. The normal move would have been  21.Na4  followed by b3-b4. }
21... Qb6
{ White must have missed this move. Either the pawn on b3 falls or Black gets two pieces for the rook. }
22. Nd4 Rxd4 23. Bxd4 Qxd4 24. Rfd1 Qb6 25. b4
{ Black has a completely winning position, the two minor pieces are much stronger than White's extra rook. }
25... Bd5 26. Bxd5+ Nxd5 27. Qc4
{ White not only pins the knight but also threatens b4-b5. } 27... Re4 28. Qa2
h5 29. e3 Kh7 { So far Black is playing perfectly. } 30. Rd3 Nxe3
{ And that is an extra pawn on top of the material plus Black already had. }
31. Rd7
{ A rook on the seventh is always a bit scary.   If White plays here  31.fxe3  he loses after  31...Rxe3  because White cannot  take on e3 @@StartBracket@@it would lose the rook on c1 after ...Qxe3+@@EndBracket@@ and if the rook moves, Black gives check with either ...Re2 or ...Re1, winning at least a rook. }
31... Nd5
{ Black could have improved with  31...Ng4  ,  keeping an eye on the f2-pawn.  32.Qb2  ,  White cannot really benefit from the pin on the 7th rank because of Black's next move.  32...Rd4  and all problems solved.  33.Qxd4  Qxd4  34.Rxd4  Bxd4  ,  with a completely winning endgame. }
32. Rd1
{ It would have been best for Black to step out of the pin with  32...Kh6  and if White plays  33.Qd2+  , Black can respond with  33...f4  . }
32... Rd4 { A blunder, now the game is equal again. } 33. Rxg7+
{ Completely missed by Black. } 33... Kh8
{ And another blunder, Black had to play  33...Kh6  to keep protecting the pawn on g6. }
34. Rxd4 Qxd4
{ And now White can simply win with  35.Rxg6  , Black's kingside completely collapses. }
35. Rxb7
{ After this blunder by White it is equal again, Black can make a draw with a simple sacrifice. }
35... Qd1+ 36. Kg2 Nf4+ { The move White must have missed. } 37. gxf4 Qg4+
{ And perpetual check, there is no way for White to escape. } 38. Kf1 Qd1+ 39.
Kg2 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. Learn from Your Own Games"]
[Black "Adrien Levacic vs. Michiel Abeln, Ohrid 2009"]
[Result "*"]

{ I have been playing the Leningrad System for many years and despite the mistakes that you can see in theBloopers chapter, I have also scored a lot of points with Black. In this chapter, I want to show you some of these games.  The intention is not to impress you because the careful analysis will tell you that there were many ups and downs in these games. I want to use these moments to show you, at an amateur level, what typical Leningrad games look like, what are the things to focus on when you don’t play at grandmaster level, when you cannot calculate 10-move deep tactics, but you still want to enjoy and win games with the Leningrad System. }
1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. c4 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Nf3 d6 7. O-O Nc6
{ A slightly dubious but aggressive system. } 8. b3 e5 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Ba3 Re8
{ 10...e4  has the idea to win two pieces for the rook but it doesn't work.  11.Bxf8  exf3  .  Taking back on f8 means Black will be a full exchange down without sufficient compensation.  12.Bxg7  fxg2  ,  if White would now take on g2, Black's plan would succeed, he can take the bishop on g7 and have a clear advantage with knight and bishop for the rook. But White doesn't have to take on g2.  13.Qxd8+  Nxd8  14.Rfd1  and White is winning, he keeps extra material.   Taking on d1 is not correct:  10...Qxd1  11.Raxd1  Re8  12.Nb5  and the pawn on c7 will drop. }
11. Qxd8 Rxd8
{ Taking with the knight was a valid alternative:  11...Nxd8  12.Nb5  .  It may seem as if White now wins the pawn on e5, but it is poisoned.  12...Ne6  13.Nxe5  a6  14.Nc3  Ne4  15.Nxe4  fxe4  and White is losing material. }
12. e4 { This is a tricky position for a Black player: what to do? } 12... Nd4
{ It is not bad to develop the knight but I played it with some hesitation because the bishop on c8 is not yet developed.   Developing the bishop is not bad but doesn't look natural:  12...Be6  13.Ng5  .  Perhaps this was Black's best option, just to play ...Bd7, at least all the pieces are coordinated.   After  12...fxe4  ,  the engine says this is okay for Black, but White has  13.Ng5  Bf5  14.Ngxe4  and I don't like the look of the pawn on e5 with the bishop on g7 and the powerful knight on e4.   12...a6  is preventing Nb5 but is really slow and White can also attack the pawn on c7 with a future Nd5.  13.Rad1  ,  again the engine says it is okay for Black, but to the human eye it seems that Rad1 was more useful than ...a7-a6.   The idea of  12...h6  is to play next ...Be6 because there is no more Ng5.  13.Nh4  and suddenly White has a clear advantage since both the pawn on g6 and f5 have become weak. }
13. Rad1 { Taking on e5 is not correct:  13.Nxe5  Nxe4  14.Nxe4  fxe4  . }
13... c6 14. exf5
{ White could have taken on e5:  14.Nxe5  Nxe4  15.Nxe4  fxe4  16.f4  exf3  17.Nxf3  Bg4  and maybe Black is a little better because of the activity of the pieces, but with the symmetrical pawn structure, the chances for a draw are high. }
14... Nxf3+ 15. Bxf3 Bxf5
{ Of course, Black wants to develop a piece and not play  15...Rxd1  16.Rxd1  gxf5  17.Rd8+  when White has a clear advantage. }
16. Be7 Rd4 17. Rfe1 Nd7
{ Giving up the e4-square is not great, but Black wanted to take some risk to unbalance the position. }
18. Ne4 Bxe4 19. Bxe4 a5
{ With the idea to create counterplay on the queenside. } 20. Bf3
{ If White blocks with  20.a4  ,  the pawn on b3 can become weak. } 20... a4
{ Again Black takes risk. The logical continuation would have been to fight for the dark squares.   20...Bf8  21.Bxf8  Rxf8  22.Bg4  .  This move is the reason Black did not play ...Bf8, there is no way for Black to escape to a drawish position.  22...Rd8  23.Rxd4  exd4  24.Bxd7  Rxd7  and it will be hard to create winning chances. }
21. Bg4 { White had also a good option in  21.b4  . } 21... Nf8
{ First taking on b3 would have been more exact because White can then no longer block with b3-b4. }
22. Bxf8
{ White should have played:  22.Rxd4  exd4  23.b4  ,  with a clear advantage. }
22... Bxf8 23. Be6+ Kg7 24. Rxd4 exd4
{ Bishops of the opposite color, White must have thought he was close to a draw. }
25. Rd1
{ Black is hoping to land the rook on e2 to create pressure against f2 and a2. Ideally, that should happen when the pawn reaches a3, so that it can become a passed pawn. The problem is that to make these dreams come true, Black needs to play ...a4-a3, ...Bf8-c5, ...h7-h5 @@StartBracket@@to prevent a bishop on g4, protecting the square e2@@EndBracket@@, ...Re8 and then ...Re2. This is a lot of moves and White has time to prevent this. It is not obvious what the right move order for Black is. }
25... Re8
{ What else? If Black plays  25...Bc5  to defend  the pawn on d4, White could consider  26.b4  . Maybe activating the king with @@StartFEN@@r4b2/1p4kp/2p1B1p1/8/p1Pp4/1P4P1/P4P1P/3R2K1 b - - 1 25@@EndFEN@@  25...Kf6  would have been best. }
26. Bd7
{ Clearly White should have played  26.Bg4  to take control over the e2-square, but even after the game move, White can still make a draw. }
26... Re2 27. Rxd4
{ This is the real blunder. Had White taken  27.bxa4  , the game would likely have ended in a draw. }
27... a3
{ Black could also have started with  27...Bc5  , both moves give a winning advantage. }
28. Rd1 Rxa2 { The pawn on a3 is a monster. } 29. Be6 Bc5
{ And that is the end of f2. } 30. b4 Bxf2+ 31. Kf1 c5
{ It is important to block the white pawn on c4 so that White cannot play c4-c5 and get control over a2 to stop Black's a-pawn. }
32. bxc5 Bxc5 33. Bd7 Rxh2
{ White resigned, he is not only two pawns down, but the a-pawn is also ready to promote. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. Learn from Your Own Games"]
[Black "Wim Heemskerk vs. Michiel Abeln, Leiden 2008"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. c4 f5
{ The Leningrad setup against the English. } 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. d3
{ Note that up to here White still had the choice to transpose to one of the main lines in the Leningrad System by playing  6.d4  . }
6... O-O 7. O-O Nc6 8. Rb1 a5 9. a3 Nh5 10. Bd2 f4 11. b4 axb4 12. axb4 Bg4 13.
Nd5 e5
{ I was out of book but both the game move as well as  13...fxg5  have been played multiple times. }
14. b5 Ne7 15. Qb3
{ This move is rare, most other games continue with  15.Ng5  . } 15... Kh8
{ The engine likes  15...Nxd5  better, but I find it hard to assess when to take on d5 @@StartBracket@@opening the c-file for White but reducing the power of the g2-bishop@@EndBracket@@ and when not. }
16. Bc3 { White could have improved by playing  16.b6  . } 16... Qd7 17. c5
{ Not a good move, maybe White missed the bishop retreat? He should have taken on e7. }
17... Be6 { A nasty pin. } 18. Ng5 Bg8 { The bishop is completely safe here. }
19. cxd6 cxd6 20. Nb6 Qd8 21. Nc4
{ White has managed to save the knight, but it comes at a price. } 21... Nc8
{ Black had a much stronger continuation:  21...fxg3  22.hxg3  Nf5  23.Nf3  d5  and White loses material because if the knight on c4 moves, Black has ...d5-d4, attacking both the bishop on c3 and the queen with the bishop on g8. }
22. Nf3 d5 23. Bxe5
{ Taking with the f3-knight was to be preferred, but Black will still play with an extra piece. }
23... dxc4 24. dxc4
{ Black is a piece up against two pawns. It should be winning, but Black needs to play almost as if he didn't have an extra piece: maximize the power of the pieces and try to win material @@StartBracket@@e.g. a pawn@@EndBracket@@. }
24... Qe7 25. Qc3 Nb6 { It turns out that the c-pawn is a bit weak. } 26. c5
Na4 27. Qd4 Qxc5 { Now White has very little compensation for the piece. } 28.
Qxc5 Nxc5 29. Bd6 Rfc8 30. Bh3
{ White is trying to trick Black but he has a simple response. } 30... Be6
{ And White has nothing. } 31. Bg2 Ne4 32. Be5 fxg3 33. hxg3 Nhf6 34. Rbc1 Bd5
{ Black keeps on activating the pieces. } 35. Nd4 Nd7
{ Exchanges are fine for Black with the extra piece against one pawn. } 36.
Bxg7+ Kxg7 37. Bh3 Rxc1 38. Rxc1 Ndf6 39. Rc7+ Kh6 40. f3 Ng5
{ Taking on g3 was also winning. } 41. Bg2 Ra4 42. e3 Ra1+ 43. Kh2 Ra2
{ Black is threatening to take on f3. } 44. Kg1 Rd2 45. Re7 Ng4
{ White resigned since more material will be shed. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. Learn from Your Own Games"]
[Black "Mark Lamprecht vs. Michiel Abeln, Schwäbisch Gmünd 2005"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 d6 2. Nc3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 e5
{ Not a move I recommend in our repertoire but soon we will be in familiar territory. }
5. e3 f5 6. d3
{ In this type of position I dorecommend for Black to put the pawns on e5 and f5. }
6... Nf6 7. Nge2 a5 { Preventing a direct b2-b4. } 8. Rb1 O-O 9. O-O c6
{ Considering White's bishop on c1 and the knight on e2 which exercise control over f4, it is unlikely Black will be able to push ...f5-f4 any time soon. The alternative plan of building a strong center with ...c7-c6 followed by ...d6-d5 is logical, especially since there is no pressure on Black's e5-pawn. }
10. a3 Be6 11. b4 axb4 12. axb4 d5
{ This position has been reached a few times in practice and usually White takes on d5. }
13. d4 e4 { Of course, the only reasonable move. } 14. c5
{ Again,  14.cxd5  would lead to a position seen before in practice. } 14... g5
{ For a number of moves Black decides to leave his knight on b8 so that if White, after b4-b5, takes on c6, he has the option to take back with the knight on c6. The engine doesn't approve and prefers normal development with the knight to d7 or even a6. }
15. b5 Qe8
{ It is unlikely that with the queen on h5 Black will be able to deliver mate soon. But that will weaken White's kingside a bit, which is something Black might be able to benefit from later. }
16. Rb4 { A strange move, something like  16.Bd2  is more natural. } 16... Qh5
{ Instead of this logical move Black also had the creative option of  16...Bf7  with the idea of ...Bh5 followed by ...Bf3 and only then ...Qh5. }
17. Bd2 Ng4
{ Black can sacrifice a pawn with  17...f4  , but White can defend against the attack at any point with  18.f3  and will remain a healthy pawn up. }
18. h3 Nf6
{ Black has lost two tempi with his knight to provoke h2-h3, but White now always needs to watch for ...f5-f4 followed by ...Bxh3. }
19. Kh2 Bh6 20. Nc1 Qf7 21. N1e2 Qc7
{ Black insists on preparing ...f5-f4, but developing the b8-knight was stronger. }
22. Kg1
{ White could also have played more actively with  22.Qb3  followed by taking on c6 and after ...bxc6 play Rb7, but the engine says the position is still equal. }
22... Nh5 23. Nf4 { This move was missed by Black. } 23... Nxf4
{ The only move, Black cannot allow Qxh5. } 24. exf4 gxf4 25. Qh5
{ This is not good, White should have played  25.Qc1  so that the bishop on h6 is pinned and, at a later stage, he can take on f4. }
25... Qg7 26. Bxf4 Bxf4 27. gxf4
{ The engine says Black has a clear advantage, but that is not how it felt during the game. }
27... Kh8 28. Qg5 Qf7 { 28...Qxg5  was also a good option. } 29. Rfb1 Rg8 30.
Qh4 Ra3
{ Incorrect, Black should have simply played  30...Qg7  or  30...Qg6  and White is forced to play an endgame a pawn down after  31.Qg5  . }
31. R1b3
{ A blunder, White had to play  31.Ne2  , although even then Black has a clear advantage. }
31... Rxb3 32. Rxb3 Qg7 33. Qg5 Qxd4 34. bxc6 Rxg5 { And White resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. Learn from Your Own Games"]
[Black "Raoul Van Ketel vs. Michiel Abeln, Bussum 2003"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 d5 4. Bxf6 exf6 5. e3 Be6 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. Qf3 Qd7 8.
Nge2 O-O-O 9. O-O-O Kb8 { 9...Nb4  was a serious alternative. } 10. Nf4 Bf7 11.
Bb5 Bb4 12. Nce2 a6 13. Ba4 Qe8
{ A strange move. More constructive would have been  13...h5  . } 14. Ng3 g6
15. c3 Bd6 16. Rhe1 b5
{ Playing on the other side with  16...h5  was stronger. } 17. Bc2 Ne7 18. Rd2
h5 { Black's position seems easier to play. } 19. Qe2 h4 20. Nf1 g5 21. Nd3 Bh5
22. f3 g4
{ Too impatient. Black should have played something like  22...Qc6  followed by ...a6-a5, there is not much White can do. }
23. Nc5
{ Not the right moment for this jump, White should have done nothing, so a move like  23.Qf2  . }
23... Bxc5 24. dxc5 Qc6
{ Not the best. Black should have taken  24...gxf3  followed by ...Nc6-e5 and it will be hard for White to defend the f3-pawn. }
25. b4 h3 26. Ng3 hxg2 27. Nxh5
{ Instead,  27.f4  was called for, to maintain the balance. } 27... Rxh5 28.
Qxg2 Qe6 29. Qf1 Rdh8 { Suddenly White is in trouble. } 30. a4 c6
{ Too simple, spoiling a large part of the advantage. The move  30...d4  was winning because next Black will play ...Qa2, with a strong attack. }
31. Ree2 g3
{ Making use of the fact that  32.hxg3  fails to  32...Rh1  , winning the white queen. }
32. Qg1 Rh3 33. Kb2 Qe5
{ Black forgets to activate the knight, which was pretty simple:  33...Ng6  followed by ...Ne5. }
34. f4 Qc7 35. hxg3 { Suddenly White is a pawn up. } 35... Rh1 36. Qg2 a5 37.
Rd1 Rxd1 38. Bxd1 axb4 39. cxb4 bxa4 40. Bxa4 Qb7
{ Time trouble is over and Black has sufficient compensation for the pawn deficit. White's extra pawn is on e3 and it is going nowhere. }
41. Kb1 Qa6 42. Ra2 Qd3+ 43. Qc2
{ A blunder, the position would have been equal after  43.Kb2  . } 43... Qxe3
{ It would have been much stronger to start with  43...Rh1+  because the white  king is much more vulnerable on b2 than on a2. }
44. Rb2 { Now the king can hide on a2. } 44... Qa3
{ Threatening ...Rh1+. After  44...Qxg3  , White generates counterplay with  45.b5  . }
45. Qd1 d4 46. b5
{ A final blunder, White had to prevent ...Nd5 by playing  46.Bb3  . } 46...
Nd5 { White is lost, Black has a winning attack. } 47. bxc6+ Kc8 48. Qb3 Rh1+
49. Kc2 Rh2+ 50. Kc1 Qa1+ 51. Rb1 Rh1+ 52. Kc2 d3+
{ And White resigned, he is losing the rook. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. Learn from Your Own Games"]
[Black "Patrick Legrand vs. Michiel Abeln, Capelle la Grande 2003"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. Bg5 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. h4 h6
{ Ensuring that h4-h5 can be answered with ...g6-g5. } 5. Bf4 Nf6 6. Nf3 d6 7.
e3 Nc6 { First castling kingside was also OK. } 8. a3 e6 9. Bb5
{ I had expected  9.Bc4  since a2-a3 was played. } 9... Bd7 10. Qe2 a6 11. Bc4
Qe7 12. Bb3 e5 13. d5
{ Not a great move, White should have taken on e5:  13.dxe5  dxe5  14.Bh2  O-O-O  and Black more space. }
13... exf4
{ The simple13...Na5  followed by taking on b3 was maybe even stronger. } 14.
dxc6 Bxc6 15. exf4 Nh5
{ Black is winning a pawn because  16.g3  ,  to defend f4, doesn't work with the black bishop on c6. }
16. Qxe7+ Kxe7 17. Kd2 Nxf4
{ Black is a healthy pawn up and has a strong pair of bishops. } 18. Rhe1+ Kd7
19. Rg1 Rae8 { Rooks belong on open files. } 20. Rae1 g5
{ Sometimes we are afraid to exchange these beautiful bishops, but here it would have resulted in a simple, winning endgame.  20...Bxc3+  21.bxc3  Bxf3  22.gxf3  Rxe1  23.Rxe1  Re8  and White has no counterplay, is a pawn down, and has so many weak pawns that the game will not last much longer. }
21. hxg5 hxg5 22. Nxg5 Bh6 23. Nf7
{ Instead, White could have played  23.Rxe8  Rxe8  and then  24.Nf7  but Black remains on top after  24...Ne2+  ,  picking up the rook on g1. }
23... Nxg2+ 24. Kd1 Nxe1 25. Nxh8 Bf3+ { Suddenly White gets mated. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. Learn from Your Own Games"]
[Black "Lexy Ortega vs. Michiel Abeln, Aosta 2004"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 d5 4. Bxf6 exf6 5. e3 Be6 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. Qf3 Qd7 8.
a3 O-O-O 9. Nge2 g6 10. h3 h5 11. Nf4 Bf7
{ So far Black has played only standard moves. } 12. Bb5 Kb8 13. Nd3 Qe6
{ Perhaps it was more precise to first play  13...a6  and only after  14.Ba4  continue with  14...Qe6  and ...Na5. }
14. O-O
{ This is an extremely risky move. White is counting that his attack on the queenside will be quicker than Black's on the kingside. }
14... Na5 15. b4 Nc4 16. Rfd1 Nd6
{ The immediate  16...g5  was also a valid alternative. } 17. Nc5 Qc8
{ It feels a bit like Black is trying to organize his attack while all his pieces are on the back rank. }
18. a4 g5
{ Both sides have started running, but Black's attack looks more threatening because of the pawn on h3 and the queen on f3. Note that if White moves his queen, Black can consider first ...h5-h4 and only then ...g5-g4 to open the kingside and avoid White's h3-h4. }
19. g3 { No idea what White intended with this move. } 19... g4 20. hxg4 h4
{ The simple  20...hxg4  followed by ...Rh3 and the other rook to h8 was even stronger. }
21. Be2 hxg3 22. fxg3
{ If  22.Qxg3  , Black has  22...fxg4  with an unstoppable attack. } 22... Bh6
23. Nb5 Rhe8
{ Still winning, but first  23...fxg4  ,  and then ...Rde8 was stronger. } 24.
Ra3 fxg4 25. Qf2
{ After  25.Qxg4  f5  , the g-file can also be used for the attack. } 25... Ne4
26. Nxe4 Rxe4
{ Black is ready to put another rook on e8 and if needed, the queen on e6, to win e3. }
27. Qxf6 Bxe3+ 28. Kg2 Bg5
{ The simple  28...Be6  is equally strong, but this is a nice move to play! }
29. Qxg5 Rxe2+ 30. Kg1 Rh8
{ You don't need to calculate a lot to see that Black's attack must be winning. }
31. Re3 Reh2 32. Rf1 Bg6 33. Re6
{ Yes, this move was actually played, with two seconds on the clock, after which White resigned. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. Learn from Your Own Games"]
[Black "Gilles Gaignierre vs. Michiel Abeln, La Fère 2003"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. Bg5 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. e3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 O-O 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. c3
{ Defending the pawn on d4.   An immediate  7.e4?  loses the d4-pawn.  7...fxe4  8.Nxe4  Nxe4  9.Bxe4  d5  10.Bd3  Nxd4  and Black is a healthy pawn up. }
7... h6
{ First playing for ...e7-e5 via ...d7-d6 would have been more precise. } 8.
Bh4 { Taking on f6 was a lot more challenging. } 8... d6 9. h3 e5 10. dxe5 dxe5
11. Bc4+ Kh8 { Not clear whether the king is better on h7 or h8. } 12. Qc2 Qe8
{ This is a bit slow, Black should have grabbed the initiative with  12...g5  or  12...e4  followed by ...Ne5. }
13. O-O-O a6
{ The advance  13...e4  was still the way to go so that Black maintains control over the center. }
14. g4 b5
{ The right continuation and certainly not  14...g5  because White would take  15.Bxg5  followed by h3-h4 with a strong attack thanks to the bishop on c4. }
15. Bxf6
{ White could also have played  15.Be2  , but then after  15...g5  followed by ...f5-f4, the dark-squared bishop is out of the game. }
15... Bxf6 { Taking back with the rook was also a valid alternative. } 16. Bd5
Be6
{ 16...Rb8  with the threat of ...Ne7 attacking the d5-bishop was much stronger. }
17. Bxe6 Qxe6 18. gxf5 gxf5 19. Nb3
{ The pawn on a2 was hanging, but the simple  19.Kb1  was a better move because the knight on b3 can easily be attacked with ...a6-a5. }
19... Ne7 { As said,  19...a5  came into consideration. } 20. Nc5
{ White blunders material, a move like  20.e4  was the way to go. } 20... Qc6
{ Suddenly there are two knights under attack. } 21. Nxe5 Qxc5
{ Maybe taking the knight on e5 with the bishop was a little better, but the game move is not bad either. }
22. Nd7 Qc6 23. Nxf8 Rxf8
{ We have reached a situation of unbalanced material. Black has two minor pieces for a rook and a pawn. In the long run, Black may have some advantage, but for now White should activate the rooks on the open files as soon as possible. }
24. Rhg1 a5 { Hoping to create some form of an attack. } 25. Qe2
{ This is an error, the queen should not have moved away from the king and the pawn on c3. Had White played something like  25.Kb1  , the situation would have remained unclear. }
25... b4 26. c4 a4 27. Rd2 a3 28. b3
{ An important theme in the Leningrad system: especially if White has castled queenside, the opening of the long diagonal of the g7-bishop can be nearly decisive. Just imagine a black queen here on f6... }
28... Bg7 29. Qd3 Qe6 { No  29...Qf6  yet because of  30.Qd4  . } 30. f3 f4
{ If now White plays  31.e4  or  31.exf4  ,  he will no longer control the square d4,  and  31...Qf6  will be decisive. }
31. Rxg7 { Desperation. } 31... Kxg7 { Black is a piece up for just one pawn. }
32. Rg2+ Kh8 33. e4 Qf6 { And the white king is still in trouble. } 34. Kb1 Rg8
35. Rxg8+ Nxg8
{ White resigned, with the mating threat on b2 his position is hopeless. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. Learn from Your Own Games"]
[Black "Roland Ruemmler vs. Michiel Abeln, Dresden 2003"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. Nc3
{ This setup was new for me. } 6... d6
{ Instead, ...d7-d5 with a Stonewall setup was also possible. The white knight on c3 stands in the way of the c2-pawn and therefore it will take much longer for White to create anything serious on the queenside. }
7. d5 c6
{ First  7...e5  and only  after dxe6, the move ...c7-c6 was more precise. } 8.
e4
{ Instead,  8.Nd4  was a good option so that if  Black plays ...e7-e5 @@StartBracket@@or ...e6@@EndBracket@@ White can regain the pawn but lose the pair of bishops. }
8... e5
{ Black had also a very different way of playing:  8...fxe4  9.Ng5  Bg4  10.Qd2  Qd7  11.Ngxe4  Nxe4  12.Nxe4  Na6  and the position is about equal. }
9. dxe6
{ White should probably have taken on  9.exf5  followed by Bg5 with a nasty pin. }
9... fxe4 10. Ng5 d5 11. f3
{ White could also have played  11.Nf7  followed by Nh6+, and to avoid perpetual check Black would need to give up the g7-bishop. }
11... h6
{ Black should have taken  11...exf3  and then start attacking the e6-pawn with ...Qe7 and ...Na6-c5 @@StartBracket@@or ...Nc7@@EndBracket@@ and is likely to be a pawn up soon. }
12. Nf7
{ White should have sacrificed a piece with  12.fxe4  , but it takes the engine more than 10 moves to show adequate compensation, impossible for a human to calculate. One can only play like that if having a good intuition for which sacrifices in the long term may work. }
12... Qb6+ 13. Kh1 Bxe6
{ Black has a large advantage with the strong center and the knight on f7 being in trouble. }
14. Nxh6+ Kh7 15. Ng4 Nxg4 16. fxg4 Nd7
{ From a strategic point of view, Black must be winning unless White can at some point sacrifice on e4 to create space for his pieces. }
17. Rf4 Ne5 18. h3 Nc4
{ Instead,  18...Rae8  was more appropriate, developing the rook and indirectly defending the pawn on e4. }
19. Qe1 Be5
{ Not a good move, often White can just sacrifice the rook on f4, so there is no threat after ...Be5. Again  19...Rae8  was the right way to go. }
20. Rb1 Qb4
{ It is never easy to give up your g7-bishop in the Leningrad System, but here it would have been really strong.  20...Bxc3  21.Qxc3  d4  22.Qe1  e3  and White is completely tied up. }
21. a3 Qd6 22. b3 Nxa3
{ Black has completely lost the plot and has thrown away a winning advantage. }
23. Bxa3
{ 23.Nxe4!  and White is fine.  23...dxe4  24.Bxa3  Qxa3  25.Rxe4  Bxg3  26.Qxg3  Bd5  .  The position is suddenly equal. }
23... Qxa3 24. Bxe4 { The wrong move order for White. } 24... dxe4 25. Qxe4
{ Taking with the rook on e4 now loses:  25.Rxe4  Bxc3  26.Qxc3  Bd5  and Black wins. }
25... Bxf4 26. gxf4 { Black is a full rook up. } 26... Rae8 27. Qd4 Qe7 28. Qf2
Qf6 { White has no threats so Black starts attacking. } 29. Ne2 Bd5+ 30. Kg1
Rxe2 { The simplest way to win. } 31. Qxe2 Qxf4
{ And White resigned, not only is he a piece down, but he will also soon be mated. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. Learn from Your Own Games"]
[Black "Raoul Van Ketel vs. Michiel Abeln, Haarlem 2006"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d6
{ I had played against the same opponent before and it was a 2.Nc3 Leningrad system. I figured that my opponent may repeat that 'safe' system and I was in a must-win situation for an IM norm. So I played a different move order, to reach the Leningrad Variation. }
2. c4 f5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5
{ I could not recall any theory, but the next few moves just seemed logical. }
4... Nbd7 5. Qc2 g6 6. e4 fxe4 7. Nxe4 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O
{ A risky decision − it is likely White will castle on the queenside and it is not clear whose attack will come first. }
9. Ng3 e5
{ Typical play for the Leningrad System, but  9...c5  was a good alternative with the idea to open the diagonal for the g7-bishop and potentially open more lines on the queenside in Volga-style with ...b7-b5 after White plays d4-d5. }
10. O-O-O
{ On  10.d5  Black can continue with  10...e4  11.Nd4  Nc5  with a sharp position. }
10... exd4
{ Of course Black takes on d4, now that the king is on the queenside it is essential to open the diagonal for the g7-bishop. }
11. Nxd4 Ne5 { The knight could also have gone to c5. } 12. Be2
{ A slow move, many other players would have played  12.h4  . } 12... a6
{ Preparing ...b7-b5, but the engine prefers  12...Nf7  ,  which was also played by Leningrad expert Malaniuk. }
13. h3 Bd7 { Preparing ...b7-b5. } 14. f4 Nf7
{ 14...Nc6  was also possible,  but in the Leningrad, the knight so often ends up on f7 that this also felt like a natural move to make. }
15. h4 Qe8
{ Since White played 14.f4 there is a nice square on e3 for the queen and if White prevents it, Black will be ready to play ...b7-b5. }
16. f5
{ This is just losing material, not clear what White missed in his calculations. }
16... Nxg5 17. hxg5 Qe3+ 18. Kb1
{ Equally bad is  18.Qd2  Qxg3  19.gxf6  Bxf6  20.Kb1  Bxd4  21.Qxd4  Bxf5+  and Black has a winning position. }
18... Qxg3 { This is good, but taking on  18...Qxg5  was even stronger. } 19.
gxf6 Rxf6 20. Bd3
{ Taking on g6 is not something White has time for:  20.fxg6  Rf2  ,  a nasty pin.  21.gxh7+  Kh8  .  The king is safe here behind White's h-pawn.  22.Rhf1  Re8  23.Rxf2  Qxf2  and White will lose more material. }
20... Raf8 21. Be4 c6
{ Black is a pawn up and has two strong bishops and the rooks are ready to enter on f2. }
22. Rh3 Qe5 23. g4 Qf4 24. Rb3 Re8 25. g5
{ A blunder by White, he probably missed the ...Bf5 threat. } 25... Rxe4 26.
gxf6 Rxd4
{ Black threatens to win the queen with ...Bf5, so White cannot take on g7. }
27. fxg6
{ But this doesn't help against the main threat. White was lost anyway. } 27...
Bf5 28. gxh7+ Bxh7 { And White resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. Learn from Your Own Games"]
[Black "Valerie Maupin vs. Michiel Abeln, La Fère 2003"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. c4 Nf6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. Nc3 Qe8
{ There was a time I played  7...Qe8  a lot more than  7...c6  but nowadays the queen move has gone out of fashion because it seems slightly dubious. }
8. d5 Na6 9. Nd4 Nc5
{ The main line is  9...Bd7  , but I wasn't sure behind the board, sometimes you cannot remember the exact line and the move I play is quite sensible. }
10. Rb1 a5 11. a3 Bd7 12. b3
{ A somewhat strange move, especially because soon White plays b3-b4, so losing a tempo. }
12... c6 13. dxc6
{ If White doesn't take, Black may take on d5 followed by ...Rc8, ...Nce4 and ...b7-b5. }
13... bxc6 14. b4
{ Logical but still with a loss of tempo because of White's 12th move. } 14...
axb4 15. axb4 Nce4 16. Nxe4 Nxe4
{ Black wants to take with the knight and not the pawn on e4 so the diagonal for the g7-bishop is opened and White would need to give up the g2-bishop to get rid of the knight. }
17. Qd3 Qf7
{ Black had a valid alternative in playing  17...c5  . White needs to take  18.bxc5  and after  18...Nxc5  Black can claim that  the pawn on c4 is a bit weak. }
18. Nf3
{ A passive move after which Black is better. It would have been more logical to play  18.b5  and after  18...c5  jump with the knight  19.Nc6  . }
18... Be6 19. Nd2 d5
{ Black misses a big opportunity: had he played  19...Ra2  White would have no moves and would have suddenly been lost. Black's threat  is to take on d2 with the knight and then on c4 with the bishop and White's pieces have no coordination and soon more material will be lost. }
20. cxd5 cxd5 21. Nf3 d4
{ Black has to play actively if White would manage to get a knight on d4 Black could easily end up worse. }
22. Bb2
{ A logical move but here it actually loses.   22.Ng5  was the way to play for White.  22...Nxg5  23.Bxa8  .  This is not good.   23.Bxg5  is what White should play to keep the balance.  23...Nh3+  White's king will be in an awkward place in order to regain the piece.  24.Kg2  Rxa8  25.Kxh3  Black has two fantastic bishops.  25...Bc4  26.Qd1  Qe6  27.Rb2  Ra1  and Black has a winning advantage because of the poor coordination of White's pieces and the king on h3.   The simple  22.Nxd4  fails to  22...Rad8  23.e3  Bc4  and Black wins an exchange. }
22... Bc4 23. Qd1 Ra2
{ 23...Rad8  followed by ...d4-d3 would have been even stronger. } 24. Re1 Rd8
25. Qc1 Nc3 { A dream position for any Leningrad player. } 26. Bxc3 dxc3 27. e3
c2 { White resigned, the rook has nowhere to go. } *

