21... Qb6
{ The white knight doesn't have any good squares, Black either wins an important pawn or gets two pieces for the rook. }
22. Nd4 { 22.Nc3  Bxb3  is bad for White because ...Rd2 is coming next. } 22...
Rxd4 23. Bxd4 Qxd4
{ Black's two minor pieces are much stronger than White's rook. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Puzzles"]
[Black "Puzzle 2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "7k/pR6/2p3p1/3n1p1p/1P1q4/P5P1/Q4P1P/6K1 b - - 0 35"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black's position is hopeless with the king in danger, an exchange down and no attack. But still, Black can escape. How? }
35... Qd1+ 36. Kg2 Nf4+ 37. gxf4 Qg4+ 38. Kf1 Qd1+ { Draw by perpetual check. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Puzzles"]
[Black "Puzzle 3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/4pqbp/2ppb1p1/5p2/1PP1n3/3Q2P1/3NPPBP/1RB2RK1 b - - 0 19"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black can increase the advantage significantly. How exactly? } 19... Ra2
{ White is zugzwang, it is hard to come up with a move, and not only the pawn on c4 will be lost, but White is likely to lose even more material.   19...Nxd2  immediately is too hasty and allows White to put up further resistance with  20.Qxd2  since  20...Bxc4  will be answered by  21.Bxc6  . }
20. Re1
{ 20.Qb3  doesn't change the outcome.  Rxd2  21.Bxe4  Bxc4  22.Qf3  Bxe2  23.Bxd2  Bxf3  24.Bxf3  Qc4  and Black is winning. }
20... Nxd2 21. Bxd2 Bxc4 { Black wins material. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Puzzles"]
[Black "Puzzle 4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/4pqbp/4b1p1/5p2/1P1Nn3/3Q2P1/4PPBP/1RB2RK1 b - - 0 22"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Find the way for Black to win material. } 22... Rad8
{ White has big problems because of the pin. } 23. e3
{ The problem with  23.Bb2  is that Black can attack the knight again with the e-pawn after moving the bishop from e6.  23...Ba2  ,  attacking the rook, so White has no time to move the queen away from the rook on d8.  24.Ra1  Bxd4  .  This is stronger than immediately ...e5 because then White 'only loses' an exchange after Rxa2 followed by Qb3+.  25.Bxd4  e5  26.Qa3  Ra8  27.Qb2  exd4  . }
23... Bc4
{ And Black wins the exchange.   Attacking the rook and then playing ...e7-e5 doesn't win material:  23...Ba2  24.Rb2  e5  25.Qc2  ,  White is lucky to escape from the rook on d8 by attacking the bishop on a2 twice. In the line after Bb2, this was not possible because the bishop is in between the rook and the queen, so the bishop on a2 is only attacked once @@StartBracket@@and defended once by the queen on f7@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Puzzles"]
[Black "Puzzle 5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1n4rk/1p3q1p/2p1b3/1PPp1p2/1R1PpP1Q/rRN4P/5PB1/6K1 b - - 0 31"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Material gain is now possible for Black. Lead the charge! } 31... Rxb3
{ By taking on b3, Black ensures that the rook on b4 is no longer defending the pawn on d4. }
32. Rxb3 Qg7 { Threatening mate on g2. } 33. Qg5 Qxd4
{ Black has a winning position, the queen on d4 can come back to g7 to threaten mate again, while ...d5-d4 would attack the knight on c3 and the rook on b3. There are too many threats for White to defend against. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Puzzles"]
[Black "Puzzle 6"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3rr1k1/p5qp/bp6/2p5/2PnBp2/1P1Q2P1/PN3P1P/2R2RK1 b - - 0 29"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black has a forcing and winning operation, which one? } 29... Rxe4
{ Black wins on the light squares, the combination of a bishop on b7 and knight on d4 is lethal. }
30. Qxe4 Bb7 31. Qb1 { 31.Qd3  Nf3+-+ } 31... Ne2# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Puzzles"]
[Black "Puzzle 7"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1r5k/pp1bp1r1/n2p1nqp/2pP1p2/P4Pp1/1PP1N1P1/2Q1PNBP/4RR1K b - - 0 25"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Find the best plan for Black. } 25... h5
{ A strong strategic move − Black has to create play on the kingside and not on the queenside nor on the center.   Another alternative was to play  25...Nc7  saying that the knight is not doing much on a6, but the same is the case on c7 and it is not easy to activate this knight on the kingside.  Black could probably also have started with  25...Rh7  ,  but we don't really need the rook on h7 yet, Black can first push ....h6-h5-h4, see how White responds, and then decide. Maybe the rook needs to be on the h-file or perhaps we want to play ...Nh5 to attack the pawn on g3. }
26. Kg1 h4
{ Black has the advantage in view of the kingside initiative while all of White's pieces look a bit clumsy and are not threatening much. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Puzzles"]
[Black "Puzzle 8"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bn1r1k/p1p3bp/1p5n/4p1pq/4P3/1PP2PP1/PB1NQNB1/R2R2K1 b - - 0 22"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ What is Black's best continuation? } 22... g4
{ Black has to open the kingside to develop the initiative further. Any other moves such as  22...Be6  are slow because they only postpone what Black needs to do anyway: open lines against White's king. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Puzzles"]
[Black "Puzzle 9"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3bbk1/q6p/2pp2p1/pp1PP1n1/3n4/PP1N2PP/1B3QBK/4RN2 b - - 0 27"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black to play and win. } 27... Ndf3+
{ White has to give up the queen because taking with the bishop loses even more material. }
28. Bxf3 Qxf2+ 29. Nxf2 Nxf3+ 30. Kh1 Nxe1 { Black is a rook up. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Puzzles"]
[Black "Puzzle 10"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r5k1/p1p1Rrbp/1p1p4/n2P1bpq/1QPB1p2/2P2P2/P2N2BP/4R1K1 b - - 0 21"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Another nice tactic − how can Black win immediately? } 21... c5
{ Making use of the fact that a knight on c6 attacks both the queen and the rook. }
22. dxc6 Bxd4+ { 22...Nxc6  is less precise because of  23.Re8+  . } 23. cxd4
Rxe7 24. Rxe7 Nxc6
{ Black will win an exchange but also has the much better position with active pieces while White's bishop on g2 is dead. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Puzzles"]
[Black "Puzzle 11"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3k2r/pp1n2p1/2p1pn1p/q2p3P/3PbBP1/2P2N2/P1PQ2B1/1K1R3R b kq - 0 16"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ How should Black increase the strength of the attack? } 16... Nb6
{ There is no reason to wait with trying to give mate on b2, the simple concept of a knight on c4 or a4 followed by a check with the queen on b6 or b5 is very powerful. }
17. Ne5 Bxg2 18. Qxg2 Na4 19. Rd3 Ne4
{ Taking away the d2-square from the white king and the pawn on c3 will soon be captured. White is completely lost. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Puzzles"]
[Black "Puzzle 12"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/pp2p1p1/n4n1p/1NPp4/4pBP1/5P2/PPP4P/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 8"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Find the strongest continuation for Black. } 8... e5
{ By sacrificing the e-pawn, we can take on c5 with the bishop, stop any threats from White on the d6-square, while pointing out that the dark squares on the white side @@StartBracket@@f2-e3 and also h4@@EndBracket@@ are weak. }
9. Bxe5 Bxc5
{ Black has a winning advantage, the white king is in danger while the knight on b5 and the bishop on c5 are loose. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Puzzles"]
[Black "Puzzle 13"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1k1r3r/pp2q2p/2p1bb1P/5pp1/2Ppn3/1P1NP1P1/PBQ2PB1/1K1RR3 b - - 0 22"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black has the chance to create weaknesses on the dark squares, a typical theme in the Leningrad System. Can you see it? }
22... Nc3+
{ The pawn on c3 is strong for Black because there are all kinds of mating threats and there is no way for White to win the pawn. The alternative, taking on e3, is not great because White can exchange the bishops on f6 and take on e3 with the rook. After that, both rooks are active on the d- and e-file and Black has nothing special. }
23. Bxc3 dxc3
{ For the rest of the game White needs to watch out for ...Qa3 or setups with a bishop on g7 and the queen on f6, when Black sacrifices the c-pawn with ...c3-c2. Besides these attacking ideas, the pawn is also strong in an endgame. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Puzzles"]
[Black "Puzzle 14"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "5rk1/pb1N2pp/1p3q2/1Bpp1n2/3Pr3/2P3P1/PP3PK1/R2Q1R2 b - - 0 21"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black has a very dangerous attack and the icing on the cake is...? } 21...
Nh4+ { White needs to sacrifice the queen to avoid mate. } 22. gxh4
{ 22.Kh2  Qh6  23.Kg1  Nf3+  and Black wins a queen.   22.Kg1  Qe6  threatening ...Qh3.  23.Kh2  Nf3+  24.Kg2  Rh4  .  The rook cannot be taken because of ...Qg4+ followed by ...Qh3 mate.  25.Rh1  Qe4  26.Rxh4  Nxh4+  27.Kh3  Rxf2  ,  Black's attack cannot be stopped.  28.Qg1  Qf5+  29.g4   Taking on h4 results in mate:  29.Kxh4  g5+  30.Kh5  Qh3+  31.Kxg5  Rf5  29...Rf3+  30.Qg3  Qf4  .  The engine says mate in 10, but to the human eye, it is clear that White at least loses the queen and the attack continues.   22.Kh1  Qe6  results in the same line as above with 22.Kg1 if White now plays  23.Kh2  to prevent ...Qh3+. }
22... Qg6+ 23. Kh3 Rff4 { The engine says mate in 6, ...Rxh4 is hard to stop! }
