{ Black has a very beautiful continuation now. Unfortunately, it only results in a draw. }
21... Rxf2 { That's the kind of moves we like! } 22. Kxf2 Bxg3+ 23. Kg1
{ After  23.Ke3  Bxe1  Black has sufficient counter play against the white king for hardly any material deficit @@StartBracket@@rook against piece plus pawn@@EndBracket@@, perpetual check is still a likely scenario. }
23... Bh2+
{ And another piece sacrifice, the best way to make a draw through perpetual check. }
24. Kxh2
{ In case of  24.Kh1  ,  the king is not safe in the corner.  24...Qh4  and now White needs to give perpetual check.  25.Qxc7+  Kg8  26.Qb8+  Kg7  27.Qc7+  with a draw, Black cannot escape from the checks. }
24... Qh4 { White cannot defend against the series of checks. } 25. Qxc7+ Bd7+
26. Kg1 Qg3+ 27. Kf1 Qh3+
{ After all these complications, we end with a draw because of perpetual check, there is no way Black can play for mate. }
